[Black "Our Venom"]
[Result "*"]

{ 1.c3 Venom... you can't be serious... 1. c3 for real???  Yes. I'm deadly serious.  Hello and welcome to the Spider's Lair!  I'd first like to congratulate you for making it here! You've finally made the practical decision to skip out on all the heavy theoretical battles and troublesome memorisation of Lifetime Repertoires, and instead ventured into the path of the unknown...   ...well, that is, unknown to everyone except for you — and the few others who buy this course!   When we sit down at the board to decide what opening to play, many players already go wrong at this stage of the game. They immediately go in with the mindset of playing the very best moves from move 1, since this is the right way to win a game of chess.  Wrong. If we were robots built from head to toe in Stockfish 16, then this would be a superb way to go about it. However, as limited humans, it's much better to consider these several factors:  - how can I get my opponent into uncharted waters so THEY actually have to play chess @@StartBracket@@rather than their coach or computer@@EndBracket@@?  - how can I find a repertoire that I won't have to constantly update, and can play even if I'm having an off day?  - what style of player am I, and which opening will suit me best?    This last point is probably the most important, and unfortunately I cannot answer that for you in this course!  However, I can certainly address the first two points, and believe me, your opponents will certainly have a headache when facing 1.c3 Venom! }
1. c3
{ So, what exactly is the idea behind playing 1. c3?  Principally, we @@StartBracket@@should@@EndBracket@@ know that there are three golden rules of the opening: 1. control the centre, 2. develop your pieces, and 3. get your king safe. This is fundamental to good opening play, but as soon as we get a little stronger, we see that openings are breaking these rules all the time.   Take the most popular Sicilian Najdorf for instance: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  a6  Black ends up playing 4 out of 5 pawn moves at the start of the game @@StartBracket@@one of which being ...a6@@EndBracket@@, so clearly there is something beyond these basic principles.   Once we get even stronger, we start to appreciate openings as their own entities. The French has a certain character to it, as well as the Caro-Kann, as well as the Modern, and so on.   For the most part of chess history, the player starting with the White pieces is advised to choose between 1. e4 or 1. d4, and be prepared for whichever pet opening that comes their way. Objectively speaking, this is the best way to go. But practically speaking, this is quite the nightmare!   For instance, when you play  1.e4  , you are giving your opponent the choice to play whichever opening suits them and their style best @@StartBracket@@remember point #3?@@EndBracket@@. So if you play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  , your opponent may respond with  1...e6  @@StartBracket@@the French@@EndBracket@@, and the fact that they're willingly playing the French Defence means they actually like playing the French!? And that's a serious issue. A French player likes the challenge of a cramped position where they may get slaughtered on the kingside, but if they survive, they get to enjoy much better endgame prospects.   So to conclude this point, we really want to avoid Black having the choice to set the tone for the rest of the game. }
1... e5
{ At the age of 15 @@StartBracket@@having played 1. e4 unsuccessfully for 5 years@@EndBracket@@, I came across a beautiful opening:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  — also known as — the Reti.  I loved it because my opponents were completely unprepared, and they couldn't play their favourite pet lines @@StartBracket@@which I have experienced on the receiving end with the black pieces against the Reti!@@EndBracket@@. I have been playing the Reti ever since @@StartBracket@@in the style of  2.c4  ,  3. g3/b3@@EndBracket@@ with much better results than if I'd stuck to  1.e4  @@StartBracket@@or  1.d4  , which I'd tried for some time also@@EndBracket@@. However, unfortunately, this best kept secret of the Reti has slowly been uncovered, with the opening gaining serious popularity of late, and being played at all levels.  In short, the Reti was no longer my unexpected surprise for my opponent, and my opponents were actually prepared. It took me some time to even pick up on this, but when I did, I immediately began my search for something else. What opening could I play that would bring my opponent into uncharted waters? }
2. d4
{ Now, if I were to address this journey in its entirety, that would probably take up all your time to read! So I'll shorten it down to one sentence:   Take reverse systems to the next level.   So if you remember, I spoke about the drawback of playing 1. e4 or 1. d4, since Black has the choice of how to dictate the nature of the game? Well, with 1. c3, we, as White, are in fact dictating the nature of the game. We are taking the game into Reverse Caro-Kann / London System territory, no matter what Black plays. And this is what's really nice about 1.c3 Venom. Against the most principled response of 1...e5, we enter a Caro-Kann Reversed — a tempo up — where the extra tempo makes ALL the difference in a lot of lines.   Most of these lines are completely unexplored, which will make for an uncomfortable experience for your opponent to have to figure out everything over the board. And against everything else, we will play a very simple London System, but not as simple as 'develop the pieces around a triangle and then push e4' — but instead, I'd like you to take note of your opponent's setup, be responsive, and make use of basic strategies to frustrate your opponent and take them away from their pet lines.   And finally, at the end of the theoretical chapters and model games, I provide some bonus systems starting with 1. c3 — namely The Slug and The Snail — leading at the forefront of this chapter. I have a 100% record with the Slug @@StartBracket@@5/5 wins in classical against similarly rated opponents@@EndBracket@@, and it is the most remarkably provocative surprise weapon you will ever come across — so you have been warned!   So on that note, let's delve straight into this course! I wish you the very best on this journey of learning 1.c3 Venom, and I am excited to see how far the philosophy of this opening takes you!   Yours,   Michael Green   First time Chessable Author & FIDE Instructor   23/11/2023 }
*

