{ Before we go down the rabbit hole of studying our 1.c3 Venom theory, I'd first like to showcase to you some evidence of what playing 1.c3 Venom is all about!   If you've been an avid studier of the mainlines for a long while, there may still be some doubt in your mind that 1. c3 may not live up to the expectations presented in my introduction. However, I hope by the end of these two model games, you will understand the power of what playing a sound, but offbeat, opening system can achieve!    Several months ago, I met up with an old chess friend of mine for some casual blitz chess. I'd say I was always roughly a couple hundred ELO higher rated than him, but that doesn't mean I'd win every game against him! However, that evening, I was on a hot streak, and had won my first two blitz games  (5|0)  against him. As a result, I decided to experiment with a Caro-Kann with Black for our third game. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The Classical Variation. I haven't played the Caro-Kann seriously for several years @@StartBracket@@the reasons of which I'll get into in the upcoming chapters!@@EndBracket@@, but of all the variations White could try, I quite liked playing against the Classical Variation! There are several ways to play against it, but I like to capture on e4, and then immediately develop the bishop to f5. }
3... dxe4 4. Bc4
{ Completely unexpected! I felt that the move had to be objectively dubious, but I really had no idea. Perhaps my opponent had cooked up an aggressive gambit in his home preparation against the Caro-Kann? }
4... Bf5
{ I won't comment so much on the following moves. I simply developed my pieces as any Caro-Kann player would. }
5. Nge2 e6 6. Ng3 Bg6 7. h4 h6 8. h5 Bh7 9. f3 exf3 10. Qxf3 Nf6 11. O-O Be7
12. Nce4
{ My opponent had blitzed out all these moves, which unnerved me a little. After-all, I'm a clean pawn up, and have made only natural moves...   Surely I shouldn't be in any trouble here? }
12... O-O 13. c3 Nbd7 14. Bb3 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Since I was a pawn up, I automatically went to trade the pieces, feeling happy about my endgame prospects. However, I had overlooked a surprising tactical blow! }
16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bxh6
{ Although my position was indeed much better several moves ago, my opponent clearly has experience in these open attacking positions, and has won the pawn back with an attack. The engine still prefers Black, but that's beside the point! Practically speaking, this is a tough position for Black to play. }
17... Qa5 18. Qg3 Bf5 19. Bxg7
{ Another strong move to continue the attack! Now I'm in big trouble. } 19...
Bxg7 20. h6 { And now I am objectively lost. How the tables have turned! }
20... Bg6 21. Bxe6
{ I had seen Bxe6, but was hoping my opponent hadn't! In any case, I had nothing better than to play 20...Bg6. }
21... Qh5 22. hxg7 Kxg7
{ Here, White should simply retreat  23.Bb3  ,  and keep a healthy pawn advantage with good attacking chances on my weakened king.   But instead, my opponent creates unnecessary complications for himself and his pieces! }
23. Bg4 Qg5 24. Rae1 Rae8 25. Re5
{ Having let his advantage slip, the momentum was turning back in my direction, and now my opponent blundered.   This is what happens when you don't talk to your pieces, and give yourself multiple loose pieces @@StartBracket@@Bg4 and Qg3@@EndBracket@@ that can be tactically exploited! }
25... f5
{ A great find @@StartBracket@@if I do say so myself!@@EndBracket@@, and now I am winning once more. }
26. Rxe8 Rxe8 27. Qc7+ Re7 28. Qd8 fxg4
{ My opponent played on for several more moves before running out of time in a dead lost position.   Despite winning this game, it was by no means a simple win! My opponent had prepared an aggressive gambit against the Caro-Kann that I had no option but to enter into, and I was almost defeated by my opponent's strong attacking play in the open position. Regardless of the objective strength of his gambit line, my opponent understood his strengths as a player, which is attacking chess in open positions! If you remember, I had won the first two games, and this was now my third win of the evening.   For my fourth game, I decided to test out my new project — a Caro-Kann Reversed! }
