{ Having just barely survived playing the Caro-Kann with Black, I decided to try the Caro-Kann Reversed against my friend to see if I could do any better!   Let's see how this game went! }
1. c3 e5
{ After burning some time on the clock, my opponent confidently played 1...e5.   My opponent is an aggressive 1.e4 player — so why wouldn't you play 1...e5 and try wipe me off the board? }
2. d4
{ Again, my opponent had to stop and think. 'What on earth is going on here?' }
2... e4
{ Although objectively speaking there is nothing wrong with this move @@StartBracket@@in fact, this is the Caro-Kann Reversed Advance Variation which we will cover soon!@@EndBracket@@, my opponent had accidentally entered into a closed position, that he isn't as strong at.   I knew this about my friend, but you can also see this from his decision against the standard Caro-Kann to play an open aggressive gambit, rather than entering the Advance Variation.   In conclusion, we have tricked our opponent into playing against their playing style, as early as move 2! }
3. Bf4
{ Uh oh @@StartBracket@@for my opponent@@EndBracket@@. My friend takes an even longer think, trying to understand what on earth he has gotten himself into.   What he hasn't realised, is that he's playing a Caro-Kann Advance Variation, a tempo down, which is an opening system which he has no experience of! }
3... d5 4. e3 Nc6
{ A Reverse Advance Variation Shirov Gambit!? Not that names matter. The nature of this position will be completely different due to White's extra tempo. }
5. c4
{ Always our go-to plan when Black doesn't immediately harass our bishop on f4, since this allows us the time to immediately hit the centre. }
5... g5 6. Bg3 h5 7. h4 Bg4 8. Qb3 Be6
{ It is clear my opponent is out of depth, having to move the same piece twice so soon in the opening. It's not surprising that their position soon collapses. }
9. Nc3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Bxc4 11. Qxc4
{ I am strategically winning now. The position is already evaluated at +3 by Stockfish 16, and my opponent immediately goes from bad to worse! }
11... Qd7 12. d5 Nb4 13. Qxe4+ Ne7 14. Qxb4
{ At this point, I'm a piece up, and went on to win without any difficulties. If we compare the outcome of this Caro-Kann Reversed to the standard Caro-Kann, the practical advantage is clear! My opponent immediately got themselves into the wrong kind of position that didn't suit their playing style, and lost without a fight. Of course, my opponent blundering a full piece helped with my conversion of the resulting position, but this blunder didn't come out of thin air! In fact it was heavily influenced by the lack of understanding and experience in the position.   In the standard Caro-Kann, my opponent was prepared and dangerous, having given the opening plenty of thought, after countless games and personal experience of how best to tackle the standard Caro-Kann. For you and I, our opponents will be facing 1. c3 for the first time, and they won't have any easier of a time trying to navigate these resulting positions.   Finally, I'd like to clarify that the surprise element of 1.c3 Venom is by no means the only thing going for it. The repertoire you are about to embark on is strategically and concretely sound, and I have been utilising it in my own chess ever since I started work on this course. From crushing an FM out of the opening in 13 moves in blitz  (which you'll see in the London System Model Games!)  , to having great results with the repertoire in over-the-board tournaments, I can assure you that the repertoire will be suitable for all time controls and environments! My hope is that after studying 1.c3 Venom, you will be able to outplay your opponents in ways you never thought were possible, and reach new heights in your overall chess ability!  On this note, I will now present to you the different lines I will be offering in this 1.c3 Venom repertoire. It is a complete and full repertoire, and I have covered what I consider to be the mainlines, sidelines, and even rare lines — to ensure you're not the one caught out by surprise! I hope you find our study of these unchartered waters to be as fascinating as I did! }
