[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4
{ Here, we begin our journey, playing the Caro-Kann Reversed!   For us to fully appreciate the nuances of the Caro-Kann Reversed, we first must begin with understanding the basics of the Caro-Kann. At the start of each chapter, I will show you the basic ideas in a Caro-Kann line, and then we will see the same line, but with reverse colours and a tempo up for White. But before we discuss any specific lines, let's discuss what the Caro-Kann is all about!   Strategically, the Caro-Kann is a perfect opening. We're incredibly solid @@StartBracket@@yet imbalanced@@EndBracket@@, have better endgame prospects, and play on simple strategies. The reason I don't recommend the opening as a response to 1. e4, is that it's extremely trendy nowadays, and as a result, everyone is booked up to the teeth on it. When you play an opponent that either has strong memory of computer moves, or they have access to high level resources @@StartBracket@@say, a course by a GM explaining the plans and ideas@@EndBracket@@, these factors can make a huge difference in their playing strength when facing the Caro-Kann.   However, when playing the Caro-Kann Reversed, our opponents cannot rely on computer moves, or the exact plans/ideas given by top players, to navigate these novel positions. For instance, the theory heavy 'Advance Variation' is no longer critical @@StartBracket@@and even risky to follow the same mainlines as in a standard Caro-Kann!@@EndBracket@@, and our extra tempo will avoid many of the Caro-Kann sidelines.   To examine Black's responses further, you'll be glad to hear that Black has nowhere near as many options as White would have against a standard Caro-Kann! For instance, there is no Pseudo-Panov @@StartBracket@@1. e4 / 2. c4@@EndBracket@@, or tricky 2. Nf3 gambits, to worry about with reverse colours. The Fantasy variation is just plain bad in our reverse system, and the Two Knights becomes irrelevant since we can play against it in the same way that we will play against the Classical @@StartBracket@@which is not possible in a standard Caro-Kann@@EndBracket@@.   So all in all, less work for us, and the resulting positions will be much easier @@StartBracket@@and much less critical@@EndBracket@@ to play. The rest of this chapter is just for your information of what we're going to cover on the course. So don't worry about the lines so much for now, but if you ever want to have an all-encompassing view of all the lines you'll be learning, you can find this here! }
2... exd4
{ 2...f6  3.e4!  The Fantasy Variation is really bad when Black has one tempo less to execute it. We are +1.0 in eval already according to Stockfish 16.   2...Nc6  3.dxe5  Nxe5  4.Bf4  Ng6  5.Bg3  The Two Knights Variation is in fact only 'One Knight', and as a result, we can transpose into a mainline Classical Variation — a tempo up!   2...d6  3.e4  Rather than play into any endgame lines, I suggest we take the full centre with e4.  White has a small, but comfortable, edge in these lines.   2...e4  3.Bf4  Although objectively equal, the Caro-Kann Reversed Advance Variation is a risky attempt for Black to try, since Black does not have the same critical responses to test White's setup, while White retains all the strategical benefits of a Caro-Kann. }
3. cxd4 d5
{ The Caro-Kann Exchange Variation.   This is the most principled decision by Black, since the extra tempo should play less of a factor in a quieter position compared to a sharp position. However, we have in fact directly transposed to a Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ Exchange Variation — a line that many Black players would hate to enter, since the game leads to the most typical '2 result game' @@StartBracket@@win or draw@@EndBracket@@ that we can imagine in chess!   You will see that the extra tempo allows us to post our pieces on much nicer squares than in a standard Caro-Kann Exchange Variation, so I am very happy to recommend this line to you! }
4. Nc3 c6 5. Bf4
{ In all our variations of the Caro-Kann Reversed, we will either be able to establish our dark-squared bishop outside of the forthcoming triangle pawn chain, OR we will have been able to take a healthy centre, achieving both e4- and d4-pawns in the centre.  Let's now move onto lines where Black doesn't start with 1...e5. Against all other Black responses, I'll be advocating for a London System! }
