1. c3
{ So you might be wondering, why exactly have I chosen to recommend the London System, as our opening against  1...d5  ?   In fact, I actually had several possibilities here. I could have stuck to the theme of 'Reverse Setups' by venturing into the land of reverse Slavs, or even reverse Semi-Slavs @@StartBracket@@see the final chapter on 'Revolutionary Thinking'!@@EndBracket@@  but I found these systems to be particularly sharp and require difficult engine play to realise some of the advantages. And for this reason, I chose the London System, which is the complete opposite in nature!   To put it simply:   You will be able to play this opening with the knowledge of basic plans and ideas, and infuriate your opponent to no end, since they won't be able to showcase their favourite pet lines.   For this reason, I believe the London System is the best practical solution to facing 1...d5, and all other starting moves from Black @@StartBracket@@aside from 1...e5 — where we'll play our Caro-Kann Reversed setup@@EndBracket@@.   I hope you will enjoy the following positions, and the logic behind the nuances of our setup. Let's take a look at the different lines! }
1... Nf6
{ 1...d5  2.d4  Nf6  3.Bf4  I begin our London System journey with lines following 1...d5 and 2...Nf6. We can consider this to be our mainline of the London System.   1...d5  2.d4  c5  3.Bf4  This ambitious setup will be covered in the '2...c5 Fireworks' chapter. We will use our opponent's optimistic and ambitious play against them!   1...d5  2.d4  Nc6  3.Bf4  I cover this weak 'Chigorin Attempt' in the Unprincipled Setups chapter.   1...c5  2.d4  cxd4  3.cxd4  d5  Here we transpose to an Exchange Slav. I really like our play in this line, since we can use our extra tempo to call the shots.   1...c6  2.d4  d5  3.Bf4  Bf5  Since we haven't played so ambitiously in the centre, our opponent can actually consider copying our moves! But this isn't a great strategy for Black, and we'll have the practical advantage that our opponent can't think for themselves, and the symmetry will eventually be broken in our favour!   1...f5  2.d4  I cover the Dutch in the 'Unprincipled Setups' chapter. The Dutch is a great practical weapon against most d4 / Reti / English setups, but not against the London! }
2. d4 g6
{ 2...c5  3.Bf4  This ambitious setup will be covered in the '2...c5 Fireworks' chapter. }
3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3
{ I have split the King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@ into two separate chapters based on whether Black plays for ...e5, or plays for ...c5.   Our approach is fundamentally different depending on which plan Black opts for, so I believe the distinction is useful! }
6... b6
{ 6...Re8  7.Be2  e5  This is the starting position of the KID with ...e5 } 7.
Be2 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bh2 c5
{ This is the starting position of the KID with ...c5 } 10. Nbd2
{ ...and this concludes the summary of our London System lines! Before we start studying the theory of our 1.c3 Venom, I would first like to suggest to you how to study the course. There are several considerations one should make, so I'd like to outline what these are, to help tailor the course to you! }
