{ I'm sure you're all keen to move on from the introduction and see what lines are in store for you! But I wanted to first offer some advice on how to study 1.c3 Venom, because there are some important clarifications to be made depending on your chess level, as well as what you're looking to get out of the course!  So firstly, let me cover some universal rules for studying 1.c3 Venom!    1@@EndBracket@@ I want you to read through ALL informational variations within the chapters. This will mostly apply to the Caro-Kann Reversed section, where the informational variations will be showing standard Caro-Kann positions, which we don't need to study, but do need to appreciate, in order to gain a full understanding of our Reverse structures.    2@@EndBracket@@ If you are under 2000 ELO @@StartBracket@@online ratings@@EndBracket@@, please ignore the ADVANCED Material chapters of the course @@StartBracket@@labelled with a 📓@@EndBracket@@. It is not because you wouldn't be able to understand them @@StartBracket@@I believe you could!@@EndBracket@@, but it is simply not practical to study the lines.   Your opponents will probably go wrong far sooner, and as an intermediate player, your focus and attention on chess study could be better spent elsewhere! So stick to the core chapters of the course and master that — this will be more than enough!    3@@EndBracket@@ I would like you to follow the Model Games wherever I link them in a variation. This can be tedious, in the sense that you might want to keep stream rolling ahead with the theory and not break your flow to go study a game. However, I believe while the theory is currently fresh in your mind, associating the plans and ideas from a model game with the connected theory will be hugely beneficial to your resulting play in these lines. I have chosen only the most relevant Model Games to assist your understanding of 1.c3 Venom, so please study these alongside the theory!   Next, I'd like to suggest two different methods of studying 1.c3 Venom — one to maximise understanding, one to maximise practicality.   Let's examine both options! }
1. c3
{ Here are the two different ways to study 1.c3 Venom that I can recommend:   1@@EndBracket@@ Pure Venom: The purest path to learn 1.c3 Venom is to study the course in order of the chapters and variations presented. This is the best way to study the course if you want to understand 1.c3 Venom to its fullest. I have put great thought into the order of the chapters, as well as the order of the variations within each chapter, in order to maximise your understanding of the opening.   2@@EndBracket@@ Shot of Venom: Next, I will recommend the most practical method of study, if you are looking to get results right away @@StartBracket@@or if you have a tournament next week and are in urgent need of a White repertoire!@@EndBracket@@   First, you should study chapter '5@@EndBracket@@ Caro-Kann Reversed Exchange Variation', since this will arise in over 50% of your games starting with 1...e5.   I would also recommend skipping variations within this chapter on the 'Panov Attack', since this will occur far less compared to a typical Exchange Variation. After studying the Exchange Variation lines, it is essential that you still study ALL the Model Games on the Minority Attack from this chapter, since understanding the resulting middlegame play @@StartBracket@@particularly in this Exchange Variation@@EndBracket@@, will matter even more than the memory of precise theory of this chapter.   Then, I'd recommend that you move on straight to the London System chapters, covering '6@@EndBracket@@ London System: 1...d5 Mainlines' first, followed by the two King's Indian Defence chapters '7@@EndBracket@@ London System: KID with ...e5' and 8@@EndBracket@@ London System: KID with ...c5'.   These 4 chapters will provide you sufficient knowledge to cover Black's main responses of 1...e5, 1...d5, and 1...Nf6. I would recommend as you play 1. c3 against various different opponents, when you experience a new response that you haven't studied before @@StartBracket@@or for example, if your opponent plays 1...Nf6, but then follows up with 2...c5 — which is covered in its own chapter called '2...c5 Fireworks'@@EndBracket@@, you should then study the relevant course chapter corresponding to your opponent's setup, to find out what I recommend you should play. So have a think carefully what your priorities are as a player, and pick whichever path suits you best.   Without further ado, let's begin our journey of 1.c3 Venom, starting with the Caro-Kann Reversed, followed by the London System.   @@HeaderStart@@Let's go!@@HeaderEnd@@ }
