[White "1) Caro-Kann Reversed: One Knight / Classical Variation"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Classical Variation"]
[Result "*"]

{ Before studying the Caro-Kann Reversed variations, it is important to understand where the plans and ideas come from, and what difference this one tempo will make in a lot of these lines.   The next two variations will showcase an important nuance between the Classical and the Two Knights Variation of the Caro-Kann, and if understood properly, it will make our life much easier to understand and remember our corresponding line in the Caro-Kann Reversed! }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5
{ This is the starting position of the most typical Caro-Kann lines. For us in the Caro-Kann Reversed, the d4-pawn has yet to be played — which is obviously in our favour!   Here, White has several different options, and I'd like to start by explaining to you the basics of the 3. Nc3 Classical Variation. }
3. Nc3
{ So firstly, I'd like to address what the Caro-Kann player is looking to achieve. Black would like to lock up the pawn structure with ...e6, to form a very solid pawn chain in order to restrict the 1. e4 player's attacking possibilities. However, if this is done too quickly, the poor light-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@LSB@@EndBracket@@ will be imprisoned behind the pawn chain, and won't be very useful to us.   Therefore, the Caro-Kann player must always start their thinking with this essential question: how am I solving the development of my light-squared bishop?   The Caro-Kann player would like to develop their bishop outside of the forthcoming pawn chain, to either g4 or f5, before playing ...e6. However, in this current position, ...Bg4 is unavailable @@StartBracket@@due to Qxg4@@EndBracket@@, and so is ...Bf5 due to the pawn on e4.   So what should Black do? }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5
{ By capturing the e4-pawn, Black successfully completes the development of this troublesome LSB, and can cement the solid Caro-Kann pawn structure soon with ...e6! }
5. Ng3
{ White's usual response to ...Bf5 is to retreat the knight with tempo on the bishop. Now that the LSB has been developed outside of the forthcoming pawn chain, it should be kept outside of the chain by retreating to g6! }
5... Bg6 6. Nf3
{ At this moment, we reach our first major RULE #1 to remember: Always meet Nf3 with ...Nd7! }
6... Nd7
{ If ...Nd7 isn't played, White will establish a strong knight on e5, and Black will experience serious troubles @@StartBracket@@just trust me for now — you'll see in the next variation on the Two Knights Variation the 'serious troubles' I'm talking about!@@EndBracket@@. }
7. h4
{ At this moment, we reach our second major RULE #2 to remember: In the Classical Variation, always meet h4 with ...h6! }
7... h6
{ Black would much prefer to play ...h6 than ...h5, since Black would actually be very happy to see White push their pawn further to h5.   After h5, Black has the simple retreat of the bishop to the h7-square, and this h5-pawn will be a weakness for the rest of the game, causing serious suffering for White in any resulting endgames! }
8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3
{ Black does not want to lose castling rights by allowing Bxh7, so it's best to simply capture on d3.   It is also worth noting that Bd3 is White's strongest attacking minor piece, so after its removal, Black's king safety will improve significantly upon castling kingside! }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6
{ White normally chooses between Bd2 and Bf4 here.   The reason behind Bd2 is to prevent a specific 11...Qa5!? line. However, we're not going to worry about this, and we should focus on the same setup in both cases after Bd2 and Bf4, which is the following: ...e6, ...Nf6, ...Be7, ...O-O }
11. Bf4 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 O-O
{ This is what I'd consider the starting point of the Classical Variation. If I could get this position every time in the Caro-Kann, I'd probably play it as Black against 1.e4! The reason why this position is so pleasant, is because most of the endgames are in our favour. The h5-pawn is a weakness, and very often White will push c4, leading to the d4-pawn being weakened on the half-open d-file.   Black's position is super solid, and there is zero — I mean zero — attacks that work on the black king. The knights on g3 and f3 may look a little scary, but without White's light-squared bishop, their attack is dead!   Having said this, I would still much prefer to play our Caro-Kann Reversed position a tempo up @@StartBracket@@aka this position without the king on b1@@EndBracket@@, for two main reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ our opponents will have no concrete theory to rely on, and   2@@EndBracket@@ the extra tempo allows for a more ambitious take-over of the position for us.  Objectively speaking, this current position @@StartBracket@@with Kb1 played@@EndBracket@@ is a slight advantage for White, while with colours reversed, we will instead have the slight objective advantage!   Now, before we head to our Caro-Kann Reversed, I'd like us to briefly discuss an opening problem that Black has against the Two Knights Variation. This will be very relevant for us when we try to understand the move order nuances in our reverse setup.   Let's go! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Caro-Kann Reversed: One Knight / Classical Variation"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Two Knights Variation Problem!"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Nc3
{ Rather than push  2.d4  ,  our opponent favours the development of their knights. }
2... d5 3. Nf3
{ Rather than take the centre with e4 and d4 in a traditional manner, the Two Knights Variation aims to seek active development with the knights instead.   I will not go into detail on how to face the Two Knights @@StartBracket@@since it won't be necessary for us!@@EndBracket@@, but I would like to show you why we can't play against it in the same way as we just looked at in the Classical Variation.   Now, if we take the same initial mindset as in the Classical Variation, we want to solve the development problem of our light-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@LSB@@EndBracket@@. At first glance, it looks like we can transpose to a Classical Variation after: }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { We have successfully developed our LSB, right...? } 5.
Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6
{ Black appears to have followed all the same rules as in the Classical Variation, but the evaluation is far different! The reason being, that a key rule has been violated! If you remember, RULE #1 stated the importance of meeting Nf3 with ...Nd7 in order to prevent the active Ne5 jump.   However, in this position, Nf3 is already on the board! Since Black has not had the time to meet Nf3 with ...Nd7, White immediately punishes Black with the following combination: }
7. Ne5
{ 7.d4?!  Nd7!  A careless move from White allows Black back into the game  8.h5  Bh7  9.Bd3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  e6  This would indeed be a transposition to the Classical Variation we just looked at!   After 7. Ne5, our bishop is attacked, so the natural retreat is... }
7... Bh7 8. Qh5
{ Terrifying! Suddenly there is immediate pressure on f7, and the only way to defend it is the ugly ...g6. }
8... g6 9. Bc4
{ What a nightmare!   White is able to offer a queen sacrifice with mate as early as move 9. This is why it is so important to remember RULE #1: meet Nf3 with ...Nd7. }
9... gxh5 10. Bxf7#
{ Don't worry. We won't be having any such trouble in the Caro-Kann Reversed.   Let's now take a look at the 'One Knight' Variation of the Caro-Kann Reversed, and put our understanding of these positions to the test! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Caro-Kann Reversed: One Knight / Classical Variation"]
[Black "Classical Variation: 13...Ne4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 Nc6
{ The Two Knights Variation is in fact only 'One Knight' in these colours reversed positions. As a result, the system is quite limited, and we can transpose into a mainline Classical Variation a tempo up!   Just like in a standard Caro-Kann, we should begin by asking ourselves, what to do with our bishop on c1? In this case, you will notice that we are in fact discussing the development of our DARK-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@DSB@@EndBracket@@, as opposed to our light-squared bishop in a standard Caro-Kann! However, the structures are the same, and I hope you can work out our next move! }
3. dxe5 Nxe5 4. Bf4
{ We have again successfully completed the development of our troublesome bishop, and are now ready to secure our solid pawn structure with e3. }
4... Ng6 5. Bg3
{ If we compare this position to the Classical/Two Knights Variations we looked at in a standard Caro-Kann, we can make a very important observation: Black has yet to develop a knight to f6! As a result, there are no savage lines involving a quick ...Ne4 and ...Qh4, and we are in time to implement RULE #1: always meet ...Nf6 with Nd2! }
5... Nf6
{ 5...h5  In the Classical Variation, it is quite possible that our opponent will play a slightly different move order than what we've prepared @@StartBracket@@e.g. with ...h5 first, before ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, we should always be observant of our opponent's moves, and think logically, what is our opponent trying to achieve?   After ...h5, the threat is always to trap our bishop with ...h4, which is why we'd play h3. So as long as you remember the themes of the position, different move orders won't trouble you!   5...N8e7  I should note at this moment that there is an alternative approach to the Classical Variation, which involves an entirely different plan to bring a knight to f5 to attack our Bg3.   This, combined with a quick ...h5, ...h4, can be very tricky to deal with. Black's plan can either start via 5...Ne7, or via 5...Nh6, and we will examine these moves in the ADVANCED Material section of the course! }
6. Nd2
{ Implementing RULE #1! Now there will be no ...Ne4 jump, targeting our DSB. }
6... d5 7. e3 h5
{ The threat is ...h4 to trap our bishop, and now it is important to remember RULE #2: In the Classical Variation, we should always meet ...h5 with h3! }
8. h3
{ 8.h4?!  As we spoke about in a standard Caro-Kann, there is no need to prevent Black advancing their pawn to h4, since this h4-pawn will only create a weakness for them in any resulting endgames! }
8... h4
{ 8...Bd6  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  Black can also play without the inclusion of the h4 push, but our play will be exactly the same.   This is likely to be a slightly better version for Black since the h5 will be less weak than on h4, but in my research, I've found that there are no critical differences in the resulting variations, so I've purposefully chosen to omit these lines! }
9. Bh2 Bd6 10. Bxd6
{ White does not want to lose castling rights by allowing Bxh2, so it's best to simply capture on d6.   We should always be happy to exchange these bishops in our Caro-Kann Reversed. The point being — when we castle on the kingside, without this bishop for Black, our king will be MUCH safer from any kingside attack attempts! }
10... Qxd6
{ Now on anything Black does, we always follow the same development plan: Nf3, Be2, and O-O. }
11. Ngf3
{ At this moment, Black will typically choose between 11...Bd7 or 11...Bf5. I will examine the nuances between these moves in the ADVANCED Material section, but for now, we can treat them exactly the same! }
11... Bd7
{ 11...Bf5  Despite being less common @@StartBracket@@due to additional theory required with lines involving Qa4+ ideas@@EndBracket@@, I do believe 11...Bf5 is a more serious approach to this reverse Classical Variation for Black. However, the nuances are very subtle, so let's explore these details in the ADVANCED Material section of the course. }
12. Be2 O-O-O 13. O-O
{ If you compare this position to the standard Caro-Kann we looked at, you will notice that Black's king has yet to protect itself on b8. Let's see what difference this makes to the resulting positions! Black will typically choose between 3 candidate moves here: Kb8, Ne5, and Ne4. }
13... Ne4
{ The ...Ne4 variation is only playable in setups involving 11...Bf5.   Here, the move is just losing a pawn by force, illustrating how frail Black's pawn structure is in these Classical Variation lines! }
14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qxd6 cxd6 16. Ng5
{ Here Black's setup falls apart immediately. This is quite typical against players who have studied the Classical Variation, but have jumbled up lines of theory in their mind, and don't really understand their own setup.   You'd be surprised how often this happens with players who only study the mainlines! }
*

