12. Be2 O-O-O 13. O-O
{ If you compare this position to the standard Caro-Kann we looked at, you will notice that Black's king has yet to protect itself on b8.   Let's see what difference this makes to the resulting positions! Black will typically choose between 3 candidate moves here: Kb8, Ne5, and Ne4. }
13... Kb8
{ Since Black has made a slow improving move, we too should improve our position! }
14. Rc1
{ A useful improving move that can come in handy if ever the c-file opens! }
14... c5
{ 14...Ne5  As soon as ...Ne5 is played, we can use our understanding of 13...Ne5 lines to navigate these kinds of position:  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Nf3  Qd6  17.Qd4!  @@StartBracket@@refer to 13...Ne5 if you need a refresher on why 17. Qd4 is a useful move!@@EndBracket@@ }
15. b4
{ 15.c4?!  The thematic looking c4 break is not so effective due the strong response:  15...d4!    If Black is able to play d4, they will undermine our e3 pawn, which is KEY to controlling the otherwise weak f4-square. If Black is able to control the f4-square, their attacks can be pretty dangerous. For instance:  16.exd4  Nf4  17.d5  Bxh3!  +/- Therefore, we should only ever play c4 when Black is unable to meet it with ...d4. }
15... cxb4
{ 15...c4?  Aside from weakening the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@making it a backwards pawn forever more@@EndBracket@@, this also blunders tactically to  16.Nxc4! }
16. cxb4 Qxb4 17. Rb1
{ Again, objectively speaking, the position is equal. However, I think any strong human player would take White!   Practically speaking, it will be very difficult for Black to survive the incoming attack on the queenside, since it's easy for White to attack with the open b-file, while Black's knights are nowhere near to aid in the defence. We should also remember that Black will not have a kingside attack here. They can try sacrifice a piece, but it shouldn't ever be working, so with this in mind, it makes our defensive task much easier!   If you would like to see how a typical game in the Classical Variation goes, I would recommend checking out this Model Game. To summarise, we have the more solid pawn structure @@StartBracket@@while Black has several weak pawn targets@@EndBracket@@, endgames will often be in our favour, and it is common for Black to self-destruct since they can't find an active plan to cause us problems! }
