3. dxe5 Nxe5 4. Bf4
{ We have again successfully completed the development of our troublesome bishop, and are now ready to secure our solid pawn structure with e3. }
4... Ng6 5. Bg3
{ If we compare this position to the Classical/Two Knights Variations we looked at in a standard Caro-Kann, we can make a very important observation: Black has yet to develop a knight to f6! As a result, there are no savage lines involving a quick ...Ne4 and ...Qh4, and we are in time to implement RULE #1: always meet ...Nf6 with Nd2! }
5... Nf6
{ 5...h5  In the Classical Variation, it is quite possible that our opponent will play a slightly different move order than what we've prepared @@StartBracket@@e.g. with ...h5 first, before ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, we should always be observant of our opponent's moves, and think logically, what is our opponent trying to achieve?   After ...h5, the threat is always to trap our bishop with ...h4, which is why we'd play h3. So as long as you remember the themes of the position, different move orders won't trouble you!   5...N8e7  I should note at this moment that there is an alternative approach to the Classical Variation, which involves an entirely different plan to bring a knight to f5 to attack our Bg3.   This, combined with a quick ...h5, ...h4, can be very tricky to deal with. Black's plan can either start via 5...Ne7, or via 5...Nh6, and we will examine these moves in the ADVANCED Material section of the course! }
6. Nd2
{ Implementing RULE #1! Now there will be no ...Ne4 jump, targeting our DSB. }
6... d5 7. e3 h5
{ The threat is ...h4 to trap our bishop, and now it is important to remember RULE #2: In the Classical variation, we should always meet ...h5 with h3! }
8. h3
{ 8.h4?!  as we spoke about in a standard Caro-Kann, there is no need to prevent Black advancing their pawn to h4, since this h4 pawn will only create a weakness for them in any resulting endgames! }
8... h4
{ 8...Bd6  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  Black can also play without the inclusion of the h4 push, but our play will be exactly the same.   This is likely to be a slightly better version for Black since the h5 will be less weak than on h4, but in my research, I've found that there are no critical differences in the resulting variations, so I've purposefully chosen to omit these lines! }
9. Bh2 Bd6 10. Bxd6
{ White does not want to lose castling rights by allowing Bxh2, so it's best to simply capture on d6.   We should always be happy to exchange these bishops in our Caro-Kann Reversed. The point being - when we castle on the kingside, without this bishop for Black, our king will be MUCH safer from any kingside attack attempts! }
10... Qxd6
{ Now on anything Black does, we always follow the same development plan: Nf3, Be2, and O-O }
11. Ngf3
{ At this moment, Black will typically choose between 11...Bd7 or 11...Bf5. I will examine the nuances between these moves in the ADVANCED Material section, but for now, we can treat them exactly the same! }
11... Bd7
{ 11...Bf5  Despite being less common @@StartBracket@@due to additional theory required with lines involving Qa4+ ideas@@EndBracket@@, I do believe 11...Bf5 is a more serious approach to this reverse Classical Variation for Black. However, the nuances are very subtle, so let's explore these details in the ADVANCED Material section of the course. }
12. Be2 O-O
{ Black can also opt to castle kingside, but then we should ask Black, what is their pawn doing on h4? }
13. O-O c5 14. b4
{ Many moves are strong here, but I like the simplicity of this move.   We aim to undermine Black's centre, with the goal to open up the queenside and centre, and flood in with our pieces to mop up the weak black pawns.   14.c4?!  We should be careful not to break with c4 for the same reason as in the mainline: due to the thematic response  14...d4!  Our e3-pawn is forced to react by capturing exd4, thus weakening the f4-square for Black to jump in with a very scary knight, resulting in a very scary attack!  15.exd4  Nf4!  16.d5  Bxh3!  Black has achieved a successful kingside attack — which should NOT be possible in our line of the Classical! }
14... cxb4 15. cxb4 Qxb4 16. Rb1
{ Black must greedily capture more pawns here, otherwise they will be left with no compensation for their weak pawn structure. }
16... Qa3
{ Black aims to grab the a2-pawn, in order to compensate for their weak pawn structure. }
17. Rxb7 Qxa2 18. Qa1
{ Despite currently being a pawn down, we should fancy our chances in the resulting endgame! }
18... Qxa1 19. Rxa1 a5 20. Bb5 Bxb5 21. Rxb5
{ White is a pawn down temporarily, but Black has three @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ weak pawns that we can aim to pick off, one by one. The a5-pawn is already a goner @@StartBracket@@we can meet a4 with Rb4, then a3 with Rb3, and finally a2 with Rb2 where the a pawn can run no further!@@EndBracket@@.   With best play, the position is drawn, but White can continue to squeeze this position without any risk of losing. Now that you have finished studying the basic theory of the 'One Knight' / Classical Variation, I'd highly recommend you check out ourModel Game on the system. This will give you more confidence to outplay your opponent in the resulting endgames that follow a typical variation of the Classical Variation! }
