[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Advance Variation Tal #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ We now come to White's other main try against the Caro-Kann — the Advance Variation.   At the start of any Caro-Kann variation, we should always begin by asking ourselves the same question: how are we going to solve the development of our light-squared bishop, before locking up the pawn chain with ...e6? }
3... Bf5
{ This time it's easy! We can develop our bishop to f5 before White is able to control this f5-square with Bd3.  At this moment, the two mainlines are the Tal Variation @@StartBracket@@with  4.h4  @@EndBracket@@ and the Short Variation @@StartBracket@@with  4.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@.   We will examine both variations separately! }
4. h4
{ The aggressive Tal Variation.   If you remember in the Classical Variation, we would always meet h4 with ...h6. However, in the Advance Variation, ...h6 will lead to problems, since White can harass our bishop with g4, and gain a lot of space on the kingside!   Make sure to always meet h4 with ...h5 in the Advance Variation! }
4... h5
{ 4...h6?!  5.g4!  White begins their harassment:  5...Be4  6.f3!  Bg6  7.h5!  Bh7  8.e6!  Black is not in time to play ...e6, and suddenly gets caught in a very cramped position.   Black is already worse, but things can get really bad after:  8...fxe6  8.Bd3  Bxd3  10.Qxd3  Nd7??  11.Qg6#  Whoops! Let's not allow any of these lines where White pushes Black back, and therefore we should simply meet h4 with ...h5. }
5. Bd3
{ 5.c4!?  This is quite an annoying sideline that I struggled to deal with when I played the Caro-Kann with Black. However, in our Caro-Kann Reversed, we have a very pleasant way to meet it which I will come to later! }
5... Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Qb6 8. Nd2 c5
{ At first glance, it feels like Black's position is very healthy. We have traded off our 'bad' light-squared bishop, and will have good pressure against White's d4-pawn. If White plays slowly here with c3, Black would indeed get a slight strategical advantage with ...Nc6, ...Ne7-f5, and so on.   However, White players of the Tal Variation are well prepared, and will almost always play: }
9. c4
{ White instigates maximum chaos, by attacking the d5-pawn. Black has no choice but to grab material and hope it's enough compensation for the collapsing central pawn structure... }
9... Qxb2 10. Rd1
{ This is an interesting sideline that prevents Black from immediately grabbing in the centre since after: }
10... Qxd4 11. Qb3 Qxe5+ 12. Ne2
{ You'd think Black has survived the worst, and has successfully kept a three pawn advantage? But White's initiative is not over yet! }
12... b6 { After saving our b7-pawn, White continues with: } 13. Nf3 Qc7 14.
cxd5
{ Black's centre falls apart, and since Black is so poorly developed with their king stranded on e8, Black is complete toast here! }
