[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Advance Variation Tal #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 e6 7. Bg5 Qb6 8. Nd2
c5 9. c4 Qxb2 10. Rb1 { Another critical try. } 10... Qxd4 11. Qe2
{ White keeps the queens on! A smart idea given Black's king is stuck in the centre of the board. }
11... b6
{ Necessary to prevent White from entering into Black's territory after Rxb7. }
12. Ngf3
{ This position is evaluated as 0.00 — but in fact, Black is one wrong move away from being completely lost.   In general, if a position is zeros, the side with the initiative and development is to be more favoured than the side with material, since it's much harder to find a perfect defence than natural attacking moves! Thankfully, in the Caro-Kann Reversed, our opponents won't even come close to having this level of counterplay for the lost material.   Let's take a look at how this Tal Variation fares with the reverse colours! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Advance Variation Tal: 10...Rb8?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 e4
{ Although the engine assesses the position as equal, we can be very happy to meet the Caro-Kann Advance Variation a tempo up for us.   Firstly, our opponent will not have concrete theory to rely on. Secondly, the sharper the position, the greater the 'extra tempo' will be felt in our favour! Just like in a standard Caro-Kann, our first goal is to solve the development of our dark-squared bishop, before locking up the pawn chain with e3. Therefore, we should play: }
3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 h5
{ Here Black enters the Tal Variation, but a tempo down for them. } 5. h4
{ This is the first rule to remember in the Advance Variation: always meet h5 with h4! By doing this, we successfully prevent black from gaining too much space on the kingside with ...g5. }
5... Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. c4
{ A tempo down, White would only be playing e3 at this point, but instead, we can already strike the center with c4! }
7... Bg4
{ If Black insists on playing the mainline Tal Variation a tempo down, we can punish them deservingly! In principle, the side a tempo down should avoid critical sharp lines, since the extra tempo can make all the difference to the evaluation of the position! }
8. Qb3 Nd7
{ Black is intending to play as in the mainline Tal Variation, with ...c5 next. We should use our extra tempo to simply develop! }
9. Nc3 c5 10. Qxb7
{ In the standard Tal Variation, this is the critical test, and our opponent gets a lot of initiative for the lost material.   In our case, we will simply be much better, and Black has nothing to show for their material deficit. }
10... Rb8 11. Qxd5 Qe7 12. Qxe4
{ Since our knight is already developed to Nc3 @@StartBracket@@compared to the standard Tal Variation@@EndBracket@@, Qxe4 is now possible! If White can trade queens, there will be no compensation for Black for being two pawns down! }
12... Rxb2
{ 12...Be6?!  Forcefully avoiding the queen trade doesn't end well after:  13.d5!   12...cxd4?!  Lots of moves are working here, but I like:  13.Qxd4!  The queens stay on, but our queen stands well on d4, and we have very easy development to follow:  13...Rxb2  14.Be2  Ngf6  15.Nf3  O-O  16.O-O  Rfb8  17.Rab1  With two pawns up, we have great chances to convert this endgame. }
13. Qxe7+ Nxe7 14. Be2
{ Black's initiative will evaporate without queens, and since we are approaching an endgame, we are much better with the two pawns up. }
