[Black "Advance Variation Tal: 10...Rd8?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 e4
{ Although the engine assesses the position as equal, we can be very happy to meet the Caro-Kann Advance a tempo up for us.   Firstly, our opponent will not have concrete theory to rely on. Secondly, the sharper the position, the greater the 'extra tempo' will be felt in our favour! Just like in a standard Caro-Kann, our first goal is to solve the development of our dark squared bishop, before locking up the pawn chain with e3. Therefore, we should play: }
3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 h5
{ Here Black enters the Tal Variation, but a tempo down for them. } 5. h4
{ This is the first rule to remember in the Advance Variation: always meet h5 with h4! By doing this, we successfully prevent Black from gaining too much space on the kingside with ...g5. }
5... Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. c4
{ A tempo down, White would only be playing 'e3' at this point, but instead, we can already strike the centre with c4! }
7... Bg4
{ If Black insists on playing the mainline Tal Variation a tempo down, we can punish them deservingly! In principle, the side a tempo down should avoid critical sharp lines, since the extra tempo can make all the difference to the evaluation of the position! }
8. Qb3 Nd7
{ Black is intending to play as in the mainline Tal Variation, with ...c5 next. We should use our extra tempo to simply develop! }
9. Nc3 c5 10. Qxb7
{ In the standard Tal Variation, this is the critical test, and our opponent gets a lot of initiative for the lost material. In our case, we will simply be much better, and Black has nothing to show for their material deficit. }
10... Rd8 11. Qxd5 Qb6 12. Qxe4+ Ne7 13. Qxe7+
{ With the extra tempo of Nc3 in the position, Black does not get to keep their initiative, and in fact White takes over with this beautiful queen sacrifice! Don't worry, we're not doing some crazy attacking queen sacrifice, we're simply regaining the queen straight after, and simplifying into a winning endgame.   For the record, if you forget the queen sacrifice, there's 4 other moves that are completely winning, so no problem, really! }
13... Kxe7 14. Nd5+ Kd6 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. Ne2
{ White is up 3 pawns, and with no queens on the board, the position is winning for White. }
