[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Advance Variation Tal: Early 4...g5?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 e4
{ Although the engine assesses the position as equal, we can be very happy to meet the Caro-Kann Advance a tempo up for us.   Firstly, our opponent will not have concrete theory to rely on. Secondly, the sharper the position, the greater the 'extra tempo' will be felt in our favour! Just like in a standard Caro-Kann, our first goal is to solve the development of our dark squared bishop, before locking up the pawn chain with e3. Therefore, we should play: }
3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 g5 5. Be5 f6 6. Bg3 h5
{ So long as we always remember to meet ...h5 with h4, we'll be doing great here! }
7. h4 g4
{ Black's unprincipled pawn play has gained nothing, and simply leaves holes for our pieces to use.   Here, Ne2-f4 leads to a beautiful game for us, where we have no issues on the kingside, and can eventually push c4 with play on the queenside and against the weak d5-pawn. }
