[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 e4
{ Although the engine assesses the position as equal, we can be very happy to meet the Caro-Kann Advance a tempo up for us.   Firstly, our opponent will not have concrete theory to rely on. Secondly, the sharper the position, the greater the 'extra tempo' will be felt in our favour! Just like in a standard Caro-Kann, our first goal is to solve the development of our dark-squared bishop, before locking up the pawn chain with e3. Therefore, we should play: }
3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 h5
{ Here Black enters the Tal Variation, but a tempo down for them. } 5. h4
{ This is the first rule to remember in the Advance Variation: always meet h5 with h4! By doing this, we successfully prevent Black from gaining too much space on the kingside with ...g5. }
5... c5
{ This annoying 'early c4' line of the Caro-Kann is no longer that strong. We can meet it with the immediate: }
6. c4
{ In a standard Caro-Kann, Black has to meet c4 with ...e6. But with the extra tempo, we can already strike the centre, since our d4-pawn is protected by e3 already! }
6... cxd4
{ This is Black's best response. I contemplated whether to provide lots of analysis of different 6th move alternatives for Black here, but I felt this would cloud our memory of the more frequent and more important lines!   So aside from 6...cxd4 and  6...dxc4  @@StartBracket@@that I've analysed@@EndBracket@@, I'd recommend you only investigate other lines that Black can try after facing them in training games online.  You'll probably be able to play against them intuitively without my guidance!   6...dxc4?!  allows White to get a great initiative after  7.Bxc4  cxd4  8.Qb3! }
7. Qxd4 { We are threatening to win the d5-pawn, so Black must defend: } 7...
Nf6 8. Bxb8
{ I like the idea behind this move! By removing the knight from b8, our queen is much more likely to stay standing on the strong, central d4-square! }
8... Rxb8 9. Nc3 Be6
{ If Black tries too hard to defend the d5-pawn, the position can easily collapse. }
10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bb5+
{ Although 9...Be6 was by no means forced, we see that after 6...cxd4, it is us who has the front foot, putting the pressure on Black. }
