[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Advance Variation Tal: 7...c6 (Passive, but Correct)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 e4
{ Although the engine assesses the position as equal, we can be very happy to meet the Caro-Kann Advance a tempo up for us.   Firstly, our opponent will not have concrete theory to rely on. Secondly, the sharper the position, the greater the 'extra tempo' will be felt in our favour! Just like in a standard Caro-Kann, our first goal is to solve the development of our dark squared bishop, before locking up the pawn chain with e3. Therefore, we should play: }
3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 h5
{ Here Black enters the Tal Variation, but a tempo down for them. } 5. h4
{ This is the first rule to remember in the Advance Variation: always meet h5 with h4! By doing this, we successfully prevent Black from gaining too much space on the kingside with ...g5. }
5... Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. c4
{ A tempo down, White would only be playing 'e3' at this point, but instead, we can already strike the center with c4! }
7... c6
{ Black's best option is to play passively with ...c6, but now we have a strategically fantastic position!   Not only have we gotten rid of our 'bad bishop', we have also eliminated their best bishop that would normally cause us a great deal of suffering when executing a successful kingside attack. Here, they will have no such hopes! }
8. Nc3
{ I would suggest that you focus on developing your pieces towards targeting the d5-pawn. If d5 collapses, then e4 will collapse too! }
8... Nf6 9. Nge2
{ Temporarily blocking the bishop's development, but our plan is to move to f4 next, pressuring d5, and allowing for the bishop to develop next! }
9... O-O
{ 9...dxc4  10.Ng3!  It should be noted that the knight doesn't have to develop to f4, and can develop to g3 if it's more useful here! }
10. Nf4
{ 10.cxd5?!  Although objectively fine, I found that there's a trick Black can play for if we're unaware:  10...cxd5  11.Nf4  Nc6  12.Qb3?  Nxd4!  Typically, this trick would not be working with our 'bad bishop' on c1, x-ray defending our knight on f4.   So we should pay attention to detail! That's why, I prefer to avoid 10. cxd5, until the black knight from b8 has committed to d7. }
10... Bg4 11. Qb3 { Black will struggle to defend both the pawn on b7 and d5. }
11... Nbd7
{ 11...dxc4  12.Bxc4  Engine suggests Black can hang on here, but White is definitely to be preferred. After getting our king safe, we can continue operations on the queenside, even making use of a minority attack @@StartBracket@@which we will come to in much greater detail by the end of our study on the Caro-Kann Reversed!@@EndBracket@@ }
12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nfxd5
{ This is the most typical result from the variation starting 7...c6. We develop with purpose, and are rewarded for our play against the d5-pawn! }
