[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Advance Variation Short #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ We face the Advance Variation again! Do you remember what Black's first priority is in this position? }
3... Bf5
{ We must solve the development of our light-squared bishop at all costs! } 4.
Nf3
{ The Short Variation.   White chooses to develop their pieces, before chasing after our bishop! }
4... e6 5. Be2 c5
{ This is the old mainline, but nowadays is avoided due to the incredible lengths of theory here! However, to best understand the Short Variation, we should start by examining this line: }
6. Be3 { The only move for advantage! } 6... Qb6
{ At first glance, it looks like Black has a great French Defence with the light-squared bishop developed outside of the pawn chain. With an extra tempo, Black would indeed be doing great, but White can in fact play very actively to push for an advantage here! }
7. Nc3 { This move looks dodgy since Qxb2 would attack the hanging knight. }
7... Qxb2
{ At this moment, there are two main moves for White:  8.Qb1  and  8.Nb5  , both of which are strong. }
8. Qb1 Qxb1+ 9. Rxb1 b6
{ The only move to save the b-pawn.   You will see that Black is just one tempo too slow to deal with this incoming attack. Black can keep parrying all of White's threats, but only for four more moves before collapsing! }
10. Nb5 Kd7 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Nd6 Bxd6 13. exd6 Kxd6 14. Bf4+
{ White wins the knight on b8, thus having a much better position.   As we can see, Black was strategically doing very well in a lot of lines @@StartBracket@@healthier pawn structure, material up etc.@@EndBracket@@, but concretely, White has ways to punish Black, with very active play. Thankfully for us, in the Caro-Kann Reversed, none of these aggressive tries come close to working, while we keep the strategical benefits of our Caro-Kann setup! }
