[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Advance Variation Short #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 c5 6. Be3 Qb6 7. Nc3 Qxb2 8. Nb5
c4
{ The only move to play for equality! We have a very complicated position in front of us.   In Short @@StartBracket@@pardon the pun!@@EndBracket@@, White cannot immediately capture the rook on a8 with  9.Nc7+?  ,  since the knight will get trapped, and Black will have full compensation.   However, with the precise  9.Rb1+!  ,  White is able to win the rook, AND recover the knight with a better position!   9.Nc7+?  Kd7  10.Nxa8  Bb4+!  11.Nd2  Bxc2  12.Qc1  Qxc1  13.Rxc1  Bg6  -/+ With ...Ne7 and ...Nc6 to follow, Black will be able to capture the trapped knight on a8, with a better position. }
9. Rb1 Qxa2 10. Nc7+ Kd7 11. Nxa8
{ Black is unable to continue with  11...Bb4+  @@StartBracket@@since the bishop would now be hanging@@EndBracket@@, and if Black tries to continue the tactics... }
11... Bxc2 12. Rxb7+ Kc8 13. Rc7+
{ For the record, we will reach a very similar position to this in our colours reversed setup — and you will see why we are completely winning if we have an extra tempo! }
13... Kd8 14. Qd2
{ White's knight survives in the corner, and manages to help secure a huge material lead for White — a rook for two pawns up!  Now let's head to the Caro-Kann Reversed, and understand how a single tempo can make a huge difference! }
