[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Caro-Kann Reversed: Advance Variation (Tal + Short)"]
[Black "Advance Variation Short: 8...Qb8?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 e4
{ Although the engine assesses the position as equal, we can be very happy to meet the Caro-Kann Advance Variation a tempo up for us.   Firstly, our opponent will not have concrete theory to rely on. Secondly, the sharper the position, the greater the 'extra tempo' will be felt in our favour! Just like in a standard Caro-Kann, our first goal is to solve the development of our dark-squared bishop, before locking up the pawn chain with e3. Therefore, we should play: }
3. Bf4 { ...a successful development of our dark-squared bishop! } 3... d5 4.
e3 Nf6 { Here we have the Short Variation, but a tempo up for us! } 5. c4
{ We should not be afraid to play the most principled old mainline for White, since White is a tempo up! }
5... Be7 6. Nc3 Be6
{ If Black has made it this far, it is likely that they play the Short Variation with the White pieces against a standard Caro-Kann, and will follow their 'theory' with ...Be6. This, however, is very naive, since even one tempo extra in a sharp variation can make all the difference — as it does here! The real issue for Black in the position just before 6...Be6, is that they have no good alternatives.   The best attempt at this stage is to find equality in  6...c6  ,  but White will have all the play. We have a French Defence Advance Variation where the 'bad bishop' is outside of the pawn chain, so we are simply doing great. White will continue to add pressure to Black's d5-pawn with moves like Qb3, and perhaps Ne2-f4, and eventually, play down the c-file with our rooks. }
7. Qb3
{ Black's position is already worse, but let's see what happens if Black tries to play in the same way as in the standard Caro-Kann Short Variation: }
7... Nc6 8. Qxb7
{ Do you remember what our opponent's critical tries were in this position?   In fact, both of them are now dubious, given we have the extra tempo in this sharp position! }
8... Qb8 9. Qxb8+ Rxb8 10. O-O-O
{ A huge improvement over the lines involving b3 @@StartBracket@@or technically ...b6, in a standard Caro-Kann@@EndBracket@@!   We stay a pawn up, and there is no way for Black to continue the attack. }
10... Nb4 11. c5
{ With the extra control over the d3-square @@StartBracket@@now the rook, as well as our bishop@@EndBracket@@, Black has no Nd3 ideas.   Next we will play a3 to kick away the knight, and we have a great position! A pawn up, our bishop outside of the pawn chain, and no weaknesses — what more can we ask for? }
