{ We should not be afraid to play the most principled old mainline for White, since White is a tempo up! }
5... Be7 6. Nc3 Be6
{ If Black has made it this far, it is likely that they play the Short Variation with the White pieces against a standard Caro-Kann, and will follow their 'theory' with ...Be6. This, however, is very naive, since even one tempo extra in a sharp variation can make all the difference — as it does here! The real issue for Black in the position just before 6...Be6, is that they have no good alternatives.   The best attempt at this stage is to find equality in  6...c6  ,  but White will have all the play. We have a French Defence Advance Variation where the 'bad bishop' is outside of the pawn chain, so we are simply doing great. White will continue to add pressure to Black's d5-pawn with moves like Qb3, and perhaps Ne2-f4, and eventually, play down the c-file with our rooks. }
7. Qb3
{ Black's position is already worse, but let's see what happens if Black tries to play in the same way as in the standard Caro-Kann Short Variation: }
7... Nc6 8. Qxb7
{ Do you remember what our opponent's critical tries were in this position?   In fact, both of them are now dubious, given we have the extra tempo in this sharp position! }
8... Na5
{ The fact that this is the best move shows how desperate Black's position is!   Just like in the standard Caro-Kann, this move gives us a pleasant edge after: }
9. Qxc7 Qxc7 10. Bxc7 Nxc4 11. Bxc4 dxc4 12. Nge2
{ We are a clean pawn up and have the healthier pawn structure. This more than compensates for our loss of the bishop pair.  ...and that concludes our analysis of the Short Variation, and the Advance Variation overall! I'd like to point you in the direction of this Model Game, which covers how a typical, non-theoretical, game of the Advance Variation can go. In short  (pardon the pun!)  , Black's overextended structure gets punished, as it often does in the Caro-Kann Reversed Structures! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Caro-Kann Reversed: (Bad) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Fantasy Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3
{ For the Caro-Kann player, the Fantasy Variation is quite a challenge to meet!   If we remember, the first principle in the Caro-Kann is to solve the issue of the development of our light-squared bishop. Here, White has setup with f3 and e4, taking control of both g4- and f5-squares that our light-squared bishop would otherwise like to develop to.   The main move here is  3...e6  ,  whereby Black immediately accepts defeat with regards to developing their light-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain.   The old mainline with  3...dxe4  does solve their bishop's development, however, it can get very sharp after: }
3... dxe4 4. fxe4 e5 { The only move... } 5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black solves the development of their light-squared bishop, but the resulting play is not easy to navigate!   Do note that White cannot pull off a good Fantasy Variation with the reverse colours, so you don't have to worry so much about the following variations! }
6. Bc4 Nd7 { Again, an only move... } 7. c3 Bd6
{ 7...Ngf6?  The only move against 7. O-O, but against 7. c3, this is in fact a mistake!   This just illustrates how careful you have to be to play the most critical Caro-Kann lines for Black.  8.Qb3!  Bh5  9.Ng5!  +/- }
8. Qb3 Qe7 9. Qxb7 Rb8 10. Qxc6
{ Black has survived and can equalise with perfect play, but one second rate move here, and Black will be lost! White is two pawns up, and has the easier play with a huge target on f7 — I wouldn't fancy playing this position unless we're willing to commit another 5-10 moves to memory!   But don't worry, the Fantasy Variation is seriously non-existent in our Caro-Kann Reversed positions. Before checking this out, let's take a look first at an early deviation in the Fantasy Variation — leading to positions similar to a Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Caro-Kann Reversed: (Bad) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Blackmar-Diemer Style Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 dxe4 4. Nc3
{ This idea is similar to a Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. The line is pretty bad, but there is one trick that Black should be aware of: }
4... exf3 5. Nxf3 Bf5 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Ng5
{ It looks like Black has achieved everything they could ever want, but here comes the trick!   As soon as Ng5 is played, Black MUST play ...Bg6, in order to avoid White sacrificing their rook with a serious attack! }
8... Bg6
{ White has no attack and is simply a pawn down  8...Be7??  9.Rxf5!  exf5  10.Nxf7  +- Both 10. Nxf7 and  10.Bxf7  are completely winning.   In the Caro-Kann Reversed, we will need to remember this rule as well! }
