[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Caro-Kann Reversed: (Bad) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Fantasy Variation: 3...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 f6
{ This Fantasy Variation @@StartBracket@@a tempo down for Black@@EndBracket@@ looks seriously dodgy, and it is! Without ...d5 played, White can simply take the full centre with: }
3. e4
{ White is already much better, since ...f6 just weakens the king, and prevents Black from developing their knight to the natural ...f6-square. I could stop here — but we'll analyse some of the most logical tries from Black: }
3... d5
{ This is the only move that somewhat works here. But we can also very easily gain a clear advantage after: }
4. dxe5 { Our simplest path to advantage. } 4... fxe5
{ 4...dxe4  This is a better try, but White still gets a clear edge after:  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Nd2  +/= I've decided to leave the line here since Black has multiple reasonable looking moves, all of which are bad!   I wouldn't commit these additional lines to memory, but you're welcome to investigate this position further to see how White punishes Black here! But even without further investigation, should this position ever arise, you should feel confident enough in your basic chess opening principles and understanding to gain at least a slight advantage! }
5. Qh5+
{ This is exactly why ...f6 is a terrible move in the opening. Here we get that classic attacking motif we learn as a beginner to pick up the rook in the corner after: }
5... g6 6. Qxe5+ Ne7 7. Qxh8
{ White is a whole rook up and Black can resign already. } *

