[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Caro-Kann Reversed: (Bad) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Style Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 d5
{ While we're in the realms of ...f6, it makes sense to cover the Blackmar-Diemer Style Gambit. As mentioned in the standard Caro-Kann lines, there is pretty much one trick Black can play for, and we just need to be aware of it! Once we avoid the trick, White is simply much better, a clean pawn up. }
3. dxe5 f6 4. exf6 Nxf6 5. Bf4
{ We should always take the opportunity to develop our bishop to f4 when possible. This neutralises a potential attacking threat of ...Bd6, and now we're ready to secure our pawn structure with e3. }
5... Bc5 6. e3 O-O 7. Nf3 Ng4
{ Here comes the trick! At first glance, this looks completely harmless, but if White is naive and develops Be2, they will be hit by a nasty rook sacrifice surprise!  Instead, as soon as ...Ng4 is played, White should drop the dark-squared bishop back to g3, to avoid any rook sacrifices, and secure f2. In principle, if Black tries a quick attack on us, we should take the time to consolidate to ensure they don't get any counterplay. }
8. Bg3
{ Black has no attack. Ever. And White is simply a clean pawn up!   8.Be2??  Rxf4  9.exf4  Nxf2!  -+ Both 9...Nxf2 and 9...Bxf2 are winning — so seriously watch out for this trap! }
