[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Caro-Kann Reversed: 2…d6 Variation"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: 2.d3 Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3
{ 2.Nf3  d5  3.d3  The 2. d3 line can also be reached with this move order, but since 2. Nf6 isn't possible in our reverse setup, we will simply look at the variation starting with 2. d3! }
2... d5 3. Nf3
{ This line has become increasingly trendy for White, due to two interesting paths the game can take, both taking Black out of a typical Caro-Kann!   Before we see these lines, let's understand why this position is tricky for Black: Firstly, Black would love to develop their light-squared bishop to f5, but as we can see, even after  3...dxe4  ,  White maintains control over the f5-square with  4.dxe4  .   As a result, if I were to play the Caro-Kann again, I'd probably research into making  3...Bg4  work @@StartBracket@@which isn't quite engine approved, but at least meets the principles of the opening@@EndBracket@@. Instead,  3...dxe4  is in fact the most popular move, with the idea that after  4.dxe4  ,  Black would like to enter an endgame after  4...Qxd1  5.Kxd1  .   At first glance, this looks great for Black, since White gives up castling rights. However, there is a lot of theory here, and White is more than okay @@StartBracket@@and can actually play for an advantage if they know the correct development plan for their pieces!@@EndBracket@@ In addition to this annoying endgame line for Black, the other trendy idea after  3...dxe4  here is  4.Ng5!?  . Here, there is a very sneaky trap, which has even caught players out OTB @@StartBracket@@over-the-board@@EndBracket@@! I will provide the variation below for your interest @@StartBracket@@although we won't have to worry about any such gambits in the Caro-Kann Reversed@@EndBracket@@.   3.Nd2  More traditionally, Nd2 has been played instead of Nf3, with ambitions to play for a King's Indian Attack with g3 / Bg2.   If our opponents are to try this 2. d3 setup against the Caro-Kann Reversed, they will be forced to play in this way!   We will investigate these positions in greater depth in our Reversed setup. }
3... dxe4 4. Ng5 exd3 5. Bxd3 Nf6
{ The most natural developing move in the position is in fact a blunder! } 6.
Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Bg6+
{ Black is dead lost. Black's queen will be captured next, and their king is stranded in the open. When playing the Caro-Kann, these are the kind of variations you need to be aware of, in order to keep your head above water.   Thankfully for us in the Caro-Kann Reversed, these 2. d3 / 3. Nf3 gambit lines are simply non-existent, and we can sidestep this headache altogether! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Caro-Kann Reversed: 2…d6 Variation"]
[Black "2.d3 Line: 4...g6 (with ...Nbd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 d6
{ So how does this variation compare to 2. d3, a tempo down for Black?   In some ways, Black poses the same issues to us. Typically, we are looking to develop our bishop to f4, outside of our pawn chain, before locking up the pawn structure with e3. However, here Black strongholds the e5-pawn, thus preventing all hopes of an eventual Bf4! Normally, in a colours reverse situation, this same position would be reached with a knight on f3 @@StartBracket@@or in our case, ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@.  In this scenario where Black has an extra tempo, we would have to be ready to enter an endgame with 3.dxe5 dxe5 4.Qxd8 Kxd8  @@StartBracket@@or meet a hyper aggressive 3.dxe5 Ng4!?@@EndBracket@@.   Thankfully, however, as you can see in the Caro-Kann Reversed, we do not have to struggle with such lines, and can instead play e4! — taking the full centre before Black has a chance to prevent us doing so with ...Nf6! }
3. e4
{ 3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  Kxd8  = This is the Caro-Kann endgame line, without Black's knight on f6.   In fact, since the queens have been traded, and the pace of the position has slowed down, the fact that Black hasn't developed with ...Nf6 doesn't make much difference to the overall evaluation. Without queens, we cannot capitalise on Black's weakened king position, and thus the position is equal at best. }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3 { Developing, and defending e4. } 4... g6
{ This is the most likely development plan for Black — to play a Pirc/King's Indian type setup.   4...Nbd7  5.Nf3  g6  transposes to our mainline with 4...g6. }
5. Nf3 { Putting immediate pressure on e5! } 5... Nbd7
{ 5...Bg7?!  Black does not address the problem of their ...e5-pawn, so we should capitalise on this!  6.dxe5!  dxe5  7.Nxe5  O-O  Since the centre has opened up, we should be quick to castle our king.  8.O-O  Re8  9.f4!  +/- We keep the extra pawn! }
6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1 O-O 8. a4 a5 9. Na3
{ I like this development plan for White.   Our minor pieces don't get in each other's way, and our knight can come to c4 soon to add more pressure on e5. As a general plan,   1@@EndBracket@@ Add more pressure to e5,   2@@EndBracket@@ Make sure e4 is well defended,   3@@EndBracket@@ Since we have more space, Black will find it more difficult to maneuver, so when they inevitably create a weakness, capitalise on it!   If you would like to investigate the resulting plans and ideas further, I would recommend you check out the Model Game between Ljubojevic vs Delemarre. The colours are reversed, but the plans and ideas of this position are the same! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Caro-Kann Reversed: 2…d6 Variation"]
[Black "2.d3 Line: 4...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 d6
{ So how does this variation compare to 2. d3, a tempo down for Black?   In some ways, Black poses the same issues to us. Typically, we are looking to develop our bishop to f4, outside of our pawn chain, before locking up the pawn structure with e3. However, here Black strongholds the e5-pawn, thus preventing all hopes of an eventual Bf4! Normally, in a colours reverse situation, this same position would be reached with a knight on f3 @@StartBracket@@or in our case, ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@.  In this scenario where Black has an extra tempo, we would have to be ready to enter an endgame with 3.dxe5 dxe5 4.Qxd8 Kxd8  @@StartBracket@@or meet a hyper aggressive 3.dxe5 Ng4!?@@EndBracket@@.   Thankfully, however, as you can see in the Caro-Kann Reversed, we do not have to struggle with such lines, and can instead play e4! — taking the full centre before Black has a chance to prevent us doing so with ...Nf6 ! }
3. e4
{ 3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  Kxd8  = This is the Caro-Kann endgame line, without Black's knight on f6.   In fact, since the queen's have been traded, and the pace of the position has slowed down, the fact that Black hasn't developed with ...Nf6 doesn't make much difference to the overall evaluation. Without queen's, we cannot capitalise on Black's weakened king position, and thus the position is equal at best. }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3 { Developing, and defending e4. } 4... Nc6
{ This is Black's alternative to  4...g6  ,  aiming to attack our centre before we can attack theirs.   As a result, we should defend the threat to d4 and develop at the same time }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black tries to reintroduce pressure on d4 by pinning our knight.   Since we cannot support our pawn again, I advise to push it! }
6. d5
{ In all honesty, I was hoping not to have to cover structures involving this d5 push, but we don't have much choice if we want to keep the advantage! But in fact, the more I looked at this position, the more I realised why we should actually be quite happy here.   Let's take a look!  6.Be3  d5!  = This becomes very messy — both sides have equal development, so it will be an equal fight in the centre. }
6... Ne7
{ Firstly, this d5 push is particularly strong when Black cannot bring their knight from d7 to c5.   The only way that would be possible is to retreat  6...Nb8  , but this is far too slow. }
7. h3
{ This is the key idea. If the bishop trades, Black will have NO attack on the kingside. And otherwise, Black has to lose a tempo retreating...  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  +/- With more space on the queenside, we will simply push c4, b4, and eventually c5. If Black has no attack on the kingside @@StartBracket@@due to the light-squared bishop trading@@EndBracket@@, Black will simply get crushed on the queenside.   7...Bh5  The black bishop is now on the wrong diagonal, not pressuring White's kingside. Again, we are completely fine here!  8.Be3  +/- As in the other lines, White will play on the queenside by simply grabbing space with c4 b4 Nc3 etc. }
7... Bc8 8. Be3
{ We have are a gazilion tempo up compared to a King's Indian, so even if we are not precise with our queenside play, we should be able to get an advantage fairly easily by pushing c4 b4 Nc3 c5 etc. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Caro-Kann Reversed: Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Exchange Variation "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5
{ And finally, we come to White's last option — The Caro-Kann Exchange.   Exchange variations @@StartBracket@@namely, the French Exchange@@EndBracket@@ have reputations of being very static and boring, since they can often lead to symmetrical positions. Here, there is no symmetry, since White has a c-pawn, while Black has an e-pawn. As a result, White tends to use the extra space on the kingside to attack that side, while Black uses their two pawns on the queenside to disrupt White's three pawns on the queenside, to induce a weakness, and establish a positional advantage.   This plan of pushing Black's queenside pawns forward is called the Minority Attack @@StartBracket@@more on this later!@@EndBracket@@. At first glance, it appears that Black's position here is completely harmless. Black can complete their development with ...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@since there is no black pawn blocking the square@@EndBracket@@, and the f5-square is free for our light-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@LSB@@EndBracket@@ — what more could we ask for? However, if White is well prepared @@StartBracket@@which most 1. e4 players certainly are!@@EndBracket@@, Black can immediately face difficulties in both the mainline Exchange Variation, as well as the Panov Attack. }
4. Bd3
{ This is the mainline Exchange Variation. White immediately prevents us from developing our bishop to f5, which means we will need to solve this development problem before we can play ...e6 to lock up the pawn chain, and stabilise our centre.   In addition, the bishop on d3 is perfectly placed to create attacking opportunities on the kingside when Black castles short. }
4... Nc6 { White needs to defend their pawn on d4 now: } 5. c3 Nf6
{ Black's idea is control the g4-square to allow for the development of their LSB. }
6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3
{ Black completes the development of their LSB, but at what cost? White has been given the time to ideally place their bishops, and Black immediately has problems to solve on the queenside.   Also, Black wanted to play for a Minority Attack, but struggles to do so while Bf4 controls the b8-square @@StartBracket@@where the rook on a8 belongs to help push ...b5@@EndBracket@@.   The theory continues, but I won't cover it here since it won't be relevant to our reverse system. We won't have anywhere near as many issues to solve, and our plan with the Minority Attack will be much easier to achieve. Now before we look at our exact theory, let's first take a look at the basics behind a Minority Attack! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Caro-Kann Reversed: Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Standard Caro-Kann: Panov Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4
{ The starting move of the Panov Attack! This is one of White's most critical tries against the Caro-Kann, since Black's centre is immediately attacked before Black has had time to develop all their pieces to harmonious squares. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3
{ There are multiple ways to face the Panov Attack, but the mainline @@StartBracket@@and most principled move@@EndBracket@@ is to continue with ...Bg4. }
6... Bg4 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3
{ At this moment, there is a long theoretical line, where Black is hanging on a tight-rope, and needs to remember their theory perfectly, not to accidentally blunder something and lose!   Let's check it out: }
8... Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6 10. Qxb7 Nxd4 11. Bb5+ Nxb5 12. Qc6+ Ke7 13. Qxb5 Qd7 14.
Nxd5+ Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5
{ This is the start of the 'Panov Endgame Line', where the theory continues much further! However, White has many practical ways to push for an advantage, and Black has to have really deep understanding of the position in order to hold for a draw.   Thankfully for us, we will be deviating much earlier in our Reverse Panov Attack, to reach positions that are much more comfortable that lead to a simple edge. You will see this soon! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Caro-Kann Reversed: Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Panov Attack: 5...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ The most frequently played answer to the Caro-Kann Reversed.   Principally, it makes sense to avoid a sharp battle since Black is playing against a reverse system, a tempo down. However, a downside for Black is that they will be tricked into entering a Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ Exchange Variation, with little hope to play for a win!   Of all the Caro-Kann Reversed set-ups, this is the only line to venture into known theoretical territory. However, there are still very good chances that our opponent will be unsuspecting to the ideas for Black, since playing 1...e5 is as different to a QGD as one can imagine! And if our opponent HAS worked out that 1...e5 is a clever way to reach a QGD Exchange, then for sure Black will have had to spend at least 5 minutes at the start of the game in order to reach this conclusion, giving us a nice time advantage on the clock.   So all in all, I believe this is still a great practical weapon for us! }
3. cxd4 d5
{ 3...Nf6  4.Nc3  d5  Black will most likely play ...d5 and transpose to our mainlines, so let's continue our analysis there. }
4. Nc3
{ Here Black reaches the same crossroad as in the Caro-Kann Exchange: do they play in the style of a standard Caro-Kann Exchange, or play for a Panov Attack @@StartBracket@@a tempo down@@EndBracket@@? Again, we see the benefits of having the extra tempo.   Here, if Black wants to play an Exchange, they cannot begin with ...Bd6, since this hangs the pawn on d5! And if Black plays ...c6 first, we are then in time to play Bf4! , to prevent Black establishing their bishop on this strong d6-square!   Alternatively, if Black plays a Panov, they will get nowhere near as much activity as in a standard Caro-Kann, and we will be the ones putting pressure on our opponent instead. Since the Panov Attack and the mainline Exchange are very different in nature, let's start by looking at the Panov Attack, before returning to our mainline. }
4... c5
{ The Reverse Panov @@StartBracket@@tempo down@@EndBracket@@ is in fact a direct transposition to the @@StartBracket@@less popular nowadays@@EndBracket@@ Tarrasch Defence.   The nature of this position is very different to a standard Panov Attack, since we will in fact be the ones to put pressure on Black's position first!   In a lot of the following variations, we will be aiming to win the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@that will never have any support from pawns on c6 or e6@@EndBracket@@.   With this in mind, it will be easier to remember the following sequences:  5.dxc5?!  It should be noted that we are not immediately winning the pawn on d5 due to our opponent playing  5...d4!  =+ under favourable circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ We should develop our knight first and see how black responds! We have good x-ray pressure on d5, so Black must be careful of dxc5, Qxd5 ideas already. }
5... Nc6 6. dxc5
{ Black cannot recapture with  6...Bxc5?  since  7.Qxd5!  just wins a pawn!   If Black continues with  6...Nf6  , we can hang onto our pawn with  7.Be3!  and develop our light-squared bishop with g3, Bg2 next. }
6... d4 { So, this is Black's only try. } 7. Na4
{ Our knight appears a little loose at first, but due to the c-pawn having been moved, our queen is protecting it — so no need to worry about ...Qa5+. }
7... Bxc5
{ Black's only try to avoid being down a pawn. At first glance, it appears like Black has blundered a piece. But of course, they win it back immediately after  8.Nxc5  Qa5+  . }
8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Qd2 { The simplest road to a slight advantage after: } 9...
Qxc5 10. e3 dxe3 11. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3
{ I really like this line since we have a really pleasant edge in the simplest of forms: the bishop pair in an open position, while the knights have zero outposts.   I remember when I was a chess junior, I attended a junior training camp in Latvia where we were instructed to play out positions like this. At first, I couldn't believe that the bishop pair would have any real significance here. But try it yourself against a friend, taking turns to be White.   You will notice that the tactics just fall into place, and that you'll have the much easier game! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Caro-Kann Reversed: Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Panov Attack: 5...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ The most frequently played answer to the Caro-Kann Reversed.   Principally, it makes sense to avoid a sharp battle since Black is playing against a reverse system, a tempo down. However, a downside for Black is that they will be tricked into entering a Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ Exchange Variation, with little hope to play for a win!   Of all the Caro-Kann Reversed set-ups, this is the only line to venture into known theoretical territory. However, there are still very good chances that our opponent will be unsuspecting to the ideas for Black, since playing 1...e5 is as different to a QGD as one can imagine! And if our opponent HAS worked out that 1...e5 is a clever way to reach a QGD Exchange, then for sure Black will have had to spend at least 5 minutes at the start of the game in order to reach this conclusion, giving us a nice time advantage on the clock.   So all in all, I believe this is still a great practical weapon for us! }
3. cxd4 d5
{ 3...Nf6  4.Nc3  d5  Black will most likely play ...d5 and transpose to our mainlines, so let's continue our analysis there. }
4. Nc3
{ Here Black reaches the same crossroad as in the Caro-Kann Exchange: do they play in the style of a standard Caro-Kann Exchange, or play for a Panov Attack @@StartBracket@@a tempo down@@EndBracket@@? Again, we see the benefits of having the extra tempo.   Here, if Black wants to play an Exchange, they cannot begin with ...Bd6, since this hangs the pawn on d5! And if Black plays ...c6 first, we are then in time to play Bf4! , to prevent Black establishing their bishop on this strong d6-square!   Alternatively, if Black plays a Panov, they will get nowhere near as much activity as in a standard Caro-Kann, and we will be the ones putting pressure on our opponent instead. Since the Panov Attack and the mainline Exchange are very different in nature, let's start by looking at the Panov Attack, before returning to our mainline. }
4... c5
{ The Reverse Panov @@StartBracket@@tempo down@@EndBracket@@ is in fact a direct transposition to the @@StartBracket@@less popular nowadays@@EndBracket@@ Tarrasch Defence.   The nature of this position is very different to a standard Panov Attack, since we will in fact be the ones to put pressure on Black's position first!   In a lot of the following variations, we will be aiming to win the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@that will never have any support from pawns on c6 or e6@@EndBracket@@.   With this in mind, it will be easier to remember the following sequences:  5.dxc5?!  It should be noted that we are not immediately winning the pawn on d5 due to our opponent playing  5...d4!  =+ under favourable circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ We should develop our knight first and see how black responds! We have good x-ray pressure on d5, so Black must be careful of dxc5, Qxd5 ideas already. }
5... Nc6 6. dxc5
{ Black cannot recapture with  6...Bxc5?  since  7.Qxd5!  just wins a pawn!   If Black continues with  6...Nf6  , we can hang onto our pawn with  7.Be3!  and develop our light squared bishop with g3, Bg2 next. }
6... d4 { So, this is Black's only try. } 7. Na4
{ Our knight appears a little loose at first, but due to the c-pawn having been moved, our queen is protecting it — so no need to worry about ...Qa5+. }
7... Nf6
{ If Black doesn't immediately recapture the c5-pawn with the Bxc5 tactic, then we can take over after: }
8. e3 dxe3 9. Qxd8+
{ Black has to choose between permanently weakening their king, or deactivating their knight! }
9... Nxd8 10. Bb5+
{ In an open position, developing with tempo is a great way to put the opponent on the back foot. }
10... Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. Bxe3 Nc6 13. O-O-O
{ The tension in the position has settled, and White stays a healthy pawn up! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Caro-Kann Reversed: Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Panov Attack: 5...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ The most frequently played answer to the Caro-Kann Reversed.   Principally, it makes sense to avoid a sharp battle since Black is playing against a reverse system, a tempo down. However, a downside for Black is that they will be tricked into entering a Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ Exchange Variation, with little hope to play for a win!   Of all the Caro-Kann Reversed set-ups, this is the only line to venture into known theoretical territory. However, there are still very good chances that our opponent will be unsuspecting to the ideas for Black, since playing 1...e5 is as different to a QGD as one can imagine! And if our opponent HAS worked out that 1...e5 is a clever way to reach a QGD Exchange, then for sure Black will have had to spend at least 5 minutes at the start of the game in order to reach this conclusion, giving us a nice time advantage on the clock.   So all in all, I believe this is still a great practical weapon for us! }
3. cxd4 d5
{ 3...Nf6  4.Nc3  d5  Black will most likely play ...d5 and transpose to our mainlines, so let's continue our analysis there. }
4. Nc3
{ Here Black reaches the same crossroad as in the Caro-Kann Exchange: do they play in the style of a standard Caro-Kann Exchange, or play for a Panov Attack @@StartBracket@@a tempo down@@EndBracket@@? Again, we see the benefits of having the extra tempo.   Here, if Black wants to play an Exchange, they cannot begin with ...Bd6, since this hangs the pawn on d5! And if Black plays ...c6 first, we are then in time to play Bf4! , to prevent Black establishing their bishop on this strong d6-square!   Alternatively, if Black plays a Panov, they will get nowhere near as much activity as in a standard Caro-Kann, and we will be the ones putting pressure on our opponent instead. Since the Panov Attack and the mainline Exchange are very different in nature, let's start by looking at the Panov Attack, before returning to our mainline. }
4... c5
{ The Reverse Panov @@StartBracket@@tempo down@@EndBracket@@ is in fact a direct transposition to the @@StartBracket@@less popular nowadays@@EndBracket@@ Tarrasch Defence.   The nature of this position is very different to a standard Panov Attack, since we will in fact be the ones to put pressure on Black's position first!   In a lot of the following variations, we will be aiming to win the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@that will never have any support from pawns on c6 or e6@@EndBracket@@.   With this in mind, it will be easier to remember the following sequences:  5.dxc5?!  It should be noted that we are not immediately winning the pawn on d5 due to our opponent playing  5...d4!  =+ under favourable circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ We should develop our knight first and see how black responds! We have good x-ray pressure on d5, so Black must be careful of dxc5, Qxd5 ideas already. }
5... Nf6
{ Here, Black defends d5, so  6.dxc5  no longer makes any sense @@StartBracket@@since we're not threatening Qxd5@@EndBracket@@. Instead, we should pin the black knight, so we renew some threats of dxc5, followed by winning the d5-pawn. }
6. Bg5
{ At this moment, the best move for Black is to support the d5-pawn with  6...Be6  . However, I've saved the extensive analysis of this position for the ADVANCED Material section, and instead, we will examine a very common inaccuracy here — ...Nc6! }
6... Nc6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ If  7...gxf6  Black is able to protect the d5-pawn, but will be left with a crippled pawn structure on the kingside. Since the c-pawn has been pushed to c5, Black won't find safety for their king on either side of the board in the open position. }
8. Nxd5 Qd8 9. dxc5 { The cleanest path to a simple advantage. } 9... Bxc5 10.
Rc1
{ This final move isn't essential, but it's a nice tempo gaining move on the bishop @@StartBracket@@while developing the rook@@EndBracket@@, and it ensures that the knight on d5 will have a supported home to return to on c3 if it should ever feel the need to have to retreat.   Of course, 6...Nc6?! is by no means forced, but it is a common mistake players make, so I felt like it would be good to cover it here! }
