{ Here Black reaches the same crossroad as in the Caro-Kann Exchange: do they play in the style of a standard Caro-Kann Exchange, or play for a Panov Attack @@StartBracket@@a tempo down@@EndBracket@@? Again, we see the benefits of having the extra tempo.   Here, if Black wants to play an Exchange, they cannot begin with ...Bd6, since this hangs the pawn on d5! And if Black plays ...c6 first, we are then in time to play Bf4! , to prevent Black establishing their bishop on this strong d6-square!   Alternatively, if Black plays a Panov, they will get nowhere near as much activity as in a standard Caro-Kann, and we will be the ones putting pressure on our opponent instead. Since the Panov Attack and the mainline Exchange are very different in nature, let's start by looking at the Panov Attack, before returning to our mainline. }
4... c6
{ 4...Nf6  Here, White can enter mainlines of the QGD Exchange with  5.Bg5  . However, I like to keep things simple with 5. Bf4,  which will transpose to our mainlines after  5.Bf4  c6  6.Qc2  etc.   4...Bd6?  aiming to prevent Bf4 fails immediately to  5.Nxd5!  .  This is why Black must defend their d5-pawn on move 4. }
5. Bf4
{ I like starting out with Bf4. We prevent Black from establishing their dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@DSB@@EndBracket@@ on the most active diagonal with ...Bd6.   Thinking as a Caro-Kann player, to achieve Bf4 would be a dream scenario, since this reduces most of the attacking possibility on our king @@StartBracket@@Black's main source of counterplay@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. Qc2
{ This appears to transpose to our mainline @@StartBracket@@and it would after ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@, however, Black has a clever way to develop instead with: }
7... Ne7 { Supporting the plan of ...Bf5! } 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3
{ 9...Qg6!?  Black aims to take advantage of our temporarily weakened kingside.   I doubt you will ever come across this move @@StartBracket@@since it is a novelty, and only possible in this exact move order@@EndBracket@@, but it is worth seeing the following tactical shot at least once:  10.Bxf5  Nxf5  11.Nxd5!?  with counterplay.   I was tempted to make this a trainable, but we are already deep in novel territory so it felt unnecessary. Feel free to explore the resulting position yourself if you'd like to understand the position better, but let's focus our efforts on understanding the typical positions we will reach from this Caro-Kann Exchange variation @@StartBracket@@e.g. a Minority Attack@@EndBracket@@, since we will need to make use of this knowledge far more often in our games. }
10. Qxd3 Nd7 11. Nf3 Nf6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfb1
{ We will address this position in MINORITY ATTACK #3. @@StartBracket@@As a reminder, please after finishing the main theory section, study the model games on the Minority Attack, before returning to the 'MINORITY ATTACK #1, #2, #3, and #4' positions@@EndBracket@@ }
