[Black "Exchange Variation: MINORITY ATTACK #4 (w/ ...g6 & ...Bf5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ The most frequently played answer to the Caro-Kann Reversed.   Principally, it makes sense to avoid a sharp battle since Black is playing against a reverse system, a tempo down. However, a downside for Black is that they will be tricked into entering a Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ Exchange Variation, with little hope to play for a win!   Of all the Caro-Kann Reversed setups, this is the only line to venture into known theoretical territory. However, there are still very good chances that our opponent will be unsuspecting to the ideas for Black, since playing 1...e5 is as different to a QGD as one can imagine! And if our opponent HAS worked out that 1...e5 is a clever way to reach a QGD Exchange, then for sure Black will have had to spend at least 5 minutes at the start of the game in order to reach this conclusion, giving us a nice time advantage on the clock.   So all in all, I believe this is still a great practical weapon for us! }
3. cxd4 d5
{ 3...Nf6  4.Nc3  d5  Black will most likely play ...d5 and transpose to our mainlines, so let's continue our analysis there. }
4. Nc3
{ Here Black reaches the same crossroad as in the Caro-Kann Exchange: do they play in the style of a standard Caro-Kann Exchange, or play for a Panov Attack @@StartBracket@@a tempo down@@EndBracket@@? Again, we see the benefits of having the extra tempo.   Here, if Black wants to play an Exchange, they cannot begin with ...Bd6, since this hangs the pawn on d5! And if Black plays ...c6 first, we are then in time to play Bf4! , to prevent Black establishing their bishop on this strong d6-square!   Alternatively, if Black plays a Panov, they will get nowhere near as much activity as in a standard Caro-Kann, and we will be the ones putting pressure on our opponent instead. Since the Panov Attack and the mainline Exchange are very different in nature, let's start by looking at the Panov Attack, before returning to our mainline. }
4... c6
{ 4...Nf6  Here, White can enter mainlines of the QGD Exchange with  5.Bg5  . However, I like to keep things simple with 5. Bf4,  which will transpose to our mainlines after  5.Bf4  c6  6.Qc2  etc.   4...Bd6?  aiming to prevent Bf4 fails immediately to  5.Nxd5!  .  This is why Black must defend their d5-pawn on move 4. }
5. Bf4
{ I like starting out with Bf4. We prevent Black from establishing their dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@DSB@@EndBracket@@ on the most active diagonal with ...Bd6.   Thinking as a Caro-Kann player, to achieve Bf4 would be a dream scenario, since this reduces most of the attacking possibility on our king @@StartBracket@@Black's main source of counterplay@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6
{ Despite being the most played move, I don't believe ...Nf6 addresses the nuances of this position!   By giving White another free tempo to develop, we can then prevent the natural development of Black's light squared bishop @@StartBracket@@LSB@@EndBracket@@ to the square f5! We can achieve this by playing: }
6. Qc2
{ Comparing this to the standard Caro-Kann Exchange Variation, we are in fact faster to post our pieces on the best squares to restrict Black from getting both ...Bd6 and ...Bf5.   Since we are in much better control over the position, I would like to recommend to play for the principled Minority Attack! }
6... g6
{ If not with  6...Bg4  ,  Black should aim to solve the problem of their light-squared bishop with the immediate 6...g6 and 7...Bf5. }
7. e3
{ We must play e3 when ...Bf5 is playable. This is in order to counter ...Bf5 with Bd3. }
7... Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Nf3 Nbd7 12. O-O O-O 13.
Rfb1
{ This is in fact the same resulting position as 'MINORITY ATTACK #4', but with the black pawn on g6.   The plans and ideas will be the same for us! @@StartBracket@@As a reminder, please after finishing the main theory section, study the model games on the Minority Attack, before returning to the 'MINORITY ATTACK #1, #2, #3, and #4' positions@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Caro-Kann Reversed: Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 5...Qb6!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ The most frequently played answer to the Caro-Kann Reversed.   Principally, it makes sense to avoid a sharp battle since Black is playing against a reverse system, a tempo down. However, a downside for Black is that they will be tricked into entering a Queen's Gambit Declined @@StartBracket@@QGD@@EndBracket@@ Exchange Variation, with little hope to play for a win!   Of all the Caro-Kann Reversed setups, this is the only line to venture into known theoretical territory. However, there are still very good chances that our opponent will be unsuspecting to the ideas for Black, since playing 1...e5 is as different to a QGD as one can imagine! And if our opponent HAS worked out that 1...e5 is a clever way to reach a QGD Exchange, then for sure Black will have had to spend at least 5 minutes at the start of the game in order to reach this conclusion, giving us a nice time advantage on the clock.   So all in all, I believe this is still a great practical weapon for us! }
3. cxd4 d5
{ 3...Nf6  4.Nc3  d5  Black will most likely play ...d5 and transpose to our mainlines, so let's continue our analysis there. }
4. Nc3
{ Here Black reaches the same crossroad as in the Caro-Kann Exchange: do they play in the style of a standard Caro-Kann Exchange, or play for a Panov Attack @@StartBracket@@a tempo down@@EndBracket@@? Again, we see the benefits of having the extra tempo.   Here, if Black wants to play an Exchange, they cannot begin with ...Bd6, since this hangs the pawn on d5! And if Black plays ...c6 first, we are then in time to play Bf4! , to prevent Black establishing their bishop on this strong d6-square!   Alternatively, if Black plays a Panov, they will get nowhere near as much activity as in a standard Caro-Kann, and we will be the ones putting pressure on our opponent instead. Since the Panov Attack and the mainline Exchange are very different in nature, let's start by looking at the Panov Attack, before returning to our mainline. }
4... c6
{ 4...Nf6  Here, White can enter mainlines of the QGD Exchange with  5.Bg5  . However, I like to keep things simple with 5. Bf4,  which will transpose to our mainlines after  5.Bf4  c6  6.Qc2  etc.   4...Bd6?  aiming to prevent Bf4 fails immediately to  5.Nxd5!  .  This is why Black must defend their d5-pawn on move 4. }
5. Bf4
{ I like starting out with Bf4. We prevent Black from establishing their dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@DSB@@EndBracket@@ on the most active diagonal with ...Bd6.   Thinking as a Caro-Kann player, to achieve Bf4 would be a dream scenario, since this reduces most of the attacking possibility on our king @@StartBracket@@Black's main source of counterplay@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Qb6
{ This is an interesting try to take advantage of our incomplete development, and put immediate pressure on our b2- and d4-pawns. }
6. Qd2
{ Since our dark-squared bishop is developed to f4 already, we can develop our queen without blocking the bishop in on c1. }
6... Bf5 7. e3
{ We must play e3 quickly so we are ready to combat Black's light-squared bishop with the move Bd3. }
7... Nf6 8. Bd3
{ At first, this looks like we hang the b-pawn, but in fact, we are doing more than fine. }
8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Qxb2 10. Rb1
{ This is a common resource when our opponents capture this greedy pawn on b2.   Our rook will capture b7, and in general, our rook will be more beneficial on the 7th rook, than their queen potentially getting stuck in our half of the board. }
10... Qa3 11. Rxb7 Bb4 { 11...Qc1+  is just a single check  12.Nd1  +/- } 12.
Ne2 { Supporting our c3-knight, and defending the c1-square. } 12... Nbd7 13.
O-O O-O 14. Rb1 Nb6 15. Rb3 Qa5 16. h3
{ Now that the queenside play has come to a standstill, I'd like to recommend that you take the time to improve your position statically where possible! Moves like 16. h3 may not look particularly critical, but creating an escape square for your king may make all the difference in any future tactics or combinations that arise over the board! }
16... Rfe8 17. Qf5
{ Black will no longer be able to use the d7-square to regroup their knights. Also, we plan to play Be5 next to put more pressure on Black's kingside, which will be especially annoying for Black since their knight on f6 is pinned @@StartBracket@@to the weak f7-pawn!@@EndBracket@@.   I won't explore this position any further @@StartBracket@@since this ...Qb6 plan is quite unique, and not resulting in our standard Minority Attack plan@@EndBracket@@, but this is already Black's most active play after ...Qb6, and we're doing more than fine!   On that note, let's now return to the study of the Minority Attack. I cannot emphasise this enough: the study of the Master Games I have selected on the Minority Attack are ESSENTIAL to your ability to execute a successful Minority Attack. So please don't skip these games. You can access the games in the 📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: Classical Variation #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ 4NCL Online, Division 3, Heffalump Hunters. } 1. e4
{ I am very much aware that we are examining a model game of the standard Caro-Kann as opposed to the Caro-Kann Reversed, but the plans and ideas exhibited in this game are exemplar, and what we would hope to reproduce in our own games of the Caro-Kann Reversed One Knight / Classical Variation.   Let's take a look! }
1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4
{ Remembering to solve the problem of our light-squared bishop! } 4. Nxe4 Bf5
5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7
{ Remembering to always meet Nf3 with ...Nd7 to prevent any unwanted activity from the White knight jumping to e5! }
8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3
{ Removing this bishop will always be welcomed. White's attacking potential on the kingside will be far less as a result! }
10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bf4 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1
{ In our theory, we'd reach this same position, but with ...O-O already played @@StartBracket@@due to the extra tempo in our Caro-Kann Reversed@@EndBracket@@. }
13... O-O 14. Ne5
{ Now, in fairness, in our main theory section, I examine the Classical Variation with 'Bd2' having been played instead of 'Bf4' @@StartBracket@@which I saved for the ADVANCED Material section of the course@@EndBracket@@. However, let's see if you can find the right move anyway — what would you play here for Black? }
14... Nxe5
{ There are multiple options here for Black, but I like this choice! As I said in the Classical Variation, many of the endgames favour Black. So when we have an option to trade, it's often a good idea to trade! }
15. Bxe5 Ng4 16. Qf3 Nxe5 { Another trade. } 17. dxe5 Qc7
{ Developing, and gaining a tempo on the weak e5-pawn. } 18. Qe4 Rad8 19. Ne2
Rxd1+
{ Again, not the engine's 'top move', but I like the spirit of this plan! Basically saying to the opponent — 'I'm confident about my endgame chances, bring it on!' }
20. Rxd1 Rd8 21. Rxd8+ Qxd8
{ Despite being objectively equal, White is one move away from being slightly worse... }
22. Kc1
{ ...and White is slightly worse! It is too early to centralise the White king while the queens are still on the board. }
22... Qa5
{ Again,  22...Bc5!  was objectively better according to engine, but this is good enough! Black targets the a2-pawn, which White must attend to.   23.Kb1??  would lose a queen after  23...Qe1+  24.Nc1  Qxe4  +- }
23. Nc3 Bb4 24. Qd3
{ Engine conjures up the tough defensive find of  24.Nd1!?  — avoiding the trade, and preventing  24...Qxa2  due to tactics of the bishop hanging to  25.Qxb4  . Instead, White tries to hold the position with the queen, or at least hope for counterplay down the d-file. But the queen is a terrible defender in chess, and Black is ready to take over.   When one side has multiple static weaknesses @@StartBracket@@the h5-pawn, the e5-pawn, and the a2-pawn@@EndBracket@@, it can be much harder to hold the position, regardless of what the engine evaluation says. So players on the White side of the Classical Variation should be very careful not to enter these sorts of endgames where they're at risk of being grinded down!   For us, of course, this is a dream come true! }
24... Bxc3 { Again, trading more pieces! } 25. bxc3 Qxe5
{ Better than capturing on a2, where the queen would be quite offside. A centralised queen @@StartBracket@@when no minor pieces can attack it@@EndBracket@@ is very powerful. }
26. Qd8+ Kh7 27. Qd7 Qe1+ 28. Kb2 Qxf2 29. Qxb7
{ White is now threatening to take another pawn, and hopefully enter some kind of race with their queenside pawns vs our central pawns. What would you play now? }
29... Qb6+
{ A brilliant move!   Black manages to trade the final piece, entering into a pawn endgame a pawn up. Of course, Black should still be careful that the resulting position is indeed winning, but this is textbook play from Black! }
30. Qxb6 axb6 31. Kc1 g6 32. c4 c5
{ A key move! Now White won't be able to create a passed pawn by pushing c5 themselves. }
33. hxg6+ Kxg6 34. Kd2 f5 35. Ke3 e5 36. g3 Kg5 37. Kf3 e4+ 38. Kf2 Kg4 39. Kg2
f4 40. gxf4 Kxf4
{ With our more active king, and an extra pawn, White's position is hopeless. White saw nothing better than to resign. Even if this is not a Caro-Kann Reversed game, I hope this model game will give you the confidence that the endgame is often in our favour in the Classical Variation, and we can punish our opponents for over-extending!   As I said once before already, if Black could get the Classical Variation every time when playing the Caro-Kann, I'd 100% play it as my repertoire against 1.e4! But unfortunately, there are many more highly sharp, and highly critical lines, that completely put me off playing the Caro-Kann with Black!   But anyway, that's a problem for Caro-Kann players to worry about — not for us with our 1.c3 Venom! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: Classical Variation #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org Blitz, 3+0 Rated    I had just lost two games in a row with the Black pieces, and was looking for some redemption with the White pieces! I hope you stick around for the resulting middlegame, since there are some very instructive moments to learn from! }
1. c3 e5 2. d4 Nc6 { The Classical / One Knight Variation } 3. dxe5 Nxe5 4. Bf4
Ng6 5. Bg3 Nf6 6. Nd2 { Remembering the rule — always meet ...Nf6 with Nd2! }
6... d5 7. Ngf3 c6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Be2 Be7 10. O-O O-O
{ As you can see, my opponent has played the Classical Variation without pushing ...h5 -> ...h4 ! I cover these positions in the ADVANCED section of the course @@StartBracket@@calling this the 'Quiet Setup'@@EndBracket@@. In any case, let's see how play continued: }
11. Qb3 Qb6 12. Rfd1 Rfd8 13. Rac1
{ My last three moves have simply been completing my development. Chess doesn't have to be so complicated! 😊 }
13... Nd7 14. a4 Nc5 15. Qa2 Be6
{ Incredibly, I completely overlooked the fact that my opponent's queen was trapped! I simply wasn't looking at such tactics. But this is why we should analyse our games. Next time my opponent has a rook on d8, a knight on c5, and I've pushed my pawn to a4 — I'll definitely be looking out for this a5 resource... }
16. Nd4 { 16.a5+-  The Queen is trapped! } 16... a5 17. N2b3 Nxb3 18. Qxb3 Qxb3
19. Nxb3 b6 20. Nd4
{ So far, I have made the most simple and logical moves. Improving my position, not creating any weaknesses for myself. Now let's see my opponent's moves? Black somehow has weak pawns on b6 and c6. Also their bishops don't control any significant squares. The knight on g6 is a bit awkward, and the rook on a8 is undeveloped. This is the strength of the Caro-Kann pawn structure. The pieces flow nicely, and our opponents create easy targets for us to attack! }
20... Rd7
{ Now, I have no clue whether this was intentional, or if it was a mouse-slip @@StartBracket@@for instance, if they meant to play ...Bd7 instead@@EndBracket@@. In any case, I wasn't going to worry about this any longer, and just take the free pawn! }
21. Nxc6 Bc5
{ Now I understand that this is an opening's course, but that doesn't mean we can't learn something from the resulting middlegame too! What would be your mentality here? How would you try convert this position? }
22. Bb5
{ For me, the plan was simple. Don't do anything overly committal. Now that I have a clear advantage @@StartBracket@@better pieces, healthier pawn structure, AND a pawn up@@EndBracket@@, it was time to just improve every piece to the max before exploring my dynamic options. }
22... Rb7 23. Nd4
{ Again, my knight is more secure on d4 @@StartBracket@@defended by both pawns@@EndBracket@@, than only defended by the bishop on c6. }
23... Ne7 24. h3
{ Not taking any risks with a possible back rank checkmate someday! } 24... Bd7
25. Bxd7
{ Aside from the consolidating, I should also be keeping in mind that trading will in general be good for me. Whenever we're up material, the general rule is that the game will be easier to win with the more pieces that we trade! }
25... Rxd7 26. Nb5 { My knight replaces the strong bishop on b5. } 26... Rc8
27. Rd2
{ My conversion was going so well against this 2587! But this was my first inaccuracy. You may think nothing of it. I'm doubling my rooks on the d-file, what can possibly be wrong with this move?   But in fact, it's extremely careless. When we convert in chess, we should be maximally accurate. Not in terms of making Stockfish top moves, but in terms of taking zero risk in the position, and having the cleanest path to victory.   Here, I completely neglect one VERY important aspect of the position: we are playing a middlegame with bishops, namely, the dark-squared bishops. As a result, we should avoid putting our heavy pieces @@StartBracket@@rooks, queens, kings@@EndBracket@@ on dark squares. Very simple, right? But look at my pieces. Both my rooks and my king are on dark squares!! Although there is no immediate tactic in the position, I am asking for trouble with this careless play.   Had I simply played 27. Rd3, I would have no issues whatsoever in the following complications:   27.Rd3!  The same idea, but using the safe light squares for my heavy pieces!  27...Nf5  28.Be5!  Here, my intuitive move works a treat. I can safely retreat to d4 next move, and there are no tactics that work for my opponent. Of course, there's still potential for me to mess up this position. But with every trade that comes, and for every piece of mine that consolidates, the harder it will be for my opponent to turn the tables. }
27... Nf5 28. Be5
{ My bishop was attacked, so I move it. And of course, when you play with your pieces, you should think where they want to be heading. Here, my bishop belongs on the d4-square, so 28. Be5 is extremely natural of a move.  Yet it is a complete blunder! Not because of the bishop, but because of my earlier, careless, 27. Rd2?! Can you spot how Black can punish my careless play? }
28... Nxe3
{ At this moment, I went into full tilt. 'My GOD MICHAEL HOW DID YOU BLUNDER IN THIS POSITION????' Tilt during the game is never useful. If you have to tilt, wait until after the game! }
29. fxe3
{ As a result of my immediate tilt, I proceed to make an even worse blunder. Had I stopped to calm down and think on the previous move, I'd have realised that I'm still actually winning — despite dropping the pawn on e3. I could simply play 29. b3, covering the c4-square so that the knight can't retreat there, and I'd have the better play against the isolated d-pawn.   In fact, this line of thought was called out in the early 20th century by none other than Alexander Alekhine — the 4th World Champion. What Alekhine stated was something along the lines of:   If you blunder in chess, your next move MUST be the best move in the position.   What Alekhine meant by this, is everyone blunders from time to time in chess. But you must mitigate the damage and avoid tilt by focusing on making the best move in the position, in order to bounce back. Sometimes you won't be able to bounce back and the position is simply lost, many times, you actually can. And this is a perfect example, whereby I had the move 29. b3 to keep a slight advantage.   29.b3!  I keep the advantage, and have serious chances of winning this game still — despite my one move blunder! }
29... Bxe3+ 30. Kf1 Bxd2
{ Now I am dead lost. As opposed to being equal in material @@StartBracket@@since I blundered a pawn that I'd previously won@@EndBracket@@, I am now a pawn AND an exchange down. My 2587 opponent didn't hesitate to convert this position cleanly, giving me no chances to fight back! As we can see, the loss of this game was by no means as a result of the opening. Be critical with yourself and learn from your mistakes.   Even though I knew Alekhine's advice before this game, I still made this mistake. You will continue to make the same mistakes over and over, but at some point, after consciously spotting your mistake enough times, you may overcome this mistake in your play! In any case, I had to include this game. Maybe I'll release a middlegame course someday on all the psychological pitfalls that a club player may possess — but that's for another day! }
31. Rd1 Bg5 32. Bd4 Bd8 33. Re1 Kf8 34. Be5 Rc6 35. Bd4 Re6 36. Rd1 Be7 37. Bf2
Bc5 38. Bg3 Re4 39. Nc7 Rxa4 40. Nb5 Ra2 41. Re1 Rxb2 42. Nc7 Rxc7 43. Bxc7 a4
44. Ra1 a3 45. Be5 a2 46. c4 d4 47. Rd1 Rb1 48. Ke2 Rxd1 49. Kxd1 a1=Q+ 50. Ke2
d3+ 51. Kf3 Qxe5 52. h4 d2 53. h5 d1=Q# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: Advance Variation"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org Blitz, 5+0 Rated  As I was working on the 1.c3 Venom course, I also taught the opening to some of my stronger students.   This was a beautiful game played by my student that I had to include in the course @@StartBracket@@but they wanted to stay anonymous to avoid being prepped against@@EndBracket@@! }
1. c3 e5 2. d4 e4 3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 Bd6 5. Bxd6
{ White is more than happy to trade off these bishops. Without Black's dark-squared bishop, there will be far less kingside attacking prospects for Black. }
5... Qxd6 6. c4
{ Whenever White has the time to strike the centre with c4, they absolutely should! }
6... c6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Qb3
{ White is playing in the style of a 'French Defence Advance Variation', where White seeks to put great pressure on the d5-pawn.   White hopes to mount further pressure on the d5-pawn, since if the d5-pawn drops, the e4-pawn will drop too. In addition, Qb3 pressures the b7-pawn, tying Black's bishop down to the defence of the b7-pawn. }
8... O-O 9. Nge2
{ Here, Black is already facing difficulties developing. If the bishop moves, the b7-pawn drops. }
9... dxc4 10. Qxc4 Be6 11. Qa4 Nbd7
{ Since Nf4 no longer targets d5, White should now target the weakened e4-pawn. }
12. Ng3 Bd5 13. Be2 b5
{ An ugly move that permanently weakens the c6-pawn @@StartBracket@@unless Black is able to play ...c5 quickly@@EndBracket@@  13...c5  Black could not unravel so easily due to  14.O-O  cxd4  15.Qxd4  Now Black's e4-pawn will drop. }
14. Qc2 Rfe8 15. O-O Nb6 16. Nxd5 Nbxd5
{ 16...cxd5?!  now drops a pawn to  17.Bxb5  . } 17. Rfc1 Nb4 18. Qc5 Qxc5 19.
Rxc5 Rac8
{ 19...Nd3  the strong knight is short lived  20.Bxd3  exd3  21.Rd1  and the d3-pawn drops. }
20. a3 Na6 21. Rc2 Nd5 22. Rac1
{ The pressure on c6 is too much, and Black has no way to hold the position. }
22... Re6 23. Bg4
{ Black resigned.   All of White's pieces are perfectly placed, putting pressure on every weakness of Black's. A fantastic game by my student, and a perfect example of how to dismantle Black's over-extended position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: 2...d6 Line"]
[Result "*"]

{ For the 2...d6 lines of the Caro-Kann Reversed, the resulting positions are similar to an old line against the Caro-Kann starting with 2. d3, played in the style of a King's Indian Attack.   Therefore, I'd like to use a game from the standard Caro-Kann as our model game for this line  (keeping in mind we'll have an extra tempo to implement the plans and ideas seen in this game!)  . }
1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2
{ This move @@StartBracket@@as opposed to  3.Nf3  @@EndBracket@@, allows Black to take a full centre, just like in our theory of the 2...d6 line. }
3... e5 4. Ngf3 Bd6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. c3 Bg4
{ In my theory, I advocate for the simple ...a5 and ...Na6 instead, where all pieces can join the game. However, this idea is also interesting, to voluntarily give up the light-squared bishop, in order to outplay the opponent with the knights in the closed position! }
9. h3 Bh5
{ Black chooses to stay flexible for now, since g4 would be overambitious for White. Black keeps the option to trade on f3 at any time. }
10. Re1 Nbd7
{ Black chooses to develop with ...Nbd7.   The idea is the same as ...Na6 — to eventually head to the c5-square. }
11. Qc2 Bf8 12. Nf1 a5 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Nh4 dxe4 16. dxe4 g6 17.
Ne3 Nc5
{ The knight stands strong on c5, but Delemarre in fact has a different idea with the knight @@StartBracket@@rather than pressuring the e4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
18. a4 Red8 19. Nc4 Nd3 { The knight enters into the heart of White's camp! }
20. Re3 Nf4 21. Nf3 Bxf3 22. Rxf3 Nxh3+ 23. Kh2 Qe6 24. Bxh3 Qxc4
{ A very sweet sequence of moves, resulting in a slight advantage for Black. Despite being a pawn up, the position is only a slight advantage since the only minor pieces remaining are opposite coloured bishops.   Sometimes, this can lead to wild attacking games @@StartBracket@@since both sides have dominance of a single colour@@EndBracket@@. However, since the kingsides are somewhat closed, this attacking game cannot arise, thus the position is most likely heading towards an endgame of opposite coloured bishops, which is much more drawish in nature. }
25. Bf1 Qe6 26. b3 Qg4 27. Be2 Qg5 28. Rd1 Rxd1 29. Qxd1 Rd8 30. Rd3 Rxd3 31.
Qxd3 Bc5 32. Kg2 Qf6 33. Qf3 Kg7
{ 33...Qe7=+  Black could play for a win by keeping the queens on, and defending f7 @@StartBracket@@to avoid Bc4 ideas@@EndBracket@@. White can probably hold this, but the task would be much harder with the queens still on! }
34. Qxf6+ Kxf6
{ Now that the queens have traded, despite Black having the extra pawn, the opposite colour bishops ending increases the likelihood of a draw.  Of course, White still needs to prove that it's a draw, so we can certainly consider this opening result as a positive, given that Black has achieved a two result game. }
35. Bg4 Ke7 36. Bc8 b5 37. Kf3 Kd6 38. Ba6 bxa4 39. bxa4 Bb6 40. Bc4 f5 41. Bd3
Ke6 42. Bc4+ Kf6 43. Bd3 Ke6 44. Bc4+ Kf6 45. Bd3 h5 46. exf5 gxf5 47. Kg2 Kg5
48. Ba6 Bc7 49. Bb7 c5 50. Bc6 Bd8 51. Be8 Bf6 52. c4 Be7 53. Bf7 Bd6 54. Be8
Be7 55. Bf7 Kg4 56. Bd5 Bd6 57. Bc6 Be7
{ Black was unable to convert his slight advantage of the extra pawn in the opposite colour bishop endgame, and the game was agreed to a draw. }
