[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: Exchange Variation (Michael Green vs. Chess.com Danny Bot)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Rather than show you all master games, I also wanted to showcase a selection of 1. c3 games that I played against chess.com bots!   I have done this so you can test the opening out yourself against the bots, before playing 1.c3 Venom in OTB or rated online matches.   Personally, I'd say just go ahead and start experimenting with 1.c3 Venom in OTB and rated online games already, but I can also completely understand if you want to practice in a less competitive environment first! }
1. c3
{ Here is my first game against a Chess.com bot, against the Danny Rensch Bot rated 2500! }
1... e5
{ Since my opponent has played 1...e5, we will be entering a Caro-Kann Reversed. }
2. d4 exd4 3. cxd4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bb4
{ An unexpected move to me, not following up with the most principled ...d5. Let's see how I dealt with it!   For the record, I haven't included this move in the course since I preferred to focus the entirety of the Caro-Kann Exchange variation on the Reverse Panov, and the Minority Attack. I feel that seeing this model game once will be enough, in case you ever happen to face this line over the board! }
5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 Ne4
{ 6...Nd5!?  After playing e3, I thought this move may be interesting for Black. At first glance, it looks like we can't solve both the pressure on c3, as well as the pressure on our bishop on f4. However, we keep a slight edge after:  7.Ne2!  an important move we should keep in mind if ever ...Ne4 with ...Bb4 having been played. We don't mind giving up Bf4, only because we have a great lead in development  7...Nxf4  8.Nxf4⩲  Black already must play very accurately to fight for equality.   We have the centre, and a lead in development, and we will be able to establish a bishop on d3 with great pressure on Black's kingside now that the ...Nf6 has been removed. In addition, White has great control over the d5-square, so ...d5 won't be as easy to play for Black. }
7. Qc2 d5 8. Bd3 Nc6
{ So far I have played well, and am in fact +1 against the 2500 Danny bot! This is why I haven't covered every single possible line from Black — so long as you know the fundamental ideas of 1.c3 Venom, you can navigate most foreign positions that come your way. }
9. Bxe4
{ This, unfortunately, was far too naive. I was grabbing pawns in the opening before completing development, and getting my king to safety! I am by no means lost, or even worse at this point, but the position becomes much harder to play from here on in.   9.Ne2!  I should not be greedy and simply develop!  9...Bf5  10.O-O  Now that my king is safe, I am threatening to win a pawn.  10...Nxc3   10...Ne7?!  11.Nxe4  Bxe4  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.Qxe4  11.bxc3  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  Be7  13.c4±  White has an advantage due to the easy play on the open files against Black's queenside pawns. }
9... dxe4 10. Qxe4
{ My greediness now gets punished expertly by the chess.com engine!   In my defence, I was playing this game on a flight to Singapore, while waiting for my movie to reload... but this is still not a valid excuse!   Let's see how the rest of the game panned out. }
10... Re8 11. Qd3 Qxd4
{ Black regains the pawn with a much more pleasant position compared to 9. Ne2! }
12. Qxd4 Nxd4 13. O-O-O Ne6 14. Bg3 Bxc3
{ Black gives up the bishop pair, but in fact not only my pawn structure is weakened, but my king safety is too! }
15. bxc3 b6 16. e4
{ My plan is to set up a solid pawn chain with e4 f3 g2, but Black is very quick to undermine it... }
16... Nc5 17. f3 f5
{ Undermining my centre before I can complete my development! } 18. e5
{ What else? } 18... Be6 19. Kb2 Bc4
{ I ended up losing this game, but I stopped the notation here since Black already has a clear advantage. They're infiltrating with ...Nd3+, or perhaps starting with ...Rad8 first, but the issue for me is that my knight is still on g1!   My problems started when I prematurely grabbed a central pawn before completing my opening development. Mistakes like this are not the fault of 1.c3 Venom, since we were even up +1 in eval after move 8! We should instead make sure to follow the opening principles @@StartBracket@@whichever level of chess player you are!@@EndBracket@@ and only break them in exceptional circumstances. }
