[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: A Beautiful Minority Attack (Karpov, A. vs. Ljubojevic, L.)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1rnk1/pp2qppp/2p5/3p4/3Pn3/2NBPN2/PPQ2PPP/1R3RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ One of the greatest masters of the Minority Attack was none other than the 12th World Champion, Anatoly Karpov.   Although Karpov never started his games with 1. c3, the resulting positions he would get from the QGD Exchange Variation would feel surprisingly similar to the sort of positions we'd get in our Caro-Kann Reversed Exchange Variation main lines! Therefore, I have hand picked several classics from Karpov and other experts, to examine deeper how to play out a successful Minority Attack.    In this exact position, White has completed their development, and traded off the troublesome attacking Black dark-squared bishop. How should White continue? }
13. b4 { ...with a Minority Attack, of course! } 13... a6 14. a4
{ Whenever Black tries to prevent us from pushing b5 with ...a6, we should prepare b5 once again with a4. }
14... Bf5 15. Ne5
{ Karpov does not hurry to push b5, and instead improves his knight. The strong centralised knight will also give more possibilities for Karpov to trade off the minor pieces, reducing Black's attacking prospects on the kingside. }
15... Rad8
{ A move that doesn't achieve much. When Black doesn't have an obvious kingside attack, it can be very difficult to come up with a reasonable plan for Black against our Minority Attack! }
16. Rfc1 Ng6
{ At this moment, Karpov enters into a mass trade, nullifying all hopes of a successful kingside attack for Black. }
17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Nxg6 hxg6
{ Now that White has successfully traded off the last remaining minor piece, it is time to progress our position.   What did Karpov play now? }
20. b5
{ Of course! It is time to capitalise on the queenside with the thematic Minority Attack. Black decides that the best option is to leave themselves with a weakness on a6. }
20... cxb5 21. axb5 Rd6 22. bxa6 bxa6 23. Qa4 Qd7 24. Qxd7 Rxd7 25. Rc5
{ White is aiming to blockade the a-pawn, since, after all, it is a passed pawn! }
25... Ra7 26. Ra5 Kf8 27. Rb6 Rea8
{ White completely shuts down Black's rook activity, while maintaining a pair of active rooks himself. }
28. h4
{ Since the rooks are fantastically placed, it makes sense to bring the king in next! h4 is preferred over h3, since White gains space on the kingside, limiting Black's options, if Black would ever like to play ...g5 and ...f5. }
28... Ke7 29. Kh2 Kd7 30. Kg3 Kc7
{ Black's finally creates a meaningful threat, but White maintains full control over the position. }
31. Rb2 Rb7 32. Rc5+ Kb8 33. Ra2 Re7 34. Kf4
{ Now Black has two weaknesses to seriously worry about! The a6-pawn, and the e4-pawn. }
34... Kb7 35. Rb2+ Ka7 36. Rc6 Rh8 37. Ra2 a5
{ 37...Rxh4+  38.Kg3  Rh8  39.Rcxa6++-  No matter where the king moves, a Black rook is lost. }
38. Rxa5+ Kb7 39. Rca6 Rxh4+ 40. Kg3 Rh5 41. Ra7+ Kc6 42. R5a6+ Kb5 43. Rxe7
Rg5+ 44. Kh2 Kxa6 45. Rxf7
{ Quite incredibly, this is the first time White is gaining a material advantage, despite being in full control of the every moment of this game. Black doesn't waste any more time, and resigns.   Karpov was famous for converting these small advantages, and not allowing any counterplay from the opponent. A beautiful game and conversion of the Minority Attack! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: White Establishes a Strong Knight on c5 (Karpov, A. vs. Beliavsky, A.)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqrnk1/pp3p1p/2p2bp1/3p4/3P4/2NBPN1P/PPQ2PP1/R4RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Next, we examine another Karpov game in the Carlsbad structure. Karpov has finished his opening development, and is now ready to continue with his middlegame plan.   What do you think Karpov played next? }
13. b4
{ There is no need to prepare this push with either Rfb1 or Rab1, since Black has no control over the b4-square.   When we can accelerate our Minority Attack, it's usually a good idea to do so! }
13... Ne6 14. Rfd1
{ A useful placement of the f-rook! Although not essential for the Minority Attack, White does reduce the chances of Black meeting b5 with ...c5 @@StartBracket@@which you will see in the game after this one, between Pickett vs Timman@@EndBracket@@, since with the centre opening up, both the black d-pawn, and the queen on d8, will be vulnerable to White's rook on d1. }
14... a6
{ Whenever ...a6 is played to prevent the b5 threat, we should renew the threat with: }
15. a4 { White is again ready to push b5. } 15... Qd6 16. Qb3
{ White could break with b5 immediately, but what's the rush? In essence, the b5 push is the dynamic break we're hoping to achieve to gain a positional advantage.   However, when we have the space advantage @@StartBracket@@here, on the queenside@@EndBracket@@, and Black doesn't have sufficient counterplay, we should aim to prepare the b5 push as much as possible before going for it! This is why 16. Qb3 is an excellent preparatory move. }
16... Rd8 17. Bf1
{ Karpov keeps waiting to push b5. 17. Bf1 appears to be a general 'slow and improving' move, but in fact, it is actually key to White's plan!   Aside from adding reinforcement to White's kingside castle, the move also makes way for a knight to reroute from Nf3-e1-d3! This is a critical maneuver in the Minority Attack that is worth remembering. From the d3 square, the knight is most powerful. It can infiltrate to c5 @@StartBracket@@as we will see in this game@@EndBracket@@, protect the important b4-square, and secure important kingside squares e5, f4, and f2 @@StartBracket@@in case of incoming kingside counterplay from Black@@EndBracket@@. }
17... Bg7 18. Ra2
{ Another useful move, protecting White's second rank in case the rook is needed in the defence of the kingside. }
18... Nc7
{ Now, do you remember what was the deeper reason behind Bf1? If so, you'll know Karpov's next move! }
19. Ne1 { Preparing to bring the knight to the strong d3-square! } 19... Bf5
20. Ne2
{ Now you might have thought, what's wrong with the immediate 20. Nd3...? In fact, nothing's wrong with it, but Karpov wants to ensure a knight stays on d3! Therefore, Karpov plans to bring the other knight via Ne2-f4-d3, so that even if Bxd3 is played, White can still recapture with a knight, establishing a strong knight on d3!   We will soon appreciate the strength of this plan! }
20... Bf8 { Black attacks b4, so White defends it: } 21. Rb2 Qf6 22. Nf4
{ Following the plan... } 22... Ne8 23. Rc1
{ The rook no longer x-rays the queen, so Karpov prefers the rook on the c-file! }
23... h5 24. Ra2
{ Black is correct in trying to play on the kingside. In some situations, Black can try to advance ...g5-g4 to smash open White's kingside. However, this of course would weaken the Black king too. }
24... Bd6 25. Nfd3 Nc7
{ A knight has finally reached d3! Let's see what it can achieve: } 26. Nc5
{ Karpov doesn't hesitate to sink this knight into the c5-square!   What's so special about it's placement? For starters, the knight attacks both the b7 and a6 pawn weaknesses. The knight also controls the e4-square which Black may have wanted to use @@StartBracket@@e.g. for a rook lift@@EndBracket@@. And what's great about this knight is that it's very hard to be removed. If the knight is ever captured, then bxc5 opens up the b-file, resulting in the b7-pawn becoming even more weak.   If ...b6 is ever played, then both the a6- and c6-pawns become weak. The knight coming to c5 is the #1 most important motif from this game, so remember it well! When Black has tried to prevent the Minority Attack with ...a6, attacking this defensive structure by bringing a knight to c5 is the way to go! }
26... Rab8
{ Black chooses a passive defence with ...Rb8. White has all the pressure and play on the queenside, and takes it up a notch. What move is it finally time for? }
27. b5
{ At long last, White pulls the trigger and hits Black with b5! The plan is simple. Now that White's pieces are all optimally placed, it's time to induce a permanent weakness on White's queenside. }
27... b6
{ Black realises it's already time for drastic measures, since Black has no counterplay on the kingside, and goes all in for a pawn sacrifice. }
28. Nxa6 Nxa6 29. bxa6 c5
{ Karpov accepted the pawn sacrifice, but in doing so, allowed Black to get some play with the c5-break! Black is aiming to play ...c4, to give themselves a protected passed pawn. However, White is also quick to make a passed pawn of their own: }
30. Nf3 c4 31. Qb5 h4 32. a5 bxa5 33. Qxa5
{ Both sides have a passed pawn, but it is White who has the extra pawn in material. }
33... Bb4 34. Qa4 Bd6 35. Rca1 Bc7 36. a7 Ra8
{ Once the a-pawn has reached the 7th rank, Black is severely tied down. What follows is some patient maneuvering, where slowly but surely, White is able to infiltrate with his pieces, resulting in Black eventually collapsing. Since converting this position is outside the scope of our opening course, we will move onto our next Minority Attack motif! @@StartBracket@@However, I have left the remaining moves of the game in case you'd like to see how Karpov converted this advantage!@@EndBracket@@ }
37. Qb4 Be4 38. Ra6 Bd6 39. Qb7 Qe7 40. Qc6 Bc7 41. Qb5 Bf5 42. Be2 Bc8 43.
R6a2 Qd6 44. Kf1 Kg7 45. Bd1 Qf6 46. Qb2 Re8 47. Qb4 Rd8 48. Be2 Rd7 49. Qb5
Rd8 50. Kg1 Qd6 51. Ne5 f6 52. Ra6 Qe7 53. Nc6 Qd6 54. Kf1 Bxa6 55. Rxa6 c3 56.
Nxd8 c2 57. Qb2 Qh2 58. Ne6+ Kh6 59. Ke1 Rc8 60. Nc5 { 1-0 White wins. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: Black Meets b5 with ...c5 (Piket, J. vs. Timman, J.)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1nqp1p/2p2np1/3p4/3P4/2NBPN2/PPQ2PPP/R3R1K1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Unlike the previous two examples from Karpov, we start by looking at a position between Piket and Timman where Piket cannot immediately conduct the Minority Attack with b4.   Therefore, Piket decided to prepare the principled b4 push with: }
13. a3 { Bringing a rook to b1 to play for b4 would also have been fine. }
13... Nb6 14. b4
{ Since Black didn't prevent White from playing b4 with ...a5, White seizes the opportunity to start their Minority Attack! }
14... Re8
{ Imagine you're Karpov.   Would you play for the immediate b5? Or would you instead optimize your pieces before playing for the b5 break? }
15. b5
{ Personally, I feel that this move is premature. b5 is very difficult to prevent, so White can spend more time to maneuver their pieces to optimal squares, let Black build up their frustration from not finding a good plan, and only then push b5!   15.h3!?  a6  16.Nd2  Be6  17.Nb3  Rac8   17...Nc4!?  18.Nc5  b5  19.Bxc4!?  dxc4  20.e4⩲  with an interesting game ahead!  18.Nc5  Rc7  19.Rab1  Rb8  20.a4⩲  It's clear that White certainly has easier improving moves than Black! }
15... c5
{ This is a very typical response to our b5 push that we should watch out for!   In this Model game, I'd like to examine this motif in greater detail. }
16. dxc5 Qxc5
{ We have an interesting imbalance here! Black has given themselves an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@, which is a weak pawn, but in return, Black has more space for their pieces to coordinate and attack.   The IQP is typically useful in its added grip over the e4- and c4-squares. In this instance, the control over the c4-square is even greater than usual, since White has pushed their b-pawn all the way to b5. As a result, this c4-square is particularly weak, and Black definitely has some compensation here for their IQP. }
17. e4
{ Piket decides to immediately remove the IQP, hoping that his slight lead in development will be enough to prove an advantage. In fact, due to Black's loose queen and knight on f6, Black can quickly find themselves worse after several natural moves.   So despite not being the engine's strongest move, the e4 break in response to the ...c5 break is worth keeping in mind! Decisions like this are not easy to come to, so it helps to see games by Masters to understand the consequences of such decisions! }
17... Qf8
{ Timman does well to avoid the pitfalls.   17...dxe4??  18.Nxe4!  Nxe4  19.Qxc5!  Nxc5  20.Rxe8++-   17...d4??  18.Nd5!  Qxc2  19.Nxf6++- }
18. Qd2
{ 18.e5!?  Had White continued pressing in this position, perhaps Black would have collapsed? For instance, after:  18...Nfd7?  19.a4!  Nc5  20.a5±  By removing the knight on b6, the d5-pawn falls.   White has a great advantage here! }
18... Be6 19. a4 Rad8 20. Qg5 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Nbd5 22. Nxd5 Nxe4 23. Rxe4 Rxd5
24. Qe3 Qc5 25. Rc1 Qxe3 26. fxe3 Kf8 27. Nd4
{ The strong centralised knight compensates for the weakened pawn on e3. The players agreed a draw here.   The most important motif to learn from this game was the ...c5 push from Timman, as well as Piket's interesting reply with e4. The ...c5 push can be a strong reply to the move b5 in the Minority Attack, so the ...c5 push must be evaluated carefully before pushing forward with b5. }
