[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: White Meets ...Nb6 with a4 (Karpov, A. vs. Kharitonov, A.)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qrnk1/pp1nbppp/2p1b3/3p4/3P1B2/2NBPN1P/PPQ2PP1/R1R3K1 b - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We again return to the Minority Attack expert — Anatoly Karpov. In this position, Black's knight on d7 is poised and ready to fight on the queenside, which adds a different dynamic to the position. Kharitonov engages in this fight immediately with: }
13... Nb6
{ A common defensive motif against the Minority Attack is this ...Nb6 move. The idea is that when White pushes b4, the c4-square becomes weak, and potentially Black can infiltrate.  As we saw in the last game between Piket and Timman, this isn't the end of the world, and we can still play for b4, b5 @@StartBracket@@see the sideline of 15.h3!? with 17...Nc4!?@@EndBracket@@. However, I'd like to show you a game where Karpov finds an alternative way of facing this ...Nb6 move. }
14. Rab1 Bd6 15. Ne2 Ng6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ The dark-squared bishops trade @@StartBracket@@reducing chances of a successful kingside attack for Black@@EndBracket@@, and White is ready to play on the queenside.   You may be expecting the typical plan of preparing b4 @@StartBracket@@for instance, Nd2 @@StartBracket@@to cover ...Nc4@@EndBracket@@, and then b4@@EndBracket@@, but Karpov comes up with a different idea instead! }
17. a4
{ Karpov is looking to directly exploit this knight on b6!   17.Nd2  a5  18.a3  Qe7  19.b4⩲  Also a good way to continue! }
17... Rac8
{ 17...a5  In fact, Karpov didn't mind this blocking move, as you'll see soon in the resulting positions! }
18. Qc5
{ 18.a5  Nc4⇆  Since ...Nc4 is available here, I imagine this is why Karpov wanted to wait on the a5 push. }
18... Qb8 { 18...Qxc5  19.dxc5  Nxa4??  20.b3+- } 19. Qa3
{ White is sneakily preparing a fast a5, then a6, to disrupt Black's queenside and create a weakness in the c6-pawn. }
19... a6 { Black stops this possibility. } 20. Rc3 Qc7 21. Rbc1 Ra8 22. Nd2
{ Now White's a5 push is a strong space gaining move, given that the c4-square has been covered from potential ...Nc4 jumps! }
22... a5
{ Understandably, Black now cuts out this option, by playing ...a5 themselves. It would appear that White's queenside play has been shut down @@StartBracket@@since we're unable to establish a pawn on b4 with the typical a3 b4 push@@EndBracket@@.   Let's see how Karpov tackles this pawn structure. }
23. Rb1 Nc8 24. b4
{ Karpov plays for b4 anyway! The plan is to open the b-file, and and pressure the weak b7-pawn. }
24... axb4 25. Qxb4 Nd6
{ Black achieves bringing a knight to d6 @@StartBracket@@as we'll see in the next chapter, this can be a serious pain for the White player!@@EndBracket@@, but here, White is in full command of the queenside play, and continues to dominate. }
26. Nb3 Bc8
{ I don't think I'd be able to hold back from planting a knight onto c5, but again, Karpov patiently improves his position first — over the next 6 @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ moves! }
27. a5 Ne7 28. Ng3 g6 29. Rcc1 h5 30. Ra1 h4 31. Nf1 Bf5 32. Be2 Ne4 33. Nc5
{ The knight finally lands on the strong c5-square. Just take a moment to appreciate Karpov's last 6 moves, improving his pieces one by one, in order to maintain full control over the position. The Knight on c5 can be traded immediately, but Black's weak queenside structure will collapse in any case. }
33... Nxc5 34. Qxc5 Be6 35. Nd2 Nf5 36. Nf3 Qd8
{ Black has achieved no counterplay of any sort, and White crashes through: }
37. a6 bxa6 38. Rxa6 Rxa6 39. Bxa6 Qa8 40. Qxc6 Qxc6 41. Rxc6 Ra8 42. Bd3
{ Just like in our Caro-Kann Reversed One Knight / Classical Variation, we see that the overextended h-pawn is more of a weakness than some sort of attacking strength. Since the h-pawn is lost by force, Black decides they have seen enough, and resigns! }
