[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Model Game: Black Establishes a Strong Knight on d6 (Bobotsov, M. vs. Petrosian, T.)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r5k1/pp2rp2/2p3p1/3p2qp/3Pn3/3NP2P/PP3PP1/2RQ1R1K w - - 0 26"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ For our final Master game on the Minority Attack, we examine this position between Bobotsov vs Petrosian. White has successfully traded off a lot of Black's minor pieces  (reducing chances of a successful kingside attack for Black)  , however, Black has one trick up their sleeve! }
26. Nc5
{ White has planted a knight on c5, however, in this position, Black has a mighty strong move of their own!   What should Black play? }
26... Nd6
{ We now come to the counterpart of the 'knight on d3', which is the 'knight on d6' for our opponent! Here, the knight protects the b7-pawn and the b5-square, controls e4 @@StartBracket@@potentially for an attack with ...Ne4@@EndBracket@@, controls f5 @@StartBracket@@potentially for an attack with ...Nf5, ...Nh4@@EndBracket@@, and controls c4 @@StartBracket@@potentially with a defensive setup of meeting b4 with b5, and then ...Nc4@@EndBracket@@. Ideally, we should try and prepare our attack fast enough and avoid the possibility of our opponent establishing a knight on d6! }
27. Nd3
{ Bobotsov, being the weaker player, repeats with Nd3, hoping that Black will follow suit with ...Ne4. However, Black can play for the win here, since there is still some potential for a kingside attack.   One should take note that White has been very slow with their Minority Attack — b4 hasn't even been played yet! }
27... Qf5 28. Ne5 f6 29. Nf3 Rg7 30. Nh2
{ White has chosen to defend passively as a means to play for a draw. This, of course, is a sure way to play for a loss! }
30... Re8 31. Kg1 Ne4 32. Qf3 Qe6 33. Rfd1 g5 34. Qxh5 f5 35. Re1
{ White's a- and b-pawns look miserably on, while White continues to make insignificant moves. The position is already unsavable, and a strong master like Petrosian doesn't let this advantage slip! }
35... g4 36. hxg4 fxg4 37. f3 gxf3 38. Nxf3 Rh7 39. Qe5 Qc8 40. Qf4 Rf8 41. Qe5
Rf5
{ White even managed to have their queen trapped! Don't allow yourself to get squashed like this, while your a- and b-pawns never make a move on the queenside. Even if we're playing a stronger opponent, we should be looking to fight for an advantage with the Minority Attack. Trying to defend the whole game without any source of counterplay is likely to end in defeat.  This concludes our brief analysis on the most important motifs in the Minority Attack. Before we return to our theory, I'd like to show you a couple of my own Minority Attack games, and then with our newfound knowledge, we'll see how these ideas can be implemented in our starting middlegame positions — 'Minority Attack #1, #2, #3, and #4'.  After we discuss these middlegames, I will then give you some final advice on how to explore the Carlsbad Structure even further! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "My Own Minority Attack: A Success (PonzianiMaster vs. RefikBalkan)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess Blitz, 5+0 } 1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. cxd4 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bf4 c6
{ Here, I forgot my own theory! Before playing e3, I should look to prevent Black from establishing a strong bishop on f5, with Qc2. }
6. e3
{ 6.Qc2!  Successfully limiting Black's bishop from establishing itself on the active f5-square. }
6... Bf5
{ But of course, this is not a sharp position where one wrong theoretical move can lose me the game! I continue our usual development scheme: }
7. Bd3 Ne7
{ I'm always hesitant to capture on f5, since I don't want to encourage Black's knight maneuver of ...Nd7 -> ...Nf5 -> ...Nd6!   As we know from the Model Game between Bobotsov vs Petrosian, we would like to avoid our opponent establishing a knight on d6 if at all possible! }
8. h3 O-O 9. Nf3 h6 10. O-O Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Qc2 Be6 13. Rfb1 Qd7
{ What would you play now? } 14. b4
{ Of course! Even though my opponent is rated 2377 @@StartBracket@@online rating@@EndBracket@@, it is common for Black to be completely out of their depth, and doesn't even know where to begin with dealing with the incoming Minority Attack.   You have to remember, that all the master games we've studied, offer very high level defensive play from Black. In reality, you will have a much easier time conducting the Minority Attack.   Having studied my course, I'm sure you could convert the following position too! }
14... a6 15. a4 f5 16. b5 axb5 17. axb5 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 f4
{ Understandably, Black tries to generate some kind of attack. I don't want to open lines for their pieces, so I keep the position closed with: }
19. e4 dxe4 20. Nxe4
{ Sensing that they will suffer a slow death @@StartBracket@@with inevitable weaknesses on the queenside to be created@@EndBracket@@, Black decides to throw the kitchen sink at me! }
20... Bxh3 21. gxh3 Qxh3
{ The next move is critical. Stockfish will suggest everything wins, but practically speaking, we should ensure that our next few moves lead to a strong and stable defensive setup. I find one! }
22. Qb3+ Nd5 23. Bf1
{ A discovered defence, enabling the queen to defend my knight on f3.   In addition, I gain a tempo on the queen, and get ready to shelter my king from ...Qg4+ with Bg2. }
23... Qg4+ 24. Bg2
{ Having secured the defence of my king, I am in full command of the position, a piece up. }
24... Rf5 25. bxc6 Nxc6 26. Qxb7 Nxd4
{ Again, to convert this position requires patience. Sure, the knight on d4 is hanging, but do I really want to risk the complications after ...f3? Again, I find a cleaner solution to the position. }
27. Qc8+ Kh7 28. Nxd4
{ This time, I have nothing to worry about with regards to the f3 push! } 28...
f3 29. Qxf5+
{ Once the queens have traded, the win is in the bag!   You're welcome to play through the rest of the game, but even I would struggle to mess up this advantage! }
29... Qxf5 30. Nxf5 fxg2 31. Ra7 Nf4 32. Rxg7+ Kh8 33. Ned6 Nh3+ 34. Kxg2 Ng5
35. Nf7+ Nxf7 36. Rxf7 Kg8 37. Ra7 h5 38. Nh4 Kf8 39. Kf3 Ke8 40. Ke4 Kd8 41.
Kd5 Kc8 42. Kc6 Kb8 43. Rh7 Kc8 44. Rh8# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "My Own Minority Attack: A Failure (PonzianiMaster vs. TharolbisSpringRun)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org Blitz, 3+0   I had just lost the last few games and was tilting badly, but nevertheless, the resulting position was very instructive to analyse! }
1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. cxd4 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bf4 Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. h3
{ 7.Qc2!  We should be preventing ...Bf5 first and foremost! } 7... Nd7
{ 7...Bf5!  My opponent should be taking this diagonal given the chance! } 8.
Qc2 Ndf6 9. e3 Ne7 10. Nf3
{ At first, I thought I'd 'played too quickly' again, and missed the chance to slow down Black's development with 10...Bf5, by not playing  10.Bd3  first.   However, the more I analysed 10. Bd3, the more I realised that perhaps encouraging Black's knight to f5 isn't desirable, since it can then maneuver to the d6-square more easily?   10.Bd3  g6!  11.Nf3  Bf5  12.Bxf5  Nxf5!  13.O-O   13.g4!?  Interestingly, Stockfish likes this g4!? push — with the idea to dislodge the knight from f5 before it has a chance to reroute to the strong d6-square!  Qe7  14.Rfb1  Nd6∞  Of course, the game is far from over, but Black does establish a strong knight on d6.   NOTE from Michael: Upon reviewing all the content from 1.c3 Venom, I realised an error in my above analysis here! Maybe you can spot it too?   In short, we actually have no obligation to capture the bishop on f5 with 12. Bxf5 ! As a result, playing the early 10. Bd3 is clearly in our favour, since we force Black to waste a tempo playing 10...g6 in order to play for 11...Bf5. We should just remember not to trade off this bishop, otherwise the knight may reroute and cement itself on the strong d6-square!  The reason I have left the above analysis in is for you to see my thought process when getting to understand our lines. I am still growing as a 1.c3 Venom player, and I hope to share with you this journey! }
10... Bf5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O
{ 12...g6!?  Perhaps there's an argument to be said about playing for the ...Nf5, ...Qe7, ...Nd6 plan anyway!?  13.b4!  But the engine fights back immediately with 13.b4! — the point being that the pawn can't be taken without allowing Rb1, Rxb7.   So I guess moves like  12...g6  are too slow to aim to reach this ideal setup with the black knight on d6. }
13. O-O Ng6 14. Rfb1 a5 15. a3 a4
{ Now for some reason, this move is never mentioned in any of the Minority Attack resources that I researched. I assumed it was because the pawn is just weak on a4, and we can just aim to win it. I was correct. }
16. Qc2 b5
{ Now this is where it gets interesting!   Suddenly, I am unable to win the a4 pawn outright, and what's going on with Black's structure!? Typically, when you reach a position you don't understand, this is the most important time to stop and think. However, playing 3+0 while tilting, all good chess principles go out the window... }
17. Nd2
{ You will see that I start faffing around with my knights without a clear plan. Meanwhile, my opponent had a very strong plan that they were working towards!   17.b3!  This was in fact the break that needed to happen, and needed to happen fast! Since the threat of winning a4 is back on, Black needs to take on b3.  17...axb3  18.Qxb3!  keeping the rooks connected is useful.  18...Nd7  Black continues their plan as in the game, to bring the knight to the c4-square.  19.a4!  Again, White must act quickly! Now Black's structure is undermined, and with the b-pawn in trouble, Black again has no choice but to take on a4.  19...bxa4  20.Rxa4!  Recognise this type of position? We have the classic Minority Attack pawn structure that we'd like to aim for, where Black has a weak pawn on c6.   If we could get a knight on c5 with our pieces on the c-file, I'd be sure of White's advantage. But can't Black try for ...c5 here?  20...c5?!   20...Rxa4  21.Qxa4  c5?!  22.Rb7!  Nf6  23.Nb5!  Qc6  24.Rc7±  A sequence of precise moves and we find that Black's central pawns and exposed queen are temporarily too weak to get away with!  21.Rxa8  Rxa8  22.Qxd5±  Another advantage of our earlier 18. Qxb3 — White's queen has greater pressure on the d5-pawn! }
17... Nd7 18. Na2 Nb6 19. Nb4 Nc4
{ When I was playing this game, it was only at this moment that it dawned on me that I cannot remove the knight with the usual motif of b3, since the a4-pawn controls the b3-square!   Usually, the knight would only be able to hop to c4 when White had already played b4, but we see here that this is another instance where ...Nc4 can be established! }
20. b3 axb3 21. Rxb3
{ With my opponent establishing a knight on c4 and creating a weak a3-pawn to target, I went on to lose this game. When you play your own games in the Minority Attack, I am sure your opponents will find ways to play the resulting positions in ways that I haven't covered in the course. But this is where it will be on you, to analyse your own games, and see what you can understand from it @@StartBracket@@just like I did in this game!@@EndBracket@@.   I would highly recommend to analyse every game you lost @@StartBracket@@no matter how you lost it@@EndBracket@@, since there will almost always be something you can learn from it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "MINORITY ATTACK #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1r1k1/pp2np1p/2pq1np1/3p4/1P1P4/2NBPN1P/P1Q2PP1/RR4K1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Although the following positions are not Model Games, I decided to include these resulting positions in this section since I wanted to make sure you study the plans and ideas of the Minority Attack first, before looking specifically at the Minority Attack positions we will reach in our own games.   I would like to add a disclaimer, that most of the positions we are about to analyse are objectively equal. However, we should remember that it is likely that our opponents will be unprepared for the upcoming strategical battle, while we instead have the knowledge and experience from the likes of Karpov to guide us. I hope you will look past the engine evaluations, and appreciate the complex fight we are about to embark on!    Now, let's first take a look at our MINORITY ATTACK #1 position. Since Black was careless with the move order of their opening development, they have had to spend several extra moves to complete their development, with ...Bf5 coming next. As a result, White has had time to complete development themselves, play b4, and as a result, White has a great advantage!   Let's see how: }
15. b5
{ Here, Black has three options:   1@@EndBracket@@ They can ignore our push @@StartBracket@@and allow bxc6@@EndBracket@@.   2@@EndBracket@@ They can try to push ...c5.   3@@EndBracket@@ They can try to play capture ...cxb5.   Let's examine each of these moves!   15.a4  This is often a useful move to support the b5 push, but typically only necessary when Black plays with ...a6 to prevent b5.   So in general, when we can be direct with pushing b5 to create pawn weaknesses, we should just go for it! }
15... Kg7
{ We first examine OPTION 1 where Black ignores our b5 push.   OPTION 2  15...c5  16.dxc5  Qxc5  Here, Black may feel optimistic about their chances because despite the fact they have an isolated d-pawn, they at least don't have an open b-file to deal with! However, upon closer inspection, we realise that the isolated d-pawn is weaker than in the lines following 15...cxb5 — the reason being that White's own d4-pawn has been removed, thus the isolated d5-pawn is sitting on an open file for White.   In principled fashion, White should first blockade the d-pawn @@StartBracket@@to prevent it from ever pushing to trade itself for the e-pawn@@EndBracket@@, and then White will mount pressure on the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@using the open d-file and maneuvering all of the minor pieces@@EndBracket@@, in order to win it.  17.Nd4!  Black, like in other lines from the starting position, will suffer in this game too, because they will have to miserably defend this d5-pawn.   Our kingside is very solid, so it won't be easy for Black to conduct a kingside attack — Black's main source of counterplay when stuck with a structural weakness like an isolated queen's pawn. In addition, if you remember in our model game between Piket vs Timman, the main asset for Black was this weak c4-square. However, Black's knights will need to spend a lot of tempi to make use of this square.  17...Bd7  18.a4  Nc8  19.a5  Nd6  20.Qb3  Nc4?  Here, Black is not even able to establish a knight on c4.  21.Nxd5±   OPTION 3  15...cxb5  In this specific position, ...cxb5 fails to immediate tactics, but strategically, the move has its problems too. The d5-pawn is now isolated and will be weak. In addition, the b7-pawn will be weak due to White's open b-file with the rook on b1.  16.Nxb5+-  with Nc7 next.   16.Bxb5  @@StartBracket@@to illustrate the strategical advantage of the position@@EndBracket@@  16...Bf5  17.Bd3  Bxd3  18.Qxd3  Rab8  19.a4⩲  Black will suffer for the rest of the game, since their play will revolve around ensuring that both b7 and d5 are safe. }
16. bxc6 bxc6
{ When Black recaptures on c6 with their b-pawn, despite supporting their d5-pawn, now the c6-pawn is weak @@StartBracket@@since it is a backwards pawn on an open file@@EndBracket@@. Black would love to play for ...c5, and eventually ...d4 too, to get rid of these weaknesses.   However, we should aim to immediately blockade this c6-pawn to ensure Black never achieves their plan!   16...Nxc6⩲  This has a similar strategic outcome as 15...cxb5, where White gets the open b-file, and the weak isolated d5-pawn to play against.   This is a better defensive scenario for Black than 16...bxc6. }
17. Na4 Bf5 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. Nc5 Reb8 20. Qa4
{ White is threatening to win the a7-pawn with @@StartFEN@@rr6/p4pkp/2pq1np1/2Np1n2/Q2P4/4PN1P/P4PP1/RR4K1 w - - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  21.Rxb8  Rxb8  22.Qxa7  , or the c6-pawn with  @@StartFEN@@rr6/p4pkp/2pq1np1/2Np1n2/Q2P4/4PN1P/P4PP1/RR4K1 w - - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  21.Rxb8  Qxb8  ,  22.Qxc6  .   As we can see, Black is again suffering to hold this position. The Minority Attack is a very strong weapon to create permanent weaknesses for the opponent, and that is why they cannot afford to lose multiple tempi on development @@StartBracket@@like in this MINORITY ATTACK #1@@EndBracket@@, since they'll need those tempi to generate a kingside attack @@StartBracket@@their main source of counterplay against the Minority Attack@@EndBracket@@.   If Black is unable to generate a kingside attack @@StartBracket@@for instance in this position where too many minor pieces have been traded off, and Black is several tempi too slow@@EndBracket@@, Black should at least try to prevent White's Minority Attack before it becomes too powerful. In the subsequent Minority Attack study positions, we will see how Black aims to achieve this! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "MINORITY ATTACK #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/pp1n1ppp/2pq1n2/3p4/3P4/2NNP2P/PPQ2PP1/RR4K1 b - - 4 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here, we have a more typical Minority Attack where Black is not down several tempi. However, a key feature of this position is the knight's position on d3.   The knight on d3 is a useful asset to the Minority Attack, which we will see in the following variations.  In MINORITY ATTACK #1, we saw how White executes the b5 push. Now it is time to see Black's different ideas to defend against the Minority Attack. }
15... Nf8
{ Let's see what happens when Black ignores what White is doing.   A.  15...Nb6  The '...Nb6-c4 with ...b5 plan'.   Black's idea is to sink a knight into the c4-square. Afterwards, Black will be free to push the b-pawn, since the c-file is blocked, thus protecting the weakened c6-pawn!  16.b4   16.a4!?  We can also play in a similar style to Karpov in his game against Kharitonov!  Nc4  17.a4!  preventing Black from playing ...b5 to strengthen their knight.   Next, we will aim to push b5 ourselves.   17.a3  We would never actually play a3 here when a4 is available to us, but I wanted to include this line to illustrate that allowing ...b5 isn't actually a problem for us!  17...b5  I considered showing a model game for this defensive structure from Black, but I struggled to find games in which White handles it well!   Black's defensive structure is simple. At the cost of weakening the c6-pawn and c5-square permanently, Black clogs up the queenside, while establishing a strong knight on c4. However, all is not lost, and I like the following plan to break down this structure:  18.a4!  a6  19.Ra2!  We now see an added benefit of playing Rfb1, as opposed to the more common Rab1. Here, White is fast to double on the a-file, to put more pressure on Black's setup.  19...Qe7  20.Rba1  Rab8  21.axb5  axb5  22.Nc5⩲  White will infiltrate with their rooks on the 6th or 7th rank, and eventually bring the knight on c3, as well as the queen, into Black's territory.  17...Kh8  In reality, Black would aim to create kingside counterplay. But in order to illustrate White's plan, let's see what happens if Black loses a couple tempi.  18.Rb3  preventing the ...Na3 fork trick.   18.b5?!  We must watch out for tactics!  18...Na3!  19.Rxa3  Qxa3  20.Nc5⩲  Interestingly, according to Stockfish, White has full compensation for the exchange here. But this is somewhat unnecessary to allow.  18...Kg8  19.b5!  Kh8  20.bxc6  bxc6  21.Nc5  Even if the c-file is blocked by the knight on c4, we can still try to make use of the open b-file.  21...Rab8  22.Rab1  Rxb3  23.Rxb3  Rb8  24.N3e4!  This tactical motif is good to have seen at least once! Despite Black's knight on c4 appearing solid, it does result in the d5-pawn being 'pinned' to the defence of the knight on c4.  24...Nxe4  25.Nxe4  Qc7  26.Ng5!  , threatening mate!  26...g6  27.Nxf7++-  This is a nice example of 'the principle of two weaknesses'. Of course, none of this was forced @@StartBracket@@in fact, Black's play was very suboptimal with the ...Kh8/...Kg8 repeat!@@EndBracket@@, however, it's more important to see the key motifs and ideas.   B.  15...a5  The '...a5 to prevent b4 plan'.   Black aims to prevent the b4 push using their a-pawn. We can consider preparing b4 conventionally with a3, but with the added support from the knight on d3, I actually like playing b4 immediately!  16.b4!  axb4  17.Rxb4  Ra7  18.a4⩲  This position resembles that of Karpov vs Kharitonov. I fancy White's chances here on the queenside!   C.  15...b5?!  The '...b5 with ...Nb6-c4 after plan'.   If Black ever plays ...b5 before we push b4, we should be hesitant to push b4 ourselves. We don't get a bad position after b4, but we can do better with the added flexibility of playing b3 if needed!  16.Rc1!  Now that the c6-pawn has been permanently weakened, the rook belongs on the c-file!  16...Nb6  17.a4!  b4   17...a6  18.a5  Nc4  19.b3+-  The Black knight is trapped!  18.Na2±  Both b4- and c6-pawns are hanging, and cannot both be saved. }
16. b4 a6 { The '...a6 to prevent b5' plan. } 17. a4
{ This is the thematic response to ...a6. Black prevents us playing b5, so we should counter their prevention! }
17... Ng6 18. Nc5
{ With the black pawn on a6, this is a great opportunity to sink a knight into the c5-square! Black cannot kick away the knight with ...b6 without creating further weaknesses, and b5 is incoming next for White. }
18... Rab8
{ 18...b6  19.Nd3  Now that the b7-pawn has moved, now the c6-pawn is weak!  19...Rec8  Black aims to defend c6, with some hopes of pushing ...c5.  20.a5!  b5  21.Ne2  Rc7  22.Rb3  Rac8  23.Rc1  Nd7  24.Rc3  Nb8  25.Nc5  Ne7±  With all of Black's pieces defending the c6 weakness, White can now turn their attention to the kingside or centre!   One plan could be to play f3 and e4. Another plan could be Qd1, Nf4, Qg4. Black will struggle to defend both sides of the board, and most likely collapse with a lost position. }
19. b5
{ With a knight on c5, the b5 push just hits so much harder! Black must now take their pick of which weakness to be left with. }
19... cxb5
{ 19...axb5  20.axb5  cxb5  21.Rxb5  b6  22.Nd3±  Black's weak pawns on b6 and d5 will be a headache to defend! }
20. axb5 Rec8 21. bxa6 bxa6
{ Black is left with a weak, isolated, a6-pawn. I would suggest revisiting the game between Karpov and Ljubojevic to see how to follow up this advantage! }
*

