[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "MINORITY ATTACK #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp2nppp/2pq1n2/3p4/3P4/2NQPN2/PP3PPP/RR4K1 b - - 6 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We now move onto a more typical position where White hasn't had the chance to reroute a knight to d3.   Let's see how this changes our approach to Black's defensive measures on the queenside!  White is already threatening to push b4, so it is likely that Black will try to prevent this with: }
13... a5
{ 13...Ng6  If Black prioritises kingside activity, White will be able to begin their Minority Attack instantly with:  14.b4!  We have plenty of experience of how to play out this resulting position now! }
14. Nd2
{ We should prophylactically cover the e4-square, so that our c3-knight can jump via a4 to c5!   14.Na4?!  This is the right spirit to try to plant a knight on c5. However, this can be met by the annoying:  14...Ne4!  We should keep this resource in mind, and make sure to always have ample cover of the e4-square. }
14... Ng6
{ 14...b5?!  Although preventing our Na5 plan, whenever ...b5 is pushed prematurely, the c6-pawn can become very weak for Black.  15.a4  b4  16.Ne2  Rfe8  17.Rc1! }
15. Na4 Rfe8 16. Nc5 Rab8 17. b4
{ White has achieved the signature b4 push, and our play on the queenside continues! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "MINORITY ATTACK #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pq1n2/3p4/3P4/2NQPN2/PP3PPP/RR4K1 b - - 5 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We finally come to our final middlegame position to study. At first glance, it looks like there's nothing special happening, but in fact, Black's pieces are well placed. For instance, the knight on d7 covers the important c5-square, while the queen covers the b4-square.   Black is also not several tempi down, since they were able to efficiently develop their bishop to f5 early on. Nevertheless, I'm not concerned about our chances to successfully conduct a Minority Attack here, let's see how! }
12... Rfe8
{ If Black ignores our queenside play, we'd be more than happy to play:   12...a5  In the MINORITY ATTACK #4 starting position, the move ...a5 makes a lot of sense.   We don't have a knight on d3 to support b4. We also don't have full control over the c5-square in order to play Na4-c5. Therefore, I'd like to recommend an idea from one of the Karpov games we studied!  13.a4!  Do you remember the game between Karpov vs Kharitonov? We will aim to play for an eventual b4, and open up the b-file!   13.Na4?!  Ne4!  Black takes further control over the key c5-square, while establishing a strong knight in the centre, controlling the kingside too.  13...Nb6  14.b3!  With b3, we slow down the pace of the game. Rather than try push for b4 immediately, we should secure our position.   Play h3, Ra2, and slowly improve our position before striking with b4 and opening the b-file. Do look over the Karpov games provided to see how expertly Karpov improves this sort of position before continuing play on the queenside! }
13. b4 { ...and the Minority Attack begins! } 13... a6
{ Rather than play for the immediate a4, then b5, I think it's best to improve the position first. }
14. h3
{ We should aim to limit our opponent's play on the kingside as much as possible! Here, h3 prevents ...Ng4 ideas @@StartBracket@@that could be tricky to face if we ever remaneuver our knight from f3@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Nb6 15. Nd2
{ Having prevented Black's entry into the position, we can now think about playing for a4, and then b5. But we should never hurry with our queenside play if we can first put a stop to Black's kingside counterplay! Do look over Karpov vs Beliavsky to remind yourself of how Karpov expertly handles this prophylactic play! }
*

