[White "📖 Model games: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Further Exploration of the Carlsbad Structure!"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/4P3/PP3PPP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ From the above Model Games, and analysis of resulting positions from our theory section, I hope you are feeling a lot more confident with how to handle the Carlsbad Structure, and outplay your opponent in a Minority Attack!    However, now that we have come this far, I'd like to reveal to you a secret. In fact, the Minority Attack is just scratching the surface of the Carlsbad Structure, and the depths of this opening pawn structure go far deeper! Many other plans have been tried, including Kasparov's Nge2 / f3 / e4 ideas, the Pillsbury Attack, or even castling O-O-O!    I want to reassure you, however, that these ideas are only necessary for the most ambitious of players. Practically speaking, the Minority Attack alone is already nuanced enough for a complex battle, where the side that understands the plans and ideas better will come out on top.   I would advise you to stick to the Minority Attack plan for now when reaching the Carlsbad Structure, and later, you can branch out with more of these ideas!  If you would like a reference for these different ways to handle the Carlsbad Structure, I can recommend a great YouTube series by GM Sune Berg Hansen on the Carlsbad Structure. And while we're on the topic of YouTube, another video I'd love to recommend on the Minority Attack is a lecture given by GM Yasser Seirawan, on the Saint Louis Chess Club YouTube channel. He shows two of his games involving a Minority Attack, one of which leads to the destruction of former world champion, Mikhail Tal!    As you can see, players that have understood the Minority Attack well have been able to utilise it against the strongest of players. I wish you all the best in your own adventures of this pawn structure! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Classical Variation: Alternative Approaches 5...N8e7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 Nc6
{ To begin our ADVANCED Material section on the 'One Knight' / Classical Variation, I'd like to examine all the alternative approaches that Black can setup against our Caro-Kann Reversed Structure. In my experience, opponents playing 2...Nc6 have already clocked the reverse Caro-Kann nature of the position, and are existing Two Knights or Classical Variation players with the White pieces.   So I will examine the most frequent sidelines, as well as reasonable tries from Black, that they may try to play for over the board. }
3. dxe5 Nxe5
{ 3...Qe7  It is very unlikely that Black will have prepared this, but perhaps after playing Nc6 and not fancying Nxe5, they may stumble upon this move. I like to keep things simple with:  4.Bf4  Nxe5  5.e3  We can continue our development just as we would in our mainline! }
4. Bf4 Ng6 5. Bg3 N8e7
{ I should note at this moment that there is a second approach to the Classical Variation, which involves an entirely different plan to bring a knight to f5 to attack our g3-bishop. This, combined with a quick h5, h4, can be very tricky to deal with.   Black's plan can either start via 5...Ne7, or via 5...Nh6. Let's take a look how to approach this! }
6. e3
