[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 Nc6
{ To begin our ADVANCED Material section on the 'One Knight' / Classical Variation, I'd like to examine all the alternative approaches that Black can setup against our Caro-Kann Reversed Structure. In my experience, opponents playing 2...Nc6 have already clocked the reverse Caro-Kann nature of the position, and are existing Two Knights or Classical Variation players with the White pieces.   So I will examine the most frequent sidelines, as well as reasonable tries from Black, that they may try to play for over the board. }
3. dxe5 Nxe5
{ 3...Qe7  It is very unlikely that Black will have prepared this, but perhaps after playing Nc6 and not fancying Nxe5, they may stumble upon this move. I like to keep things simple with:  4.Bf4  Nxe5  5.e3  we can continue our development just as we would in our mainline! }
4. Bf4 Ng6 5. Bg3 Nf6
{ RULE #1! In the Classical Variation, we should always meet ...Nf6 with Nd2! }
6. Nd2 d5 7. e3
{ At first glance, this just looks like the same line we studied in the main course of 1.c3 Venom.   However, rather than play ambitiously with ...h5-h4, another natural move to try is: }
7... Bd6
{ This is a very rare move that's hardly ever analysed in the standard Caro-Kann, since it gives up the advantage immediately. However, as the Black player, I can perfectly understand the mentality of choosing a quieter position @@StartBracket@@when a tempo down@@EndBracket@@, and asking White how they're going to find an advantage? Thankfully, we have some solid and simple ideas to put pressure on our opponent. We first start out with natural developing moves. }
8. Ngf3 O-O 9. Be2 Re8 10. O-O Bxg3
{ 10...c5  If Black ever plays with ...c5, we should look out for ways to play against the d5-pawn.   I have a nice Model Game against this structure, although the position started out as a London System! }
11. hxg3
{ The g3-pawn solidifies our kingside, limiting the black knight on g6. } 11...
Bf5
{ At this moment, I'd like to suggest two plans. Either we play for a two result game with the immediate  12.c4  ,  or we can keep the queen's on with  12.Qb3  . }
12. c4
{ 12.Qb3  Rb8  13.c4  dxc4  14.Bxc4  Qe7  15.Rfd1⩲  White will eventually try for a minority attack @@StartBracket@@2 vs 3 on the queenside@@EndBracket@@, as well as play down the c-file.   Keeping the queens on isn't particularly useful, but there may be more chances to outplay your opponent with the queens still on! }
12... dxc4 13. Nxc4 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Rad8 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. b4
{ With the more active centralised knights, and a clear plan with the Minority Attack, I believe that we have good chances to grind down our opponent here.  If you'd like further reference as to how to handle these quiet setups from Black, this Model Game would be worth checking out! }
