[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Classical Variation: A Deeper Dive 13...Kb8"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 Nc6
{ To begin our ADVANCED Material section on the 'One Knight' / Classical Variation, I'd like to examine all the alternative approaches that Black can setup against our Caro-Kann Reversed Structure. In my experience, opponents playing 2...Nc6 have already clocked the reverse Caro-Kann nature of the position, and are existing Two Knights or Classical Variation players with the White pieces.   So I will examine the most frequent sidelines, as well as reasonable tries from Black, that they may try to play for over the board. }
3. dxe5 Nxe5
{ 3...Qe7  It is very unlikely that Black will have prepared this, but perhaps after playing Nc6 and not fancying Nxe5, they may stumble upon this move. I like to keep things simple with:  4.Bf4  Nxe5  5.e3  we can continue our development just as we would in our mainline! }
4. Bf4 Ng6 5. Bg3 Nf6
{ RULE #1! In the Classical Variation, we should always meet ...Nf6 with Nd2! }
6. Nd2 d5 7. e3
{ At first glance, this just looks like the same line we studied in the main course of 1.c3 Venom.   However, rather than play ambitiously with ...h5-h4, another natural move to try is: }
7... h5
{ RULE #2: In the Classical Variation, we should always meet ...h5 with h3! }
8. h3 h4
{ 8...Bd6  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  Black can also play without the inclusion of the h4 push, but our play will be exactly the same. This is likely to be a slightly better version for Black since the h5 will be less weak than on h4, but in my research, I've found that there are no critical differences in the resulting variations, so I've purposefully chosen to omit these lines! }
9. Bh2 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ Now on anything Black does, we always follow the same development plan: Nf3, Be2, and O-O. }
11. Ngf3
{ In the main course we studied 11...Bd7, so let's take a look at the more ambitious 11...Bf5 here. }
11... Bf5 12. Be2 O-O-O 13. O-O
{ Normally, Black's king would be on b8 already @@StartBracket@@in a standard Caro-Kann Classical Variation@@EndBracket@@, and Black would have the option of either Ne4 or Ne5.   Let's take a look at all three options of ...Kb8, ...Ne4, and ...Ne5! }
13... Kb8 14. Rc1 c5
{ At first glance, this appears to be the right moment to push c4! However, whenever we consider c4, we must consider the impact of the response ...d4.   In this position when we capture exd4, we in fact weaken the f4-square too much — allowing ...Nf4! with an attack on our king! As promised, there will be no attacks on our king in this 'One Knight' Variation, but we should always keep this in mind: if our e3-pawn is ever removed, the f4-square becomes weak!   14...Ne5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Nf3  Qd6  17.c4!  transposes to 13...Ne5   14...Ne4  15.Nd4  Bc8  16.c4!  transposes to 13...Ne4 }
15. b4
{ 15.c4?!  The thematic looking c4 break is not so effective due the strong response:  15...d4!  If Black is able to play d4, they will undermine our e3-pawn, which is KEY to controlling the otherwise weak f4-square. If Black is able to control the f4-square, their attacks can be pretty dangerous. For instance:  16.exd4  Nf4!  17.d5  Bxh3-+ }
15... c4
{ 15...cxb4?!  Trying to win a pawn is too greedy for Black!  16.cxb4  Qxb4  17.Nd4⩲  In return for the pawn, we get a free attack on the black king. Since our own king is so solid, this will be a miserable position for Black to defend.   Also, the extra pawn that Black won is a sad isolated pawn on d5 — nothing to boast about! }
16. a4
{ Let's discuss this position for a second.   White has a clear plan to advance on the queenside with potential attacking success. In addition, any endgames are going to be great for us, due to the weakness of the d5- and h4-pawns. A very fine two result game we have on our hands! }
16... Ne5
{ Since the Caro-Kann endgame is in our favour, whenever we have the chance to trade, trade! }
17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Nf3 Qe7 19. Nd4 Bg6
{ 19...Bc8  20.a5  g5?!  Black can attempt to attack, but they're too slow.  21.a6!   21.Kh1∆  For illustrative purposes, even when Black has an extra move in the attack, it amounts to nothing:  21...g4  22.Bxg4  Nxg4  23.hxg4  h3  24.g3⩲  It is useful to know this concept! The attacking Black h3-pawn acts as a shield of protection for our own White king, and since the rest of the kingside is blocked by our own pawns, our king is completely safe here!  b6??  Black doesn't get a chance to keep their kingside closed due to:  22.Nc6++- }
20. Bf3
{ As mentioned previously, White has a great game due to retaining attacking prospects on the queenside, while also having a favourable endgame in case the pieces trade, due to the weaknesses of d5 and h4.   We should be very happy to face the Caro-Kann Reversed 'One Knight' Variation, now that we've understood the logic behind the opening, and been able to utilise the extra tempo to avoid several critical variations that would typically be faced in a standard Caro-Kann! }
