16... c5 17. Nb5 { Hitting the queen, so no time for d4! } 17... Qb6
{ Defending against the mate threat of Qa4 / Qxh7#.   At this moment, our position is in fact feeling a little loose with our queen now facing the rook on d8, so it's best to release the tension with:   17...Qe5?!  18. Nxe4 @@StartBracket@@our response to 17...Qb6@@EndBracket@@ is completely fine here too, but we can even take the advantage after:  18.cxd5  Rxd5  19.Qa4!  threatening mate  19...a6  20.Nxe4  axb5  21.Bxb5±  with a pawn up, and a weak black king to hunt! }
18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Qc2 f5 20. Rfd1
{ Compared to the early trade option with 14. Nxe4, this is certainly a better version of it.   Here, we have a juicy outpost on d5 which we can reroute our knight to, with a great game ahead of us! }
