[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Classical Variation: A Deeper Dive 13...Ne5 - the ...g5 push! (part 1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 Nc6 3. dxe5 Nxe5 4. Bf4 Ng6 5. Bg3 Nf6 6. Nd2 d5 7. e3 h5 8. h3
{ Since publishing the course, I decided to change this variation into an informational to help you guys navigate the resulting positions! This variation covers the  (dubious, but tricky)  idea of a ...g5 push in the Classical Variation. It's worth mentioning now that Black's ...g5 can be avoided altogether, so the study of these lines are purely optional  (if you'd like to avoid a ...g5 push, skip to the next variation!)  . So this variation is purely for the theoreticians who'd like to get the maximum out of these One Knight Variation lines  (playing ambitiously often comes with a cost of more hard work!)  .   In any case, enjoy the analysis! I found it quite fascinating to see how engine dismantles each and every case of Black play ...g5, despite the positions looking quite scary to play with White, practically speaking.  I would recommend studying the variation starting with 'position 1'  (the mainline)  , and then combing through the clickables to find positions 2, 3, and 4. In each position, we see a slightly different setup from Black  (either Black's bishop on d7 or f5, and Black's pawn on either h5 or h4)  , resulting in 4 separate but related positions that require study to understand how ...g5 fails in each and every one of them. }
8... Bd6
{ Firstly, I'd like you to address this ...g5 plan when the pawn stays on ...h5. Black will then have a choice of 10...Bd7 @@StartBracket@@position 1@@EndBracket@@, or 10...Bf5 @@StartBracket@@position 2@@EndBracket@@. After studying both of these, then return to this position, and see how 8...h4 alters the outcome of this ...g5 plan!   8...h4  9.Bh2  Bd6  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  11.Ngf3  Again, Black has a choice of how to develop their bishop.  11...Bd7   11...Bf5  12.Be2  O-O-O  13.O-O  Ne5  14.Nxe5  Qxe5  15.Nf3  Qd6  16.Rc1  g5!?  ...g5 position 4 @@StartBracket@@...h4 & ...Bf5@@EndBracket@@.   We finally come to our final '...g5 position' to analyse. If you're really fed up with these lines already, you can skip to the next chapter, that offers a remedy for ...g5, in return for an objectively equal position. But for the keen theoreticians out there, let's keep delving into the nuances of meeting this ...g5 plan!   Since our opponent is playing ...g5 with the bishop on f5, we should meet ...g5 with:  17.c4!   @@StartBracket@@  17.Nxg5?  here, Nxg5 isn't even an option! This is why I like to keep things simple with my rule - with the bishop on d7, Nxg5 is correct. With the bishop on f5, don't enter these sharp positions, and play the counterattacking @@StartBracket@@and safer!@@EndBracket@@ c4 instead!  17...Rhg8  18.Nxf7  Qd7⩱  White is hanging on a tight rope, and even with perfect play, stands worse.@@EndBracket@@  17...g4  18.Nd4  Bd7  At this moment, unlike '...g5 position 2', we don't have h4 to close the kingside attack. However, we do have our c5-c6 plan, and if we immediately play it, we'll be faster in the attack!  19.c5!  Qe5  20.c6  Bxc6  21.Nxc6  bxc6  22.Bxg4+±  Black's king is weaker than ours, with the ...c6 pawn dropping very soon! We have a serious advantage.  12.Be2  O-O-O  13.O-O  Ne5  14.Nxe5  Qxe5  15.Nf3  Qd6  16.Rc1  g5!?  ...g5 position 3 @@StartBracket@@...h4 & ...Bd7@@EndBracket@@. Since Black has developed ...Bd7, we play Nxg5  17.Nxg5!   @@StartBracket@@  17.c4?!  g4⩱  Again, like in '...g5 position 1', we do not have Nd4 with tempo on the bishop. Therefore, we are not in time to stop Black's kingside attack. @@EndBracket@@  17...Rhg8  This time, it is quite easy to remember our continuation. There is no h4 since Black's pawn is on h4, so we have no choice but to play:  18.Nxf7!  Rxg2+?   @@StartBracket@@  18...Qe7!?  instead of ...Rxg2, ...Qe7 is a better try.  19.Nxd8  Bxh3  we must get out of the pin, and it's best to gain a tempo on Black's light squared bishop, so:  20.Kh2!  Bxg2  21.Rg1  h3  22.Qd4⩲  Ready to protect our king with Qf4. Since the attack is dealt with, White will just have more material @@StartBracket@@even after Black takes our knight@@EndBracket@@, with great endgame prospects ahead of us! @@EndBracket@@  19.Kxg2  Rg8+  The thematic ...Rxg2+ sacrifice immediately fails here due to the strong:  20.Bg4!  Since the queen is hanging, Black cannot capture our bishop with the bishop or knight. And there is no follow up after ...Rxg4. It should be noted that we don't have this resource with the black pawn on ...h5, since the g4 square is covered!  20...Rxg4+  21.Qxg4±  hxg4 is also fine, but I like to simplify in a position where we're material up. }
9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Ngf3 Bd7
{ 10...Bf5  Having looked at 10...Bd7, let's now see the difference with 10...Bf5  11.Be2  O-O-O  12.O-O  Ne5  13.Nxe5  Qxe5  14.Nf3  Qd6  15.Rc1  g5!?  ...g5 position 2 @@StartBracket@@...h5 & ...Bf5@@EndBracket@@.   Now, do you remember our rule? With the same position but ...Bf5 instead of ...Bd7, we should play:  16.c4!   16.Nxg5  is also playable, but it is unnecessary to take such a risk when 16. c4 just gives a clean advantage!  g4  17.Nd4!  Now we see the difference of the bishop being on f5, rather than d7! We gain a tempo on the bishop, thus slowing down their attack!  17...Bd7  18.h4⩲  we are now in time to keep our kingside closed! If Black is not careful, we will follow up with c5-c6 next with a great attack! }
11. Be2 O-O-O 12. O-O Ne5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3 Qd6 15. Rc1 g5
{ ...g5 position 1 @@StartBracket@@...h5 & ...Bd7@@EndBracket@@.   Here we begin our analysis into the scary looking ...g5 move! If we are completely unprepared, this attack may turn out to be a success, but hopefully after the next two variations, you will feel satisfied with how to deal with this move.   I'd like to begin with a rule to remember: with Black's bishop on ...d7, we should capture the pawn with Nxg5! When Black's bishop is on ...f5, we should play c4! In general, 16. Nxg5 leads to a more sharp position, but with the bishop on d7, we have to go for this.   16.c4  is much safer and a preferred option, but it only works with the bishop on f5. Hopefully by the end of studying these different variations with ...g5, you'll understand why we have this nuance! }
16. Nxg5
{ We are immediately threatening the fork on f7 @@StartBracket@@hence most beginner/intermediate players will dismiss 15...g5 already on these grounds!@@EndBracket@@, but in fact, we can get in trouble if we try and go for the fork!   16.c4?!  g4⩱  Here, there is no Nd4 move to gain a tempo on Black's bishop @@StartBracket@@since Black has developed ...Bd7 rather than ...Bf5@@EndBracket@@, so we're not in time to play 16. c4. }
16... Rhg8
{ With the h5-pawn not overextended to h4, our solution is actually very simple. After capturing on g5, we cement our knight with the move h4! }
17. h4
{ We close the g-file, and White is simply a clean pawn up. We may want to consider taking on ...f7 at some point, and we will still need to watch out for Black's dubious attacking tries. But if we stay vigilant, we should be fine here!   17.Nxf7?!  Going for the fork is naive, and Black has serious counterplay after:  17...Rxg2+!!  18.Kxg2  Rg8+!  19.Kh1??  Qe6-+  Black has a winning attack. We don't want to allow such attacks on our king! }
