1. c3 e5 2. d4 Nc6 3. dxe5 Nxe5 4. Bf4 Ng6 5. Bg3 Nf6 6. Nd2 d5 7. e3 h5 8. h3
Bd6 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Ngf3 Bd7 11. Be2 O-O-O 12. O-O Ne5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3
Qd6
{ For players who really struggle to play chess when their king is weak @@StartBracket@@myself included!@@EndBracket@@, or players who would like to use 1. c3 in bullet or blitz @@StartBracket@@where it's impractical to find correct defences under time pressure@@EndBracket@@, I'd like to offer an alternative option instead of 16. Rc1 when our opponent is playing an early ...Ne5. In fact, you've already seen the solution in the main section of the course, and we can simply play: }
15. Qd4
{ This is the move in a standard Caro-Kann, and although this objectively gives up some of the advantage, it does have its practical benefits. The plan is to trade queens with Qe5 next, and ...g5 ideas are much weaker as a result. I will only provide analysis of Qd4 in this current position. Of course, you're more than welcome to analyse the same position with ...Bf5 played @@StartBracket@@instead of ...Bd7@@EndBracket@@, and the when ...h4 has yet to be pushed from ...h5. I have briefly looked, and to my understanding, the play is very much the same. }
15... Kb8
{ Black cannot begin with ...g5, since they must tend to their weak a7-pawn.   15...g5?  The immediate ...g5 fails to:  16.Qxa7  g4??  17.Qa8   15...c5  also indirectly defends the a7-pawn.  16.Qe5!  If Black moves the queen away, we now take control of this weak h2-b8 diagonal targeting our king.  16...Qxe5  17.Nxe5  Be6=  I believe we stand on the better side of equality. We have clear targets of attack, and no weaknesses. Also Black can forget about this ...g5 plan to cause problems to our king, now that the queens are traded! }
16. Qe5
{ If Black moves the queen away, we now take control of this weak h2-b8 diagonal targeting our king. }
16... Qxe5 17. Nxe5 Be6
{ I believe we stand on the better side of equality. We have clear targets of attack, and no weaknesses. Also Black can forget about this ...g5 plan to cause problems to our king, now that the queens are traded! }
