[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Panov Attack: A Deeper Dive 5...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. cxd4 d5 4. Nc3
{ Since we have already done a very deep dive into the mainline Caro-Kann Exchange, we will focus only on the Reverse Panov in this ADVANCED Material section! }
4... c5 5. Nf3
{ We should develop our knight first and see how Black responds! We have good x-ray pressure on d5, so Black must be careful of dxc5, Qxd5 ideas already.   5.dxc5?!  It should be noted that we are not immediately winning the pawn on d5 due to:  5...d4⩱ }
5... Nc6 6. dxc5 d4
{ 6...Bxc5  Black cannot recapture with the bishop since:  7.Qxd5±  ...just wins a pawn!   6...Nf6  If Black defends d5 by developing their knight, we can in fact hang onto the pawn with:  7.Be3±  and solve the development of our light-squared bishop with g3, Bg2 next. }
7. Na4
{ Our knight appears a little loose at first, but due to the c-pawn having been moved, our queen is protecting it - so no need to worry about ...Qa5+ fork ideas.   For  7...Bxc5  @@StartBracket@@Black's best try@@EndBracket@@, and  7...Nf6?!  — please see the main section of the course! }
7... b5
{ This is an interesting try that has been played online a lot. However, it's not so good for Black, after: }
8. cxb6 axb6 9. e3 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 dxe3 11. Bxb4 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Rxa4
{ 12...Nxb4?  13.Bb5++-  White defends their hanging knight on a4 while also giving a check! White's king will get safe with O-O, while Black will suffer with an unsafe king, and a lack of development. }
13. Bc3
{ Material is equal, but White is much better. White has the bishop pair, and already has threats of Bb5 in the air.  We do not mind  13...exf2+  since after  14.Kxf2  ,  we open up the e-file for our rook, and our king is relatively safe on a dark square. }
