[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: Caro-Kann Reversed"]
[Black "Panov Attack: A Deeper Dive 5...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. cxd4 d5 4. Nc3
{ Since we have already done a very deep dive into the mainline Caro-Kann Exchange, we will focus only on the Reverse Panov in this ADVANCED Material section! }
4... c5 5. Nf3
{ We should develop our knight first and see how Black responds! We have good x-ray pressure on d5, so Black must be careful of dxc5, Qxd5 ideas already.   5.dxc5?!  It should be noted that we are not immediately winning the pawn on d5 due to:  5...d4⩱ }
5... Nf6
{ Here, Black defends d5, so  6.dxc5  no longer makes any sense @@StartBracket@@since we're not threatening Qxd5@@EndBracket@@.   Instead, we should pin the black knight, so we renew some threats of dxc5, followed by winning the d5-pawn. }
6. Bg5 Be6
{ A necessary move for Black, in order to strengthen the d5-pawn. We will continue in Caro Kann Reversed style!   6...Be7?!  7.dxc5!  Bxc5  8.Bxf6  Qxf6  9.Qxd5⩲  A pawn up is worth more than the bishop pair!   6...cxd4?!  7.Nxd4±  White has the greater development, and has already blockaded Black's Isolated Queen's Pawn.   6...Nc6?!  Please check the main course material for the analysis of 6...Nc6?! }
7. e3
{ It is already critical now for Black to play ...c4.   Otherwise, White will play Bb5+ with great pressure on Black's setup. }
7... c4
{ 7...Nc6?!  8.Bb5  Be7  as soon as the dark-squared bishop moves, we should force Black into losing a tempo   8...a6  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.O-O  Be7  As soon as the dark-squared bishop moves, we should force Black into losing a tempo.  11.dxc5!  Bxc5  12.Qa4±  Black cannot keep tabs on the weak c6-pawn, a6-pawn, and the knight on f6 @@StartBracket@@i.e. if the queen moves, Bxf6, ...gxf6 leads to a crippled pawn structure@@EndBracket@@.  9.dxc5!  Bxc5  10.O-O  O-O  Now that we're fully developed and our king is safe, it's time to capitalise on our activity:  11.Bxf6  Qxf6  12.Nxd5!  Black can try and fight back with:  12...Qxb2  But the tactics work out in our favour after:  13.Nc7!  Rad8  14.Qc1± }
8. Qa4+
{ Practically speaking, this is a great try. The d5-pawn will be weak for the rest of the game @@StartBracket@@with g3 Bg2 ideas to win it@@EndBracket@@, so it's likely Black will try and stay active rather than trade queens. However, trading queens is Black's best chance for equality. }
8... Qd7
{ 8...Nc6?!  I think ...Nc6 seems to be the most natural move, but immediately this gets punished by a nice tactic to remember. Since ...Nc6 and ...Be6 are on the board, we can look for a thematic tactic to punish this piece setup.  9.Bxc4!  dxc4  10.d5!  We will regain the piece with a more active position:  10...Bxd5  11.Bxf6!  Qxf6  12.Nxd5!  Qxb2  13.O-O  ±  Black may temporarily be a pawn up, but Black is two moves away from castling kingside, and the c4-pawn is very close to dropping. Black will be lucky to survive here. }
9. Bxf6 Qxa4 10. Nxa4 gxf6 11. Nc3
{ I like this immediate retreat to prevent Black gaining an initiative on the queenside with ...b5. The engine evaluates this position as equal, but I like our chances here.   We will follow up with g3, Bg2, with pressure on the black d5-pawn for the rest of the game. Not to mention the doubled isolated f-pawns will also give us chances in the endgame, I think we can be satisfied with this position @@StartBracket@@especially since there are many pitfalls for our opponents in order to reach this position@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) London System: 1...d5 Mainline"]
[Black "1...d5 London: 5...Qb6 (Black exchanges with 6...Qxb3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3
{ Having covered the Caro-Kann Reversed, it's time to study all of Black's other responses, besides the starting move 1...e5.   As mentioned in the introduction, we will be utilising the London System against all other responses, since its style and nature is in tune with the Caro-Kann Reversed Structures.   We will begin with Black's other most principled move, 1...d5. }
1... d5 2. d4
{ Just like in the Caro-Kann, we immediately take the centre with 2. d4. } 2...
Nf6 { 2...c5  We will cover this in '2...c5 Fireworks'. } 3. Bf4
{ Unlike in several Caro-Kann Reversed lines, we really have no problems whatsoever finding a home for our dark-squared bishop, and I'd like to recommend the signature London System move: Bf4!   As you can imagine, we will follow up this move with 4. e3, solidifying our pawn structure, now that our bishop has developed outside of the pawn chain. }
3... c5
{ We can consider this ...c5 push @@StartBracket@@alongside ...d5@@EndBracket@@ to be the mainline of the London System.   Since White has set-up more passively with c3, Black plays ambitiously to attack the centre immediately. However, you will see that in many cases Black's structure becomes over-extended, and we can capitalise on this! }
4. e3 Nc6
{ After our initial development of the bishop and the strengthening of our pawn chain with c3 and e3, White now has a choice between 3 moves: Nd2, Nf3, and h3.   We should base our decision on what plan of black's we are afraid of. Black's plans include: ...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@to win our bishop@@EndBracket@@, ...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@to target b2 and possibly our rook on a1 too after ...Qxb2@@EndBracket@@, and pushing an eventual ...e5 with the support of ...Bd6. With these considerations in mind, we should play 5. Nd2! }
5. Nd2
{ The reason why 5. Nd2 is our best option is because now our rook on a1 is free to move, so that lines involving ...Qb6 then ...Qxb2 are less effective. In addition, by not developing the knight to f3, Black is unable to play ...Nh5, since the knight will be loose and get captured on h5 by our queen!   At this moment, we reach our main fork in the road. Black has six @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ ways to play the position.   1@@EndBracket@@ The over-ambitious 'old mainline'  5...Qb6   2@@EndBracket@@ The natural 'new mainline'  5...Bf5   3@@EndBracket@@ The 'playing for ...e5' line starting with  5...e6   4@@EndBracket@@ The 'Carlsbad structure' line with  5...cxd4   5@@EndBracket@@ The harmless  5...g6  and finally   6@@EndBracket@@ The blunder  5...Nh5??   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1P3/PP3PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3?!  This is the old London mainline, which doesn't make much positional sense! We allow both of Black's main ideas to be effective @@StartBracket@@...Qb6 and ...Nh5@@EndBracket@@, while only limiting Black's third idea of ...Bd6 followed by ...e5 @@StartBracket@@the slowest of Black's three options@@EndBracket@@.    5...Nh5!  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  = This is not the end of the world since we get the open h-file. But ideally, we'd want to keep our dark-squared bishop when possible!   5...Qb6!  With the knight still on b1, our rook is temporarily trapped on a1. Now comes the very famous London System tactic for Black...  6.Qb3  c4!  7.Qc2  Bf5!!  Yikes! The bishop on ...f5 appears to be hanging, but if White takes it, Black is in fact winning after:  8.Qxf5??  Qxb2!  -+ We are in fact lost due to the rook on a1 being trapped!   This is why we should play 5. Nd2 instead of  5.Nf3  , to avoid this mess. }
5... Qb6
{ I consider this 'old mainline' to be over-ambitious for Black, since Black's structure often becomes overextended, thus allowing it to be easily attacked. Let's take a look: }
6. Qb3
{ We come to our first RULE of the London System: always meet ...Qb6 with Qb3! The reason being is that we neutralise the Black queen's activity, and we also never mind the queen trade.   We will see what happens after ...Qxb3 now. }
6... Qxb3 7. axb3 cxd4 8. exd4
{ This pawn structure is honestly a dream for us to play!   We will have easy play on the a-file, and our pieces will all be able to develop and improve very naturally. If you have doubts as to how to continue this position, I'd highly recommend taking a look at this Model Game now! }
*

