{ We never trade queen's on b6 @@StartBracket@@opening the a-file for them@@EndBracket@@. We much prefer Black to take us. If we get doubled b-pawns, the structural weakness is compensated for by the activity of the open a-file!   After dxc5, Black is given a choice: trade queens, or enter complications after  7...Qxc5  ,  Qxb7! }
7... Qxc5
{ Entering complications by avoiding a queen trade is, in fact, a mistake. } 8.
Qxb7 { Now Black's position collapses. } 8... Rc8 9. Nb3
{ The queen is almost trapped, with only one retreat square. } 9... Qb6
{ At this moment, we can win an exchange by force: } 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. Ba6
{ We now use our bishop pair to hunt down this rook. } 11... Rd8
{ 11...Ra8  12.Bb7  +- wins a piece! } 12. Bc7 Rd7 13. Bxb6
{ White is two clean pawns up, while Black has zero compensation or counterplay. }
