{ After our initial development of the bishop and the strengthening of our pawn chain with c3 and e3, White now has a choice between 3 moves: Nd2, Nf3, and h3.   We should base our decision on what plan of black's we are afraid of. Black's plans include: ...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@to win our bishop@@EndBracket@@, ...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@to target b2 and possibly our rook on a1 too after ...Qxb2@@EndBracket@@, and pushing an eventual ...e5 with the support of ...Bd6. With these considerations in mind, we should play 5. Nd2! }
5. Nd2
{ The reason why 5. Nd2 is our best option is because now our rook on a1 is free to move, so that lines involving ...Qb6 then ...Qxb2 are less effective. In addition, by not developing the knight to f3, Black is unable to play ...Nh5, since the knight will be loose and get captured on h5 by our queen!   At this moment, we reach our main fork in the road. Black has six @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ ways to play the position.   1@@EndBracket@@ The over-ambitious 'old mainline'  5...Qb6   2@@EndBracket@@ The natural 'new mainline'  5...Bf5   3@@EndBracket@@ The 'playing for ...e5' line starting with  5...e6   4@@EndBracket@@ The 'Carlsbad structure' line with  5...cxd4   5@@EndBracket@@ The harmless  5...g6  and finally   6@@EndBracket@@ The blunder  5...Nh5??   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1P3/PP3PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3?!  This is the old London mainline, which doesn't make much positional sense! We allow both of Black's main ideas to be effective @@StartBracket@@...Qb6 and ...Nh5@@EndBracket@@, while only limiting Black's third idea of ...Bd6 followed by ...e5 @@StartBracket@@the slowest of Black's three options@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5!  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  =   This is not the end of the world since we get the open h-file. But ideally, we'd want to keep our dark-squared bishop when possible!   5...Qb6!  With the knight still on b1, our rook is temporarily trapped on a1. Now comes the very famous London System tactic for Black...  6.Qb3  c4!  7.Qc2  Bf5!!  Yikes! The bishop on ...f5 appears to be hanging, but if White takes it, Black is in fact winning after:  8.Qxf5??  Qxb2!  -+ we are in fact lost due to the rook on a1 being trapped!   This is why we should play 5. Nd2 instead of  5.Nf3  , to avoid this mess. }
5... Bf5
{ Nowadays, this is the most popular move, hence I am considering it to be the 'new mainline'. Black establishes their light-squared bishop on this strong diagonal before White can prevent it @@StartBracket@@unlike the old mainline where we can prevent the bishop developing to f5 with  5...Qb6  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2!  g6  8.e4!  @@EndBracket@@.   I'd like to introduce our second RULE of the London: as soon as the light-squared bishop develops, we meet this with Qb3! }
6. Qb3
{ Since we are attacking the b7-pawn, Black must decide how to defend it, and will most likely choose between ...Qb6, ...Qd7, and ...Qc8.   The first of these options is dubious which we will examine next.  6...Qd7  has the drawback of potentially being vulnerable to Bb5 & Nf3-e5 ideas.   And finally,  6...Qc8  has the drawback of being on the c-file, where we can play for a quick c4 and Rc1. The lines following ...Qd7 and ...Qc8 run quite deep, so I have provided further analysis of these positions in the Advanced Section of the course! }
6... Qd7
{ So the current theory suggests the following plan: White will develop naturally @@StartBracket@@with Ngf3, Be2 etc.@@EndBracket@@, and if Black doesn't do anything significant, we break the centre with c4.   If Black ever pushes ...c4 themselves, we drop back to Qd1, and will later undermine Black's queenside with b3. The downside of this plan is that this b3 plan to break Black's pawn chain is extremely nuanced. In many cases, playing b3 at the wrong time can lead to an immediate loss @@StartBracket@@see the variation after  7.Ngf3  c4  8.Qd1  e6  9.b3?  @@EndBracket@@   For this reason, I would like to propose a different plan. Since the queen is on d7, we will begin with Ngf3, in case Black is caught napping, and allows a quick attack of Bb5! and Ne5! If Black instead plays actively with 7...c4, we will not retreat to d1, but advance to b5!? The idea being that we will safely be able to undermine Black's pawn structure with b3, since ...b5 is blocked by our queen!   Let's examine these lines: }
7. Ngf3 c4 8. Qb5
{ The main move by far is Qd1, where the theory continues real deep. Instead, we sidestep all of this with this rare move, which has a very clear plan: we want to play b3 to undermine Black's pawn chain, without allowing Black to play ...b5 with nasty ...b4! ideas @@StartBracket@@see the variation after  8.Qd1  e6  9.b3?  @@EndBracket@@.   Against most of Black's moves, we will be playing b3 next, with a fine position. For instance, I was able to beat an FM online after 13 moves in this line!   There is only one critical reply for Black, so this is what we will examine here:  8.Qd1  e6  9.b3?  Here, the thematic b3 fails due to the following sequence:  9...b5!  10.a4  b4!  -/+ This is a well known combination for Black, which leads to an advantage for Black! }
8... a6
{ This is the most critical move in the position. Any slow move can be met with b3, leading to a great position for White. }
9. Qb6
{ We have prevented Black from playing ...b5, and we will follow up with b3 next to undermine Black's overextended c4-pawn.   We will end the analysis here for now — if you'd like to look deeper into this line, please check out the ADVANCED Material section of the course! }
*

