6. Qb3
{ Since we are attacking the b7-pawn, Black must decide how to defend it, and will most likely choose between ...Qb6, ...Qd7, and ...Qc8.   The first of these options is dubious which we will examine next.  6...Qd7  has the drawback of potentially being vulnerable to Bb5 & Nf3-e5 ideas.   And finally,  6...Qc8  has the drawback of being on the c-file, where we can play for a quick c4 and Rc1. The lines following ...Qd7 and ...Qc8 run quite deep, so I have provided further analysis of these positions in the ADVANCED Material section of the course! }
6... Qc8
{ When Black plays 6...Qc8, our plan is easy to remember. Since the queen isn't on d7, it doesn't make much sense to continue with Nf3-e5 and Bb5 @@StartBracket@@since there's no ...Qd7 as a target@@EndBracket@@, and instead with the queen on c8, we can target it immediately by opening the c-file after 7. c4!   7.Ngf3  c4   @@StartBracket@@  7...e6  = is also completely fine here since there's no Bb5, Ne5 ideas.@@EndBracket@@  8.Qd1   @@StartBracket@@  8.Qb5?!  with 6...Qc8 having been played instead of 6...Qd7, our Qb5 ideas don't work due to the immediate  8...Bd7!  =+. This is why Qb5 is only a strong response to 6...Qd7.@@EndBracket@@  8...b5  = Here the theory continues. Instead of 8...b5, Black also has 8...h6 and 8...e6.   While Black has a definite advantage on the queenside, it's unclear where White's compensation is. I'd prefer to avoid these lines with 8. Qd1 in both 6...Qc8 and 6...Qd7 lines. }
7. c4
{ Black has two principled responses here.   7...e6  leads to Black getting an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@, and  7...dxc4  leads to us getting an IQP.   Since the analysis runs quite deep in all these lines, I will save it for the ADVANCED Material section! Meanwhile, I will show you one natural variation for Black that in fact is dubious for them to play! }
7... cxd4 8. cxd5 dxe3 9. fxe3
{ We weaken our structure, but have great activity to compensate. } 9... Nd8
10. e4 { Black cannot capture due to  10...Nxe4  11.Nxe4  Bxe4  12.Qa4+  . } *

