{ We can consider this ...c5 push @@StartBracket@@alongside ...d5@@EndBracket@@ to be the mainline of the London System.   Since White has setup more passively with c3, Black plays ambitiously to attack the centre immediately. However, you will see that in many cases Black's structure becomes over-extended, and we can capitalise on this! }
4. e3 Nc6
{ After our initial development of the bishop and the strengthening of our pawn chain with c3 and e3, White now has a choice between 3 moves: Nd2, Nf3, and h3.   We should base our decision on what plan of black's we are afraid of. Black's plans include: ...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@to win our bishop@@EndBracket@@, ...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@to target b2 and possibly our rook on a1 too after ...Qxb2@@EndBracket@@, and pushing an eventual ...e5 with the support of ...Bd6. With these considerations in mind, we should play 5. Nd2! }
5. Nd2
{ The reason why 5. Nd2 is our best option is because now our rook on a1 is free to move, so that lines involving ...Qb6 then ...Qxb2 are less effective. In addition, by not developing the knight to f3, Black is unable to play ...Nh5, since the knight will be loose and get captured on h5 by our queen!   At this moment, we reach our main fork in the road. Black has six @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ ways to play the position.   1@@EndBracket@@ The over-ambitious 'old mainline'  5...Qb6   2@@EndBracket@@ The natural 'new mainline'  5...Bf5   3@@EndBracket@@ The 'playing for ...e5' line starting with  5...e6   4@@EndBracket@@ The 'Carlsbad structure' line with  5...cxd4   5@@EndBracket@@ The harmless  5...g6  and finally   6@@EndBracket@@ The blunder  5...Nh5??   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1P3/PP3PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3?!  This is the old London mainline, which doesn't make much positional sense! We allow both of Black's main ideas to be effective @@StartBracket@@...Qb6 and ...Nh5@@EndBracket@@, while only limiting Black's third idea of ...Bd6 followed by ...e5 @@StartBracket@@the slowest of Black's three options@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5!  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  =   This is not the end of the world since we get the open h-file. But ideally, we'd want to keep our dark-squared bishop when possible!   5...Qb6!  With the knight still on b1, our rook is temporarily trapped on a1. Now comes the very famous London System tactic for Black...  6.Qb3  c4!  7.Qc2  Bf5!!  Yikes! The bishop on ...f5 appears to be hanging, but if White takes it, Black is in fact winning after:  8.Qxf5??  Qxb2!  -+ we are in fact lost due to the rook on a1 being trapped!   This is why we should play 5. Nd2 instead of  5.Nf3  , to avoid this mess. }
5... e6
{ Black is playing for the plan of ...Bd6, ...e5. Therefore, we should play Ngf3 next to take extra control over the e5-square. }
6. Ngf3 Bd6
{ Whenever our opponent plays ...Bd6, we should consider three options:   1@@EndBracket@@ capture  2@@EndBracket@@ ignore  3@@EndBracket@@ retreat   When in doubt, I believe it's best to retreat since if Black captures us, we can recapture with the h-pawn and gain an open file. In addition, if Black plays ...Nh5, we can then choose to capture on d6 @@StartBracket@@having provoked an awkward knight on h5!@@EndBracket@@, or allow Black to take us with the knight, in which we still open the h-file.   Capturing would also be fine here, followed by simple development with Be2, O-O, h3 etc.   Here, ignoring doesn't make sense, because although ...Bxf4 exf4 increases our grip over the e5-square, here, Black has played ...c5, thus the undermining of our weakened d4-pawn @@StartBracket@@after exf4@@EndBracket@@, is very much on the cards! }
7. Bg3 O-O 8. Be2
{ A rare, but simple, move!  You're welcome to investigate the more ambitious  8.Bd3  ,  but this requires more concrete theory, as well as the ability to be able to execute a complicated kingside attack! If you are going to look into this, make sure to study/understand the theory after  8...Re8  9.Ne5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.f4  Qb6  . We cover this line in our course with 8. Be2, which is a much more easy-to-play version than with 8. Bd3. }
8... cxd4
{ 8...b6  9.O-O  The resulting positions are quite complex, so I've left the analysis in the ADVANCED Material section of the course! But ultimately, this position isn't overly critical, so we shouldn't be too worried here!  In addition to Black's plan to play for ...e5, this 5...e6 variation allows for Black to try for ...cxd4 in arguably the most favourable conditions possible.   Let's see why! }
9. exd4
{ After exd4, Black is aiming for a minority attack on the queenside, which has some potential strength already since our bishop has no control over the b8-square @@StartBracket@@therefore ...Rb8, ...b5 has the potential to be played@@EndBracket@@.   On the brightside, since Black's light-squared bishop was unable to develop outside of the pawn chain, this means we will have good attacking chances on the kingside with an eventual Bd3, eyeing up the h7-pawn.   I was considering whether to analyse the forthcoming minority attack from Black here, or leave it for the ADVANCED Material section of the course. And I think all in all, it would actually be best for you to experience losing to a minority attack first-hand, to see how difficult it is to defend against Black's queenside pawns marching down the board! Then, I'd recommend studying these 8...cxd4 lines in the ADVANCED Material section of the course, to see my recommendation of how to confidently meet this exact minority attack of Black's!   In addition, if you've been studying this course in order of the chapters given, you'll already have a pretty decent understanding of the minority attack, so maybe you'll surprise me and already expertly defend against the incoming queenside pawns! 😁  Perhaps it's too extreme of me to suggest to my readers to lose at chess! But as they say, 'the master has failed more times than the beginner has even tried...' }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) London System: 1...d5 Mainline"]
[Black "1...d5 London: 5...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3
{ Having covered the Caro-Kann Reversed, it's time to study all of Black's other responses, besides the starting move 1...e5.   As mentioned in the introduction, we will be utilising the London System against all other responses, since its style and nature is in tune with the Caro-Kann Reversed Structures.   We will begin with Black's other most principled move, 1...d5. }
1... d5 2. d4
{ Just like in the Caro-Kann, we immediately take the centre with 2. d4. } 2...
Nf6 { 2...c5  we will cover this in '2...c5 Fireworks'. } 3. Bf4
{ Unlike in several Caro-Kann Reversed lines, we really have no problems whatsoever finding a home for our dark-squared bishop, and I'd like to recommend the signature London System move: Bf4!   As you can imagine, we will follow up this move with 4. e3, solidifying our pawn structure, now that our bishop has developed outside of the pawn chain. }
3... c5
{ We can consider this ...c5 push @@StartBracket@@alongside ...d5@@EndBracket@@ to be the mainline of the London System.   Since White has set-up more passively with c3, Black plays ambitiously to attack the centre immediately. However, you will see that in many cases Black's structure becomes over-extended, and we can capitalise on this! }
4. e3 Nc6
{ After our initial development of the bishop and the strengthening of our pawn chain with c3 and e3, White now has a choice between 3 moves: Nd2, Nf3, and h3.   We should base our decision on what plan of black's we are afraid of. Black's plans include: ...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@to win our bishop@@EndBracket@@, ...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@to target b2 and possibly our rook on a1 too after ...Qxb2@@EndBracket@@, and pushing an eventual ...e5 with the support of ...Bd6. With these considerations in mind, we should play 5. Nd2! }
5. Nd2
{ The reason why 5. Nd2 is our best option is because now our rook on a1 is free to move, so that lines involving ...Qb6 then ...Qxb2 are less effective. In addition, by not developing the knight to f3, Black is unable to play ...Nh5, since the knight will be loose and get captured on h5 by our queen!   At this moment, we reach our main fork in the road. Black has six @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ ways to play the position.   1@@EndBracket@@ The over-ambitious 'old mainline'  5...Qb6   2@@EndBracket@@ The natural 'new mainline'  5...Bf5   3@@EndBracket@@ The 'playing for ...e5' line starting with  5...e6   4@@EndBracket@@ The 'Carlsbad structure' line with  5...cxd4   5@@EndBracket@@ The harmless  5...g6  and finally   6@@EndBracket@@ The blunder  5...Nh5??   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1P3/PP3PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3?!  This is the old London mainline, which doesn't make much positional sense! We allow both of Black's main ideas to be effective @@StartBracket@@...Qb6 and ...Nh5@@EndBracket@@, while only limiting Black's third idea of ...Bd6 followed by ...e5 @@StartBracket@@the slowest of Black's three options@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5!  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  =   This is not the end of the world since we get the open h-file. But ideally, we'd want to keep our dark-squared bishop when possible!   5...Qb6!  With the knight still on b1, our rook is temporarily trapped on a1. Now comes the very famous London System tactic for Black...  6.Qb3  c4!  7.Qc2  Bf5!!  Yikes! The bishop on ...f5 appears to be hanging, but if White takes it, Black is in fact winning after:  8.Qxf5??  Qxb2!  -+ we are in fact lost due to the rook on a1 being trapped!   This is why we should play 5. Nd2 instead of  5.Nf3  , to avoid this mess. }
5... cxd4
{ This is quite a rare move, but we should still understand how to meet it!   When possible, we will recapture with the e-pawn, to create an imbalance. }
6. exd4
{ At this moment, we enter a typical Carlsbad structure.   Black is likely to play for a minority attack @@StartBracket@@which we'll know very well if we've just finished studying the Caro-Kann Reversed Exchange lines!@@EndBracket@@, while we will play in the centre and on the kingside. Here, we have retained all our minor pieces, and can therefore attack Black quickly before they get a minority attack going. Let's see how!   6.cxd4=  This is not ideal since our knight is developed to d2, rather than c3. Despite the tempo advantage, I believe Black has no problem equalising here. }
6... Bf5
{ Preventing us from playing Bd3, the best diagonal for our bishop in the Carlsbad structure. }
7. Qb3
{ We follow our rule: whenever Black develops their light-squared bishop, we target the weakened b7-pawn immediately with Qb3.   As you can see, this is very similar to our 5...Bf5 lines, but there is one critical difference: There is no black c5-pawn, and no white e3-pawn. As a result, the critical lines involving Black pushing ...c4 are no longer present, and therefore this entire line is very chill! There is more theory here, but to be completely honest, I wouldn't spend time analysing this 5...cxd4 further, since it is already rare, and we can simply develop naturally.   With our understanding of previous analysis, I believe we should feel comfortable with handling the resulting positions! }
