1. c3
{ Having covered the Caro-Kann Reversed, it's time to study all of Black's other responses, besides the starting move 1...e5.   As mentioned in the introduction, we will be utilising the London System against all other responses, since its style and nature is in tune with the Caro-Kann Reversed Structures.   We will begin with Black's other most principled move, 1...d5. }
1... d5 2. d4
{ Just like in the Caro-Kann, we immediately take the centre with 2. d4. } 2...
Nf6 { 2...c5  we will cover this in '2...c5 Fireworks'. } 3. Bf4
{ Unlike in several Caro-Kann Reversed lines, we really have no problems whatsoever finding a home for our dark-squared bishop, and I'd like to recommend the signature London System move: Bf4!   As you can imagine, we will follow up this move with 4. e3, solidifying our pawn structure, now that our bishop has developed outside of the pawn chain. }
3... c5
{ We can consider this ...c5 push @@StartBracket@@alongside ...d5@@EndBracket@@ to be the mainline of the London System.   Since White has set-up more passively with c3, Black plays ambitiously to attack the centre immediately. However, you will see that in many cases Black's structure becomes over-extended, and we can capitalise on this! }
4. e3 Nc6
{ After our initial development of the bishop and the strengthening of our pawn chain with c3 and e3, White now has a choice between 3 moves: Nd2, Nf3, and h3.   We should base our decision on what plan of black's we are afraid of. Black's plans include: ...Nh5 @@StartBracket@@to win our bishop@@EndBracket@@, ...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@to target b2 and possibly our rook on a1 too after ...Qxb2@@EndBracket@@, and pushing an eventual ...e5 with the support of ...Bd6. With these considerations in mind, we should play 5. Nd2! }
5. Nd2
{ The reason why 5. Nd2 is our best option is because now our rook on a1 is free to move, so that lines involving ...Qb6 then ...Qxb2 are less effective. In addition, by not developing the knight to f3, Black is unable to play ...Nh5, since the knight will be loose and get captured on h5 by our queen!   At this moment, we reach our main fork in the road. Black has six @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ ways to play the position.   1@@EndBracket@@ The over-ambitious 'old mainline'  5...Qb6   2@@EndBracket@@ The natural 'new mainline'  5...Bf5   3@@EndBracket@@ The 'playing for ...e5' line starting with  5...e6   4@@EndBracket@@ The 'Carlsbad structure' line with  5...cxd4   5@@EndBracket@@ The harmless  5...g6  and finally   6@@EndBracket@@ The blunder  5...Nh5??   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1P3/PP3PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nf3?!  This is the old London mainline, which doesn't make much positional sense! We allow both of Black's main ideas to be effective @@StartBracket@@...Qb6 and ...Nh5@@EndBracket@@, while only limiting Black's third idea of ...Bd6 followed by ...e5 @@StartBracket@@the slowest of Black's three options@@EndBracket@@  5...Nh5!  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  =   This is not the end of the world since we get the open h-file. But ideally, we'd want to keep our dark-squared bishop when possible!   5...Qb6!  With the knight still on b1, our rook is temporarily trapped on a1. Now comes the very famous London System tactic for Black...  6.Qb3  c4!  7.Qc2  Bf5!!  Yikes! The bishop on ...f5 appears to be hanging, but if White takes it, Black is in fact winning after:  8.Qxf5??  Qxb2!  -+ we are in fact lost due to the rook on a1 being trapped!   This is why we should play 5. Nd2 instead of  5.Nf3  , to avoid this mess. }
5... g6
{ Black can play with a fianchetto against our London setup.   Since ...g6 can be played at any point @@StartBracket@@before, or after, move 5@@EndBracket@@, rather than give you concrete lines at each move, I will offer a simple way to meet this fianchetto system that can be played at any time Black plays for ...g6 ! }
6. Ngf3 { We will begin by developing the rest of our pieces. } 6... Bg7 7. Be2
O-O 8. O-O Qb6 9. Qb3 c4 10. Qa3
{ Since Black's dark-squared bishop has developed to g7, this gives us another square for our queen to move to upon the ...c4 push. With the queen now on a3, we are ready to support the b3 push, while Black cannot play for their thematic ...b5, ...b4 counterplay @@StartBracket@@since their own queen blocks this pawn advance@@EndBracket@@. Black should probably play to reroute their bishop to f8, but this takes several moves too many! }
10... Re8 11. b3
{ Black's overextended pawn chain will now be undermined, while Black is still two tempi away from harassing our queen with their dark-squared bishop! To avoid dropping a pawn, it is likely that Black will play ...cxb3, in which we can reply with axb3 @@StartBracket@@opening the a-file, and taking towards the centre@@EndBracket@@. And in this case, as soon as Black threatens ...Bf8, and ...e6 @@StartBracket@@or even ...e5!?@@EndBracket@@, then we can simply retreat our queen to the b2-square in good time to avoid any trouble. Later we can prepare our rooks on the queenside for a timely c4 push. }
