[Round "?"]
[White "6) London System: 1...d5 Mainline"]
[Black "1...d5 London: 4...Qb6 (with 6...Bf5?? - London Trap Fail)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3
{ Having covered the Caro-Kann Reversed, it's time to study all of Black's other responses, besides the starting move 1...e5.   As mentioned in the introduction, we will be utilising the London System against all other responses, since its style and nature is in tune with the Caro-Kann Reversed Structures.   We will begin with Black's other most principled move, 1...d5. }
1... d5 2. d4
{ Just like in the Caro-Kann, we immediately take the centre with 2. d4. } 2...
Nf6 { 2...c5  we will cover this in '2...c5 Fireworks'. } 3. Bf4
{ Unlike in several Caro-Kann Reversed lines, we really have no problems whatsoever finding a home for our dark-squared bishop, and I'd like to recommend the signature London System move: Bf4!   As you can imagine, we will follow up this move with 4. e3, solidifying our pawn structure, now that our bishop has developed outside of the pawn chain. }
3... c5
{ We can consider this ...c5 push @@StartBracket@@alongside ...d5@@EndBracket@@ to be the mainline of the London System.   Since White has set-up more passively with c3, Black plays ambitiously to attack the centre immediately. However, you will see that in many cases Black's structure becomes over-extended, and we can capitalise on this! }
4. e3 Qb6
{ Black has also tried this early 4...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@rather than 4...Nc6, 5...Qb6@@EndBracket@@ — but it doesn't achieve much.   At first glance, it looks as if Black can pull off the 'famous London tactic' that we saw when White plays 5. Nf3?! instead of 5. Nd2! — but here it doesn't work! Let's see why. }
5. Qb3
{ We are always happy to offer this queen trade, since the doubled pawns allow for our rook to be active on the a-file.   For further analysis of the queen exchange, remind yourself of these lines. }
5... c4 6. Qc2 Bf5
{ At first glance, it looks like the 'famous London tactic' is working just the same here! The idea being that the bishop on f5 is immune to Qxf5, since ...Qxb2 will win a rook @@StartBracket@@and thus the game!@@EndBracket@@. However, Black has overlooked one critical detail of this position, and we can in fact take this hanging bishop! }
7. Qxf5 Qxb2 8. Qc8#
{ BOOM! We have checkmate — which is only available to us since the knight on b8 has yet to develop.   This is why Black should complete their development with the principled 4...Nc6, before trying to attack us with 4...Qb6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) London System: 1...d5 Mainline"]
[Black "1...d5 London: 4...Qb6 (with 6...g6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3
{ Having covered the Caro-Kann Reversed, it's time to study all of Black's other responses, besides the starting move 1...e5.   As mentioned in the introduction, we will be utilising the London System against all other responses, since its style and nature is in tune with the Caro-Kann Reversed Structures.   We will begin with Black's other most principled move, 1...d5. }
1... d5 2. d4
{ Just like in the Caro-Kann, we immediately take the centre with 2. d4. } 2...
Nf6 { 2...c5  we will cover this in '2...c5 Fireworks'. } 3. Bf4
{ Unlike in several Caro-Kann Reversed lines, we really have no problems whatsoever finding a home for our dark-squared bishop, and I'd like to recommend the signature London System move: Bf4!   As you can imagine, we will follow up this move with 4. e3, solidifying our pawn structure, now that our bishop has developed outside of the pawn chain. }
3... c5
{ We can consider this ...c5 push @@StartBracket@@alongside ...d5@@EndBracket@@ to be the mainline of the London System.   Since White has set-up more passively with c3, Black plays ambitiously to attack the centre immediately. However, you will see that in many cases Black's structure becomes over-extended, and we can capitalise on this! }
4. e3 Qb6
{ Black has also tried this early 4...Qb6 @@StartBracket@@rather than 4...Nc6, 5...Qb6@@EndBracket@@ - but it doesn't achieve much.   At first glance, it looks as if Black can pull off the 'famous London tactic' that we saw when White plays 5. Nf3?! instead of 5. Nd2! - but here it doesn't work! Let's see why. }
5. Qb3
{ We are always happy to offer this queen trade, since the doubled pawns allow for our rook to be active on the a-file.   For further analysis of the queen exchange, see the analysis after 4...Nc6 / 5...Qb6. }
5... c4 6. Qc2 g6
{ Now, since you've made it to the end of our 1...d5 London System theory, I'd like to share with you a little secret that London players like to keep to themselves...   ...which is that there is a very strong @@StartBracket@@and rare@@EndBracket@@ line in this 4...Qb6 line — which is 6...g6! here! Unlike the 5...Qb6 lines, we cannot meet ...g6 with e4, since we have yet to develop our knight onto d2.   As a result, Black will be able to achieve their desired ...Bf5 plan! }
7. Nd2
{ If Black doesn't play ...Bf5 immediately, we can play e4 next @@StartBracket@@just like in the 5...Qb6 lines@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Bf5
{ 7...Nc6?!  8.e4!  +/= and we transpose to lines previously covered! } 8. Qc1
Nc6
{ This may be the most critical attempt of Black's to equalise in the 1...d5 mainline of the London System. Black has a queenside space advantage and has established the light-squared bishop on f5.   But before you lose all hope, let's develop our pieces on the kingside, and then discuss the resulting position! }
9. h3
{ A useful move to throw in first in order to preserve our dark-squared bishop in case of any ...Nh5. }
9... Bg7 10. Ngf3 O-O 11. Be2 Rfc8 12. O-O
{ We have completed our development, so what now? Ultimately, we would like to undermine Black's pawn structure with e4 or b3. However, the ...Bf5 stands very strong, making it difficult to achieve both plans @@StartBracket@@for instance, we may want Rb1, but can't, due to this annoying bishop@@EndBracket@@.   Therefore our plan is very logical: we want to remove this light-squared bishop! }
12... Qd8
{ This is theory, and makes sense. The queen on b6 has done its job, so now gets out of the way for a queenside expansion with ...b5 soon! }
13. g4
{ This may be the one and only time that I'll advocate for weakening your kingside! But as mentioned previously, this bishop on f5 is simply too strong. g4 puts an end to it! }
13... Be6 14. Re1
{ My stockfish engine gives this position as +0.1, so I'll be generous with the +/= annotation.   But regardless of the objective evaluation here, there is certainly a game! Next we want to play Bf1, with ideas of pushing e4 soon. We should also consider breaking with b3 as well. So long as we remember to kick Black's bishop on f5 off the b1-h7 diagonal, we will have an interesting game ahead of us! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) London System: KID with ...e5"]
[Black "KID: with 9...e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6
{ Having covered the mainline with 1...d5, we come to the second most popular setup you'll come across: The King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@.  Very often, the King's Indian player will try to play the KID against everything except for 1. e4 — so that includes 1. d4, 1. Nf3, and 1. c4 — sticking to one setup.   As much as I admire this mentality, since the KID is very predictable, we can in fact exploit this mindset. Very often, Black will aim for the same kind of kingside attack, which often works well due to a closed centre @@StartBracket@@arising from 1. d4 mainlines@@EndBracket@@. However, we will not be closing the centre @@StartBracket@@unless it is on our terms@@EndBracket@@, and therefore these attacks are far more likely to fail. It should be noted that the typical way to combat a kingside @@StartBracket@@flank@@EndBracket@@ attack, is to strike back in the centre @@StartBracket@@which is easier to achieve when the centre is open@@EndBracket@@!   Overall, I've very happy with our remedy against the King's Indian, and we shouldn't have anything to fear! }
3. Bf4
{ When we play against the KID, the first RULE to remember is: We should focus on developing our kingside to completion first, and then worry about the rest! }
3... Bg7 4. e3
{ 4...Nh5  5.Be5!  f6  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  +/= Black has an ugly pawn on f6, and we have an open h-file to play with.   The normal setup for Black against the open h-file would be to play with ...f7, ...g6, ...h5, but this isn't possible now with g6 having been weakened! }
4... d6 5. h3
{ Now that Be5 isn't possible, it is important to play h3 to give our bishop a retreat square on h2, in case of ...Nh5. }
5... O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2
{ Black has gotten on with their King's Indian Defence setup, while we have set up our bog-standard London setup.   Here, it is important to emphasise that Black has two main options here: either to play for an eventual ...c5 OR to play for an eventual ...e5. Since we treat both of these plans differently, I have separated the lines into two separate chapters! }
7... Re8 8. O-O e5
{ For the sake of understanding the plans and ideas of our setup, I will suggest a sub-optimal move here! In most cases when ...e5 is played, it is best to retreat the bishop to h2 @@StartBracket@@which is what we will look into next@@EndBracket@@. However, in this exact position, we can actually do BETTER and already win a pawn after dxe5!   We will investigate these nuances in the ADVANCED Material section of the course, but for now, let's get back to understanding our basic setup! }
9. Bh2
{ At this moment, Black can go for a few different options. Either, they can push ...e4 @@StartBracket@@which we welcome with open arms!@@EndBracket@@, play for ...f5 @@StartBracket@@dutch style attack@@EndBracket@@, or play in the centre with ...c6 @@StartBracket@@aiming for ...d5@@EndBracket@@. In all cases, our strategy is to play on the queenside with c4! }
9... e4 10. Nfd2
{ This is why it's important to develop our kingside first!   In fact, in most cases against the KID, we leave our knight undeveloped on b1 temporarily, until we know exactly where we want to develop it! }
10... d5
{ 10...c6  11.Bxd6!  This pawn blunder is VERY common. The bishop often gets forgotten about on h2! }
11. c4
{ Imagine this position with reverse colours. We have a French Defence where our 'bad bishop' is developed outside of the pawn chain. Also Black has fianchettoed in this setup which makes little sense, since Black will not be able to initiate as dangerous of a kingside attack this way. }
11... c6 12. Nc3
{ We will put great pressure on Black's queenside and the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@with b4, Qb3 ideas@@EndBracket@@, and our king will be safe. Black also cannot easily push ...f5, since the knight on f6 has nowhere to go. Black is strategically lost already. }
