[White "7) London System: KID with ...e5"]
[Black "KID: with 9...c6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6
{ Having covered the mainline with 1...d5, we come to the second most popular setup you'll come across: The King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@.  Very often, the King's Indian player will try to play the KID against everything except for 1. e4 — so that includes 1. d4, 1. Nf3, and 1. c4 — sticking to one setup.   As much as I admire this mentality, since the KID is very predictable, we can in fact exploit this mindset. Very often, Black will aim for the same kind of kingside attack, which often works well due to a closed centre @@StartBracket@@arising from 1. d4 mainlines@@EndBracket@@. However, we will not be closing the centre @@StartBracket@@unless it is on our terms@@EndBracket@@, and therefore these attacks are far more likely to fail. It should be noted that the typical way to combat a kingside @@StartBracket@@flank@@EndBracket@@ attack, is to strike back in the centre @@StartBracket@@which is easier to achieve when the centre is open@@EndBracket@@!  Overall, I've very happy with our remedy against the King's Indian, and we shouldn't have anything to fear! }
3. Bf4
{ When we play against the KID, the first RULE to remember is: We should focus on developing our kingside to completion first, and then worry about the rest! }
3... Bg7 4. e3
{ 4...Nh5  5.Be5!  f6  6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  +/= Black has an ugly pawn on f6, and we have an open h-file to play with.   The normal set up for Black against the open h-file would be to play with ...f7, ...g6, ...h5, but this isn't possible now with g6 having been weakened! }
4... d6 5. h3
{ Now that Be5 isn't possible, it is important to play h3 to give our bishop a retreat square on h2, in case of ...Nh5. }
5... O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2
{ Black has gotten on with their King's Indian Defence setup, while we have set up our bog-standard London setup.   Here, it is important to emphasise that Black has two main options here: either to play for an eventual ...c5 OR to play for an eventual ...e5. Since we treat both of these plans differently, I have separated the lines into two separate chapters! }
7... Re8 8. O-O e5
{ For the sake of understanding the plans and ideas of our setup, I will suggest a sub-optimal move here! In most cases when ...e5 is played, it is best to retreat the bishop to h2 @@StartBracket@@which is what we will look into next@@EndBracket@@. However, in this exact position, we can actually do BETTER and already win a pawn after dxe5!   We will investigate these nuances in the ADVANCED Material section, but for now, let's get back to understanding our basic setup! }
9. Bh2
{ At this moment, Black can go for a few different options. Either, they can push ...e4 @@StartBracket@@which we welcome with open arms!@@EndBracket@@, play for ...f5 @@StartBracket@@Dutch-style attack@@EndBracket@@, or play in the centre with ...c6 @@StartBracket@@aiming for ...d5@@EndBracket@@. In all cases, our strategy is to play on the queenside with c4! }
9... c6
{ This move is terribly weakening, since even if Black gets in ...d5, our dark-squared bishop will have great control over the h2 - b8 diagonal! }
10. c4 exd4 11. exd4 d5
{ Black just about managed to get in d5, but let's see how the resulting position goes! }
12. Nc3 dxc4 13. Bxc4
{ In lines where Black has managed to play ...d5 where we've already played c4, we might find ourselves in an Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@ position!   In this instance, I think we have a great version of an IQP for several reasons: 1@@EndBracket@@ We have all minor pieces still on the board 2@@EndBracket@@ We have great control over the c5- and e5-squares, and can try infiltrate on them. }
13... Nb6 14. Bb3 Nbd5 15. Na4
{ As you can see, White is already looking to infiltrate on the c5- and e5-squares. Also, White has avoided trading pieces with 14. Bb3 and 15. Na4!   This is good middlegame play, and the resulting position can easily collapse for Black.   For instance:  15...b6  16.Ne5!  Bb7  17.Rc1  +/- with great activity! }
