[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) London System: KID with ...c5"]
[Black "KID: with 6...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Bf4
{ When we play against the KID, the first RULE to remember is: We should focus on developing our kingside to completion first, and then worry about the rest! }
3... Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3
{ Having discussed the King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@ with ...e5, it's time to see how to approach Black's setup when they play for ...c5. Black can play for ...c5 immediately @@StartBracket@@with no support from ...b6 or ...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@.   Much more common is for Black to play both ...b6 and ...Nbd7 before breaking with ...c5.   Finally, Black can play ...b6 @@StartBracket@@without ...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@ before playing ...c5, with the idea to develop the black knight to c6 rather than d7.   We will examine the lines in this order! }
6... c5
{ When Black plays ...c5 without any support from ...b6 or ...Nbd7, then I like to capture on ...c5! }
7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Nbd2
{ So what is going on here?   The pawn structure is symmetrical, except for the fact we have a London style development on the kingside, as opposed to Black's fianchettoed kingside. To me, I feel that White has the better squares for their pieces, and so long as we can keep the b2- + c3-pawns in place, we will restrict Black's dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@whereas our dark-squared bishop will be very strong now that there's no black pawn on d6!@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Qb6
{ 8...a6  9.a4!  We should restrict Black from playing ...b5, otherwise they can push further with ...b4, and undermine our b2- &  c3-pawns. If these pawns get disrupted, the dark-squared bishop on g7 will become much stronger! }
9. Qb3
{ As discussed extensively in 1...d5 lines, we should meet ...Qb6 with Qb3! }
9... Qxb3 10. axb3
{ Despite having Nxb3 as an option, I prefer axb3! We are more active with the open a-file, and the weakness of b3 is well defended by our knight on d2. }
10... Be6 11. Bc4 Bxc4 12. Nxc4 b5 13. Nb6
{ Of course, Black doesn't have to blunder with 12...b5, but I wanted to show you the practical benefits of having the open a-file.   Feel free to explore 12...Nc6 deeper yourself @@StartBracket@@Black's most principled line of play@@EndBracket@@ — but you'll see that very often Black's pawn structure is a lot looser than it appears at first glance, and with very normal active play, White very often gains a clear advantage! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) London System: KID with ...c5"]
[Black "KID: with 6...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Bf4
{ When we play against the KID, the first RULE to remember is: We should focus on developing our kingside to completion first, and then worry about the rest! }
3... Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3
{ Having discussed the King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@ with ...e5, it's time to see how to approach Black's setup when they play for ...c5. Black can play for ...c5 immediately @@StartBracket@@with no support from ...b6 or ...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@.   Much more common is for Black to play both ...b6 and ...Nbd7 before breaking with ...c5.   Finally, Black can play ...b6 only before playing ...c5, with the idea to develop the black knight to c6 rather than d7.   We will examine the lines in this order! }
6... Nbd7 7. Be2
{ Here Black has the choice to play for ...e5 or ...c5. We examined ...e5 positions in the last chapter, so time to check out ...c5 lines! }
7... b6
{ 7...c5  There is no need to analyse '...c5 with ...Nbd7 only' as some separate analysis, since Black really doesn't have any choice but to follow up with ...b6 and ...Bb7 next!   So lines will transpose to our mainline after  8.O-O  b6  9.Bh2  Bb7  . }
8. O-O Bb7 9. Bh2
{ Since Black hasn't setup with either ...e5 or ...c5 yet, I like to stay fully flexible with our setup! Bh2 is always a useful moves in these variations, since we avoid Black playing ...e5 with tempo on our bishop, and the bishop is very sneaky on h2, constantly pressuring this h2-b8 diagonal for the remainder of the game. }
9... c5
{ Black has committed to the ...c5 setup, so it's time to understand Black's plan!   Typically, Black will aim for one of two plans:   1. Playing in the centre with ...Re8 and ...e5   2. Playing for ...Rc8, ...Rc7, ...Qa8!?, ...Rfc8 with play down the c-file, and long range pressure on the centre.   Against our setup, plan 1 makes little sense, since our dark-squared bishop is not a target on f4, and our light-squared bishop isn't a target on d3, where pushing the black pawn from e7-e5-e4 @@StartBracket@@fork!@@EndBracket@@ could be a worry. So we will only have to be actively prepared to face plan 2.   9...Re8!?  An interesting plan to switch to ...e5 setups without playing ...c5. See our previous chapter on this setup! }
10. Nbd2
{ Developing our final minor piece! Now it is time to understand our plan. What I'd recommend is we continue to make improving moves, until it is clear what plan Black is aiming for. Then, we can play precisely in the centre to take over, and gain the advantage! }
10... Rc8
{ 10....Re8  As I said already, this plan with ...Re8 and ...e5 is really nothing to worry about, so I've just covered it briefly here!  11.a4!  Just like in the mainline, after completing development, I think this a4-push is always a useful addition against 'KID with ...c5' setups.  11...a6  12.Re1  e5  13.Nc4!  with the black pawns on both ...c5 and ...e5, Black's pawn structure is even weaker than usual!  13...Qc7  14.dxe5  dxe5  15.Nd6!  +/- After the rook on e8 moves away, next we will take the light-squared bishop, gaining the bishop pair advantage.   This poor play by Black is by no means forced, but in fact, it is very common to see when Black is out of their depth against the London @@StartBracket@@which is also very common to see!@@EndBracket@@. }
11. a4
{ Having completed our basic development, I like to start our middlegame play by throwing in a4. If Black doesn't respond with ...a6, then we get great pressure on the queenside with a5! }
11... a6
{ 11...Qc7  12.a5!  bxa5  13.Qa4  +/= Black's a5-pawn will drop, and the a7-pawn will be a weakness all game!   11...Rc7  12.a5!  Now Black's main development plan is prevented!  12...Qa8  13.axb6  Nxb6  +/=   Of course,  13...axb6  is impossible since the queen will hang to  14.Rxa8!  After 13...Nxb6, the a7-pawn will be a weakness all game! }
12. Re1
{ Another simple improving move! Since Black will be aiming for ...Rc7, ...Qa8 with pressure on the long diagonal, it is often useful to place our bishop on f1 where it overprotects the g2-pawn. }
12... Rc7 13. Bf1 Qa8 14. c4
{ A timely push! We have sufficiently improved our pieces, and are now preparing to shut down Black's ...Qa8 ...Bb7 battery with d5!  For the record, a lot of London System players play for the b4 break, or the e4 break, both of which are just really bad plans here! Having played countless games from the Black side — which in many ways is a 'Reverse Reti' — the only plan that ever caused me trouble was when White bravely pushed c4 here! }
14... cxd4
{ Normally, Black would like to capture here so that when d5 comes, they at least have the free c5-square for their knight to jump to. However, since we timed c4 to perfection @@StartBracket@@i.e. right after Black played ...Qa8, and before Black is able to improve their position with ...Rfc8@@EndBracket@@, Black's position is immediately under serious pressure!   14...Ne4  15.d5!  This is the point of our c4 move — to play d5 and shut down Black's ...Qa8 ...Bb7 battery.   In this exact position, there is no time to take for Black to capture the pawn on b2 since their knight is hanging on e4!  15...Nxd2  16.Qxd2  +/-   14...e6?  15.Bxd6!  +/- I've lost count of the number of times Black has blundered this pawn against me.   With everything else going on, Black often forgets the strength of our dark-squared bishop hiding on h2! }
15. exd4
{ Let's take note of this position.   Black's e7-pawn is immediately hanging. Our g2-pawn is secured which means our knight on f3 is free to roam. Black's d6-pawn is pinned, and Black's b6-pawn is potentially weak to Qb3 ideas. Black will struggle to avoid this position completely collapsing!   Also, do take note of the timing of our c4 push. If we are too slow to push c4 @@StartBracket@@i.e. Black has already developed ...Rfc8@@EndBracket@@, Black can consider defending e7 with ...Nf8!? @@StartBracket@@with a discovered defence from the rook on c7@@EndBracket@@.   Of course, this is not the end of the world, but playing c4 before Black completes their setup will put even more stress on Black's position! }
15... Nb8
{ 15...Re8  16.a5  bxa5  17.Rxa5  +/- With ideas of b4 and Qa1 incoming! } 16.
Qb3 { Whenever this knight from d7 moves, the b6-pawn is always a target! }
16... Qa7 17. d5
{ Closing down Black's light-squared bishop and knight on b8 in a single move! Black's only active plan here is to try and unravel their cramped position by bringing the knight from b8 to c5. But this doesn't even work after: }
17... Re8 { ...in order to play ...Nbd7 without dropping the e7-pawn! } 18. Re3
Nbd7 19. Rae1
{ Developing our rooks to the open file to pressure Black's most serious weakness. It's as easy as that! }
19... Nc5 20. Qa3
{ b4 is coming next, and Bxd6 is even a threat. Black has nothing to hope for here, and White is much better! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) London System: KID with ...c5"]
[Black "KID: with 6...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Bf4
{ When we play against the KID, the first RULE to remember is: We should focus on developing our kingside to completion first, and then worry about the rest! }
3... Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3
{ Having discussed the King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@KID@@EndBracket@@ with ...e5, it's time to see how to approach Black's setup when they play for ...c5. Black can play for ...c5 immediately @@StartBracket@@with no support from ...b6 or ...Nbd7@@EndBracket@@.   Much more common is for Black to play both ...b6 and ...Nbd7 before breaking with ...c5.   Finally, Black can play ...b6 only before playing ...c5, with the idea to develop the black knight to c6 rather than d7.   We will examine the lines in this order! }
6... b6 7. Be2 Bb7 8. O-O c5 9. Bh2 Nc6
{ It is also fairly common to see this approach with developing the b8-knight to c6, rather than d7.   The main drawback of this is that the knight is not able to protect the b6-pawn, which can often become weak. We should play this position in the same way we'd play the mainline: }
10. Nbd2 Rc8 11. a4 a6 12. Re1 Rc7 13. Bf1 Qa8
{ So far Black has played in the same manner as our mainline with 6...Nbd7, but with the knight on c6 instead of d7.   Rather than push  14.c4  @@StartBracket@@which might in fact justify the knight being on c6, giving Black the b4-square and pressure on our d4-pawn@@EndBracket@@, we should instead head straight to pressuring the b6-pawn with: }
14. Nc4 Nd7
{ The most commonly tried move in this position!   14...Na5!?  In my analysis, I found that Black only has one real way to continue the position @@StartBracket@@which for the record, has never been found!@@EndBracket@@.   This 14...Na5 is an interesting try — aiming to trap the knight after Nxb6 — however, the tactics work out in our favour. After all, we haven't played any unprincipled moves, so why shouldn't this work out for us?  15.Nxb6!  Qa7  16.dxc5!  The d-pawn is pinned by our bishop on h2 to the rook on c7.  16...Rxc5  17.b4!  +/- I doubt our opponents will ever find 14...Na5, but it's good to know that these trapping attempts don't work out for Black. After  17...Qxb6  18.bxc5  ,  White will finish the complications an exchange up! }
15. d5
{ Another drawback of the knight being on c6. There is far less control over the d5-square for Black, and we can already shut down this ...Qa8 ...Bb7 battery. }
15... Na5
{ 15...Nce5?  16.Nfxe5  Of course, ...Nxe5 is impossible here since the b6-pawn is still loose!  16...Bxe5  17.Nxe5  Nxe5  18.c4 }
16. Nxa5 bxa5 17. e4
{ Black will suffer in this cramped position. ...e6 will be very difficult to achieve since we have long range pressure on the d6-pawn from our bishop on h2. We would aim to play c4 soon to further cramp Black's position, and begin to target the weak black a5-pawn! As we can see from the resulting play in this variation, it is clear that Black's best option is to develop the b8-knight via ...Nbd7 rather than ...Nc6.   This concludes our analysis on the King's Indian, and we can now attend to other critical setups that Black can try! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) London System: 1...c5 Exchange Slav"]
[Black "Exchange Slav: 6...Qb6?!"]
[Result "*"]

{ Having looked at typical London play against the conventional  1...d5  ,  and King's Indian Defence setups, it is time to prepare ourselves against the early ...c5 lines.    We begin with the immediate 1...c5. Most of our opponents playing 1...c5 are likely to be Sicilian players, but we will not be transposing to any Sicilians. Instead, we will continue with our 2. d4, which will most likely enter an Exchange Slav  (probably the opposite to what a Sicilian player would hope for!)  . If Black avoids an Exchange Slav, they will likely give up any hope for equality very fast.   Let's take a look! }
1. c3 c5 2. d4
{ In this chapter on 1...c5, I will only be analysing 2...cxd4, since  2...d5  or  2...Nf6  will transpose to our next chapter @@StartBracket@@on 2...c5 lines@@EndBracket@@. }
2... cxd4
{ 2...d5  3.Bf4  transposes to '2...c5 Fireworks'.   2...Nf6  3.Bf4  transposes to '2...c5 Fireworks'.   2...Qb6?!  Here, the really early ...Qb6 doesn't make much sense since b2 isn't even undefended yet. But on the other hand, Black has successfully prevented us from playing a London with Bf4! Thankfully, we have very simple and principled play to just take the centre with  3.e4  ,  and enjoy a pleasant position!   There aren't any good setups for Black, but here's one example of how White can quickly take over:  3...Nf6  4.e5  Nd5  5.c4  Nb4  6.d5  +/= so long as we avoid trades @@StartBracket@@to ensure Black stays as cramped as possible@@EndBracket@@, we should realise a huge advantage by after some normal developing moves! }
3. cxd4 d5
{ The Exchange Slav.   At first glance, we might feel miserable about our prospects of playing a symmetrical position. How are we ever going to prove our advantage? Well in fact, it's actually quite simple! Due to our tempo advantage, we will be able to call the shots when the positions inevitably become tactical. }
4. Nc3
{ A bit like in the Caro-Kann Reversed Exchange Variation, I like to begin our development with Nc3.   Of course,  4.Bf4  is completely fine too. }
4... Nc6
{ Black could also play  4...Nf6  ,  but it doesn't really matter. Both sides will develop their pieces, and then we will see how to play the resulting position! }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bf4
{ Here, I'd like to break down the following positions into 3 lines you need to know:   1@@EndBracket@@ Black mirrors with  6...Bf5  ,  in which case we follow our rule of meeting ...Bf5 with Qb3! After  7.Qb3  ,  Black can play the inaccurate  7...Qb6?!  ,  or the precise  7...Na5  .   2@@EndBracket@@ Black plays the inaccurate  6...Qb6?!  right away.   3@@EndBracket@@ Black plays the trendy  6...a6  . }
6... Qb6
{ Players who ambitiously develop their queen to b6 are often the kinds of players that will be hoping to capture our pawn on b2.  7.Qb3  Qxb3  8.axb3=  not terrible, but no ideal either! We'd much prefer for the b-pawns not to be isolated. }
7. a3
{ This is the best move in the position AND the best move to exploit ...Qxb2.   Our idea is to take control of the key b4-square @@StartBracket@@especially in positions when ...Qxb2 has been played@@EndBracket@@. We will aim to get Na4-c5 if Black doesn't take our b2-pawn. }
7... Qxb2
{ The path to exploit ...Qxb2 is not the easiest to memorise. However, I would like you to remember that this position is WINNING for White. So with this in mind, it may be easier to find the winning moves over-the-board. In any case, let's see how this precise win comes about! }
8. Na4 { The black queen only has one safe square. } 8... Qb5
{ We would love to play e3 here to trap the queen. However, there is the a5-square the queen can still make use of! Therefore, we should play: }
9. Bd2
{ e3 is coming next and the queen is trapped. If our opponent is very strong, they may find the one defence: }
9... Qa6 10. e3 b5
{ Black has successfully saved their own queen from getting captured, however, the resulting position is massively in our favour! }
11. Nc5 Qb6 12. a4
{ We immediately pressure Black's queenside. Since Black has made several moves with the queen, White makes use of the extra tempi to crash through! }
12... bxa4 13. Qxa4
{ Black is far too underdeveloped to survive the incoming onslaught! } *

