{ Having looked at typical London play against the conventional  1...d5  ,  and King's Indian Defence setups, it is time to prepare ourselves against the early ...c5 lines.    We begin with the immediate 1...c5. Most of our opponents playing 1...c5 are likely to be Sicilian players, but we will not be transposing to any Sicilians. Instead, we will continue with our 2. d4, which will most likely enter an Exchange Slav  (probably the opposite to what a Sicilian player would hope for!)  . If Black avoids an Exchange Slav, they will likely give up any hope for equality very fast.   Let's take a look! }
1. c3 c5 2. d4
{ In this chapter on 1...c5, I will only be analysing 2...cxd4, since  2...d5  or  2...Nf6  will transpose to our next chapter @@StartBracket@@on 2...c5 lines@@EndBracket@@. }
2... cxd4
{ 2...d5  3.Bf4  transposes to '2...c5 Fireworks'.   2...Nf6  3.Bf4  transposes to '2...c5 Fireworks'.   2...Qb6?!  Here, the really early ...Qb6 doesn't make much sense since b2 isn't even undefended yet. But on the other hand, Black has successfully prevented us from playing a London with Bf4! Thankfully, we have very simple and principled play to just take the centre with  3.e4  ,  and enjoy a pleasant position!   There aren't any good setups for Black, but here's one example of how White can quickly take over:  3...Nf6  4.e5  Nd5  5.c4  Nb4  6.d5  +/= so long as we avoid trades @@StartBracket@@to ensure Black stays as cramped as possible@@EndBracket@@, we should realise a huge advantage by after some normal developing moves! }
3. cxd4 d5
{ The Exchange Slav.   At first glance, we might feel miserable about our prospects of playing a symmetrical position. How are we ever going to prove our advantage? Well in fact, it's actually quite simple! Due to our tempo advantage, we will be able to call the shots when the positions inevitably become tactical. }
4. Nc3
{ A bit like in the Caro-Kann Reversed Exchange Variation, I like to begin our development with Nc3.   Of course,  4.Bf4  is completely fine too. }
4... Nc6
{ Black could also play  4...Nf6  ,  but it doesn't really matter. Both sides will develop their pieces, and then we will see how to play the resulting position! }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bf4
{ Here, I'd like to break down the following positions into 3 lines you need to know:   1@@EndBracket@@ Black mirrors with  6...Bf5  ,  in which case we follow our rule of meeting ...Bf5 with Qb3! After  7.Qb3  ,  Black can play the inaccurate  7...Qb6?!  ,  or the precise  7...Na5  .   2@@EndBracket@@ Black plays the inaccurate  6...Qb6?!  right away.   3@@EndBracket@@ Black plays the trendy  6...a6  . }
6... Bf5 7. Qb3 Qb6
{ This is the most natural move in the position, but the resulting position works out in our favour!   8...Qd7  is in fact an even worse try for Black after:  9.e3  e6  10.Ne5!  Nxe5  11.dxe5!  And wherever the knight moves, White will follow up with Bb5! skewering the queen to the king. }
8. Qxb6 axb6 9. a3
{ If we compare our setups, we can notice one clear difference. Black can't really play ...Nb4, but we can play Nb5! If Black develops with ...e6, we can also develop very naturally with e3, Be2, Rc1, O-O etc. }
9... Nb4
{ Seeing that the a-pawn is pinned, I can imagine a lot of players trying for this tactic on the c2-square. }
10. Rc1
{ The typical way to deal with the pressure on c2.  10.axb4??  Rxa1+  Be careful not to take free pieces that our opponents give us, without having a serious inspection of the entire board! -+ }
10... Nc6 { 10...Nc2+  11.Kd1  +/- The knight is trapped on c2. } 11. Nb5 Rc8
12. e3 e6 13. Bc7
{ Rather than use the c7-square for a knight, we can also make use of the square with our bishop. The doubled isolated b-pawns will likely both drop! }
*

