{ By playing Bf4 here, we transpose to an interesting sideline of the London System.   Normally, White would have the pawn on e3 instead of c3 here, but c3 is definitely playable, and far less explored!   The lines will get pretty sharp, but very often in our favour! If our opponents accidentally stumble into this position, we have very decent chances of winning out of the opening, since we'll have studied the complications beforehand! }
3... Qb6
{ If our opponents play ...Qb6 here, they are likely to be an over-ambitious opponent! It is likely that they have studied the same positions with e3 instead of c3 in the position, but since these positions become very sharp, it's risky to play 3...Qb6 here without concrete knowledge!   3...d5  We'd welcome this chance to transpose to our 1...d5 mainlines, the biggest reason being that we'll have more experience there, so a greater chance to outplay our opponent in the opening stage of the game!  4.e3  Nc6  5.Nd2  Qb6  6.Qb3  We have transposed to our 1...d5 mainlines. }
4. Nd2
{ This is the best move, and the start of some very sharp continuations.   Normally, this would be a deal-breaker for me, but I like to think that if you have only one sharp line in every repertoire, you can remember the variation as 'the sharp line', and just make sure to memorise it! In addition, lots of the continuations here lead to an instant advantage for White, so I think it's worth putting in the effort for this!   4.Qb3?!  Now hold on a second... didn't you say that we should 'always meet ...Qb6 with Qb3'? I did indeed say this previously in the course, but as you get more experienced as a chess player, you will find that all rules in chess have exceptions!   I would love to recommend this simple remedy of meeting ...Qb6 with Qb3 here — but it doesn't quite work since Black can play  4...Qxb3  5.axb3  cxd4!  6.cxd4  Nc6!  7.e3  Nb4!  =+ where Black's developed knights cause immediate problems to White's setup.   Thankfully, we have a great alternative to 4. Qb3 in the 2...c5 lines following 1...Nf6, which I'm very excited to recommend to you now! }
4... Qxb2
{ This is the move we'd love to see, since Black is one natural looking move away from being completely lost. }
5. e4
{ Here we take the full centre! Black will most likely feel horrid regarding their queen's positioning, and they'll want to get their queen out of trouble ASAP. If Black just retreats to ...Qb6, they may feel that their pawn up may not be enough to compensate their lack of development, so given that they were greedy enough to take our b2-pawn, they may try and grab the c3-pawn too... }
5... Qxc3
{ Black has in fact fallen into a trap, and their position is likely to get even worse! }
6. Rc1
{ If Black starts to panic here and wants out, the most natural retreating move for the queen is to play  6...Qa5?  , but this leads to a quick death after:  7.Rxc5!  Qd8  8.Bc7!  +- }
6... Qxd4 7. Be3
{ This is a tricky move to find, since we are moving a developed piece twice in the opening.   That's why we need to memorise it! However, it is well worth knowing, since it is the key move to start off a beautiful tactical sequence!   Wherever the queen moves, the queen is lost! }
7... Qb4 8. Bxc5 Qa5 9. Bb6 { A very powerful double attack! } 9... Qxb6 10.
Rxc8+ Qd8 11. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ White is a queen up for a rook and two pawns. Given that Black will never be able to castle, we should have very good winning chances here. }
*

