[Result "*"]

{ Having now looked at typical London play against the conventional  1...d5  ,  King's Indian Defence setups, and the immediate  1...c5  ,  it is time to prepare ourselves against lines with 2...c5.   For lines starting with  1...Nf6  / 2...c5,  these lines will typically be chosen by Benoni / Benko players, or perhaps anti-London players who have foreseen our plan with 1. c3 is to enter a London System, and are aiming for a quick ...Qb6.   As for the lines starting with  1...d5  / 2...c5, these are likely to be 1. d4 players, or again, anti-London players who are aiming for a quick and critical ...Qb6.    Just as a warning, this chapter will involve the sharpest lines of our repertoire — so be ready for a good memory workout! For those with bad memory  (like me)  , a good way to view these lines is by remembering that these 2...c5 lines are the 'sharp variations' of the repertoire.   The rest of the course can be played more or less on the understanding of plans and ideas. However, against Black's most critical try, we need to meet them with a critical response, so here it is! }
1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 c5
{ For the record, I think we will see this 2...c5 less frequently than you'd think, since our opponents may be afraid of us playing  3.dxc5  ,  followed by 4. b4, to support the c5-pawn. I've looked into these lines myself and don't think it's worth it @@StartBracket@@and prefer our thematic 3. Bf4@@EndBracket@@, but the opponent doesn't know what to expect! }
3. Bf4
{ By playing Bf4 here, we transpose to an interesting sideline of the London System.   Normally, White would have the pawn on e3 instead of c3 here, but c3 is definitely playable, and far less explored!   The lines will get pretty sharp, but very often in our favour! If our opponents accidentally stumble into this position, we have very decent chances of winning out of the opening, since we'll have studied the complications beforehand! }
3... Qb6
{ If our opponents play ...Qb6 here, they are likely to be an over-ambitious opponent! It is likely that they have studied the same positions with e3 instead of c3 in the position, but since these positions become very sharp, it's risky to play 3...Qb6 here without concrete knowledge!   3...d5  We'd welcome this chance to transpose to our 1...d5 mainlines, the biggest reason being that we'll have more experience there, so a greater chance to outplay our opponent in the opening stage of the game!  4.e3  Nc6  5.Nd2  Qb6  6.Qb3  We have transposed to our 1...d5 mainlines. }
4. Nd2
{ This is the best move, and the start of some very sharp continuations.   Normally, this would be a deal-breaker for me, but I like to think that if you have only one sharp line in every repertoire, you can remember the variation as 'the sharp line', and just make sure to memorise it! In addition, lots of the continuations here lead to an instant advantage for White, so I think it's worth putting in the effort for this!   4.Qb3?!  Now hold on a second... didn't you say that we should 'always meet ...Qb6 with Qb3'? I did indeed say this previously in the course, but as you get more experienced as a chess player, you will find that all rules in chess have exceptions!   I would love to recommend this simple remedy of meeting ...Qb6 with Qb3 here — but it doesn't quite work since Black can play  4...Qxb3  5.axb3  cxd4!  6.cxd4  Nc6!  7.e3  Nb4!  =+ where Black's developed knights cause immediate problems to White's setup.   Thankfully, we have a great alternative to 4. Qb3 in the 2...c5 lines following 1...Nf6, which I'm very excited to recommend to you now! }
4... d5
{ Given how tricky  4...cxd4  and  4...Qxb2  are to navigate for Black, I can imagine a lot of experienced players deciding to avoid complications, and play the more standard 4...d5 instead. }
5. Qb3
{ Do you remember the discussion we had about why 4. Nd2 was chosen instead of the principled 4. Qb3 ? On 4. Qb3, we would face difficulties dealing with the doubled isolated b-pawns, but now, we already have a knight on d2 developed! This means we can meet any ...Qxb3 with Nxb3 to avoid our pawn structure being too badly crippled. }
5... Qxb3 6. Nxb3
{ 6.axb3?!  cxd4  7.cxd4  =+ We get to avoid playing this position with the isolated, doubled b-pawns! }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4
{ We have the slightly better position, since our pieces are more active. The knight on b3 is well placed, eyeing up the weak c5-square. Since we are also threatening to dominate the c-file with Rc1, Black is mostly playing the logical ...Nc6 here. }
7... Nc6 8. e3 Bf5
{ If Black tries to play actively @@StartBracket@@while behind in development@@EndBracket@@, their position can quickly crumble. For instance: }
9. Rc1 Nb4 10. a3 Nd3+ 11. Bxd3 Bxd3 12. Nc5 Bf5 13. Nxb7
{ Of course, 9...Nb4?! is by no means forced, but this is a good example of how our pieces can quickly activate, jump to action, and take over the position! }
