{ Do you remember the discussion we had about why 4. Nd2 was chosen instead of the principled 4. Qb3 ? On 4. Qb3, we would face difficulties dealing with the doubled isolated b-pawns, but now, we already have a knight on d2 developed! This means we can meet any ...Qxb3 with Nxb3 to avoid our pawn structure being too badly crippled. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxb6 axb6 7. cxd4
{ Now we're the ones to be playing against the isolated b-pawns. In general, we're fine here, but there is one critical line we have to know: }
7... Nc6 { Playing for a quick ...Nb4, while hitting our d4-pawn with tempo. }
8. e3 Nb4 9. Rc1 Nxa2 10. Ra1 Ra5
{ Since the knight is pinned to the rook, Black will most likely want to stabilise their rook. However, we don't allow the rook to rest! }
11. Nb3
{ Here, White is much better unless Black finds the precise combination to bail out: }
11... Nb4 12. Rxa5
{ 12.Nxa5!?  is a more ambitious try to play for an advantage, which I have covered in the ADVANCED Material section. }
12... bxa5 13. Nxa5
{ White is slightly more active, but the position is objectively equal. } *

