[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) London System: 2...c5 Fireworks"]
[Black "1...Nf6 2...c5: An Early 3...cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

{ Having now looked at typical London play against the conventional  1...d5  ,  King's Indian Defence setups, and the immediate  1...c5  ,  it is time to prepare ourselves against lines with 2...c5.   For lines starting with  1...Nf6  / 2...c5,  these lines will typically be chosen by Benoni / Benko players, or perhaps anti-London players who have foreseen our plan with 1. c3 is to enter a London System, and are aiming for a quick ...Qb6.   As for the lines starting with  1...d5  / 2...c5, these are likely to be 1. d4 players, or again, anti-London players who are aiming for a quick and critical ...Qb6.    Just as a warning, this chapter will involve the sharpest lines of our repertoire — so be ready for a good memory workout! For those with bad memory  (like me)  , a good way to view these lines is by remembering that these 2...c5 lines are the 'sharp variations' of the repertoire.   The rest of the course can be played more or less on the understanding of plans and ideas. However, against Black's most critical try, we need to meet them with a critical response, so here it is! }
1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 c5
{ For the record, I think we will see this 2...c5 less frequently than you'd think, since our opponents may be afraid of us playing  3.dxc5  ,  followed by 4. b4, to support the c5-pawn. I've looked into these lines myself and don't think it's worth it @@StartBracket@@and prefer our thematic 3. Bf4@@EndBracket@@, but the opponent doesn't know what to expect! }
3. Bf4
{ By playing Bf4 here, we transpose to an interesting sideline of the London System.   Normally, White would have the pawn on e3 instead of c3 here, but c3 is definitely playable, and far less explored!   The lines will get pretty sharp, but very often in our favour! If our opponents accidentally stumble into this position, we have very decent chances of winning out of the opening, since we'll have studied the complications beforehand! }
3... cxd4
{ Our opponents can also try ...cxd4 before ...Qb6, which will lead to a different position, since we don't have our Nc4! @@StartBracket@@with tempo on the queen on b6@@EndBracket@@ resource when the black queen has yet to develop to b6! In this section, I will offer a simple remedy to this line.   There is a way to play more ambitiously against ...cxd4, but the lines are extremely sharp — so I'll cover it in the ADVANCED Material section of the course! }
4. cxd4 Qb6
{ At first glance, this queen development looks very tough to meet, since there is immediate pressure on both our b2- and d4-pawns. But White has a couple ways of meeting it — setting a trap with Qc1 @@StartBracket@@which I'll recommend here@@EndBracket@@, and developing quickly with Nc3 @@StartBracket@@which I'll recommend in the ADVANCED Material section of the course@@EndBracket@@.   4...d5  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bf5  7.e3  transposes to 1...c5 lines. }
5. Qc1
{ Setting a little trap!   5.Nc3!?  Going for quick development is an ambitious try for White that will give White good chances for an advantage. However, the lines are very sharp, so I've analysed this position further in the ADVANCED Material section of the course. }
5... Nc6
{ Black must develop the knight from b8 immediately to avoid a catastrophic loss of their light-squared bishop on c8!   5...Qxd4??  would be a lovely blunder for our opponents to fall into!  6.Qxc8#  . }
6. e3 d5 7. Nc3 Bf5 8. Nf3
{ Here, White is plain equal. But that doesn't mean the game will end in a draw. It is likely that we will have more experience of these structures than our opponents, and will find small ways to improve our position, or pick up on small ways our opponents are weakening theirs.   I would recommend you examine the various moves here that Black can try, and see how Stockfish approaches Black's natural development. I'd like to give you an example here of what can quickly go wrong for Black if they're not careful: }
8... e6 9. Be2 Be7 10. O-O O-O
{ Since our bishop covers the b8-square, I like the plan of bringing a knight to c5 to pressure the b7-pawn! }
11. Na4 Qa5 12. Nc5 b6
{ A natural move to try and remove the strong knight on c5. But this would weaken the black knight on c6! }
13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. Qxc6
{ White wins a pawn! Of course, Black has many ways to deviate before blundering this pawn, and with precise play, can reach equality.   If this is a concern for you, I recommend checking out the ADVANCED Material section of the course where I cover the ambitious 5. Nc3 instead of 5. Qc1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
