[Round "?"]
[White "10) London System: 2...c5 Fireworks"]
[Black "1...d5 2...c5: 3...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

{ Having now looked at typical London play against the conventional  1...d5  ,  King's Indian Defence setups, and the immediate  1...c5  ,  it is time to prepare ourselves against lines with 2...c5.   For lines starting with  1...Nf6  / 2...c5,  these lines will typically be chosen by Benoni / Benko players, or perhaps anti-London players who have foreseen our plan with 1. c3 is to enter a London System, and are aiming for a quick ...Qb6.   As for the lines starting with  1...d5  / 2...c5, these are likely to be 1. d4 players, or again, anti-London players who are aiming for a quick and critical ...Qb6.    Just as a warning, this chapter will involve the sharpest lines of our repertoire — so be ready for a good memory workout! For those with bad memory  (like me)  , a good way to view these lines is by remembering that these 2...c5 lines are the 'sharp variations' of the repertoire.   The rest of the course can be played more or less on the understanding of plans and ideas. However, against Black's most critical try, we need to meet them with a critical response, so here it is! }
1. c3 d5 2. d4 c5
{ Having covered the variations following 2...c5 when 1...Nf6 has been played, it's time to turn our attention to the 2...c5 lines that follow 1...d5!   You'll be glad to hear that the 2...c5 lines to come are not as sharp as the previous variations we've seen! }
3. Bf4
{ After our thematic 3.Bf4, Black will have the same options to play  3...Qb6  and  3...cxd4  , as well as the additional option of  3...Nc6  . We don't have to worry about  3...Nf6  since that will transpose to our 1...d5 mainlines!   3...Nf6  e3  and we are back in 1...d5 mainline territory! }
3... Qb6
{ Unlike our 2...c5 lines starting with 1...Nf6, we don't have to enter sharp complications here with  4.Nd2  .   Instead, we can follow our old rule of meeting ...Qb6 with Qb3! }
4. Qb3 Qxb3 5. axb3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Nc6 7. e3 Nb4
{ At first glance, this resulting position looks no different to the refutation to 4. Qb3 in the 2...c5 lines starting with 1...Nf6. However, there is a big difference: since the black knight is still on g8, we can safely defend the c2-square with 8. Kd2! }
8. Kd2
{ In the 2...c5 lines starting with 1...Nf6, Black could attack us immediately with 8...Ne4+. But this isn't possible here! }
8... Nf6 9. Nc3
{ We have a slight edge in this position, since Black will need to spend a move preventing our activity, which will then cause them to be behind in development.   We will also have increased tactical chances since we have the open a-file for our rook! }
9... Bf5
{ The most natural move in the position, but Black is not in time to freely develop like this! }
10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Ra6
{ Black's weak a7- and c6-pawns are immediately under pressure, while our weak b3-pawn can't be touched by a black rook coming to b8, since the b8-square is firmly under our control due to our bishop on f4. }
*

