[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) London System: 2...c5 Fireworks"]
[Black "1...d5 2...c5: 3...Nc6 (We Play Qxb6) #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ Having now looked at typical London play against the conventional  1...d5  ,  King's Indian Defence setups, and the immediate  1...c5  ,  it is time to prepare ourselves against lines with 2...c5.   For lines starting with  1...Nf6  / 2...c5,  these lines will typically be chosen by Benoni / Benko players, or perhaps anti-London players who have foreseen our plan with 1. c3 is to enter a London System, and are aiming for a quick ...Qb6.   As for the lines starting with  1...d5  / 2...c5, these are likely to be 1. d4 players, or again, anti-London players who are aiming for a quick and critical ...Qb6.    Just as a warning, this chapter will involve the sharpest lines of our repertoire — so be ready for a good memory workout! For those with bad memory  (like me)  , a good way to view these lines is by remembering that these 2...c5 lines are the 'sharp variations' of the repertoire.   The rest of the course can be played more or less on the understanding of plans and ideas. However, against Black's most critical try, we need to meet them with a critical response, so here it is! }
1. c3 d5 2. d4 c5
{ Having covered the variations following 2...c5 when 1...Nf6 has been played, it's time to turn our attention to the 2...c5 lines that follow 1...d5 !   You'll be glad to hear that the 2...c5 lines to come are not as sharp as the previous variations we've seen! }
3. Bf4
{ After our thematic 3.Bf4, Black will have the same options to play  3...Qb6  and  3...cxd4  , as well as the additional option of  3...Nc6  . We don't have to worry about  3...Nf6  since that will transpose to our 1...d5 mainlines!   3...Nf6  e3  and we are back in 1...d5 mainline territory!   I haven't gone into the theory of 3...Qb6, but I'd recommend you check out this Model Game  (after you finish studying this variation to the end)  to see how I went about dealing with it! }
3... Nc6
{ This move is surprisingly tricky! Black puts immediate pressure on our setup, and 4...Qb6 ideas will have a new dynamic to them! }
4. e3 Qb6
{ Since 4...Nf6  would simply transpose to our 1...d5 mainlines after   5.Nd2  , let's just examine this 4...Qb6 move.   Thankfully, we can follow our thematic rule of meeting ...Qb6 with Qb3! }
5. Qb3 c4
{ Now at this moment, I had a tough decision to make in our repertoire.   In short, I wanted to recommend  6.Qc2  since it's both thematic and objectively best. However, it's not as simple as that, and after some really crazy engine ideas of  6...e5!  followed by 7...Bf5! @@StartBracket@@the famous London System trap!@@EndBracket@@ — we really need to be extremely precise with our play. And unfortunately, if this didn't already sound problematic enough, these crazy engine ideas are actually well known theory at the higher levels!   So with all this in mind, I would like to suggest — ONLY in this line with a fast 3...Nc6 and 4...Qb6 — we play 6. Qxb6 now!   @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pp2pppp/1qn5/3p4/2pP1B2/1QP1P3/PP3PPP/RN2KBNR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qc2  e5!  The London trap with ...Bf5 doesn't quite work immediately, so Black needs to throw in this ...e5 idea  7.dxe5  Bf5!  Now the London trap is working, so White must decline the 'free' bishop  8.Qc1  g5!  9.Bg3  Taking on g5 is also possible, but even more complicated!  9...h5  10.h4  In fact, h3 is objectively better, but to me, with our understanding of the Caro-Kann, h4 feels far more natural  10...g4  11.Nd2  playing for a thematic e4 break to liquidate Black's centre.  11...Bg7!  12.e4  Bxe5!!  13.exf5  Bxg3!  14.fxg3  Qe3+  -/+ Somehow, Black has a great advantage, despite being a bishop down, and White making fairly natural moves, in my opinion.   Of course there is the chance that our opponent will miss moves like  11...Bg7  and  12...Bxe5  — but I can't in good conscience recommend such lines when they concretely fail!  Therefore, let's avoid such concrete positions that are counterintuitive, and let's understand what play we achieve after  6.Qxb6  . }
6. Qxb6 axb6
{ So typically we'd like to avoid these kinds of positions, since Black gets the open a-file, and an easy plan to push ...b5 and ...b4. The one advantage we have in this precise position compared to other situations involving Qxb6, ...axb6, is that Black is very underdeveloped on the kingside.   Therefore, before White has time to develop, we should strike! }
7. e4
{ If the knight had developed to f6 already, this immediate play in the centre would not be possible. }
7... e6 8. Nd2
{ I like this move a lot.   We prevent the immediate capture  8...dxe4  due to  9.Nxc4!  — targeting all of Black's weaknesses! }
8... b5
{ Black wants to protect c4, so that there's more chance to capture on e4. } 9.
g3
{ Since we are playing in the centre, our target should be the d5-pawn, thus our bishop is best placed fianchettoed, on the long diagonal, pressuring the d5-pawn. }
9... Nf6 10. Bg2
{ Black now has a choice. To complete development, or be ambitious with immediate queenside play.   Let's see both! }
10... b4 11. Ne2
{ The most logical development for our knight, since we don't want to block our bishop on g2. }
11... b5 12. O-O
{ We have completed development, and now we have to evaluate whether Black will achieve any permanent gains on the queenside.   In fact, Black has nothing, and can even become worse almost instantly if they continue to neglect their development, and push on, on the queenside! }
12... bxc3 13. bxc3 b4
{ Since Black is not fully developed, trying to attack is extremely risky. }
14. exd5 exd5 15. Nxc4
{ Black cannot recapture on c4 due to the knight on c6 hanging.   This is a perfect example of why development is an absolutely important factor to fulfill in the opening. }
