5. Qb3 c4
{ Now at this moment, I had a tough decision to make in our repertoire.   In short, I wanted to recommend  6.Qc2  since it's both thematic and objectively best. However, it's not as simple as that, and after some really crazy engine ideas of  6...e5!  followed by 7...Bf5! @@StartBracket@@the famous London System trap!@@EndBracket@@ — we really need to be extremely precise with our play. And unfortunately, if this didn't already sound problematic enough, these crazy engine ideas are actually well known theory at the higher levels!   So with all this in mind, I would like to suggest — ONLY in this line with a fast 3...Nc6 and 4...Qb6 - we play 6. Qxb6 now!   @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pp2pppp/1qn5/3p4/2pP1B2/1QP1P3/PP3PPP/RN2KBNR w KQkq — 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qc2  e5!  The London trap with ...Bf5 doesn't quite work immediately, so Black needs to throw in this ...e5 idea  7.dxe5  Bf5!  now the London trap is working, so White must decline the 'free' bishop  8.Qc1  g5!  9.Bg3  Taking on g5 is also possible, but even more complicated!  9...h5  10.h4  In fact, h3 is objectively better, but to me, with our understanding of the Caro-Kann, h4 feels far more natural  10...g4  11.Nd2  playing for a thematic e4 break to liquidate Black's centre.  11...Bg7!  12.e4  Bxe5!!  13.exf5  Bxg3!  14.fxg3  Qe3+  -/+ Somehow, Black has a great advantage, despite being a bishop down, and White making fairly natural moves, in my opinion.   Of course there is the chance that our opponent will miss moves like  11...Bg7  and  12...Bxe5  — but I can't in good conscience recommend such lines when they concretely fail!  Therefore, let's avoid such concrete positions that are counterintuitive, and let's understand what play we achieve after  6.Qxb6  . }
