{ So typically, we like to avoid these kinds of position, since Black gets the open a-file, and an easy plan to push ...b5 and ...b4. The one advantage we have in this precise position compared to other situations involving Qxb6, ...axb6, is that Black is very underdeveloped on the kingside.   Therefore, before White has time to develop, we should strike! }
7. e4
{ If the knight had developed to f6 already, this immediate play in the centre would not be possible. }
7... e6 8. Nd2
{ I like this move a lot.   We prevent the immediate capture  8...dxe4  due to  9.Nxc4!  — targeting all of Black's weaknesses! }
8... b5
{ Black wants to protect c4, so that there's more chance to capture on e4. } 9.
g3
{ Since we are playing in the centre, our target should be the d5-pawn, thus our bishop is best placed fianchettoed, on the long diagonal, pressuring the d5-pawn. }
9... Nf6 10. Bg2
{ Black now has a choice. To complete development, or be ambitious with immediate queenside play.   Let's see both! }
10... Be7 11. Ne2 O-O 12. O-O b4 13. Bg5
{ Creating a threat to win the d5-pawn after removing the defender of the knight on f6. }
13... Rd8
{ Therefore, Black must overprotect their pawn on d5 to retain equality! } 14.
e5 bxc3
{ 14...Nd7?  15.Bxe7  Nxe7  16.cxb4!  White can in fact hang onto the extra pawn! }
15. Nxc3 Nd7 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 17. b3
{ I can imagine a lot of players handling this position wrong with Black. Since White has the fianchettoed bishop on g2, Black should make it a priority not to allow the board to open up.   Therefore, Black should play: }
17... cxb3 18. axb3
{ Black has the healthier central pawn structure, but White has the stronger bishop. In addition, White has the potential to play Nb5, bringing the knight to an outpost with Nd6.   All in all, I think White has the slightly better chances to play for an advantage here. }
