[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) London System: Unprincipled Setups"]
[Black "Chigorin Attempt"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 d5 2. d4 Nc6
{ This 'Chigorin' attempt makes absolutely zero sense against our 1.c3 Venom.   The knight has no future of linking up with a ...Bf5 to jump to ...Nb4 with a potential attack @@StartBracket@@due to our c3-pawn@@EndBracket@@.   Black's only other plan with ...Nc6 is to aim for the ...e5 break, but we can stop any hopes of this immediately... }
3. Bf4 { Our 1.c3 Venom London is perfect against Chigorin players! } 3... Nf6
4. e3 Bf5 5. Nd2
{ Now hold on a second... didn't you make it a rule to always meet the development of ...Bf5 with Qb3?   So in the vast majority of cases, this will be the case, but we should look closer at this position, and think whether the same rule should apply here. In this exact position, Black's pawn is on c7, thus limiting our Bf4 from controlling the c7- and b8-squares.   In addition, the b7-pawn is less weak, since Black has already developed their knight from b8, so the rook is certainly not getting trapped. So here,  5.Qb3  makes less sense, and I prefer simple development!   5.Qb3?!  Rb8!  White hasn't achieved much with the early queen attack! }
5... e6
{ Since we want to play Nf3 next @@StartBracket@@blocking the queen's control over the h5-square@@EndBracket@@, I'd play h3 first to give our dark-squared bishop a retreat square. }
6. h3
{ In most cases, Black will just play with a misplaced knight on c6. However, Black does have one interesting plan here, and can get a decent game if White is unaware of it! It starts with: }
6... Be7 7. Ngf3 Ne4 8. Nxe4
{ 8.Be2?!  This natural move is inaccurate, and exactly what Black hopes to achieve with this early 7...Ne4 idea.  8...g5!  9.Bh2  h5  10.Nxe4  Bxe4!  Now we no longer have Nd2 to kick away the centralised bishop, since our g2-pawn would hang.   In addition, we wouldn't like to castle kingside due to the incoming kingside pawn storm! Because of this variation, I'd like to recommend that you remember to capture the knight on e4 immediately, and deal with the annoying bishop on e4, before proceeding with our development. }
8... Bxe4 9. Nd2
{ Once Black's bishop is removed from e4, we can freely complete our kingside development, without fear of hanging the g2-pawn! }
9... Bf5 10. Be2 g5 11. Bh2 h5 12. Bxh5
{ Black is not fast enough to generate this kingside attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) London System: Unprincipled Setups"]
[Black "Copycat #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 c6
{ It's quite possible that our opponent may be so uncertain over what to play, they might just copy our moves! This can be quite annoying, since our setup normally benefits from our opponent overpushing against us.   However, we shouldn't be too worried about this — let's take a look at how to approach this cowardly plan of Black's! }
2. d4 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5
{ Interestingly, my first ever OTB Classical Game involved a Copycat! At the time of playing, I hadn't developed specific prep, but I still found my approach to the opening instructive. Here is the Model Game if you're interested! }
4. Qb3 { Following our rule to always meet ...Bf5 with Qb3. } 4... Qb6 5. e3 e6
6. Nd2 Nd7 7. Ngf3
{ Here we will look at two options for Black. Either they will keep copying with 7...Ngf6, or they might make a retreat square for their light-squared bishop, having anticipated our plan of 8. Nh4! }
7... Ngf6 8. Nh4 Nh5
{ 8...Bg6  9.Nxg6  hxg6  10.h3  Nh5  11.Bh2  += Since we were able to play h3 in time, we keep our strong bishop on h2, and the symmetry has been broken!   If our opponent keeps copying, they will find themselves a pawn down after: }
9. Nxf5 Nxf4 10. Nxg7+
{ A check is often required to break the symmetry, and usually works in favour of the player not doing the copying! }
10... Bxg7 11. exf4 { White will stay a clear pawn up now. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) London System: Unprincipled Setups"]
[Black "Copycat #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 c6
{ It's quite possible that our opponent may be so uncertain over what to play, they might just copy our moves! This can be quite annoying, since our setup normally benefits from our opponent overpushing against us.   However, we shouldn't be too worried about this — let's take a look at how to approach this cowardly plan of Black's! }
2. d4 d5 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. Qb3
{ Following our rule to always meet ...Bf5 with Qb3. } 4... Qb6 5. e3 e6 6. Nd2
Nd7 7. Ngf3
{ Here we will look at two options for Black. Either they will keep copying with 7...Ngf6, or they might make a retreat square for their light-squared bishop, having anticipated our plan of 8. Nh4! }
7... h6
{ Now our Nh4 plan doesn't work since the bishop can avoid being captured by retreating to h7! }
8. Be2 Ngf6 9. h3 Be7
{ At first glance, it looks like Black has achieved their goal of copying us exactly. However, we can break the symmetry now with: }
10. Ne5
{ An active move! Black has several choices of how to play this position, but we have clear plans in each instance:  10...O-O  11.g4!  By not castling, we reserve this idea to attack Black's kingside! Since Black has played ...h6 creating a 'hook' for themselves, we will be able to damage Black's structure by a timely h4, g5 break!   10...Nxe5  11.Bxe5!  Black cannot play ...Nd7 without dropping their g7-pawn. If Black chooses to castle, then they'll have to deal with our plan of g4, h4, g5 etc. }
10... Ne4 11. g4
{ As with many symmetrical positions, as soon as the first player initiates dynamic play, the second player will lose very quickly if they keep copying... }
11... g5
{ Copying when so much tension exists in the position is almost always a bad idea!  11...Bh7  Black should of course retreat, but these copycat players will always struggle to know when to stop copying!  12.Nxe4  Bxe4  13.f3  Bh7  14.h4  +=   White has a small edge due to the space advantage gained on the kingside. }
12. gxf5 gxf4 13. fxe6 fxe3 14. exd7+
{ A decisive check breaks the symmetry! It's unlikely our opponent will copy us this far @@StartBracket@@with a deviation at move 10 most likely@@EndBracket@@. But it's reassuring for us to see — simply brainlessly copying an opponent's moves won't take anyone very far! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) London System: Unprincipled Setups"]
[Black "Classical Dutch #1 - Black blocks the e4 square with 8...Ne4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 f5
{ We now turn to our final topic from the main course, which is the infamous Dutch Defence!   The Dutch is an attacking system opening that aims to launch a devastating kingside attack. It's particularly popular in the UK after GingerGM @@StartBracket@@Simon Williams!@@EndBracket@@ released the course 'The Killer Dutch' many, many years ago. I've watched it myself, and was also drawn in by the fantastic attacking lines on show @@StartBracket@@and have a few excellent attacking wins under my belt as a result of it!@@EndBracket@@.   But the good news for us is that Dutch players are creatures of habit. They develop their pieces in the same way every game, and aim for a kingside checkmating attack. Since this is very predictable, we can also prepare some nice remedies against it!   In other good news, since I have lots of experience playing the Dutch myself, I also know what the typical Dutch player hates playing against!   Typically, against the Dutch, White will play ambitiously in the centre @@StartBracket@@often with d4 and c4@@EndBracket@@, and fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2. This may be the best approach according to the engine, but it's in fact what every Dutch player is looking forward to facing over the board. The reason being that although objectively reaching a less sound position for Black, the attacking prospects are fantastic.   So what's the remedy to this Dutch Defence? Well, we'll starve our opponent of all their attacking fun! In fact, we will be the ones to take an initiative @@StartBracket@@Dutch players HATE this@@EndBracket@@, and we'll castle queenside to ensure our king is safe from Black's initial @@StartBracket@@premature?!@@EndBracket@@ kingside activity.   Let's see how! }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ We start with our London System move order since the bishop is actually great on f4!   Importantly, we discourage the ...e5 push — which is one of Black's main ideas in the Dutch. Here, Black has a choice of multiple Dutch systems.   The Killer Dutch which I referenced earlier starts with  3...e6  — also known as the Classical Dutch.   Then there's also the Leningrad Dutch with  3...g6  .   And finally, the Stonewall Dutch with  3...d5  . Each of these Dutch's have a unique flavour to them, so we'll analyse each system in turn! }
3... e6 4. e3 Be7 5. Nd2 O-O 6. h3 b6
{ This is the most common way Black will set up. When White doesn't fianchetto their light-squared bishop on the kingside, it's recommended for Black to use the diagonal themselves to attack. Of course, there won't be any attacks for them, but they don't know this yet! }
7. Ngf3
{ So far all natural London System moves. However, here I recommend something different! }
7... Bb7 8. Bd3
{ Against the Dutch, I like to play for the e4 push. If our opponent wants to prevent us from pushing e4, they'll either have to play ...d5 or ...Ne4 — both of which have their drawbacks!   8...d5  As soon as ...d5 is pushed, Black gives up a lot of hope of pushing ...e5. Our bishop on f4 is perfectly placed to control the weak dark squares. We'll discuss these structures more in the immediate Stonewall Dutch lines! }
8... Ne4 9. Rg1
{ Since Black has prevented our e4 plan, here comes our plan B!   Against the Dutch, we were never planning to castle kingside anyway, and instead are going to use the black f-pawn as a hook to start our own kingside attack! }
9... d6 10. Qc2 Nxd2 11. Nxd2 Nd7 12. O-O-O a5 13. g4
{ Black can try and counterattack our queenside, but their pawn structure is simply not built for a queenside attack! In addition, normally Black can get some play on the queenside with ...Rb8, ...b5 ideas — but this is only a motif in the 1. d4 mainlines where White has a pawn on c4!   With our pawn on c3, Black's queenside attack will be far slower, while our kingside attack will advance with full force! }
