1. c3 f5
{ We now turn to our final topic from the main course, which is the infamous Dutch Defence!   The Dutch is an attacking system opening that aims to launch a devastating kingside attack. It's particularly popular in the UK after GingerGM @@StartBracket@@Simon Williams!@@EndBracket@@ released the course 'The Killer Dutch' many, many years ago. I've watched it myself, and was also drawn in by the fantastic attacking lines on show @@StartBracket@@and have a few excellent attacking wins under my belt as a result of it!@@EndBracket@@.   But the good news for us is that Dutch players are creatures of habit. They develop their pieces in the same way every game, and aim for a kingside checkmating attack. Since this is very predictable, we can also prepare some nice remedies against it!   In other good news, since I have lots of experience playing the Dutch myself, I also know what the typical Dutch player hates playing against!   Typically, against the Dutch, White will play ambitiously in the centre @@StartBracket@@often with d4 and c4@@EndBracket@@, and fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2. This may be the best approach according to the engine, but it's in fact what every Dutch player is looking forward to facing over the board. The reason being that although objectively reaching a less sound position for Black, the attacking prospects are fantastic.   So what's the remedy to this Dutch Defence? Well, we'll starve our opponent of all their attacking fun! In fact, we will be the ones to take an initiative @@StartBracket@@Dutch players HATE this@@EndBracket@@, and we'll castle queenside to ensure our king is safe from Black's initial @@StartBracket@@premature?!@@EndBracket@@ kingside activity.   Let's see how! }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ We start with our London System move order since the bishop is actually great on f4!   Importantly, we discourage the ...e5 push — which is one of Black's main ideas in the Dutch. Here, Black has a choice of multiple Dutch systems.   The Killer Dutch which I referenced earlier starts with  3...e6  — also known as the Classical Dutch.   Then there's also the Leningrad Dutch with  3...g6  .   And finally, the Stonewall Dutch with  3...d5  . Each of these Dutch's have a unique flavour to them, so we'll analyse each system in turn! }
3... g6
{ Just like in the Classical Dutch, I would recommend to refrain from castling kingside. After all, the Dutch is geared towards a kingside attack, so why put our king on that side of the board? }
4. e3 Bg7 5. Nd2
{ We commit to the same starting moves as in the Classical Dutch, but with a completely different plan!   We now look carefully to see how our opponent plays — will they commit their king to the kingside with  5...O-O  ? Or will they try to play in the centre immediately with  5...d6  ? }
5... O-O 6. h4
{ Since Black has committed the king to the kingside, I'd like to thrust this h-pawn down the board! Unlike the Classical Dutch, Black has made a hook for themselves in the pawn ...g6, so it's a good idea to try and exploit it! }
6... d6 7. Bc4+
{ This time, our bishop is not preventing Black from castling, but instead provoking the black king to the weak h-file. }
7... Kh8 8. Be2
{ Our bishop's job is done on c4, so it now turns to supporting the h5 push! }
8... Qe8
{ If Black tries to play for the central ...e5 break, we will get our pawn break in first! }
9. h5
{ As we can see, Black has developed zero initiative, and in fact Black is the side that must tred carefully through the complications taking place on their king.   Whenever we can get our opponent out of their comfort zone @@StartBracket@@which we can know by their choice of playing the aggressive Dutch Opening!@@EndBracket@@, then we should do exactly that! }
