1. c3 f5
{ We now turn to our final topic from the main course, which is the infamous Dutch Defence!   The Dutch is an attacking system opening that aims to launch a devastating kingside attack. It's particularly popular in the UK after GingerGM @@StartBracket@@Simon Williams!@@EndBracket@@ released the course 'The Killer Dutch' many, many years ago. I've watched it myself, and was also drawn in by the fantastic attacking lines on show @@StartBracket@@and have a few excellent attacking wins under my belt as a result of it!@@EndBracket@@.   But the good news for us is that Dutch players are creatures of habit. They develop their pieces in the same way every game, and aim for a kingside checkmating attack. Since this is very predictable, we can also prepare some nice remedies against it!   In other good news, since I have lots of experience playing the Dutch myself, I also know what the typical Dutch player hates playing against!   Typically, against the Dutch, White will play ambitiously in the centre @@StartBracket@@often with d4 and c4@@EndBracket@@, and fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2. This may be the best approach according to the engine, but it's in fact what every Dutch player is looking forward to facing over the board. The reason being that although objectively reaching a less sound position for Black, the attacking prospects are fantastic.   So what's the remedy to this Dutch Defence? Well, we'll starve our opponent of all their attacking fun! In fact, we will be the ones to take an initiative @@StartBracket@@Dutch players HATE this@@EndBracket@@, and we'll castle queenside to ensure our king is safe from Black's initial @@StartBracket@@premature?!@@EndBracket@@ kingside activity.   Let's see how! }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ We start with our London System move order since the bishop is actually great on f4! Importantly, we discourage the ...e5 push — which is one of Black's main ideas in the Dutch.   Here, Black has a choice of multiple Dutch systems. The Killer Dutch which I referenced earlier starts with 3...e6 — also known as the Classical Dutch. Then there's also the Leningrad Dutch with 3...g6. And finally, the Stonewall Dutch with 3...d5. Each of these Dutches has a unique flavour to them, so we'll analyse each system in turn! }
3... d5
{ Finally, we come to the Stonewall Dutch. As the name suggests, this is Black's most solid Dutch option, where Black will aim to play ...e6 next, setting up a sturdy pawn structure, with great control over the e4-square.   As sturdy as it seems, the pawn structure does have one huge weakness: the dark squares. Our bishop is placed perfectly to exploit them, and we should remember two things:   1@@EndBracket@@ trade Black's dark-squared bishop when possible @@StartBracket@@since this kills any attacking chances they may have@@EndBracket@@, and   2@@EndBracket@@ make sure to prevent Black from ever getting in the ...e5 break! }
4. e3 e6 5. Nd2
{ To make things easier for you, I've recommended the same starting position against all three Dutches! Having said that, against the Stonewall Dutch, I will not be recommending any attacking lines to take the initiative first, because I simply don't see the need! With a firm control over the h2-b8 diagonal with our dark-squared bishop, I am satisfied with our king's defence on the kingside, and since Black cannot get the usual ...e5, followed by ...f5 type of counterplay, we will be safe to castle kingside! }
5... c6 6. h3 Be7 7. Ngf3 O-O 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. O-O
{ We set up with our bog-standard London System against the Stonewall Dutch. }
9... Ne4
{ We have reached this typical stage of the Stonewall when our opponent plants a knight on e4. I'd like you to remember this rule: after trading knights on e4, if we can plant our own knight successfully on e5, then we should trade knights on e4 immediately! }
10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5
{ We should never be worried about trades in the Stonewall, since Black is banking on a kingside attack to compensate for their weakened pawn structure @@StartBracket@@with every piece that trades, their kingside attack will become less and less powerful@@EndBracket@@.   We are clearly better here since Black will not be able to challenge for the h2-b8 diagonal without trading off their own dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@their best attacking minor piece@@EndBracket@@. In addition, if we compare bishops, both of our bishops are active, while Black is left with a bad light-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@stuck behind their pawn chain@@EndBracket@@.   Since our dark-squared bishop controls the b8- and c7-squares, and our light-squared bishop aims towards the queenside, we should therefore play on the queenside. I'd recommend pushing c4, then c5, before eventually supporting this advance with b4, a4, and b5, with a game winning break through on the queenside to come! }
