4. e3 e6 5. Nd2
{ To make things easier for you, I've recommended the same starting position against all three Dutches! Having said that, against the Stonewall Dutch, I will not be recommending any attacking lines to take the initiative first, because I simply don't see the need! With a firm control over the h2-b8 diagonal with our dark-squared bishop, I am satisfied with our king's defence on the kingside, and since Black cannot get the usual ...e5 + ...f5 type of counterplay, we will be safe to castle kingside! }
5... c6 6. h3 Bd6 7. Bxd6
{ Do you remember our first rule of the Stonewall? Trade off Black's dark-squared bishop, and they'll have no attack! }
7... Qxd6 8. Ngf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O Ne4
{ Again, we reach this typical stage of the Stonewall when our opponent plants a knight on e4. At this moment, we can see that after trading on e4, we cannot plant our own knight on e5. Therefore, I prefer to wait until we're able to do so. }
11. Qc2
{ Simply connecting the rooks, and supporting the c4 push!   11.Nxe4?!  If we cannot plant our f3-knight onto the e5-square, Black will be able to achieve their desired pawn break...  11...fxe4  12.Nd2  e5!  Do you remember our second rule of how to play against the Stonewall? We should not allow Black to play the ...e5 break, which they have now achieved!  13.dxe5  Qxe5  14.Qc2  Qg5!  15.c4  Ne5∓  Even if Black has traded off their dark-squared bishop, if they are able to successfully play for ...e5, they will be able to open up their light-squared bishop, and still generate some kingside attacking potential! }
11... Ndf6
{ Now the e5-square has become available for our own knight, so we are ready to trade on e4! }
12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Ne5 Nd7
{ Trading on d7 is also fine @@StartBracket@@since we will keep a slight advantage due to our better light-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@. However, we can be more ambitious after: }
14. f4 exf3
{ 14...Nxe5  15.fxe5±  Wherever Black places their queen, White will stand better. Now that the centre has closed, any flank attacks will increase in strength. As our bishop is free and controls the queenside, while Black's bishop is blocked by their own pawn structure, we will have the more successful flank attack prospects, and a one-sided game ahead of us! }
15. Nxf3 e5
{ Black must play ...e5 in order to activate their pieces. However, our pieces are better developed for when the centre opens up! }
16. e4 { Opening up the centre to our advantage! } 16... exd4 17. cxd4 dxe4 18.
Qxe4 Nf6 19. Bc4+ Kh8 20. Qh4
{ Given how open the position is, every tempo of development makes a difference here. We will continue with either Ne5 or Ng5, and Black will struggle to defend against the incoming kingside attack! }
