{ To make things easier for you, I've recommended the same starting position against all three Dutches! Having said that, against the Stonewall Dutch, I will not be recommending any attacking lines to take the initiative first, because I simply don't see the need! With a firm control over the h2-b8 diagonal with our dark-squared bishop, I am satisfied with our king's defence on the kingside, and since Black cannot get the usual ...e5 + ...f5 type of counterplay, we will be safe to castle kingside! }
5... Bd6
{ The immediate 5...Bd6 allows Black to recapture with the c-pawn. Let's see how this changes things: }
6. Bxd6 cxd6
{ We have a very different position to a typical Stonewall that we examined in the previous two variations. Here, Black can in fact play on the queenside, with the 2 v 3 minority attack! We do not want to allow any possibility of a minority attack, so I prefer to play directly on the queenside immediately with: }
7. c4 O-O 8. cxd5
{ Black must recapture with the knight to avoid a crippled pawn structure. }
8... Nxd5 9. Bc4
{ We immediately ask questions to Black's centre. The d6- and e6- pawns are quite weak, and will have to improve themselves soon. }
9... Nf6 10. Ngf3 d5 11. Be2
{ We return to slightly more familiar Stonewall ground, but with one key difference: the open c-file. As a result, White will get improved queenside prospects, with the chance to infiltrate quickly down the c-file, towards the 7th rank utilising the c7-square.   And that, Ladies and Gentlemen, concludes our core theory of 1.c3 Venom. It means so much to me that you've made it this far, and please, if you enjoyed the course, do consider leaving a 5-star review ⭐!   I will be invested in the 1.c3 Venom community and try my best to answer as many questions as you have about the repertoire, and I hope you will join in for this discussion too!   On that note, I'd like to remind you that this is not the end of the course! After studying the model games of our London System, I will be delving deeper into our repertoire in the ADVANCED Material section of the course, and then finally showcasing a super bizarre opening idea resulting from 1. c3 in the BONUS section of the course. I hope you enjoy everything there is to come, and thanks again for studying this far into 1.c3 Venom!! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 1...d5 London (Black Trades Queens with ...Qxb3)"]
[Result "*"]

{ 2022 Autumn Marathon Blitz, 5+0 } 1. d4
{ Wait — 1. d4? What's that doing here?   Well, the London System is typically reached via 1. d4, so model games starting with 1. d4 may be quite frequent in this section of the course! No worries, we will transpose into our lines shortly. }
1... Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3
{ Transposing to our 1.c3 Venom repertoire against 1...d5. } 4... Qb6 5. Qb3
{ Following our rule of meeting ...Qb6 with Qb3! } 5... Qxb3 6. axb3 cxd4 7.
exd4
{ This is where I left the theory section. Let's see how FelixTheCatChess handles the position! }
7... a6
{ Black instantly feels the weakness of the a-file, and tries to solve it immediately. }
8. Nf3 { White calmly develops their pieces. } 8... Nc6 9. Nbd2 Bf5 10. b4
{ I like this move! The a4- and c4-squares are still under control by our other pieces, and instead we allow for our knight to potentially activate via b3 to either c5 or a5. }
10... e6 11. b5
{ Black's slow development is punished, making use of our open a-file! } 11...
Nb8 12. Bxb8
{ Not the engine's choice, but I like the idea! We are simply removing the defenders of the a6-pawn. }
12... Rxb8 13. bxa6 bxa6 14. b4
{ Fixing the a-pawn from ever moving forward @@StartBracket@@and in chess by the word 'fixing', we mean the 'sticking' kind of fixing@@EndBracket@@. This pawn will be lost by force, and White enjoys a healthy pawn up position!   For the record, any  14...Rc8  can be met with  15.Rxa6  anyway, and upon  15...Rxc3  ,  Black is too underdeveloped to be grabbing pawns, and thus  16.Bb5+!  Kd8  17.O-O  Bxb4  18.Rfa1!  leads to a great position for White! In any case, Black did not play so actively, ended up losing the pawn by force, and went down without a fight!   Let's see how FelixTheCatChess converted this position: }
14... Be7 15. Bxa6 O-O 16. O-O Rb6 17. Ne5 Rfb8 18. f3 Bc2 19. Ra2 Bf5 20. Rfa1
h5 21. Bd3 Bxd3 22. Nxd3 Bd6 23. Ra8 Bf4 24. Nb3 Be3+ 25. Kf1 h4 26. Ke2 Bg5
27. Nbc5 h3 28. gxh3
{ My only criticism in the entire game. Why allow Black any squares/weak pawns to target, when we can instead fix the h3-pawn as a weakness with  28.g3!  instead? But it doesn't really matter, White's queenside domination is enough to be completely winning! }
28... Nh5 29. Nd7 Rxa8 30. Rxa8+
{ Black resigns. A fantastic game and conversion, illustrating how pleasant the position is to play when we get an active a-file after Black's queen on b6 trades for our queen on b3. }
