[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 1...d5 London (Committing a Positional Sin with 14. dxc5?)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org, 1+0 Bullet } 1. c3
{ So you might be thinking, why is a bullet game worth analysing for our Model games section?   In actual fact, Bullet chess is a test of your first instincts in a position. Since this was early days of me playing 1.c3 Venom, my intuition in certain positions were way off! In this game, I committed a positional sin on move 14, playing 14. dxc5 instead of 14. dxe5.   Look out for this moment, it's very instructive for us to understand! }
1... d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 Bf5 4. Nf3
{ 4.Qb3!  Here, I should meet ...Bf5 with Qb3 to cause maximum disruption to Black! As I said at the start, this was one of my first games of 1.c3 Venom, so I was still getting to grips with my own rules and understandings! }
4... e6 5. h3
{ Normally in these 1...d5 structures, it's best not to play with h3, since we may want to meet ...Bd6 with Bg3 @@StartBracket@@where the h-pawn is able to support the bishop on g3 in case it gets captured@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Bd6
{ Now I can't retreat to g3 and am forced to capture on d6.   It's not the end of the world, but I'm not the biggest fan of when Black can recapture with ...cxd6!? , since Black can play with a minority attack of sorts. }
6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 Bg6 9. O-O c5 10. Bxg6 hxg6 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12. Qe2
Rfe8 13. Rfb1
{ Here, I completely mixed up my ideas. Since the centre is likely to open up, my rooks belong in the centre. I think I must've been confusing my rook placement to my 'Minority Attack lines' — which doesn't make any sense here! }
13... e5 14. dxc5
{ A serious positional mistake! By allowing my opponent to keep their e5-pawn, they can next push ...e4, take control over the f3-square, and launch a full scale kingside attack!   This is in fact what happened, and I got crushed. So instead, I should have played:   14.dxe5!  Nxe5  15.Nxe5!  In fact, what we really have, is the 'Classical Caro-Kann' pawn structure! So I should be happy to trade, and play against the slightly weak d5-pawn with my rooks on the d-file!  15...Qxe5  16.Nf3!  Qd6  17.Rd1!  Rad8  18.Qc2!  getting my queen off the file of the black rook on e8.  18...Qc6  19.Rac1  Ne4  20.c4⇆  We have no issues in the defence of our kingside, and have good play in the centre and on the queenside.   So remember this. Whenever Black breaks with ...e5 in these structures, it's almost always better to play with dxe5 as opposed to allowing the e-pawn to live! }
14... Qxc5 15. Nb3 Qd6 16. Nfd2 e4
{ Black establishes a space advantage on the kingside, and my position becomes very difficult to hold. }
17. Nd4 Ne5 18. N2b3 Nd3 19. Nc1 Ne5 20. b4
{ My queenside play is obviously too slow. } 20... g5
{ ...And the kingside attack begins! } 21. Ncb3 g4 22. hxg4 Nfxg4 23. a4 Qh6
{ I'm completely lost! But I never give up in chess @@StartBracket@@and neither should you, but that's a whole different topic!@@EndBracket@@, so I played on here. You never know if the opponent will disconnect or drop dead, fight until the very end! 😄 }
24. Qxg4 Nxg4 25. Kf1 Qh1+ 26. Ke2 Qxg2 27. Rg1 Qxf2+ 28. Kd1 Nxe3+ 29. Kc1
Qxg1+ 30. Kb2 Qf2+ 31. Ka3 Nc4#
{ My opponent made zero mistakes in their conversion, and dealt a pretty checkmate to finish! Normally, without Black's dark-squared bishop on d6, there really should be no kingside attacking chances for Black. However, we do need to remember to always meet the e5 push with dxe5! Otherwise, Black will be able to push ...e4, gain space on the kingside, and pull off a crushing kingside attack like you just saw!   Just remember to meet the e5 push with dxe5, and you won't ever get into the kind of mess I experienced in this game! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 1...d5 London (Meeting 6...Qb6?! - Too Weak Too Slow!)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Next I want to show a Blitz game I played at Loughborough Chess Club  (my local chess club)  vs Henderson Mullin @@StartBracket@@~1800 OTB@@EndBracket@@! Again, this was in the early days of the development of 1.c3 Venom, so I still had some holes in my preparation! }
1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5
{ Black has developed their light-squared bishop! Therefore, we always meet this move with: }
6. Qb3 Qb6
{ We never capture on b6 @@StartBracket@@since we much prefer for them to capture us on b3, to open the a-file for activity@@EndBracket@@, therefore I played: }
7. dxc5 Qxc5
{ At this point in time, I had only studied positions after 7...Qxb3. I felt that ...Qxc5 had to be a mistake, but how to punish it? }
8. Qxb7
{ This had to be the reason why ...Qxc5 was a mistake! @@StartBracket@@and I was correct!@@EndBracket@@ }
8... Rc8
{ Multiple moves are winning here, but the simplest to me is:     9.Nb3!  Qb6  10.Qxb6  axb6  11.Ba6  Rd8   @@StartBracket@@  11...Ra8  12.Bb7+-  wins a piece.@@EndBracket@@  12.Bc7  Rd7  13.Bxb6+-  White is two clean pawns up, while Black has zero counterplay. }
9. Ba6
{ I was having quite a bad evening of chess, and I haven't the faintest idea what I was intending with this move. We should take note that before 9. Ba6, the position is actually +4 in White's favour — but White must be precise with their activity, since after one slow move later, Black can play: }
9... e5
{ Now my advantage has dissipated into thin air! This is why we should be careful with engine evaluations — your position might be winning, but only if you know how to win! }
10. Nb3 Qd6 11. Bg3 Rb8
{ Whoops! My queen is trapped. I played too slowly, and as a result, got rightfully punished! When capturing on b7 with the queen, we should remember that if we don't act quickly / play precisely, this is a fairly common way to get punished.   Here is a LINK to the relevant theory section of this variation. You're welcome to look over the lines once more to make sure you're confident with dealing with 6...Qb6?! }
