[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 1...d5 London (Crushing an FM in 13 Moves!)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Next I'd like to show a 5+0 Blitz game I played on lichess.org against a FIDE Master from Austria rated 2250 FIDE.   Can you believe that my opponent resigned after 13 moves? These are the joys of playing 1.c3 Venom! }
1. c3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5
{ Our FM opponent is playing the 'new mainline'.   Do you remember how to always meet this bishop development? }
6. Qb3 { Remembering our first rule: always meet ...Bf5 with Qb3. } 6... Qd7
{ Out of the three options ...Qb6?!, ...Qc8 and ...Qd7, the opponent has chosen ...Qd7.   Do you remember what to play here? }
7. Ngf3
{ We are aiming to play with Bb5 and Ne5 if our opponent plays a slow move like 7...e6?!.   Instead, my FM opponent played the critical move: }
7... c4 8. Qb5
{ Here comes my interesting try! After ...a6, we'd play Qb6 to continue blocking Black's attempt to play ...b5. Then, we'd like to undermine Black's pawn on c4 with the b3 pawn break! }
8... e6
{ My opponent didn't play the critical ...a6.   Do you remember what we should do in this position when our opponent gives us a free move? }
9. b3 { We can undermine Black's pawn chain since Black cannot play ...b5 ! }
9... Ba3
{ A mistake. This is when playing on intuition alone can lead to serious problems in chess! This is the standard response to a premature b3 push in the London, since Black is aiming to play ...Bb2 to attack my c3-pawn next, and I cannot ever play Rb1 due to Black's bishop on f5! However, in this particular position @@StartBracket@@that my opponent hasn't studied@@EndBracket@@, my queen is situated on b5! Therefore, I CAN prevent this ...Bb2 motif with the move: }
10. bxc4 { A discovered defence! Now the queen protects the b2-square. } 10...
O-O
{ Since Black's bishop is on the side of the board, Black must be careful to not let their bishop get trapped. Castling, although natural, does not address this aspect of the position! }
11. c5
{ Now the bishop is completely trapped. My opponent tries to solve this issue, but is one move too slow! }
11... b6 12. Qb3 { The bishop is mine! } 12... bxc5 13. Qxa3
{ My FM opponent resigns, having lost a full piece. This is the power of 1.c3 Venom. We have complete understanding of a rare position, which throws off even titled players. If you've studied my course closely, there's no reason why you wouldn't beat an FM in the same way I just did! @@StartBracket@@and keep me updated when this happens 😄@@EndBracket@@ }
