[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 1...d5 London (Grinding Out a Small Edge)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org Blitz, 3+0.   This game was between myself and an up and coming junior. I have his omitted his username for prep reasons, but his level is of around 2300 strength @@StartBracket@@online rating@@EndBracket@@.    This game will be particularly useful to understand how to grind down a strong opponent, in a resulting pawn structure similar to the Caro-Kann Reversed: Classical Variation. }
1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 c5 5. Nd2 Bd6 6. Bg3 Qc7
{ An interesting home preparation @@StartBracket@@specifically prepped against me!@@EndBracket@@, with the plan of preventing our knight from ever jumping to the e5-square. }
7. Ngf3 Nbd7 8. Be2 { When in doubt, I like to just complete our development! }
8... O-O
{ Since I want to castle next, I prefer not having our kingside pawns damaged. So I traded on d6 first. }
9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. O-O b6 11. h3
{ Best not to take any risks with potential ...Ng4 jumps! } 11... Bb7 12. Rc1
h6 13. Re1 Rac8 14. Bf1 Rfd8 15. a3
{ Just sitting and waiting! Eventually, if Black also waits, I'd have to try something @@StartBracket@@probably the c4 break@@EndBracket@@, but for the time being, I'm extremely solid, and I can wait to see if Black overextends... }
15... e5
{ Exactly what I was hoping for! Now we will enter into positions similar to a Classical / One Knight variation from the Caro-Kann Reversed! }
16. dxe5
{ The correct pawn to capture! Think back to my second Model Game where I took on c5 instead — with disastrous consequences! }
16... Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Nf3 Qb8 19. Qa4 Bc6 20. Qh4 Rd6 21. Qf4
{ If possible, I'd like to trade off queens. My plan is to play against Black's d5-pawn, and since Black's only hope with the d5-pawn is to push ...d4, the more pieces I trade, the less effective the ...d4 push will be! }
21... Re6 22. Qxb8 Rxb8 23. Nd2 Rbe8 24. Red1 Ne4 25. Nxe4
{ Following the principle we learnt about in the Classical / One Knight variation. If we can trade, it's often good to do so! }
25... Rxe4 26. Be2 Bb7 27. Bf3 R4e5 28. c4
{ Since the bishop on b7 is temporarily loose, this is a great time to strike! }
28... Rd8 29. Rd2
{ Since Black will struggle to regroup, it's a good idea to increase the pressure on Black's main weakness. }
29... Ba8 30. Rcd1 d4 31. Bxa8 Rxa8 32. exd4 cxd4 33. Rxd4
{ We have successfully won a pawn out of the opening, without taking any risks! Now comes the tricky part, playing out the rook endgame under time pressure! }
33... Rc8 34. b4 Kh7 35. R1d2
{ This is too passive for a rook endgame. I could already have entered with  35.Rd7!  asking Black some questions as to how they will defend their weak a7- and f7-pawns! }
35... Re1+ 36. Kh2 Ra1 37. R2d3 Rc1 38. Rd7 R1xc4 39. Rxa7 Kg6 40. Rdd7
{ Too slow! I missed a direct move to win a pawn immediately:   40.Rd6+!  f6  41.Rxb6±  With the connected queenside passed pawns, Black's position is hopeless. }
40... Rf4
{ This is a thematic move to defend pressure on the 7th rank. Black ideally places a rook in front of the weak f-pawn @@StartBracket@@as opposed to behind with ...Rf8@@EndBracket@@, and now Black is maintaining an active rook, and defending at the same time. }
41. Kg3 Rf6 42. f4 Rc3+ 43. Kh2 Rc2 44. Rd4
{ With less than 20 seconds each, the resulting play was far from optimal! }
44... Rc3 45. a4 Rc2 46. a5 bxa5 47. bxa5 Ra2 48. Rd5 Ra4 49. f5+ Rxf5 50. Rxf5
Kxf5 51. Rxf7+ Kg6 52. Ra7 Ra1 53. a6 Kh7 54. Kg3 Kg6 55. h4 Kh7 56. Kg4 Ra3
57. g3 Ra4+ 58. Kh3 Ra5 59. h5 Ra4 60. g4
{ I realise this endgame is out of the scope of our course, but incredibly, having pushed my pawns up to g4 + h5, my position is now in fact winning!   The point is that Black's pawns are too far back, so when White brings their king to support the a-pawn, despite Black's rook taking the g4- and h4-pawns, after the Black rook sacrifices for the a-pawn, Black is not in time to draw since Black's kingside pawns are too slow to make it down the board in time. For instance: }
60... Ra3+ 61. Kh4
{ 61.Kg2!  Ra2+  62.Kf3  Ra3+  63.Ke4  Ra4+  64.Kd5  Rxg4  65.Kc6  Rg5  66.Kb6  Rxh5  67.Rd7  Rh2  68.Rd5!   @@StartBracket@@  68.a7?  Rb2+!  Now White's king struggles to avoid the checks, while approaching the rook would allow Black to keep the rook on the a-file, behind the passed pawn. @@EndBracket@@  68...Rb2+  69.Rb5!  Ra2  70.a7  Since Ra5 is a threat, Black has to sacrifice now...  70...Rxa7  71.Kxa7  g5  72.Kb6  Kg6  73.Kc5  Kf5  74.Kd4+  Kf4  75.Kd3  h5  76.Ke2  h4  77.Kf2  g4  78.Rh5  h3  79.Rh4+-  The pawns are just too slow, and White is well in time to get the rook behind the passed pawns, and the White king to support in stopping the pawns from advancing from the front. }
61... Ra4 62. Ra8 Ra2 63. a7 Ra4 64. Kg3 Ra6 65. g5 Ra3+ 66. Kg4 Ra4+ 67. Kf5
Ra3 68. g6#
{ A pretty fantastic way to win with 1 second on the clock! But in any case, I hope you took something from how I handled the middlegame position, despite being out of book pretty early on.   In short, having studied the entire repertoire, you should be able to use knowledge from different lines we've discussed to help you navigate novel positions that come your way!   Also, think back to the Model Game when my opponent made a pawn break in the centre with ...e5, and I took the wrong pawn on c5 instead of e5? These games were played in the space of a few months apart! So if you keep practicing, and learning from your mistakes, you'll end up developing the correct intuition to find the right moves! }
