[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 1...d5 London (Prophylactic Precision against Grunfeld-style Play)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org, 5+0 Blitz } 1. c3 g6
{ Hold on a second... this isn't 1...d5?   Well, you're right, but the resulting position becomes that of a 1...d5 game, so I'll consider this a ...d5 game! As 1.c3 Venom players, we should be flexible and adjust to the correct plans and ideas, depending on how the position in front of us develops! }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 c6 5. Nd2 Nf6
{ As you may have noticed, I haven't covered this setup in the main course. The reason being: I don't think it's that critical, and our knowledge of the other systems should provide us with the ability to think on our own here!   In any case, here is a model game I played against this structure, which I think really showcases the strength of our 1.c3 Venom! }
6. h3 O-O 7. Ngf3 Qb6 8. Qb3
{ As spoken about in many other lines, our main response to ...Qb6 is to play Qb3! }
8... Qxb3 { Giving us the a-file can only be in our favour! } 9. axb3 a6 10. b4
{ Taking more space on the queenside, and gaining control over a5- and c5-squares. }
10... Nbd7
{ Before playing any active queenside plans, I first want to make sure I've completed development: }
11. Be2 Ne8 12. O-O Nd6
{ I've finished development... so now what?   In short, I want to put pressure on Black's queenside, and the best way I can see to do that would be Nb3-c5. However, there's no hurry when we have full command over the position! }
13. Ra2
{ Given I want to play Nb3-c5, this ensures my b2-pawn isn't weak and vulnerable to ...Nc4 ideas. }
13... Nf6 14. Nb3 Nfe4 15. Nc5 Nxc5 16. bxc5
{ Taking with the b-pawn makes more sense, since I want to keep Black's dark-squared bishop inactive on g7. }
16... Ne4 17. Rfa1 Bd7 18. Bc7 h6 19. Ne5
{ I didn't mind the exchange of bishop for knight. In that instance, I'd think about how to open the position to make use of my bishop pair. }
19... Be6 20. Nd3
{ I now had a different plan for my knight. Can you see the ideal square for this piece? }
20... Rac8 21. Bh2 Bf5 22. Nc1 Rcd8 23. Nb3 Rd7 24. Na5
{ In Black's structure, the b7-pawn is weak point, so that's where I target my forces! }
24... Be6
{ I now wanted to play Ra2-a3-b3 to add pressure to the weak b7-pawn. But again, since Black has no active plan, there's no rush! I was a little afraid that Black could meet my Rb3 plan with a timely ...Nd2 to dislodge it.   So to avoid this, I played: }
25. Rd1 f5 26. Ra3 Bf7 27. Rb3 e5
{ Now at this moment, I'd love to capitalise on my activity, and take this b7-pawn. However, after:     28.Rxb7  Rxb7  29.Nxb7  Rb8!  30.Na5  Rxb2!  Suddenly Black has activity. So in order to avoid this, again, I should take my time, and play the following prophylactic moves: }
28. f3 Ng5 29. Rd2
{ Now my b2-pawn is overprotected, and I can think about capturing this b7-pawn! }
29... Be6 30. Rxb7 Rxb7 31. Nxb7 Rb8 32. Na5
{ Remarkably, Black has no future on the b-file @@StartBracket@@with every square controlled by my pieces@@EndBracket@@, so Black takes a very passive post for their rook. }
32... Rc8 33. b4 exd4 34. exd4
{ Maintaining the pawn on c3 to ensure the dark-squared bishop has absolutely no future on this diagonal! }
34... Nf7 35. Bxa6
{ While Black's position is uncoordinated, it's a good time to collect material! }
35... Re8 36. Bb7 Bd7 37. Bxc6 Re1+ 38. Kf2 Rh1
{ Unfortunately my opponent resigned now, but there was a beautiful combination for me here: }
39. Bxd7 Rxh2 40. Kg1
{ A tragic end to the black rook that only just got active! As we can see, when our opponent sets up passively, there is still a lot of potential to statically improve the position in a London System!   Keep full control, make sure Black doesn't have any easy ways to get play, and your opponent will surely meet a similar fate as my opponent here! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: King's Indian Defence (Michael Green vs Chess.com MrBeast Bot)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Do you remember how in the Caro-Kann Reversed Model Games Chapter, I showed a game vs a chess.com Danny bot?  Well, here I have another game for you against a chess.com bot — this time against the MrBeast bot, rated 1100!  I am including games like this so that you can get a feel for how effective 1. c3 can be against lower rated opponents too.   Let's see how this went down! }
1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6
{ Since Black is setting up a King's Indian Defence, I should play in the style of a London System. }
3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 d6
{ When playing against the King's Indian Defence, we should always develop our kingside first! }
5. Nf3 O-O 6. h3 Bd7
{ Perhaps a full '?' is a little harsh, but we'll see that MrBeast is aiming to play purely with the pieces, without playing for either the ...c5 or ...e5 break. Without attempting either of these breaks, Black will get crushed. }
7. Be2 Bc6 8. O-O b6
{ Since Black has wasted time playing ...Bd7-c6 @@StartBracket@@which only gets in the way of a potential ...c5 break@@EndBracket@@, White has plenty of time to optimize their pieces. Therefore, White can head straight for c4 and Nc3. }
9. c4 a6 10. Nc3 Bxf3
{ Voluntarily giving up the bishop pair in an open position?? A big no no! }
11. Bxf3 Qd7
{ A terrible blunder. Black should be more careful pushing ...b6 when the fianchettoed bishop has been removed from its post on b7! }
12. Bxa8 Qe8 13. b4 e5
{ Unless we can win the pawn tactically, it's better to retreat to h2. } 14.
Bh2 Qd8 15. Bf3 Qc8 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Bxe5 Re8 18. Bg3
{ Since ...Ne4 and ...Nh5 are unavailable @@StartBracket@@that would otherwise harass our bishop on g3@@EndBracket@@, I feel that Bg3 is a safer bet than Bh2 @@StartBracket@@which could run into some back rank checkmate ideas@@EndBracket@@. }
18... a5 19. a3
{ Ensuring that if ...axb4, axb4 keeps the b4- and c4-pawns controlling some useful squares! }
19... h6 20. Rc1 Qd7 21. Qxd7
{ Since we're material up, we should certainly trade pieces! } 21... Nbxd7 22.
Bxc7 Rc8 23. Nd5
{ I'd seen that if the knight is taken, we can play cxd5! with a discovered defence on our bishop on c7! }
23... g5 { Black misses the second reason behind my 23. Nd5 move! } 24. Ne7+
{ After this fork, the rook is lost, and so is the game for Black. The rest is an easy conversion. }
24... Kh7 25. Nxc8 Ne8 26. Bxb6 Nxb6 27. Nxb6 h5 28. c5 axb4 29. axb4 h4 30. c6
Kh6 31. c7 Nxc7 32. Rxc7 Be5 33. Rc6+ Kh7 34. Rd1 Bg7 35. Rd7 Be5 36. Nc4 Bb8
37. Rxf7+ Kg8 38. Rb7
{ it's worth noting that on my path to converting this position, I play with all my pieces on light squares, to avoid any risk of conflict with Black's dark-squared bishop.   I would advise you to take all precautions when converting a position, no matter how much material you're up! }
38... Bc7 39. Rcxc7 Kh8 40. Rb8#
{ If you're nervous about playing 1.c3 Venom in rated games from the get-go, you're welcome to begin by practicing against lower rated Chess.com bots! The experience won't be the same as playing a human, but it's a good way to practice our repertoire in a 100% stress free environment! }
