[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: KID with ...e5 (Successful Queenside Counterplay!)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org, 5+0 Blitz } 1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7
{ We have a King's Indian Defence! The main thing to remember at this stage is to complete development on the kingside first! }
4. e3 O-O 5. h3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be2 Nd7
{ I haven't covered this move in the theory, but no matter! We continue as planned: }
8. O-O e5 { When in doubt, always meet ...e5 with Bh2! } 9. Bh2 Qe7 10. Re1
{ Always useful to have a rook or bishop x-raying the opponent's queen or king. }
10... f5 11. c4
{ Against King's Indian Defence with ...e5, we want to play for c4! Let's see how this goes: }
11... e4 12. Nfd2 Nd8 13. Nc3 c6 14. Qb3 Kh8
{ So I've developed all my pieces. I could consider playing Rac1 too, but I wasn't sure where I wanted my rooks for the time being. Therefore, I carry out my queenside play immediately: }
15. Qa3
{ A sneaky move! Not only am I preparing b4, I am also creating a threat on the d6-pawn! }
15... Nf7 { My opponent is sharp to spot my tricky play. } 16. b4 Nf6 17. Rab1
{ Now we see playing Rac1 earlier would be premature. I prefer my rook on b1. }
17... Bd7 18. c5
{ Of course, my opponent is waiting for this c5 push, in order to play ...d5 themselves, close the centre, and play on the kingside. However, I feel like my queenside attack will be much faster, so I'm happy to enter into this kind of game! }
18... d5 19. b5 g5 20. bxc6 Bxc6
{ I have to be fast to generate queenside counterplay, otherwise I'll be crushed on the kingside.   20...bxc6?!  Although ensuring the d5-pawn is more secure, my queenside counterplay is accelerated:  21.Rb7!  attacking the a7-pawn  21...a5  22.Na4±  preparing to infiltrate with Nb6! }
21. Nb5 Ne8 22. Nxa7
{ It feels risky to self-pin my knight like this, but I couldn't see how Black wins it? I'm also threatening Nxc6!, since ...Rxa3 can be met with Nxe7! }
22... Qd7
{ Again my opponent is sharp to spot my Nxc6 tactic! Before anything else, I wanted to quickly unpin myself, to avoid any unwanted losses of my knight! }
23. Qa5 { Heading to b6 to unpin my knight. } 23... Nd8 24. Qb6 f4 25. Bg4
{ My bishop is more active on g4, and with a tempo, why not? } 25... Qe7 26.
Rb2
{ Do you remember the Karpov-Beliavsky model game in the Minority Attack section where Karpov plays Ra2 to just give some extra defence on the second rank? This was my thinking here!   You never know if protecting this second rank will come in handy! In addition, my knight on a7 is free to move without dropping the a2-pawn! }
26... Nf6 27. Bd1
{ I didn't like Nxg4 weakening my pawn structure. Instead, the bishop is well placed on d1 to prepare the a4 push! }
27... Nd7 28. Nxc6 { I had this move ready and waiting in case of ...Nd7! }
28... bxc6 29. Qc7
{ If possible, if you have a far advanced piece, it is quite often good to keep it in the opponent's camp as a thorn to cramp up their piece coordination. However, you have to be extra careful that this piece doesn't become trapped! }
29... Qf7 30. Nb3
{ Here we see the benefit of my earlier Rb2 move. Now both the f1 and f2 infiltrations are covered by my rooks. }
30... Ra6 31. a4
{ I wasn't sure if I was better after ...Rxa4. My plan was after ...Rxa4 to play Na5!?, asking some questions to the rook on a4 and the pawn on c6.   These are exactly the problems you want to give your opponent when they have 50 seconds left on the clock! }
31... Ne6 32. Qb7 Ndxc5
{ An unexpected blow! This is clever, since my rook on b2 hangs if I ever play dxc5.   Unfortunately for my opponent, the tactic isn't working, and with my extra 30 seconds on the clock, I'm able to find the solution: }
33. Nxc5 Nxc5 34. Qxf7 Rxf7 35. Rb8+
{ The key move! Now that my rook is no longer a target on b2, I will simply capture the knight on c5 on my next move. My opponent resigns here, since they're about to be a piece down, and their clock situation is dire. I hope you enjoyed the flow of this game!   I love games like this that are one-sided, where you're just following the principles of the opening, and getting rewarded for your play! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: KID with ...c5 (Black plays with ...e5 too!)"]
[Result "*"]

{ British Rapidplay 2024, Michael Green vs T.S. Venkataramanan, 15+10 Rated  After 7 Rounds at the British Rapidplay, I'd managed to work my way up the boards and get the chance to play a FIDE Master! It was time to put 1.c3 Venom to the test... }
1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 g6
{ My opponent opted to play for a King's Indian Defence  (KID)  setup. } 3. Bf4
Bg7 4. h3 c5
{ A VERY early ...c5 push! I considered taking it, but given the time control @@StartBracket@@15 minutes each, plus 10 seconds a move@@EndBracket@@, I felt that it was more important to reach a position that I understood well. }
5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 b6 7. Be2 Bb7 8. O-O d6 9. Nbd2 Nbd7
{ We have transposed back into our 1.c3 Venom theory against KID with ...c5. Do you remember how to continue here? }
10. a4
{ After a4, I suggest to continue with Re1 and Bf1 in KID systems where Black has chosen to play ...c5. However, my opponent decided to make a positional sin, and play for BOTH ...c5 and ...e5 ! }
10... Re8 11. Bh2 e5
{ Playing for both ...c5 and ...e5 creates too many weaknesses for Black. Here, we are ready and waiting to pounce! }
12. Nc4 Bxf3
{ My FM opponent makes the first mistake of the game, clearly out of his depth already. But that doesn't mean the follow up is easy to find! }
13. Bxf3 e4 14. Be2 d5 15. Nd6
{ So far so good! I keep a serious advantage after this move, and I could see my opponent was starting to get nervous. }
15... Re6
{ This was a critical moment. I had two good ways to continue the position, but I wasn't able to find either path. }
16. c4
{ 16.Ba6!  This was the best continuation, capitalising on the loss of my opponent's light-squared bishop, and threatening to enter immediately with Bb7! and attacking the exposed rook and d5-pawn.   16.Nb5!  This was also a decent way to continue, first improving the knight, and creating a threat, before opening up the position with c4!  Rc6   16...Re7?  17.a5  a6  18.Nc7  Ra7  19.axb6  here I'd be completely winning, Black's pieces are simply too uncoordinated!  17.c4  Now that my knight is secure, opening the position works much better. I had the right idea with c4, to open up the position for my bishop pair, but this would have been a better execution. }
16... cxd4 17. exd4 a6 18. Qb3 Qe7 19. Qa3
{ The position is opening up which is good for my bishop pair, but my knight on d6 is vulnerable! }
19... Bf8 20. c5 bxc5 21. dxc5
{ Here my opponent could have punished me and my vulnerable knight on d6 after the move:   21...Nxc5!  22.Qxc5  Qd7!  Black will regain their knight, and I'll be left a pawn down in the resulting position. }
21... Ne5 22. Rfd1 e3
{ My opponent rightfully tries to instigate play against my king. In fact, despite appearing to weaken my king, I should have just taken this pawn while I had the chance! }
23. f3
{ 23.fxe3!  Bh6  24.Kh1  Ned7  25.e4!  Nxe4  26.Nxe4  Rxe4  27.Bf3!  Here, we can see that my king has found safety, and the position looks much more playable than allowing the pawn to survive on e3! }
23... Bh6 24. b4 Nh5
{ At this moment, I had a lot to consider. I wanted to take the pawn with Rxd5, but I was worried about the activity over on the f4-square. }
25. Rd4
{ 25.Rxd5!  In fact, I should have been brave and gone for it! I would be able to defend successfully no matter how Black entered on the f4 square.  Bf4   25...Nf4  26.Bxf4  Bxf4  27.Qc1  Qh4  28.Qe1!  My queen could get back in time to help defend. Unfortunately, I wasn't able to calculate this far during the game.  26.Ne4  So long as I avoid trading the dark-squared bishops, my king would just about be safe enough! }
25... Nc6 26. Rad1
{ I'd hoped that I'd get enough counterplay with my queenside majority of pawns, and play in the centre. But the closer we get to an endgame, the stronger the rook vs minor piece becomes! }
26... Nxd4 27. Rxd4 Qf6 28. Qd3 Bf4 29. Bxf4 Nxf4 30. Rxf4
{ Another exchange sacrifice! I need to relieve pressure from my kingside, but unfortunately, the rooks were too strong in the resulting position. }
30... Qxf4 31. Qxd5 Rd8 32. b5 axb5 33. axb5 Qg3 34. Qd1 Rexd6
{ When one side has the extra material, they always have the option to give back some material in order to achieve some positional gain! Given that Black was two exchanges up, I really like this decision from my opponent to simplify their position and remove my strong knight from the board. }
35. cxd6 Rxd6 36. Qf1 Rd2
{ My position was now too passive, and Black didn't slip up in their conversion of the position! }
37. f4 Rb2 38. f5 gxf5 39. Qxf5 Rxe2 40. Qc8+ Kg7 41. Qc3+ f6 42. Qc7+
{ My position is already dead lost, so I thought to may as well try one final bullet trick! My opponent smiled, and calmly captured my queen. }
42... Qxc7
{ Respect where it's due! I resigned. An exciting game overall, and very promising that 1.c3 Venom could achieve a near +2 advantage against an FM from the opening. With more experience, we will get closer to converting games like this, while our opponents certainly won't be getting more experience against our 1. c3 first move! }
