[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 1...c5 Exchange Slav (Winning with the Initiative!)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org, Blitz 3+0 } 1. c3 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. cxd4 d5 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nf6
6. Bf4
{ The starting position of our Exchange Slav lines — starting with 1...c5. Here, my opponent chose lines starting with 6...a6! }
6... a6 { Do you remember how to meet this move? } 7. Qb3
{ This rare move restricts Black from developing their light-squared bishop! }
7... Na5 8. Qc2
{ Our queen is still on an active square @@StartBracket@@controlling f5@@EndBracket@@, while Black's knight is misplaced on the edge of the board. }
8... Bg4 9. Ne5 Bh5
{ The light-squared bishop is needed on the c8-h3 diagonal in order to return to the d7-square in case their king is attacked. }
10. e3 e6 11. Qa4+
{ Since Black's knight cannot return to the c6-square, this check is very tough for Black to deal with! }
11... b5 12. Nxb5
{ Sacrificing a piece, but keeping an initiative against the Black's king! }
12... axb5 13. Bxb5+ Ke7 14. Qb4+ Qd6 15. Nc6+
{ A discovered attack from our dark-squared bishop onto the queen! Since Bxd6 will come with check, Black is unable to counterattack our queen successfully with ...Nxc6. }
15... Nxc6 { Black tries the counterattack, but the position is lost. } 16.
Bxd6+
{ 16.Qxd6+!  I actually missed mate in three here! I am not surprised at all, since combinational finishing play is not my strong suit. In any case, 16. Bxd6+ is strong enough here!  16...Ke8  17.Bxc6+  Nd7  18.Qxd7 }
16... Kd7 17. Bxc6+ Kxc6 18. Qc5+ Kd7 19. Qc7+ Ke8 20. Qc6+ Kd8 21. Qxa8+ Kd7
22. Bxf8 Ne8 23. Bc5 Nc7 24. Qxh8 Bg6
{ Given that I was up a queen and two rooks for a knight, my opponent resigned here. I was out of book after move 7. Qb3, but the resulting play was all very natural. If Black tries to match our activity in a symmetrical position, our extra tempo @@StartBracket@@by virtue of having the White pieces@@EndBracket@@ will often count for something! }
