[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: 2...c5 Fireworks (Playing the "Qxb6" Structure)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org, 5+0 Blitz } 1. c3 d5 2. d4 c5 3. Bf4 Qb6 4. Qb3
{ Since this is the 2...c5 lines starting with 1...d5 @@StartBracket@@as opposed to 1...Nf6@@EndBracket@@, then we opt out of crazy complications with  4.Nd2  ,  and play the more solid 4. Qb3 }
4... c4
{ I hadn't covered this move in our theory section, so I had to make a call on whether to retreat with Qc2 or trade with Qxb6. In these ...d5 + ...c5 lines without ...Nf6, the Qxb6 lines are very natural to play, so I took no risks and traded queens! }
5. Qxb6
{ 5.Qc2  In fact, there is nothing to fear with playing Qc2 here, since Black cannot prevent us playing e4.  5...Nc6   @@StartBracket@@  5...Bf5??  6.Qxf5  Qxb2  7.Qc8  @@EndBracket@@  6.e4± }
5... axb6 6. e4
{ This is the benefit of playing for the Qxb6 lines when Black hasn't played ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@controlling the e4-square@@EndBracket@@ }
6... e6 7. Nd2 b5 8. g3 b4 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. Bg2 Nf6 11. O-O
{ Completing the main setup in this Qxb6 variation! } 11... h6 12. Rfe1 Be7 13.
exd5 exd5 14. Be5
{ I am hoping to remove the defender of the pawn on d5, so that we can win it with Bxd5. If the d5-pawn falls, so will the rest of Black's queenside pawns! }
14... Be6
{ I was hoping for this move, since its too short sighted. Now I'm taking over in the centre after: }
15. Nf4 O-O 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Rxe6 bxc3 19. bxc3 Nxd4
{ A crazy looking move at first, but probably necessary to try to avoid an inevitable slow death. }
20. cxd4 Bxd4 21. Bxd5
{ This leads to a cleaner resulting position to convert, although I had to be very careful with the following tactics! }
21... Bxa1 22. Rxh6+ Rf7 23. Rb6 Rd8 24. Bxf7+ Kxf7 25. Nxc4
{ Now I'm in full control of the position. } 25... Rd7 26. Rxb7
{ A nice tactic to trade off Black's most troubling piece. } 26... Rxb7 27.
Nd6+ Ke6 28. Nxb7
{ There are many ways to convert this position, but I decided to make sure my knight was not trapped, then simply advance my kingside pawns. }
28... Bd4 29. Kg2 Kd7 30. Na5 Kd6 31. Nb3 Bb6 32. f4 Kd5 33. Kf3 Kc4 34. Kg4
Kb4 35. Kg5 Ka3 36. Kg6 Kxa2 37. Kxg7 Kxb3 38. f5 Kc4 39. f6 Bd4 40. Kg6 Kd5
41. f7 Bc5 42. Kg7 Ke6 43. f8=Q Bxf8+ 44. Kxf8 Kf6 45. h4
{ My opponent resigns here, given the lost endgame.   For anyone that doesn't see that the endgame is lost immediately, the point is that Black can never capture the backwards pawn, since the other pawn will run and promote to a queen! Since the pawns are untouchable, the endgame is well and truly lost. I wanted to show this game in particular so that you have some more confidence in the structures where Qxb6 is played.   Just remember, I only ever advocate for this move in positions without ...Nf6, otherwise we can't play our thematic immediate e4-pawn break in the centre! }
