[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: The Dutch (Beating my Former Coach with 1.c3 Venom!)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Invitational Blitz Tournament, 3+2 Rated Lichess.org  I was lucky to be invited to compete in a very strong online blitz tournament! Several titled players were playing, and midway through the event, I got paired against my former coach - IM Nikola Nikolovski! }
1. c3 f5
{ Nikola is one of the deadliest Dutch players on the planet. He has more scalps with the Dutch against 2500+ FIDE rated opponents, than I have fingers! Nevertheless, I was determined to test my 1.c3 Venom against Nikola. Bring it on! }
2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 b6
{ Since it is unlikely for me to setup with a fianchetto as well as develop my bishop to f4, Nikola aims to bring his light-squared bishop to the long diagonal to add further pressure to my kingside. }
4. e3 Bb7 5. Nd2 e6 6. h3 g6 7. Ngf3 Bg7 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Be2
{ 9.Bd3  This may be more in line with our course, in order to play for the e4 push! But interestingly here, our e4 push isn't quite working:  9...d6  10.e4?!  fxe4  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Bxe4  Normally, this would be a great position after Bxe4 Qxe4. However, Black has a strong in-between move:  12...d5!  In the Classical Variation lines that we studied in the course, we could meet this in-between move with Bxh7+! and avoid the double attack. Here, with the black pawn on g6, we don't have this option. So be careful when playing for the e4 break, and make sure you calculate whether we can reach our desired position successfully! }
9... d6 10. g4
{ Since I didn't play for the e4 break, I opted to play for g4 instead! I never had any interest in castling kingside. }
10... Nbd7 11. gxf5 exf5 12. Rg1 Qe7 13. O-O-O a6 14. Ng5
{ My feeling was that ...h6 would weaken Black's g6-pawn. Next, I'd want to play h4, so that my knight has a retreat square on h3. And since my knight would have a safe retreat square on h3, I could follow up with the f3 push, to limit Black's minor pieces. }
14... b5 15. h4 h6 16. Nh3 Qf7 17. Kb1
{ 17.h5!  I could actually have attacked first and been faster!  17...Qxa2  18.Rxg6  Qa1+  19.Nb1!  In fact I am the first to crash through! I did not realise I have Nb1 as a defensive resource. Good to know for next time! }
17... Kh8 18. f3
{ Despite the position appearing seemingly under control, Nikola does a great job to outplay me here! }
18... Nh5 19. Bh2 Bd5 20. c4 bxc4 21. Bxc4 Nb6 22. Bb3 a5 23. Nf4 Nxf4 24. Bxf4
a4 25. Bxd5 Nxd5
{ After several moves, the weakness of my e3-pawn is exposed and I am in trouble. I tried to defend tactically after: }
26. Qc4
{ Black can trade on f4, but at the cost of a queen trade, which would subsequently weaken the black g6-pawn further! }
26... a3 27. b3 { I had to keep my queenside closed. } 27... Kh7
{ Nikola prophylactically defends his g6-pawn. Here, I was still not looking forward to the resulting position after ...Nxf4, but I decided to defend my e-pawn just in case he didn't take my bishop for whatever reason! }
28. Rde1 Rab8
{ Incredibly, this is the choice of stockfish and the correct move! However, in the game, I was extremely happy to see that my structure wouldn't be ruined after ...Nxf4!   28...Nxf4!?  Not as good objectively, but Black's advantage is crystal clear. This would certainly have been my choice had I had the black pieces.  29.exf4  With  29...Qxc4  30.Nxc4  Bxd4?  I assumed this would be a great position with Black, a pawn up and the healthier pawn structure. However, I do have dynamic chances here!  31.Re7+!  Suddenly, the advantage has flipped in my favour. I didn't see any of this, but sometimes in chess, you can get away with such oversights! }
29. Bh2
{ I was very happy to save my bishop, but Nikola continues to pile on the pressure! }
29... Rb4 30. Qd3
{ Here, Stockfish evaluates the position to be -2.5 in Black's favour. Nikola probably felt he had numerous wins here, but thankfully, he played the one move that blundered... }
30... c5
{ A great move — if not for my assassin dark-squared bishop lurking on h2! Even strong players forget about the sneaky London bishop sometimes! }
31. h5 { A useful move to throw in that Black had to respond to. } 31... g5 32.
Bxd6 Rc8
{ At this moment, to keep the advantage, I had to play precisely. I would need to play: }
33. Bxc5
{ 33.Rc1!  Now the black c5-pawn would be safe to capture, and I'd keep the advantage! }
33... Rxc5
{ I had actually seen this exchange sacrifice, but I thought I'd survive. In fact, I am dead lost — but to my surprise, Nikola also missed the winning continuation! }
34. dxc5 Nc3+
{ 34...Qf6!!  Removing the defence to the knight on d5 and playing for mate! Nikola would typically find this move in seconds, but I can only assume that he was somewhat shaken from the earlier blunder of 30...c5?? To stay calm and composed and continue to find the top moves after a blunder is a great skill. Don't forget Alekhine's Advice on this matter! }
35. Kc2 Nxa2 36. Nc4 Rb8
{ I just about survived the onslaught, and look to try get some active counterplay myself now: }
37. Qd6 Nb4+ 38. Kd2 Qg8 39. Qg6+ Kh8 40. Ra1
{ I didn't mind if Black would win my exchange since I felt I'd be winning the resulting endgame. }
40... a2
{ Black, quite rightly, declines my offer of the rook.   40...Bxa1?  41.Qxh6+!  Qh7  42.Qxh7+  Kxh7  43.Rxa1±  With decent chances to convert this endgame, two pawns up. }
41. Ke2
{ I use my free move to get my king a little safer. You never know when that extra bit of king safety will save you! }
41... Qd5 42. Nd6 Rf8 43. Rgd1 Qxb3 44. Rd2
{ I somehow manage to defend all the entry points with only seconds remaining for both sides on the clock. }
44... Nc2 45. Nxf5 Qc4+
{ A seemingly useful move that in fact gets my king to a safer position. Now there is no attack, and I stand better with my material advantage. A useful proverb @@StartBracket@@that I learnt from the Japanese board game similar to Chess called Shogi!@@EndBracket@@ is "to check, is to chase". This will really help avoid making unnecessary checks, that don't help with the attack. }
46. Kf2 Rxf5 47. Qxf5 Qg8 48. c6
{ Passed pawns should be pushed! I could only pray that I'd be fast enough to make a queen! }
48... Nxa1 49. Rxa2
{ An instant move from me, imagining that the only reason why I couldn't take this pawn was because the knight was blocking the way. However, I had completely overlooked Black's queen on g8 was defending the pawn! Luckily for me, both of us were down to seconds, which led to Nikola completely missing the free rook too! Time scrambles can lead to messy chess for all standards of chess player. }
49... Nb3 50. c7 Nc1
{ I really should have stayed calm and played Rc2 — getting my rook to safety, and supporting my passed pawn to promote. However, in the heat of the moment, I couldn't help but queen my pawn! }
51. c8=Q Nxa2 52. Qxg8+ Kxg8
{ Luckily for me, Black's two minor pieces are completely uncoordinated, and with the black king exposed as well, this made the conversion of this position simple: }
53. Qd5+ Kh8 54. Qxa2
{ Having lost the knight, Nikola resigned. I very rarely manage to beat Nikola, but I do think 1.c3 Venom played a part in this victory! By castling on the queenside and avoiding an all-out-Dutch-attack on my king on the kingside, I managed to get a more balanced position in terms of equal dynamic opportunities for both sides. Dutch games will always be wild, but in our lines, we will have the opportunity to takeover, as opposed to our opponents getting all the play! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📖 Model games: London System"]
[Black "Model Game: The Copycat (My First OTB Classical Game with 1.c3 Venom!)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Michael Green @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ vs J Pattinson @@StartBracket@@1700@@EndBracket@@, Leicestershire League Match, 75+10 }
1. c3 { This was my first OTB Classical game of 1.c3 Venom! } 1... d5 2. d4 c6
3. Bf4 Bf5
{ At this point in time, I hadn't worked out my exact theory on how to face a Copycat. But regardless, the game and my thoughts during it are still instructive! }
4. e3
{ 4.Qb3!  If I came across this position today, this is what I'd play! We follow our rule of meeting ...Bf5 with Qb3, and immediately pressure the b7-pawn. I cover this line of the Copycat in the 'Unprincipled Setups' Chapter!  4...Qb6  5.e3  e6  6.Nd2  Nd7  7.Ngf3  Ngf6  8.Nh4⩲ }
4... Nf6 5. Nd2 e6
{ I would like to develop with Nf3, but I wasn't satisfied with trading knight for bishop after ...Nh5. So I decided to play the thematic h3. }
6. h3 Bd6
{ My opponent breaks the symmetry @@StartBracket@@since I wouldn't have the option of playing Bd3@@EndBracket@@. Here, I am very happy to trade dark-squared bishops, since that is Black's best attacking minor piece for kingside activity. }
7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Ngf3 Nbd7 9. Be2
{ I am happy to retain my LSB, since it is the 'good' bishop on the opposite colour to my pawn chain. }
9... h6 10. Qb3
{ 10.O-O ?!  I would not want to rush with castling kingside, since Black's queen is on d6, and Black has yet to castle, and can therefore begin pushing ...g5, or start with ...Rg8.   In general, we should wait for our opponent to at least commit to ...O-O before mirroring with O-O. }
10... b6 11. Rc1
{ Still waiting for Black to show their hand before committing my king to the kingside. }
11... O-O
{ Here, Black doesn't have to worry about me playing g4 or Rg1, since Black has control of the b1-h7 diagonal. Therefore, my bishop on e2 will be ineffective in the attack, and I'd probably get bulldozed in the centre if I go for an all out kingside attack here. I have better prospects to play on the queenside. }
12. O-O { Now that Black has castled kingside, I can safely castle kingside. }
12... Ne4 13. Nxe4
{ I'm quite happy to trade, since either Black's pawn structure will be weakened, or we are removing one less potential attacking piece for Black on the kingside. }
13... Bxe4 14. Nd2
{ I want to keep my knight on the board, since it may be useful when increasing the pressure on my opponent's queenside. }
14... Bg6 15. c4
{ Now that all my pieces are developed and my king is safe, it is time to strike the centre. Perhaps I could have started with Rfd1, but then I'm not entirely sure if the c-file will open up immediately, in which case I might prefer to double rooks on the c-file straight away. }
15... Rac8 16. Rfd1
{ Improving a piece, and asking Black what they want to do. None of their breaks are working, so it's worth waiting to see if they will mess up! }
16... Nf6
{ 16...c5?!  17.Qa3!  Pinning the c-pawn to the loose queen, and adding pressure to the pawn on a7!  17...Rfd8  18.cxd5  exd5  19.dxc5⩲  Black will have a weak pawn structure in whichever way they capture.   16...e5?!  17.dxe5  Nxe5  18.Nf1!  an odd looking move, but puts Black's centre under fire immediately. Black will be left with an isolated pawn by force — and probably lost soon after, for instance:  18...Rfd8  19.cxd5  cxd5  20.Rxc8  Rxc8  21.Rxd5±  A clean pawn up! }
17. cxd5
{ I felt happy about my prospects after whichever capture came my way! When this is the case, it's a good time to capture on d5! }
17... cxd5
{ 17...exd5  This would lead to a minority attack style position, where the c6-pawn has already been weakened! I'd just have to watch out for Black unravelling with ...c5, but I felt even with ...c5, there'd be ways to undermine Black's central pawns. For instance:  18.Qa4  Rc7  19.Rc3  c5  20.Rdc1  And if Black tries to reduce the pressure on c5:  20...c4  21.b3⩲  We have a new target to aim for!   17...Nxd5?  Here, we can immediately capitalise on the awkward placement of Black's pieces.  18.Nc4!  Qe7  19.Ne5  Black cannot save both their bishop @@StartBracket@@as well as their pawn structure getting ruined@@EndBracket@@, and the c6-pawn  19...Bh7  20.Nxc6±   17...Qxd5?  18.Qa3!  White keeps the queens on, and again immediately exploits the poor placement of Black's pieces. For instance:  18...Rc7  19.Bf3!  Qd7  20.Nc4  Bh7  21.Ne5!  Qc8  22.Rxc6± }
18. Ba6
{ This is the move I'd been counting on. When we have a symmetrical pawn structure, the tiniest of advantages can evolve into serious winning chances. Here, the fight will revolve around the c-file, and whoever wins it will have great winning chances! Therefore, Ba6 controls the crucial c8-square, and also prevents the a7-pawn from moving, making it a potential target to Rc1-c7-Rxa7 some day. }
18... Rxc1
{ This is too easy. Black should not give up the fight for the c-file.   18...Rc7!  19.Rc3  This was my plan, and I had looked at the critical ...b5 too.  19...Rxc3   @@StartBracket@@  19...b5!?  20.Bxb5  Rb7   20...Rb8!  ...but I missed this! Thankfully, I am still fine after Qa4, but I am no longer able to fight for the c-file.  21.Qa4  Qb6  22.Rxc7  Qxc7=  21.Rc6!  On 20..Rb7, I had seen this move, and was happy with my position.@@EndBracket@@  20.Qxc3⩲  White wins the fight for the c-file. }
19. Rxc1 Ne4 20. Nxe4
{ Now I am quite happy to trade, since my bishop is very effective, while Black achieves nothing by controlling the h7-b1 diagonal. }
20... Bxe4 21. Qb5 { I didn't want to allow any ...b5 ideas. } 21... Qe7 22.
Rc6
{ This was definitely over-optimistic. I had seen that on the previous move, had my opponent played a 'nothing move', I'd have Rc6 @@StartBracket@@attacking the queen on d6@@EndBracket@@, and if ...Qd7, I'd have the surprising Rxb6! with advantage.   This is a nice trick, but it makes very little sense to try it here, since why on earth would Black play ...Qd7 now, having just played ...Qe7? Instead, I should be focused on playing the best moves to execute my plan   22.Rc3  Qg5  23.Qf1  This would be a better version of the game, since the rook is not loose on c6, and I have f3 immediately if needed. }
22... Qg5 23. Qf1 Re8 24. Rc3
{ 24.Rc7  This was my whole plan @@StartBracket@@making use of my c-file to enter onto the 7th rank, and target the weak a7-pawn@@EndBracket@@, but I wasn't sure how to proceed after:  24...Re7  in fact, Stockfish 16 reckons White has a slight edge after:  25.Rc8+  Kh7  26.Bd3  Bxd3  27.Qxd3+  Qg6  28.Qxg6+  Kxg6  29.Kf1⩲  I'm not sure if White really has enough here to make use of the '+0.3', but for sure Black has zero winning chances since we have control over the c-file! }
24... e5
{ I was surprised that my opponent was going for it, but I had anticipated this move too   24...Rd8  If my opponent tried to sit with this move, I would've snapped up the opportunity to play:  25.Rc7⩲   24...Kh8  What would've I done had my opponent sat and done nothing here? This is what I had planned:  25.f3  Bg6  26.Kf2  Qh4+  27.g3!?  If you think about it, this is just a regular kingside castled pawn formation with f2 g2 h2, just shifted one rank up. I didn't really see a weakness in it, and I'd hope to continue efforts with playing on the c-file.  27...Qf6  28.Qc1  Qf5  29.Kg2⩲ }
25. dxe5 Qxe5 26. Qd1
{ Unless Black can immediately unravel, they will be left with a weak d5-pawn. }
26... Rd8 27. Qd4
{ Not afraid to give up my fight against the Isolated Queen's Pawn, and instead transition the position to another slight advantage. }
27... Qxd4 28. exd4
{ By having no queens on the board, my king is now free to roam. In addition, there is a very intricate imbalance in the position. Can you see it?   It is in fact the d-pawns! Our pawn is on a dark square, while Black's in on a light square, which means there are more chances for me to target their pawn with our light-squared bishop! In addition, when I played 27. Qd4, I had anticipated a long line to follow. I actually saw a way that Black could blunder a piece, so I decided to play the next moves fairly quickly, but also in a relaxed manner, to avoid suspicion that there could be any tactical pitfalls in the position! }
28... Rd7 29. f3
{ Setting a deadly trap. As I said in the previous comment, I was very chill when playing this move! }
29... Bf5
{ The logic is sound, that perhaps the bishop can be super solid on ...Be6 in order to hold. However, this was the tactical pitfall I was hoping for!   29...Bh7??  I'm sure Black saw that this would blunder to the simple  30.Rc8+!  Rd8  31.Rxd8  After seeing this, it is quite easy to switch off tactically, and start trying to focus on purely the positional differences of playing ...Bg6 vs ...Bf5.   29...Bg6  Of course, the better square for the bishop. After the game, we had a brief look at how the position could continue here:  30.Kf2  f6  31.Rc8+  Kf7  32.Bb5!  Re7  33.Bc6!   33.Rd8?!  a worse move order since Black can play actively with:  33...Rc7!  Ke6  34.Rd8±  Black's defensive setup crumbles.   As we can see, the light squared bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal was too awkwardly placed to help with the defence, and now White has great winning chances with the active pieces, and going a pawn up! }
30. Bc8
{ My opponent resigns. I was hoping to play this position on actually @@StartBracket@@in the instance that my opponent had played 29...Bg6 instead of 29...Bf5??@@EndBracket@@, and see whether I could grind my opponent down.   But this is often how these 'solid, but slightly worse' positions go for Black. Our opponent will falter much sooner since they are having to passively defend the position. To find correct defensive setups AND watch out for tactics, is a really difficult task to carry out for the rest of the game!   This game concludes our London System Model Games. I hope you were able to learn from my failures, as well as my successes, in order to improve your skills as a complete chess player! }
