[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: London System"]
[Black "1...d5 London: A Deeper Dive 5...Bf5 (with 6...Qd7)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5
{ Nowadays, this is the most popular move, hence I am considering it to be the 'new mainline'. Black establishes their light-squared bishop on this strong diagonal before White can prevent it @@StartBracket@@as in the mainline with  5...Qb6  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2!  g6  8.e4!  @@EndBracket@@.   As before, we should remember the rule: as soon as the light-squared bishop develops, we meet this with Qb3! }
6. Qb3
{ Since we are attacking the b7-pawn, Black must decide how to defend it, and will most likely choose between ...Qb6, ...Qd7, and ...Qc8.   The first of these options is dubious which we have examined fully in the main course.  6...Qd7  has the drawback of potentially being vulnerable to Bb5 & Nf3-e5 ideas.   6...Qc8  has the drawback of being on the c-file, where we can play for a quick c4 and Rc1.   6...Qb6  Please refer to the main course 1...d5 for further analysis here! }
6... Qd7
{ So the current theory suggests the following plan: White will develop naturally @@StartBracket@@with Ngf3, Be2 etc.@@EndBracket@@, and if Black doesn't do anything significant, we break the centre with c4. If Black ever pushes ...c4 themselves, we drop back to Qd1, and will later undermine Black's queenside with b3.   The downside of this plan, is that this b3 plan to break Black's pawn chain is extremely nuanced. In many cases, playing b3 at the wrong time can lead to an immediate loss @@StartBracket@@see the variation after  7.Ngf3  c4  8.Qd1  e6  9.b3?  @@EndBracket@@ For this reason, I would like to propose a different plan. Since the queen is on d7, we will begin with Ngf3, in case Black is caught napping, and allows a quick attack of Bb5! and Ne5!   If Black instead pushes ...c4, we will not retreat to d1, but advance to b5!? The idea being that we will safely be able to undermine Black's pawn structure with b3, since ...b5 is blocked by our queen!   Let's examine these lines: }
7. Ngf3 c4 8. Qb5
{ The main move by far is Qd1, where the theory continues real deep. Instead, we sidestep all of this with this rare move, which has a very clear plan: we want to play b3 to undermine Black's pawn chain, without allowing Black to play ...b5 with nasty ...b4! ideas @@StartBracket@@see the variation after  8.Qd1  e6  9.b3?  @@EndBracket@@.   Against most of Black's moves, we will be playing b3 next, with a fine position. There is only one critical reply for Black, so this is what we will examine here:  8.Qd1  e6  9.b3?  Here, the thematic b3 fails due to the following sequence:  9...b5!  10.a4  b4!  -/+ This is a well known combination for Black, which leads to an advantage for Black! }
8... a6
{ This is the most critical move in the position. Any slow move can be met with b3, leading to a great position for White. In fact, I was able to beat an FM in 13 moves in this variation!   8...Qc8  9.b3  a6  10.Qb6  transposes to 8...a6. }
9. Qb6 { We must prevent Black from playing ...b5. } 9... Qc8
{ Black's most logical move, in order to play ...Nd7 next to displace our queen.   For the record, most players would probably play some developing move like  9...e6  ,  after which we'd play  10.b3  with a great game ahead.   So Black really has to play precisely here! }
10. Ne5 { Black tries to play ...Nd7? So we prevent their idea with Ne5! }
10... Nxe5 { Black tries to displace our queen. } 11. Bxe5 Nd7 12. Qc7 b5
{ Black has finally achieved their desired ...b5, however, compared to the mainlines with our queen on d1, our queen is far more active! As a result, I really like the following plan to undermine Black's pawn structure: }
13. a4 b4 14. e4
{ Temporarily sacrificing a pawn, but regaining the black c4-pawn on the next move. }
14... dxe4 15. Bxc4
{ We are very far out into novel territory, so I have simplified the end of this variation by giving Black the dubious 14...dxe4.   You're welcome to look into these positions further, but I felt this is far enough. I believe this 8. Qb5 line offers great practical chances compared to the traditional 8. Qd1 move. }
