{ Nowadays, this is the most popular move, hence I am considering it to be the 'new mainline'. Black establishes their light-squared bishop on this strong diagonal before White can prevent it @@StartBracket@@as in the mainline with  5...Qb6  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2!  g6  8.e4!  @@EndBracket@@.   As before, we should remember the rule: as soon as the light-squared bishop develops, we meet this with Qb3! }
6. Qb3
{ Since we are attacking the b7-pawn, Black must decide how to defend it, and will most likely choose between ...Qb6, ...Qd7, and ...Qc8.   The first of these options is dubious which we have examined fully in the main course.  6...Qd7  has the drawback of potentially being vulnerable to Bb5 & Nf3-e5 ideas.   6...Qc8  has the drawback of being on the c-file, where we can play for a quick c4 and Rc1.   6...Qb6  Please refer to the main course 1...d5 for further analysis here! }
6... Qc8
