7... e6 8. Ngf3 Be7
{ Once Black has spent a tempo on their dark-squared bishop, we should now clarify the centre: }
9. cxd5 exd5
{ 9...Nxd5  10.Bg3  +/= We are threatening to fork Black's pieces, so I believe Black has already more headaches to solve than White! }
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Rc1 b6 12. Bb5 a6 13. Bxc6+ Qxc6 14. Nd4 Qd7 15. N2f3
{ 15.Nxf5  is also strong @@StartBracket@@taking the bishop pair@@EndBracket@@, but I like this simple improving move more. The e5-square belongs to our knight, and Black just has a weak isolated d-pawn with very little compensation.   We can be happy with our chances to convert this position! }
