1. c3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5
{ Nowadays, this is the most popular move, hence I am considering it to be the 'new mainline'. Black establishes their light-squared bishop on this strong diagonal before White can prevent it @@StartBracket@@as in the mainline with  5...Qb6  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2!  g6  8.e4!  @@EndBracket@@.   As before, we should remember the rule: as soon as the light-squared bishop develops, we meet this with Qb3! }
6. Qb3
{ Since we are attacking the b7-pawn, Black must decide how to defend it, and will most likely choose between ...Qb6, ...Qd7, and ...Qc8.   The first of these options is dubious which we have examined fully in the main course.  6...Qd7  has the drawback of potentially being vulnerable to Bb5 & Nf3-e5 ideas.   6...Qc8  has the drawback of being on the c-file, where we can play for a quick c4 and Rc1.   6...Qb6  Please refer to the main course 1...d5 for further analysis here! }
6... Qc8
{ When Black plays 6...Qc8, our plan is easy to remember. Since the queen isn't on d7, it doesn't make much sense to continue with Nf3-e5 and Bb5 @@StartBracket@@since there's no ...Qd7 as a target@@EndBracket@@, and instead with the queen on c8, we can target it immediately by opening the c-file... }
7. c4
{ Black has two principled responses here.  7...e6  leads to Black getting an isolated queen's pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@, and  7...dxc4  leads to us getting an IQP.   7...cxd4  Please refer to the main course 1...d5 for further analysis here! }
7... dxc4 8. Bxc4
{ We're more than happy to recapture and develop the bishop in a single move @@StartBracket@@as a result, Black should typically wait for us to develop Be2, before capturing on c4@@EndBracket@@. }
8... e6 { Necessary to stop the immediate threat of capturing on f7. } 9. Ngf3
cxd4 10. Nxd4
{ Black is forced to take us, otherwise our lead in development will prove fatal for Black. }
10... Nxd4
{ 10...Bg6?  Black does not have time to retreat their bishop since they are behind in development and their queen is exposed.  11.Rc1  Nxd4  12.exd4  Qd7  13.Bb5  +- }
11. exd4
{ So compared to the line following 7...e6, it's now our turn to have the Isolated Queen's Pawn @@StartBracket@@IQP@@EndBracket@@ position. But the difference here, is that Black still hasn't castled, and therefore has to play VERY precisely, in order not to be lost. Bb5+ is already a threat, so Black must play: }
11... a6
{ 11...Be7?!  12.Bb5+!  Kf8  13.O-O  += With Black's king unable to castle, Black's rook on h8 is out of the game. This gives us a slight edge and full compensation for the IQP. }
12. O-O Be7 13. Rfc1
{ At first glance, it may appear that the 'wrong rook' has been placed on the c-file. However, there's a specific plan of ours involving a quick Bf1 and Nc4 incoming next. In open positions, we should be direct with our plans, and not waste any time @@StartBracket@@otherwise the opportunity to play actively might be missed!@@EndBracket@@. }
13... Qd7 14. Bf1 { ...Qxd4 is met by Qxb7, so Black should play it safe. }
14... O-O 15. Nc4
{ This position is objectively equal, but we have a lot of activity to compensate for our IQP.   Firstly, we are threatening the fork on b6.   Secondly, if Black captures d4 immediately with ...Qxd4, we can counterattack with Qxb7, and if ...Qxf4, then Qxe7. }
