[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: London System"]
[Black "1...d5 London: A Deeper Dive 5...e6 (with 8...Re8)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nd2 e6
{ Black is playing for the plan of Bd6 e5. Therefore, we should play Ngf3 next to take extra control over the e5-square. }
6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Be2
{ A rare, but simple, move! You're welcome to investigate the more ambitious Bd3, but this requires more concrete theory, as well as the ability to be able to execute a complicated kingside attack!   If you are going to look into this, make sure to study/understand the theory after  8...Re8  9.Ne5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.f4  Qb6  . We cover this line in our course with 8. Be2, which is a much more easy-to-play version than with 8. Bd3. }
8... Re8
{ Here comes another rule to keep in mind. Whenever Black is ready to push ...e5, our go to move when possible is to block this push with: }
9. Ne5 Bxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4
{ This structure looks very wild/weakening at first sight, but in fact it makes a lot of sense. We are strong-holding the e5-square, and the weak e3-pawn can be defended easily with Bf2.   Let's take a look at how this position can develop. }
11... Qb6 { Attacking b2. } 12. Qc2 { Defending b2. } 12... c4
{ Attacking e3. } 13. Bf2
{ Defending e3, and lining up against Black's queen. } 13... Qc7 14. e4
{ White is doing great here, for several reasons.   Firstly, we are slightly better developed @@StartBracket@@three minor pieces developed instead of two@@EndBracket@@.   Secondly, it is easier for us to target the d5-pawn, as opposed to Black targeting our e5-pawn.   Let's see what happens if Black tries to undermine our e5-pawn: }
14... f6 15. exf6 Nxf6
{ 15...Qxf4  16.fxg7  +/- Black's king will be less safe than ours after we O-O. }
16. e5 Nd7
{ We have undoubled our pawns, and our e5-pawn stays strong! After castling kingside @@StartBracket@@castling queenside would be an unnecessary risk since that allows Black to easily push ...b5 ...a5 ...b4@@EndBracket@@, we can develop our pieces towards the kingside, with good attacking chances! }
17. O-O
{ Bg4, Nf3-g5, Be3 with Rf3-h3 in mind, all look like strong attacking options to me! }
