[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: London System"]
[Black "1...d5 London: A Deeper Dive 5...e6 (with 8...cxd4) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nd2 e6
{ Black is playing for the plan of Bd6 e5. Therefore, we should play Ngf3 next to take extra control over the e5-square. }
6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Be2
{ A rare, but simple, move! You're welcome to investigate the more ambitious  8.Bd3  , but this requires more concrete theory, as well as the ability to be able to execute a complicated kingside attack! If you are going to look into this, make sure to study/understand the theory after  8...Re8  9.Ne5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.f4  Qb6  . We cover this line in our course with 8. Be2, which is a much more easy-to-play version than with 8. Bd3 @@StartBracket@@where our b2- and e3- pawns come under immediate fire!@@EndBracket@@. }
8... cxd4
{ In addition to Black's plan to play for ...e5, this 5...e6 variation allows for Black to try for ...cxd4 in arguably the most favourable conditions possible.   Let's see why! }
9. exd4
{ After exd4, Black is aiming for a minority attack on the queenside, which is strengthened since our bishop has no control over the b8-square @@StartBracket@@therefore ...Rb8, ...b5 can be played@@EndBracket@@.   On the brightside, since Black's light-squared bishop has been unable to develop outside of the chain, and is stuck on c8, this means we will have good attacking chances on the kingside with an eventual Bd3, eyeing up the h7-pawn. In addition, I have prepared for you a nice and simple remedy to the minority attack in these positions.   Let's take a look! }
9... a6 { Since ...b5 is a threat, we should aim to prevent this: } 10. a4 Rb8
11. O-O b5
{ Black has achieved ...b5, and if we are not careful, Black may push ...b4 and gain an advantage on the queenside @@StartBracket@@by damaging our queenside pawn structure@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, we must immediately play: }
12. axb5 axb5 13. b4
{ This is the key idea! We prevent ...b4, at the cost of weakening our c3-pawn. However, after we complete the maneuver Nb3-c5, the c3-pawn will no longer be as weak since we have blocked the half open c-file.   The b5-pawn is weak for Black, and we can think of putting some pressure on the kingside with Bd3 @@StartBracket@@since Black's light-squared bishop is unable to contest the diagonal!@@EndBracket@@. }
