{ 11.Ne5?  This looks nice to pick up the h5-knight, but unfortunately, our bishop on e2 will be pinned in the end!  11...Nxe5  12.dxe5  Qxe5  -/+ }
11... a6 12. a4 Rb8 13. O-O Na5
{ What if Black doesn't play for ...b5 immediately? This is when our pressure on the kingside will show. }
14. Ne5 Nf6 15. Bd3 Bd7 16. f4 Be8 17. g4
{ I'd normally not recommend such aggressive moves on the kingside that weaken our own king! However, since the centre is completely blocked, there is very little risk to such an expansion!   The position can quickly collapse for Black if they play too slowly. }
17... Bd7 { For argument's sake. } 18. g5 Ne8 19. Bxh7+ Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21.
Rf3
{ These are the kind of destructive attacks that can occur when Black's light-squared bishop is stuck inside the pawn chain.   Thankfully for us, we never have to experience such horrors, since we are always developing the bishop outside of the chain with Bf4, protecting our kingside! }
