[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: London System"]
[Black "1...d5 London: A Deeper Dive 5...e6 (with 8...b6) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nd2 e6
{ Black is playing for the plan of Bd6 e5. Therefore, we should play Ngf3 next to take extra control over the e5-square. }
6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Be2
{ A rare, but simple, move! You're welcome to investigate the more ambitious Bd3, but this requires more concrete theory, as well as the ability to be able to execute a complicated kingside attack!   If you are going to look into this, make sure to study/understand the theory after  8...Re8  9.Ne5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.f4  Qb6  . We cover this line in our course with 8. Be2, which is a much more easy-to-play version than with 8. Bd3. }
8... b6
{ This is the main move here, basically just focusing on finishing development. We should follow suit, and complete our development first, too! }
9. O-O Bb7 10. Re1
{ I like this developing waiting move. Black needs to make a choice of where they want to play. Will they play  10...c4  and press on the queenside? Or will they play in the centre with ...e5 @@StartBracket@@starting with  10...Re8  @@EndBracket@@?   And what if they just sit, and do nothing @@StartBracket@@for example,  10...Rc8  @@EndBracket@@? }
10... Re8
{ If Black plays for an eventual ...e5, we should make sure to play dxe5, reaching a similar structure to our Caro-Kann Reversed One Knight/Classical Variation. We are far more solid, and can try to undermine Black's centre with b4 or c4, or play down the d-file.   It should be noted that White could also play  11.Ne5  here — in tune with the main course recommendation. However, I think it's useful to understand the positions where Black achieves ...e5, since we can't always prevent the pawn break forever. }
11. Rc1 e5 12. dxe5
{ By capturing the black e-pawn, we reduce chances of a kingside attack from Black. }
12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Rxe5
{ We have the Caro-Kann Reversed Classical Variation pawn structure. We will typically have the better side of equality, since we can play against Black's d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@which will be slightly weak unless Black can successfully push ...d4@@EndBracket@@.  I would recommend checking out this Model Game to appreciate how the grind may typically go! }
15. b4
{ This pawn break may look unusual at first  (since we are challenging the c-pawn when it's defended by the b-pawn)  , however there is some logic! If we can play bxc5, we will be left with an isolated c3-pawn — but the idea is that we will be able to break with c4! immediately after and remove our c-pawn weakness! }
15... Rc8 16. bxc5 bxc5 17. Bf3 Qc7 18. c4 d4 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Nf3 Ree8 21.
exd4
{ White wins a pawn! Of course, 18...d4? was by no means forced, but this is the kind of play we can often get against Black's centre. Look to play for the c4 break, when Black cannot meet it successfully with ...d4. }
