6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Be2
{ A rare, but simple, move! You're welcome to investigate the more ambitious Bd3, but this requires more concrete theory, as well as the ability to be able to execute a complicated kingside attack!   If you are going to look into this, make sure to study/understand the theory after  8...Re8  9.Ne5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  11.f4  Qb6  . We cover this line in our course with 8. Be2, which is a much more easy-to-play version than with 8. Bd3. }
8... b6
{ This is the main move here, basically just focusing on finishing development. We should follow suit and complete our development first too! }
9. O-O Bb7 10. Re1
{ I like this developing waiting move. Black needs to make a choice of where they want to play. Will they play  10...c4  and press on the queenside? Or will they play in the centre with ...e5 @@StartBracket@@starting with  10...Re8  @@EndBracket@@?   And what if they just sit, and do nothing @@StartBracket@@for example,  10...Rc8  @@EndBracket@@? }
10... c4
{ If Black plays for ...c4 instead, we should look to undermine Black's queenside immediately: }
11. b3 b5 12. a4 a6
{ 12...b4?  In some lines of the London @@StartBracket@@not our lines@@EndBracket@@, this ...b4 push can be dangerous. However, in this position, Black's pieces are not coordinated well for this push, and White can take the advantage:  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.bxc4  bxc3  15.c5±   12...Bxg3  Also worth checking, since now we don't have our Bxd6 trick in case of ...b4. However, this is not to worry, and we are still well placed to meet the ...b4 break.  13.hxg3  b4?!  14.Rc1  bxc3  15.Rxc3  cxb3  16.Qxb3⩲  We have the better light-squared bishop, and have greater development on the queenside.   12...bxa4?  It's rare that an opponent will make this mistake, but we should always remember this strong response!  13.bxc4±  We don't recapture the a-pawn, but the c-pawn instead! }
13. Qc2
{ We should bring our pieces to the queenside @@StartBracket@@e.g. Reb1@@EndBracket@@, and then open the queenside up when the position is most favourable for us.   We have a slight space advantage on the queenside @@StartBracket@@given Black's Bb7/Nc6 are in the way@@EndBracket@@, so I believe we will be able to coordinate our pieces more easily on the queenside, before playing on that side of the board!   In addition, we can consider playing e4 too, although we should be careful not to unlock the potential of Black's light-squared bishop on b7. }
