3... Bg7 4. e3 d6 5. h3
{ Now that Be5 isn't possible, it is important to play h3 to give our bishop a retreat square on h2, in case of ...Nh5. }
5... O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be2
{ In the main course, I gave  7...Re8  as Black's main response to our London System, in order for you to understand the basic plans and ideas.   In fact, Black can play more accurately than  7...Re8  ,  which in turn forces us to find some accurate moves too! But to emphasise, the previous lines you have studied on the KID with ...e5 are still important to understand our ideas here! }
7... Qe8
{ If Black wants to push ...e5, then this is the way to do it.  7...Qe8  can be considered the mainline of 'KID setups with ...e5', and we will see exactly how to deal with this! }
8. O-O e5
{ Here there is no way to win the e5-pawn, which is why having Bh2 as a default reaction is handy! }
9. Bh2
{ At this moment, Black has the same options as in the main course. ...c6 and ...Nh5 are dubious for similar reasons as we discussed already, so let's take a look at  9...e4?!  , and the main theory with  9...Qe7  . }
9... Qe7 10. Qc2
{ To understand this move, we should first understand Black's response to our principled 10. c4.   10.c4  Ne4!  11.Qc2  f5!  Black finds an efficient way to kickstart a kingside attack with ...f5. With the knight standing strong in the centre on e4, we find it difficult to get our typical counterplay in the centre. For instance, pushing  12.c5  to undermine Black's central pawn chain is more difficult due to Black's e4-knight also controlling the c5-square.   In addition, whenever White tries to develop with Nc3, Black can just trade knights, and bring their other knight to f6. Black's pieces will not get in each other's way, and continue to have strong kingside attacking prospects.   Now we can appreciate this Qc2 move — we want to prevent our opponent from playing ...Ne4, then ...f5. Alternative moves for the black knight aren't as effective to get in the ...f5 push. }
10... Ne8 11. c4 f5
{ Black achieves ...f5, but we will be quick to counter in the centre! } 12.
Nc3 g5 13. c5
{ Our classic pawn break to counter Black's King's Indian pawn centre. } 13...
g4 14. cxd6 cxd6 15. Nd5
{ We should meet a flank attack with an attack in the centre! This is exactly what a move like 15. Nd5 achieves, and although the following moves may appear complicated, White should just focus on neutralising the attack, and Black's static features of the position will be worse off. }
15... Qd8 16. hxg4 fxg4 17. Nd2 exd4 18. Bxg4 dxe3 19. Nxe3
{ The centre and kingside tension resolves, and White stands well on top! With the increased development, and the weak black d6-pawn as a target, White has a clear advantage! }
