[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: London System"]
[Black "2...c5 Fireworks: 1...d5 2...c5 An Early 3...cxd4 (with 5.Nc3! alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 d5 2. d4 c5 3. Bf4 cxd4 4. cxd4 Qb6 5. Nc3
{ In the main course, I suggested to play solidly with 5. Qc1 @@StartBracket@@as suggested in the 2...c5 lines starting with 1...Nf6@@EndBracket@@, but I think 5. Nc3 is just better here.   Black is not in time to play  5...Qxb2  due to  6.Nxd5  +- with a crushing attack.   The reason I didn't suggest 5. Nc3 in the main course is that there is one decent line Black can try, where the lines do become a bit sharp! }
5... Nf6 { Defending the weak d-pawn, and developing a piece. } 6. e3 Qxb2 7.
Bb5+
{ The only move for advantage, but a very natural one — developing a piece with tempo! }
7... Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 9. Nge2
{ White is threatening to play Rb1, and capture the pawn on b7. Therefore, Black must defend in the following way: }
9... Qa3 10. Rb1 b6 11. O-O
{ Black has saved the pawn, but at what cost?   White is planning to attack with Nb5 next with devastating consequences with the double attack on the queen and the threat of a fork on c7. }
11... a6 { The only move to defend, but now the b6-pawn is weak. } 12. Na4 b5
13. Qc2
{ With this spectacular quiet move, White keeps the advantage. The point being that the knight is untouchable, since on either  13...bxa4  or  13...Qxa4  , White will enter Black's camp with  14.Qc6! }
13... Qxa4 14. Qc6 Rd8 15. Bc7 Rc8 16. Qb7 Rxc7 17. Qa8+ Nb8 18. Qxb8+ Kd7 19.
Rfc1
{ You see why I couldn't really recommend 5. Nc3 in the main course?   But I actually think the play to reach this much better position isn't impossible to find over the board. Black feels terribly under developed throughout this whole sequence of moves, so I have faith that you'll be able to take over the position with 5. Nc3 having seen that this typical attacking play is absolutely working our in our favour! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: London System"]
[Black "2...c5 Fireworks: 1...Nf6 2...c5 An Early 3...cxd4 (with 5.Nc3! alternative) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 c5 3. Bf4
{ By playing Bf4 here, we transpose to an interesting sideline of the London System. Normally, White would have the pawn on e3 instead of c3 here, but c3 is definitely playable, and far less explored! The lines will get pretty sharp, but very often in our favour! If our opponents accidentally stumble into this position, we have very decent chances of winning out of the opening, since we'll have studied the complications beforehand! }
3... cxd4 4. cxd4 Qb6
{ 4...d5  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bf5  7.e3  transposes to 1...c5 lines } 5. Nc3
{ This is a wild move aiming to get the maximum out of the position! Practically speaking, I think it would require a lot of effort to master the variations following Nc3, since Black can capture the b2-pawn at any moment! On the plus side, it seems that whenever Black is capturing on b2, there is a way to fight for a +0.5 advantage at least! So if you're confident with your play with the initiative, perhaps this is a line for you to try, instead of the 5. Qc1 I recommend in the main course.   5.Qc1  defending the b2-pawn, as well as creating a sneaky threat on Black's light-squared bishop is what I recommend in the main course! }
5... d5 6. e3 Qxb2 7. Bb5+
{ After going a pawn down, it's essential we develop as quickly as possible, since our piece activity will be the main source of compensation for our loss of material. }
7... Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 9. Nge2 Qb6 10. Rb1 Qa6 11. O-O
{ White has completed their development, and castled their king. Black, on the other hand, has still three moves to make in order to castle kingside, while castling queenside is out of the question. This is more than enough compensation for the pawn. }
11... e6 12. Nb5 { Unsurprisingly, Black is in all sorts of trouble! } *

