[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "📓 ADVANCED Material: London System"]
[Black "2...c5 Fireworks: 1...Nf6 2...c5 The Sturdy 4...d5 (with 12.Nxa5 alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 Nf6 2. d4 c5 3. Bf4
{ By playing Bf4 here, we transpose to an interesting sideline of the London System. Normally, White would have the pawn on e3 instead of c3 here, but c3 is definitely playable, and far less explored! The lines will get pretty sharp, but very often in our favour! If our opponents accidentally stumble into this position, we have very decent chances of winning out of the opening, since we'll have studied the complications beforehand! }
3... Qb6
{ If our opponents play ...Qb6 here, they are likely to be an over-ambitious opponent! It is likely that they have studied the same positions with e3 instead of c3 in the position, but since these positions become very sharp, it's risky to play 3...Qb6 here without concrete knowledge! }
4. Nd2 d5
{ Given how tricky  4...cxd4  and  4...Qxb2  are to navigate for Black, I can imagine a lot of experienced players deciding to avoid complications, and play the more standard 4...d5 instead.  I am returning to this line in the ADVANCED Material section of the course, since I'd like to examine the more ambitious 12. Nxa5 as opposed to 12. Rxe5 — looked at in the main course! }
5. Qb3
{ Do you remember the discussion we had about why 4. Nd2 was chosen instead of the principled 4. Qb3?   On 4. Qb3, we would face difficulties dealing with the doubled isolated b-pawns, but now, we already have a knight on d2 developed!   This means we can meet any ...Qxb3 with Nxb3 to avoid our pawn structure being too badly crippled. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxb6 axb6 7. cxd4
{ Now we're the ones to be playing against the isolated b-pawns. In general, we're fine here, but there is one critical line we have to know: }
7... Nc6 { Playing for a quick Nb4, while hitting our d4-pawn with tempo. } 8.
e3 Nb4 9. Rc1 Nxa2 10. Ra1 Ra5
{ Since the knight is pinned to the rook, Black will most likely want to stabilise their rook. However, we don't allow the rook to rest! }
11. Nb3
{ Here, White is much better unless Black finds the precise combination to bail out: }
11... Nb4 12. Nxa5
{ 12.Rxa5  is the simpler alternative that I suggest in the main course! }
12... Nc2+ 13. Kd2 Nxa1 14. Bb5+ Bd7 15. Bxd7+ Kxd7 16. Nf3 bxa5 17. Rxa1 Ne4+
18. Ke2
{ After a series of forcing moves, we reach this resulting position.   With best play @@StartBracket@@either  18...f6  or  18...g5  @@EndBracket@@, the position is objectively equal, but these moves are extremely difficult to find over the board.   The most natural  18...b6  is a mistake! }
18... b6 19. Ne5+ Ke8 20. Rc1
{ White gives up pursuit for the black a5-pawn, and instead looks to capitalise on Black's lack of development instead. }
20... Nd6 21. Rc6
{ Black manages to avoid mate, but the b6-pawn is going to drop, and all of White's pieces are well placed while Black is far from completing development. White is much better. }
