[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🐌 BONUS: The Slug"]
[Black "The Slug Setup"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now before I discuss my very first opening invention as a budding theoretician in my teenage years, I would like to add a disclaimer about this chapter: the opening you are about to witness is a serious weapon I have used in classical chess, BUT it is also completely, and utterly dubious.   With an engine, the opening is definitely refuted, but since nobody in the entire world has studied the opening properly, I have actually yet to face any opponent that has played a perfect opening against it @@StartBracket@@and I've seriously played thousands of games in this opening@@EndBracket@@. The reason why I'm including the opening in this course is because it also happens to start with 1. c3, and I whole heartedly believe it's a fantastic surprise weapon!  So let's delve right into it, shall we? 😊 }
1. c3
{ So the surprise weapon that you've all been waiting for, is none other than: The Slug!  The Slug is a system opening that can be played against literally everything. Against opponents that enjoy system openings  (Modern, Dutch, etc.)  , we can take them out of their comfort zone immediately, since we'll be the ones dictating the nature of the position!  As I've already mentioned, the Slug is a dubious opening. However, I've found that the more sceptical the opponent is about the opening, the worse they play against it! This opening should not be underestimated, regardless of who is on the receiving end of it! }
1... -- 2. Na3
{ With the pawn on c3, this is clearly the appropriate square for our knight! Although, the knight can't stay on the rim of the board all game, so we quickly centralise it with: }
2... -- 3. Nc2
{ Now the knight is centralised and supporting our centre. Since this development scheme has worked so splendidly on the queenside, how about we do the same on the kingside? }
3... -- 4. f3
{ This is when our opponents really lose their mind!   For the record, the reason why I advocate starting with 1. c3 @@StartBracket@@rather than 1. f3@@EndBracket@@ is that I like to keep my opponent guessing how we are about to develop. If we start with 1. f3, this might encourage Black to go all in to attack our kingside - which may work out in our favour if they over-extend badly, but it also may end in us getting crushed quickly. So I'd prefer to let Black set up their own opening first, before revealing our complete Slug setup! }
4... -- 5. Nh3
{ It will often be required to play g3, before Nh3. But don't worry about this for now, we will examine the reasons for this in the next chapter! }
5... -- 6. Nf2
{ Now the knights are perfectly developed! You'll be surprised how well these knights control the game. Our opponents won't have any intuition on how to play against these knights  (as you'll see in the next chapter!)  , so our opponents are much more prone to blundering! }
6... -- 7. d3
{ Now, we come to our central pawns. I'd be pretty flexible as to how you push these central pawns  (either d3 + e4, d4 + e4, or d4 + e3)  , depending on how Black has setup their pieces.   For instance, if Black has developed with either ...Bc5 or ...Bf5, it may be worth using our central pawns to kick away either bishop! }
7... -- 8. e4
{ Finally, we reach the starting position of the Slug. We keep flexible as to whether we will castle queenside @@StartBracket@@with Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, g4, h4  , or kingside  (with g3, Bg2, O-O@@EndBracket@@.  It surprised me, that in recent years, I have actually heard of a Grandmaster @@StartBracket@@Alex Ipatov, I believe, in an episode of the Perpetual Chess Podcast)  reference this opening development @@StartBracket@@at least with regards to the development of the knights@@EndBracket@@.   However, I can assure you that I got there first! If you'd like to head back in time, there is in fact a teenage Michael showcasing the Slug in 2016, on YouTube, for the world to see. Here's a screenshot of the video for you to seek out if you wish. 😊 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🐌 BONUS: The Slug"]
[Black "Model Game: The Slug Knights"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org Blitz, 5+0 Rated   I believe this is the perfect game to showcase the power of the Slug knights. You'll notice that I'm playing the Slug with the Black pieces  (which you'll soon find out has a different name — the Snail!)  , but ultimately, the Slug setup can be played irrespective of colour. }
1. Nf3 g6
{ I start with the move ...g6 to keep my opponent guessing. But you'll see the complete Slug setup soon enough! }
2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O f6 5. c4 Nh6 6. Nc3 Nf7 7. d3 d6 8. Rb1 Na6 9. b4
Nc7 10. a4 e5
{ We reach the starting position of our Slug setup! My opponent has opted for a queenside expansion. }
11. b5 Bd7 12. Ba3 O-O 13. Bxd6
{ Can you imagine a 2350 online rated player blundering a full piece in a single move!! As we can clearly see, my opponent's intuition suggested that my bishop developed on d7 blocked my queen's defence of the d6-pawn, completely forgetting about my knight on f7!!! I wasn't kidding when I said players seriously blunder more often to the Slug knights! }
13... Nxd6
{ The greatest thing about this model game is that both knights have their moment in the spotlight. Let's see how the position developed! }
14. bxc6 Bxc6 15. d4 exd4 16. Qxd4 f5 17. Qd3 Ne4
{ Here, my position is wonderful. I'm offering to trade material @@StartBracket@@which would be in my favour given my piece up advantage@@EndBracket@@, and all our pieces are secured and centralised. Incredibly, my opponent misses the other Slug knight on c7 on their very next turn!!! }
18. Nd5
{ Clearly, my opponent thought that after  18...Bxd5  19.cxd5  they would gain a passed d-pawn to give them some hope of fighting back in the position. But somehow, they completely overlooked my knight hiding on c7! }
18... Nxd5
{ I have three attackers. They have two defenders. So I just won a pawn for free. }
19. cxd5 Qxd5
{ My opponent resigned. A fantastic miniature, showcasing the spectacular psychological self-destruction that the Slug can induce on an unsuspecting opponent!  I'd like to emphasise that in a Classical game, it is likely that our opponents won't completely miss our hidden knights on c7 and f7 like in this blitz game. However, what can certainly happen is that players can make mistakes in their visualisation and calculation, due to not having as much experience and intuition with dealing with the Slug knights!  Let's now take a look at when we should make use of the Slug Opening! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🐌 BONUS: The Slug"]
[Black "Learning The Slug: A Weapon Against System Openings"]
[Result "*"]

{ The Slug is particularly effective against creatures of habit  (i.e. players that like to play a particular system@@EndBracket@@. This includes Modern, Pirc, Dutch, and any other system openings!) }
1. c3 d5
{ 1...g6  The Modern.  2.Na3  Bg7  3.Nc2  d6  4.f3  e5  5.g3!  If Black's light-squared bishop is open on the c8-h3 diagonal, we cannot play Nh3 until we've first played g3 @@StartBracket@@so that we can recapture any ...Bxh3, with Bxh3!@@EndBracket@@  5...Ne7  6.Nh3  O-O  7.Nf2  f5  8.d3  Nbc6  9.e4∞   1...d6  The Pirc.  2.Na3  g6  3.Nc2  Bg7  4.f3  e5  5.g3!  f5  6.Nh3  Nf6  7.Nf2  O-O  8.d3  Nc6  9.e4∞   1...f5  The Dutch.  2.Na3  e5  3.Nc2  Nf6  4.f3  d6  5.Nh3!  Here, there's no need to start with g3, since the c8-h3 diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop is closed.  5...Be7  6.Nf2  O-O  7.d3  Nc6  8.e4∞   1...b6  The Owen's.  2.Na3  Bb7  3.Nc2  e6  4.f3  Nf6  5.Nh3  d5  6.Nf2  c5  7.d3  Be7  8.e4∞ }
2. Na3 e5
{ I'd like to note that I have also played the Slug against players that take the full centre, and I've been just fine!   You'll see in the Model game on the Slug how quickly things can go wrong for Black if they try and punish the Slug. }
3. Nc2 Nf6 4. f3 Nc6 5. g3 Bd6 6. Nh3 O-O 7. Nf2 Bf5 8. d3 Qe7 9. e4
{ White will often be behind in development at this early stage, but due to the solid pawn structure, Black will struggle to take advantage of this!   In addition, White has a lot of potential to evolve and improve the position, while Black often runs out of improving moves fairly quickly. White's flexible pawn structure also allows White to often dictate the game, and make the pawn breaks that suits White best! }
