[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🐌 BONUS: The Slug"]
[Black "Using The Slug in 1.c3 Venom"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 e5 2. d4 d6
{ Let's imagine our opponent is playing the 2...d6 line of the Caro-Kann Reversed.   Do you remember what to play? }
3. g3
{ Instead, we could start ambiguous with the move 3. g3, and wait to see what setup Black chooses...   3.e4  This is objectively the best way to play for an advantage, and what I recommend in the main section of the course.   But what if you're not a fan of taking the big centre with e4 in fear of it being undermined? What other options do we have? }
3... Nf6 4. Bg2 g6 5. f3
{ Since Black is playing for a fianchetto on the kingside, this is a great opportunity to play the Slug! }
5... Bg7 6. Nh3 O-O 7. Nf2 Nbd7 8. Na3 c6 9. Nc2 Re8 10. O-O Qc7 11. e4
{ Yes, the Slug I have showed you so far has involved d3 e4 — but we should be flexible with the system!   The main structural assets are our well placed knights on c2 and f2, which support the centre, and control the important g4- and b4-squares. Here, I believe White has a great game ahead of them, since White has many more improving moves @@StartBracket@@e.g. Be3, Qd2 etc.@@EndBracket@@, while Black suffers from a lack of space, and struggles to find ways to evolve their position with purpose. }
