[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🐌 BONUS: The Slug"]
[Black "The Snail (Reverse Slug)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Although 1.c3 Venom is a White repertoire, I'd like to introduce to you its close relative: the Snail! If you're looking for something offbeat against an unexpecting Reti/English player, this is a great weapon to make use of! }
1. Nf3
{ Against the Reti or the English, I particularly like using the Slug setup, since we are most likely facing a system player.   Since the line is a tempo down, my younger sister brilliantly coined the opening 'The Snail' — since snails are slightly slower than slugs! }
1... g6 2. g3 c6 { I like to keep my opponent guessing as long as possible. }
3. Bg2 f6
{ Here we see the trail of the Snail! You can imagine what sort of development comes next! }
4. O-O Nh6 5. c4 Nf7 6. b3 Na6 7. Bb2 Nc7 8. d4 Bg7 9. e4
{ Of course, there's nothing objectively wrong with this move. But very often, White will break their 'system opening' to try to punish Black's setup, getting into less familiar territory for themselves.   So practically speaking, we love to see this since White will now have to find new ideas over the board, while we will have plenty of experience of our setup! }
9... d6 10. Nc3 e5
{ I won't continue the analysis any further than our basic setup, since I'd like you to continue your development in a way that suits you best! Will you castle ...O-O? Will you try and go for ...O-O-O and rush the kingside pawns forwards with ...h5, ...g5, ...h4?   Let's now take a look at a model game of the Snail, that begins very similarly to the analysis we just examined! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🐌 BONUS: The Slug"]
[Black "Model Game: The Snail"]
[Result "*"]

{ Lichess.org Rapid, 10+0 Rated } 1. c4 g6 2. Nc3 c6 3. e4 f6
{ Since White has not committed to any fianchettoed bishops, it may be over ambitious to try a Snail here! However, for 10+0 games, getting ahead on the clock is very handy, so I decided the risk was worth taking! }
4. d4 Nh6 5. Nf3 Nf7 6. Bd3 Na6 7. Be3 Nc7 8. Qd2 d6 9. O-O-O e5
{ The Snail has been completed! Despite our slower opening development, it's not clear how White can open the centre to punish us.   Our knights, in fact, control a lot of squares that would otherwise be weak in our position. }
10. d5 c5
{ Objectively speaking, it would be better to keep the tension @@StartBracket@@since if ever White captures on c6, we can play ...bxc6, with good control over the d5-square@@EndBracket@@. However, I like the simplicity of Black's plan here! We will eventually play for b5, and with the centre closed, we are extremely solid. }
11. h3 a6 12. Kb1 Rb8 13. Qe2 Bd7 14. a4
{ Although White has prevented our b5 push, White has weakened their kingside, and the a4-pawn is now a target. }
14... Bg7 15. Ne1 O-O 16. Nc2 Qe8
{ A tricky move! it appears we are playing for the b5 push, and my opponent misses the obvious... }
17. Na3 Bxa4
{ Black is suddenly a pawn up out of nowhere. And since the position is closed, White finds it impossible to muster up any counterplay. }
18. Nxa4 Qxa4 19. Qc2
{ Trading queens a pawn down? Bad idea! But alternatively, White was going to suffer an incoming queenside attack with b5 — so it was going to be tough either way! I could stop my analysis here, but the endgame was too good not to include! If you'd like to see how to convert a closed position like this, a pawn up, here's how: }
19... Qxc2+ 20. Kxc2 b5 21. b3 Bh6 22. Bxh6 Nxh6 23. Ra1 f5 24. f3 f4 25. Ra2
Rb6 26. Rha1 Rfb8 27. Nb1 R8b7 28. Nc3 Nf7 29. Ra5 Kg7 30. R5a2 Kf6 31. Ne2 Ke7
32. Nc3 g5 33. Ne2 Nh8 34. Nc3 Ng6 35. Bf1 Nf8 36. cxb5 axb5 37. Ra7 Nd7 38.
Rxb7 Rxb7 39. Ra5 b4 40. Nd1 Rb8 41. Ra7 Kd8 42. Kb2 Ra8 43. Rxa8+ Nxa8 44. Kc2
Nc7 45. Nb2 Nb6 46. Nc4 Nxc4 47. Bxc4
{ Over the past 20 or so moves, I have been improving my pawn structure, and trading the appropriate pieces, in order to reach this desired endgame. This is a dream come true for us! A pawn up, with a strong knight vs weak bishop. The very nice thing about converting closed positions, is that you don't have to find the right plan first time round either. For my first plan, I wanted to enter on the kingside with my king, so that's what I tried to achieve: }
47... Ke7 48. Kd2 Kf6 49. Ke2 Kg6 50. Kf2 Kh5 51. g4+
{ Here I had to make an important choice. I believe I made the best one. }
51... Kg6
{ 51...fxg3+?!  This creates unnecessary chances for a counterattack!  52.Kxg3  Kg6  53.Be2  h5  54.Bc4  h4+  55.Kf2  Even giving White one pawn break feels a little risky!   55.Kg4??  Just like 51...Kh4?! for Black, White too should be careful about playing 'active' king moves.  55...Ne8!  White's king is trapped, and mate is threatened!  55...Kf6  56.Ke2  Ke7  57.Kf2  Kd7  58.f4!?  gxf4  59.Kf3  Kc8  60.Kg4  Kb7  61.Kxh4  Kb6  62.Kg5  Nb5  63.h4∞  Now the position is far from clear.   51...Kh4?!  This at first looks like an active move, but our king is now trapped!  52.Kg2  h5  53.Be2  hxg4  54.hxg4= }
52. Kg2 Kf6 53. Kh2 Ke7 54. h4 h6
{ 54...gxh4?!  We should not allow White's king any activity!  55.Kh3! } 55.
hxg5 hxg5 56. Kg2 Kd8 57. Kf2
{ What should Black's plan be now? If any of you suggested the immediate ...Na8-b6 to capture Bc4, this is a good idea, but we must get the timing right!   In static closed positions like this, we should use the time to improve ALL our pieces first, before executing the plan. Therefore, the black king should be on ...a5, before this plan is executed. }
57... Kc8
{ 57...Na8  58.Ke2  Nb6  59.Kd2  Nxc4+  60.bxc4  Incredibly, this position is drawn, due to the concept of 'corresponding squares'!  60...Kc7  61.Kc2  Kb6  62.Kb2!  White has taken note of a strange phenomenon in Pawn Endgames like these, namely, corresponding squares.   Here, the b3-square and a5-square are linked, since if either side steps onto these squares first, they can't achieve their desired result @@StartBracket@@Black, a win, and White, a draw@@EndBracket@@. Therefore, these squares are corresponding!   62.Kb3??  By stepping onto the corresponding square first, White now loses after:  62...Ka5!  63.Kb2  Ka4  64.Ka2  b3+  65.Kb2  Kb4+-  Black will gobble up White's pawns and win easily.  62...Ka5  63.Kb3!  Ka6  64.Kb2!   64.Ka4??  Again, we see a forward advancing 'active' king move backfire!   Now Black can force White onto the corresponding squares first, thus attaining a winning pawn endgame:  64...Kb6  65.Kb3  Ka5!  Now Black lands on the corresponding squares second, and wins!  Kb6  65.Kc2=  White holds for a draw. }
58. Ke2 Kb7 59. Kd2 Kb6 60. Kc2 Ka5
{ Black's king is now perfectly placed to execute Plan B — trying to win the bishop on c4! }
61. Kd2 Na8 { My second plan! To come to b6, and try capture the bishop! } 62.
Kc2 Nb6 63. Bf1
{ Unfortunately in chess, our opponents are also observant to our plans! Since Plan B failed, it was time to execute Plan C! Can you find it?   63.Kb2  Nxc4+  64.bxc4  Here we see the importance of improving the black king to a5 first.   Now, White hasn't the time to enter onto the b3 corresponding square, and Black wins easily after:  64...Ka4! }
63... Nc8 { Aiming to enter via b5 to the juicy d4-square. } 64. Bc4 Na7 65.
Be2 Nb5 66. Kd2 Nd4
{ The best square for the knight, targeting White's two weakest pawns, on f3 and b3. }
67. Bd1
{ Now, my opponent is almost all tied up. Black would like to play Kb5, then c4, with a winning position. However, White will meet Kb5 with Kd3, preventing this plan.   What should Black do? }
67... Kb6
{ White is now in zugzwang! Black is able to move in the shape of a triangle @@StartBracket@@triangulation@@EndBracket@@ while the opponent cannot, in order to reach the same position of ...Kb5 and Kd3, but with White's turn to move. }
68. Kd3 Kb5 69. Kd2 c4 70. bxc4+ Kxc4
{ My opponent resigns. A fitting end position to a beautiful Snail grind! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "1.c3 Has Even More to Offer..."]
[Result "*"]

{ When playing 1.c3 Venom, we should try to think outside of the box! I would like to suggest some other ways we can make use of 1. c3 to trick our opponents into positions they're unfamiliar with. }
1. c3 d5
{ 1...c5  2.e4!?  Black is now playing a Sicilian Alapin, although be warned! If Black is meeting your 1. c3 with 1...c5, then they are likely to be a Sicilian player, and will therefore welcome an Alapin. So I'd only recommend playing 2. e4 if you know your opponent doesn't play a Sicilian, and in the case you have existing Alapin knowledge.   1...e5  2.c4!?  Hold on a second... we really pushed the same pawn twice!?!? But if you look closer, we in fact have the starting position of a standard Sicilian Defence! So if you happen to be an avid Sicilian player @@StartBracket@@from the Black side@@EndBracket@@, you can get it with the White pieces too! This is particularly effective against players who you know aren't 1. e4 players, who will then struggle to meet the demands of the dynamic opening.   1...e5  2.d4  e4  3.c4!?  For the Caro-Kann players studying this course, I'd encourage you to consider how your existing Caro-Kann repertoires fit into the reverse setup! For instance, if you happen to play 3...c5 in the Advance Variation @@StartBracket@@as opposed to 3...Bf5@@EndBracket@@, you're welcome to explore 3. c4!? in the reverse setup deeper! }
2. d4
{ 2.Nf3  Nf6  3.c4!?  Just like our double c-pawn push to reach a Sicilian, we can do the same here to reach a standard Modern Benoni! So if you enjoy playing the Modern Benoni with Black, you can have it here with White!  3...d4  4.e3  c5  5.exd4  cxd4  6.d3  Nc6  7.g3  e5  8.a3  a5  9.Bg5  Be7  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Bg2  O-O  12.O-O  ⇆  A great start to a great opening! }
2... c5 { 2...Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.f4  Nc6  5.Nf3  A reverse Stonewall! } 3. Nf3
Nc6 4. dxc5
{ A reverse Slav Defence — which is in fact +0.6! So definitely worth investigating further...   4.e3!?  A reverse Semi-Slav! }
4... a5
{ The 'mainline response' of the Slav is in fact an immediate inaccuracy — with both 5. e4 and 5. Na3 leading to objective +1 advantages! I would therefore encourage you to consider how 1. c3 fits in with your existing opening repertoires, and make use of all the knowledge you have to take your opponent out of their comfort zone! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "Problem Solving! The Reti vs. The Modern"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ As I wrote about in the introduction 'Our Venom', I have been a Reti player @@StartBracket@@in the style of 1. Nf3 / 2. c4 / 3. g3 / b3 etc.@@EndBracket@@ since the age of 15.   Despite creating this 1. c3 repertoire, I haven't abandoned the Reti @@StartBracket@@and I wouldn't recommend you completely abandon any existing openings that you've spent time learning and understanding either, unless there's an inherent problem with the opening itself!@@EndBracket@@. So what I'd like to show you, is that the knowledge of 1. c3 has helped me navigate certain anti-Reti lines, that have frustrated me over the years.   Let's take a look at some! }
1... g6
{ The Modern has been a huge annoyance for me @@StartBracket@@I kid you not, I've probably spent over a hundred hours analysing different ways to play against this, none of which I'm fully satisfied with!@@EndBracket@@, because of the following reasons:   Firstly, with regards to my Reti repertoire, it helps to understand that against King's Indian Defence @@StartBracket@@so @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.c4  g6  @@EndBracket@@, I like to play  3.b4!?  — leading to a unique setup that works a treat against King's Indian players!   However, against this 1...g6 move order, I cannot reach this setup, since after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  Bg7  3.b4??  Bxa1  — I am not in time to develop my bishop to b2 @@StartBracket@@unlike the King's Indian Defence positions@@EndBracket@@.   So suddenly, I am faced with the prospect of entering mainline King's Indian Defence setups if I play  2.d4  or  2.c4  against 1...g6.   Secondly, if I try and 'refute' Black's Modern with  2.e4  , the issue is that Black can play the Modern in so many ways! They can play with ...d6 and ...a6 @@StartBracket@@pure Modern@@EndBracket@@, or ...d6 and ...Nf6 @@StartBracket@@the Pirc@@EndBracket@@, or even ...c6 and ...d5 @@StartBracket@@a hybrid between a Modern and a Caro-Kann — the Gurgenidze Modern — which is in fact a new favourite weapon of mine@@EndBracket@@, all of which require their own nuanced attention, to be able to have any hope of gaining an advantage against them, let alone 'refute' them.   So all in all, we Reti players detest the Modern. That is, until my work on 1.c3 Venom! }
2. c3
{ But wait... oh yes! We are simply able to play our 1.c3 Venom against the Modern, since any line that Black tries here will either transpose to something we know, or simply be dubious.   Let's see: }
2... Bg7 3. d4 Nf6 4. Bf4 O-O 5. e3 d6 6. h3
{ Suddenly, we're no longer in scary Modern territory, but just a King's Indian Defence vs 1. c3, which we've analysed in depth. It would make no difference if Black started with ...d6 ...a6, or even tried ...c6 ...d5 instead — because all these setups do not pose serious issues to our London System.   Instead, we will feel at home with these structures and plans, gaining experience every time we play this 1.c3 Venom opening. So happy days! The troublesome Modern vs Reti is solved! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "Problem Solving! The Reti vs. 1...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6
{ I'm not kidding when I show this move, and say that this is a legitimate anti-Reti line. It looks ridiculous, but what should White play next...?   If White tries to punish Black for not playing something more 'principled', and plays  2.e4  , suddenly Black can play  2...e5!  , and now we are playing a 1. e4 e5 game!! A horrible surprise for the unexpecting Reti player.   Ok, so what if White tries  2.c4  or  2.g3  , in Reti style?   Well, having played 1...Nc6, Black is able to meet either of these responses with  2...e5!  — and now we are playing English lines, and have very little experience of these positions, since the whole point of the Reti with 1. Nf3 is to prevent lines with 1...e5.   Ok, so that finally leaves  2.d4  .   Now, for many years, I've begrudgingly played  2. d4, since it would lead to an 'objectively good position', but I'd always fear that my opponent was a die-hard Chigorin player! Because after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.Nf3  Nc6  2.d4  d5  ,  3.c4  — we are suddenly in Chigorin mainline territory, where Black has all kinds of systems @@StartBracket@@  3...Bg4  and  3...e5  are both super interesting@@EndBracket@@, and White is suddenly having to learn Chigorin theory, to face this 1...Nc6 that will hardly ever be played! So this is far from ideal.   So again, like the Modern, I've had a huge headache over this move, that is, until recently, having written this 1.c3 Venom course! With this new knowledge and understanding, we can now play: }
2. d4 { But ok... didn't we just say that this would enter mainline Chigorin? }
2... d5 3. c3
{ Hold on a second... wait, we're back in 1.c3 Venom territory, against a weak Chigorin attempt!!   Next we will follow with Bf4, e3, h3, Nd2 etc. , with experience of these resulting positions, while Black will have none of their Chigorin fun, since the centre is far more sturdy with c3 compared to c4.   So this is perfect, 1...Nc6 headache all cured! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "Problem Solving! Black vs. The Jobava London"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ As a die-hard Modern Benoni player, the Jobava System with 2. Nc3 has been a huge pain in the neck.   The reason being that  2...c5  is simply not working, where White can get a decent advantage with precise play. }
2... d5
{ For a long while, as a Modern Benoni player, I'd resent this move. After all, I'd have to learn the nuances behind 1...d5, which is completely impractical for a Modern Benoni player! However, upon closer inspection, what do we realise...?   2...c5?!  3.d5  e6  4.e4!  exd5  5.e5±  Black is in huge trouble here. The knight has nowhere good to go, the centre is fully in White's control after either Nxd5 or Qxd5.   Engine evaluates the position as +3 or more. So this is quite the nightmare! }
3. Bf4 c6
{ We are suddenly playing our 1.c3 Venom against a weak 'Chigorin' attempt, but reversed! Since White is unable to play e4 immediately @@StartBracket@@and ...Bf5, ...e6 etc. will come next@@EndBracket@@, Black has a great game ahead of us! }
4. e3 Bf5
{ 1.c3 Venom has again served me well, solving my opening troubles, but this time with the Black pieces! The more structures we understand, the more complete our overall strength in the opening will be. It's all well and good having strong opening theory against the main openings, but the knowledge of a system opening can be very handy against the less common openings, like the Jobava London. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "Against the Aggressive Modern! (Part 1)"]
[Result "*"]

{ At the start of 2024, I played 1.c3 Venom against a strong 2000 rated opponent in classical  (75+15)  , where my opponent played a Modern, executing a very deadly kingside attack!   Having analysed the game, I came to some important conclusions about the resulting positions, but I wasn't sure where in the course would be best for me to cover this analysis. Did I want to enter this discussion in the main repertoire? Or was it best to leave this analysis in the model games section?    In the end, I decided to save it for the 'Revolutionary Thinking' section of the course  (which you're reading now)  , since I felt like the analysis would be overkill for the main repertoire, and I think the ideas of how to evolve your opening preparation is more important than the moves themselves.    In any case, let's take a look at how I got completely crushed this game  (aside from an unexpected twist at the end!?) }
1. c3 g6
{ My opponent begun with the Modern. As far as I was concerned, I would treat my opponent's setup in the same way as a King's Indian Defence. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Bf4 d6 4. h3
{ Since Black's bishop on g7 is open @@StartBracket@@no knight on f6 blocking its way@@EndBracket@@, I was a little concerned about the immediate ...e5. Whenever we're concerned for our bishop's wellbeing, we should take necessary precaution!   4.e3  e5  5.dxe5  dxe5  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  7.Bg3=  I felt that Black would be doing fine in this endgame. }
4... Nd7 5. e3 e5 6. Bh2 Ne7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 b6
{ This was the first move that surprised me a little. Typically for a King's Indian style attack, the bishop would remain on c8 with sacrificial ideas on h3. So was my opponent simply going to play passively, and let me crush them on the queenside? }
9. O-O Bb7 10. c4
{ As per the repertoire, this was my remedy to ...e5 KID systems. But in fact, the plan to play with c4 and gradual queenside play does not quite cut it here. Since the black knight is on e7 instead of f6, Black's kingside attack will in fact be much faster. As a result, we should also be faster with our queenside action, hence my suggestion of 10. a4! @@StartBracket@@which you will see in the next chapter@@EndBracket@@.   10.a4!  Against the Modern @@StartBracket@@which as far as we're concerned, is an accelerated KID!@@EndBracket@@, I recommend playing with a4 before c4.   I explain the full plans and ideas in the next chapter! }
10... e4
{ I was very happy to see this move! Whenever I'd reached this position against standard King's Indian setups, I had very good results. For instance, you can check out the model game section. }
11. Nfd2 f5 12. Nc3 Kh8
{ I had the feeling that Black was preparing for a kingside attack, but it honestly felt far too slow at this point. }
13. Rc1
{ 13.b4  This was the most natural looking move to me, but I didn't like the complications after ...c5!? @@StartBracket@@in fact, 17 .Ng5 refutes 13...c5, but I hadn't seen this far!@@EndBracket@@  13...c5  14.Bxd6  cxd4  15.exd4  Bxd4  16.Ndxe4  Bg7  OH WOW, I have Ng5 with the advantage. I calculated up to here, felt I was worse, hence 13.Rc1, so that I can safely play b4 next move.    I stopped my calculation here with the feeling that Black was better. But in fact, I have 17. Ng5 with the advantage. Since I missed this move, I decided to play 13. Rc1 instead, so that I can safely play b4 on the next move.  17.Ng5!!  Bxc3  18.Ne6  Qe8  19.Rc1  Bf6  20.c5±  Stockfish evaluates this crazy position as +2! }
13... a6 14. b4
{ Now that my knight on c3 is defended, I have nothing to fear with the ...c5 push. }
14... Nf6
{ 14...c5  15.Bxd6  cxd4  16.exd4  Bxd4  17.Ndxe4  Bg7  Since my knight on c3 is protected by my rook, I can most certainly move my knight from e4 and be better! }
15. Qb3 g5 16. a4 Ng6 17. c5
{ 17.a5!  This would have been a better way to break Black's queenside structure. In fact, this is a similar plan to my 10. a4 improvement @@StartBracket@@which you see more of next chapter!@@EndBracket@@ }
17... d5
{ At this moment, I realised I might be in grave danger. Black is pushing ...f4 next, and I have no good way to continue my play on the queenside! }
18. Rfd1
{ I wanted to free up the f1-square for my knight or bishop in order to defend. In fact, my defending skills of these kind of one-sided attacks are very poor, so I was not looking forward to the resulting battle!   18.b5!?  Interestingly, the engine believes I still have an advantage here.  18...a5  19.c6  Bc8  20.f3⩲  Presumably, the locked queenside means Black will have to worry about any potential sacrifices on c7/b6 for the rest of the game, and White will turn their attention to the centre instead. But this is why we must be careful of engines.   If you play this game, and conclude that 17. c5 is a good move, we have to understand that 17. c5 is bad in all variations EXCEPT for this one. So in reality, a +0.3 from 17. c5 compared to a more consistent +0.3 from 17. a5 is very different. }
18... f4 19. Bf1
{ 19.Nf1  I was torn between Bf1/Nf1, but in fact both are bad. Without counterplay, we will suffer as Black gradually brings more and more pieces to this attack. }
19... Bh6 20. cxb6
{ I offered my opponent a hopeful draw, which was quickly declined. } 20...
cxb6 21. a5 b5 22. Na2
{ A serious mistake. I wanted to defend b4, and later reroute with Nc1-Nb3-c5, but such plans are far too slow when our kingside is about to get ripped open. Perhaps I was still in some denial that my position was in big trouble!   22.Ne2!  Bringing the knight to the defence is obviously better, but I was worried about the complications after f3:  22...f3?  In fact, this move is a mistake. But even if it wasn't, the resulting position isn't so scary that Na2 should be chosen ahead of bringing a knight to assist in the defence!  23.gxf3  exf3  24.Nxf3!  Ne4  I was a bit worried about this @@StartBracket@@hence Na2, so I could meet ...f3 with g4!?@@EndBracket@@, but I realise now this would be far better than the game continuation. }
22... g4
{ 22...f3  23.g4⩱  Because of this defensive resource, I played Na2 instead of Ne2. However, my opponent proved there's more than one way to continue their attack! }
23. Bxf4
{ 23.Kh1!?  This may have been a better attempt to defend. Principally, we have two defenders @@StartBracket@@Bh2 and Bf1@@EndBracket@@, while Black has three immediate attackers @@StartBracket@@Nf6, Ng6, Bh6@@EndBracket@@.   We should keep hold of the defenders, since there is not much space on the kingside, so its unlikely Black will be able to organise all 3 attackers to attack in harmony. However, if we trade one pair of minor piececs @@StartBracket@@resulting in a 2 vs 1 situation@@EndBracket@@, the two attackers should be able to coordinate to attack @@StartBracket@@or there could be space for a third attacker to join!@@EndBracket@@, so I am decreasing my chances to hold. But to explain my logic behind Bxf4, I wanted to close the kingside with g3, which I only wanted to do once my bishop would no longer be imprisoned on h2 after g3. }
23... Nxf4 24. exf4 Bxf4 25. g3 e3
{ A very tough move to face! If I take the bishop @@StartBracket@@trading for my knight on d2@@EndBracket@@, my kingside is ruined. I chose the other capture. }
26. fxe3
{ 26.gxf4  Probably the better of two evils.  26...exd2  27.Rxd2  Ne4  I saw up to here and felt I was lost.  28.Rdc2  Qh4  29.Nc3!  If White can bring the pieces back to the defence, there may be some practical hope of surviving! }
26... Bxg3 27. e4
{ My hope was to hit the bishop, and close the position with e5 upon its retreat. However, Black found a nice reply! }
27... gxh3 { The bishop is untouchable due to ...Rg8. } 28. e5 Ne4
{ I misevaluated how strong this knight move was! } 29. Nf3 h2+ 30. Kg2
{ At this moment, I realised I was toast, after the forcing sequence starting h1=Q+. }
30... Rg8
{ Of course, h1=Q+ was not the only way to win. I am still completely busted.   30...h1=Q+!  This is what I thought he should have played, with just an easy mate after:  31.Kxh1  Rxf3  32.Qxf3  Qh4+-+  ...with mate to follow. I was already thinking of how best to congratulate my opponent for playing such a fantastic attacking game, but then my opponent played something different! }
31. Bxb5 axb5
{ My opponent should just have mated me. Now I at least avoid checkmate. } 32.
Rh1 Bf4+
{ I am now losing a rook. I guess most players would resign, but I felt that there may be a trick or two left in the position... }
33. Kf1 Bxc1 34. Rxh2
{ I had some vague hopes of mating on h7, but of course, the chances of this were next to none. }
34... Bf4
{ Where to move my rook? I didn't want to trade with Rg2. f2 and d2 are out of the question. And on e2 would blunder a fork with Ng3+! So with a couple seconds left on my clock, I played: }
35. Rc2
{ I was now down to my 10 second increment, and was focused on just making moves not to lose on time. }
35... Rc8 36. Nc3 Qc7
{ I am completely toast, and I'm about to lose an exchange. } 37. Nxe4 Qxc2 38.
Qxc2 Rxc2 39. Nd6
{ Of course, completely, and utterly, lost. But I did see one final trick?   If I could play Nh4-f5, and then Nf7, this would be checkmate. Since I had nothing to lose, I went about my business... }
39... Bc6 40. Nh4 Rg4
{ Wait— had my opponent really missed my mating net @@StartBracket@@since he was encouraging me to move forward with my knight@@EndBracket@@?? }
41. Nhf5
{ My heart was pounding at this moment, could he actually miss my checkmate? }
41... Bd7 { ...And this, ladies and gentlemen, is where the drama begins. } 42.
Nf7+
{ ...Checkmate! Are you reading this completely confused, or did you think I'd pulled off the greatest comeback ever? For the sharp eyed @@StartBracket@@or perhaps the functioning eyed!@@EndBracket@@, this is evidently NOT a checkmate. I had of course forgotten that once the rook had moved from g8, this was no longer a checkmate.   Of course, in the time scramble and heat of the moment, I whole-heartedly believed, that this was a checkmate. After 41...Bd7, I said to my opponent, 'I'm so sorry but unfortunately this is checkmate', and played my move Nf7. He puts his hands on his head and let out a huge groan, we shook hands, and then discussed the game a little. I was shaking my head in disbelief, and as I began to reset the pieces, at this very moment, my opponent said 'WAIT, this is not checkmate'. I looked once more, and of course, my opponent was correct!   Now if you're a merciful player, you may give the game to your opponent. After all, they did just crush you, and the final position was not checkmate. However, before I continue with this story, I'd like to share with you another crazy story from my junior chess days. I was playing in a junior tournament, and I still remember my opponent @@StartBracket@@his name was Xavier!@@EndBracket@@.   I had completely outplayed Xavier, but in converting the position, I had overlooked a surprising swindle! My opponent played the queen in front of my king, and stated very confidently that the position was checkmate. I was completely shocked, but shook hands, and agreed the result.   A few moments later, I realised: 'wait, this is not checkmate!' In fact, my rook from the other side of the board could zip across and capture the queen that was giving mate. 'So it's not!' my opponent exclaimed, but we decided it would be best to call an arbiter to explain the situation. The arbiter said that we should reset the position just before checkmate, and play on from there.   This, of course, would result in a win for me. However, before we continued, the arbiter wanted to check with the chief arbiter on the matter. The chief arbiter came over, and determined that since the players had shaken hands on an agreed result, the result stands. I lost this game, and never forgot this lesson: always check carefully of the result before shaking hands and agreeing the result of the game!!   Fast forward 10 years, we return to our game in question. I explain to my opponent briefly that since we've shaken hands on an agreed result, the result stands. Of course, my opponent was having none of it, but before we could debate it further, we decided to leave the position and discuss the matter once all the games had finished.   I personally wanted to resolve the outcome of the game before learning whether the game would impact the match result @@StartBracket@@to be completely unbiased and fair@@EndBracket@@. However, shortly into the discussion, we discover that the team has won 3-1 on other boards, so the result of this game wouldn't impact the team's result. Phew! We then discuss the situation with all the players present, outlining the events, and making sure we have the facts straight. In the mix of all this, the board 1 of the opposing team @@StartBracket@@we were playing on board 2@@EndBracket@@, proclaimed that I was a 'dishonourary player', and was tutting throughout the whole discussion. I told him to bring it up with FIDE, not with me!   In the end, the opposing team captain decided that the event would be sent to the league committee to adjudicate the result. After a couple days, I received the verdict: I was right. Since the players had shaken hands on an agreed result, the result stands. However, the committee felt that it would be a sporting gesture for me to agree a draw, post-result.   What would you do?   Since my team captain had also suggested I take the draw, I felt that this might be the best decision to make, for everyone involved. I also felt that the league committee had skimmed over an important detail: had I played Nf7+ without saying anything, I doubt my opponent would have thought the position was checkmate! So morally speaking, I felt that the draw was a fair result. What a crazy conclusion to a crazy game!   On that note, let's return to the Modern, where we will examine the nuances of this opening and move order. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
