[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "Against the Aggressive Modern! (Part 2)"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now, let's continue with our understanding of this opening, with the analysis of the following idea: }
1. c3 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Bf4 d6 4. h3 Nd7 5. e3 e5 6. Bh2 Ne7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2
{ I use the starting moves of the model game I just showed, not for any theoretical relevance, but just as an example of how an aggressive Modern player may play!   In short, any set of starting moves that accelerate the kingside attack with ...f5 may need to be addressed in the same way as my following scheme with an early a4 push! }
8... b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. a4
{ Here is my idea against aggressive Modern / KID players. In short, White needs to provoke more hooks on the queenside, in order to speed up their queenside counterplay. @@StartBracket@@to clarify, a 'hook' means an opponent's pawn that's moved forward one or two squares, that allows us to tear up that side of the board faster upon a pawn storm!@@EndBracket@@. As a result of 10. a4, Black can either respond with ...a6, ...a5, or ignore the move entirely.   10.c4?!  This is how I handled the previous game, which didn't go to plan! I much prefer the play we get after 10. a4. }
10... a6
{ Option 1 - Playing ...a6 so that they can meet the a5 push with ...b5.   10...a5  Option 2 - Blocking with ...a5.  11.Na3!  The caveat of ...a5 is now the b5-square is permanently weak. Black will not be able to play ...c6 easily since that would weaken the d6-pawn too much.  11...e4  12.Nd2  f5  13.Nb5!  Kh8  14.b4!  Just like in the mainline with 10...a6, we immediately latch onto the hook to create queenside counterplay. I have given some sample lines of how play could continue here:  14...axb4   @@StartBracket@@  14...g5  15.bxa5  Rxa5  16.Nc4  Ra8  17.a5!  bxa5  18.Nxa5⩲  @@EndBracket@@  15.cxb4  Nf6  16.a5!  g5  17.axb6±   10...e4  Option 3 - Ignoring a4.  11.Nfd2  f5  12.a5!  Since Black hasn't dealt with our a4 push, we can latch onto the b6 hook with the move a5!  12...Kh8  13.c4  g5  14.Nc3  Nf6  15.d5!  White can in fact evolve the position in a different way to playing b4 @@StartBracket@@like in my previous model game!@@EndBracket@@  15...Ng6  16.Nb3  f4  17.Nd4  Bc8  18.axb6±  Did you forget about our hook? By keeping this tension, we can choose to release it whenever it suits us better. For Black, they can never take us on a5, since that will chronically weaken their a7-pawn. }
11. b4
{ This play may seem unclear at first.  For instance, won't we face the same fate as the previous model game, by just pushing our queenside pawns forward? However, this time we will be much faster! }
11... e4 12. Nfd2 f5 13. a5
{ We immediately strike Black's queenside! By keeping the pawn on c3, we do not have to worry about immediate tactics involving the bishop on g7. If Black ignores our a5 push, they will face a nasty surprise: our lurking bishop on h2! }
13... b5 { 13...Kh8?  14.axb6!  cxb6  15.Bxd6±  A free pawn! } 14. c4
{ This is our whole idea with pushing a4-a5 first. We want to provoke a hook @@StartBracket@@the ...b5-pawn@@EndBracket@@, so that we can strike it with the c4 push now! Black is forced to capture, otherwise cxb5 will create a passed protected a-pawn for us, as well as an open c-file to attack down. }
14... bxc4 15. Bxc4+ d5 16. Be2 g5
{ Black can try to execute the same attack, but this time, we're faster: } 17.
Nb3 Kh8 18. Nc3 Nf6 19. b5 axb5 20. Nxb5 Ng6 21. Nxc7
{ Of course, none of Black's play is forced. But Black is clearly too slow to get in ...f4 and cause us serious problems on the kingside. I highly recommend you take these ideas into consideration, when you fear an accelerated King's Indian style attack is coming your way! }
