{ Lichess.org Blitz, 5+0 Rated } 1. c3 g6
{ Now, you'd think that the Modern was done and dusted? But in fact, when playing online against an International Master @@StartBracket@@IM@@EndBracket@@, I came across a different Modern line that caused me all sorts of new problems!   Upon further research, I found out that this is in fact the line recommended by Charlie Storey's famous The Sniper Opening book. So let's see what it's all about! }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Bf4 d6 4. h3 Nd7 5. e3 e5 6. Bh2 Nh6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 b6
{ Having surprised me with a very strong opening setup, my opponent then slows down his play with ...b6. As discussed in the previous chapter, this move simply gives us a hook to accelerate our queenside counterplay! }
9. O-O Bb7 10. a4 a5 11. Na3 e4 12. Nd2 f5
{ Here, I missed the very strong  13.b4!  where I'd be taking over on the queenside.  The game went back and forth and in the end I lost on time in a time scramble @@StartBracket@@aka — not worth our analysis!@@EndBracket@@. But as we can see, even an IM isn't familiar with the correct plan, even when they start off with a great opening setup! Let's now see what the IM should've played, where I'd end up in big trouble on the kingside! }
