1. c3 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Bf4 d6 4. h3 Nd7 5. e3 e5 6. Bh2 Nh6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Be2 f5
{ Rather than play the slow 8...b6, my opponent should have gone all in for the attack with 8...f5! This, unfortunately, might be the refutation to the London System. Black's King's Indian style attack is accelerated, and Black's pieces sit perfectly for the incoming attack. Play could continue as follows: }
9. O-O e4 10. Nfd2 g5 11. a4
{ A hopeful @@StartBracket@@or hopeless?@@EndBracket@@ try at queenside counterplay. With no b6-pawn to bite on, Black is much faster with their play. The issue is, there isn't much else to recommend for White! }
11... Nf6 12. a5 Kh8 13. a6 b6 14. c4 g4
{ With this precise move, Black is already crashing through, and a strong attacking player will execute this attack to perfection. So what now? Is 1.c3 Venom all for nothing?   Of course not, we should have more faith! There is in fact a very simple @@StartBracket@@and strong@@EndBracket@@ remedy to this 'London System refutation', which I will show you next! }
