[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "Against the Aggressive Modern! (Part 3.3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. e4
{ This is the simple, and strong solution! By choosing to play the Modern rather than a King's Indian, in order to play for an accelerated kingside attack, Black has neglected one of the basic opening principles: control of the centre!   You may be thinking: 'oh no, I don't want to learn 1. e4 theory' — but this is far from it. The c3 move slows the Modern game down, and White is really great without much preparation. I will even recommend to play Bf4, as if we were playing a London still. }
3... d6 4. Bd3 e5 5. Nf3 Nd7
{ 5...Bg4?!  6.dxe5!  dxe5  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  +/- White keeps an advantage with the bishop pair in the semi-open position. }
6. O-O Ngf6 7. Re1 O-O 8. a4 a5 9. Na3
{ Doesn't this position look familiar? In fact, we have a DIRECT transposition to our Caro-Kann Reversed Lines against 2...d6!!  To reiterate the plans and ideas, here they are: 'I like this development plan for White. Our minor pieces don't get in each other's way, and our knight can come to c4 soon to add more pressure on e5. As a general plan,   1@@EndBracket@@ add more pressure to e5  2@@EndBracket@@ make sure e4 is well defended  3@@EndBracket@@ since we have more space, Black will find it more difficult to maneuver, so when they inevitably create a weakness, capitalise on it!'   This is the beauty of 1.c3 Venom. We understand structures involving c3 + d4, and can get the maximum benefit from it. Now you may be wondering: 'why did I leave the last chapter in the course, since against the Modern @@StartBracket@@1...g6@@EndBracket@@, we're playing with 3. e4 ?'   Well, to understand the opening you play, you really must go on a journey of exploration. It is why that it has been recommended to me in the past, that when studying the Spanish / Ruy Lopez, it is advised to study it chronologically!! See how theory developed step by step, otherwise you'll be overwhelmed with all the moves to memorise, and not understand the subtle nuances of how the theory developed over time.   Of course, 1.c3 Venom doesn't have as deep a history as the Spanish / Ruy Lopez, but I can at least share with you a bit of this journey of my own exploration, in the hope that it helps you understand our opening better! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "💡 BONUS: Revolutionary Thinking"]
[Black "Against the Aggressive Modern! (Part 4) & CONCLUSION"]
[Result "*"]

{ To conclude our discussion on the Modern, I'd like to show you one final game!  In my final online blitz session before working seriously on importing this course into Chessable format, I happened to get paired up against the same IM opponent who played 1...g6 in the style of 'The Sniper' recommendation that we just discussed!   Do you remember what conclusion we came to regarding how to meet the Modern? }
1. c3 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. e4
{ This time I wasn't going to let my opponent get The Sniper Modern setup vs London System! }
3... c6
{ Rather than play with ...d6, my opponent chooses ...c6. In this instance, I was quite lucky to know what I'm doing since I in fact play this opening from the Black side! }
4. Bd3 d5 5. e5 f6
{ This is the engine correct move, but I'm not a fan of playing it with the Black pieces. The positions are objectively fine, but the pieces feel awkward to me! }
6. exf6 exf6 7. h3 Nh6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O a5 10. c4
{ I remembered this was the right idea in this setup. Since the d5-pawn has less protection than usual @@StartBracket@@i.e. there's no black e6-pawn, nor a black knight on f6@@EndBracket@@. However, this was the last move I somewhat understood, and then I was on my own! }
10... Na6 11. Na3
{ I thought this was an important move to overprotect my c4-pawn, but in fact I immediately give up my entire advantage @@StartBracket@@this is why it's so important to have experience and understand the positions from your preparation!@@EndBracket@@   11.Nc3!  The natural development of the knight works much better. This was my first instinct, but I had dismissed the move due to 12. Bb1?  11...Nb4  12.Be2   12.Bb1?  dxc4  I had dismissed 11. Nc3 due to this variation, overlooking the fact that I can retreat the bishop to e2 rather than b1 with no problems!  dxc4  13.Bxc4+  Nf7  14.a3  Nd5  15.Bxd5  cxd5  16.Qb3±  White's activity will result in winning a pawn! }
11... Nb4 12. Bb1
{ Now we are far from the realms of 1.c3 Venom, but I'd like to show you how the rest of the game went! }
12... Be6 13. b3 Nf5 14. Bb2 Re8 15. Re1 Qd7 16. c5 Bf7 17. Nc2 Na6 18. a3 Nc7
19. b4 Ne6
{ 19...Rxe1+  20.Ncxe1  axb4  21.a4  g5  22.Nd3  Ne7  23.Nfe1  Ng6  24.a5  Nb5  25.Bc2 }
20. Ne3 { 20.bxa5  Rxa5 } 20... Nxe3 21. Rxe3 Bh6 22. Re1 axb4 23. axb4 Rxa1
24. Bxa1 Bf4 25. Bb2 Bb8 26. Bc1 Kg7 27. Bd2 Qc7 28. g3 Qd7 29. Kg2 Nf8 30. Bd3
Be6
{ At this moment, I'd actually built up a slight advantage in the position. Had I seen my h3-pawn was hanging @@StartBracket@@spoiler: I didn't@@EndBracket@@, then I could play 31. Rh1! with the plan of pushing h4-h5, making full use of my bishops! }
31. Qa1
{ I was playing quite quickly still not to fall behind on the clock. Against these strong opponents, as soon as you get low on time, it's very difficult to avoid flagging or blundering the entire position away! }
31... Bxh3+ { Now I'm definitely worse, but we should never give up! } 32. Kg1
Bg4 33. Nh2 Be6 34. Qb1 Bf7 35. Rxe8 Qxe8 36. b5 Ne6 37. Nf3 Qc8 38. b6 Nf8 39.
Qa2 Qg4 40. Kg2 Qc8 41. Qa8
{ Somehow my opponent wasn't able to make use of the extra pawn, and now I'm the one pressing for an advantage! }
41... Be6 42. Be3 Bh3+ 43. Kg1 Bg4 44. Nd2
{ Not only do I save my hanging knight, but I see a great journey for it. Where does our knight belong? }
44... h5 45. Nb3 h4 46. Na5 hxg3 47. fxg3 Qe8 48. Bf2
{ I'd predicted this 47...Qe8 response, so I could blast out Bf2 immediately!   Suddenly, Black has no attack, and I still have serious pressure on Black's queenside pawns! }
48... Nh7 49. Qxb7+ Kh6 50. Qxc6 Qe7
{ By this point, we both had around 30 seconds left. The position is winning for me, but the clock situation meant it was still anyone's game! }
51. Qxd5 Ng5 52. Bf1 Kh5
{ 52...Nf3+!  My opponent in fact had fought back enough for a draw at this point!  53.Kh1  Bxg3?  54.Bxg3  Qe3+-  Now I'd be completely lost! Queen and Knight are a lethal combination of pieces in the attack. }
53. Qh1+
{ My opponent had clearly missed this! Now the tables have turned, and I'll be the one attacking! }
53... Nh3+ 54. Bxh3 Kg5 55. Bg2 Qe2 56. Qh4+ Kf5 57. Nc6 Qd1+ 58. Kh2 Qe2 59.
Nxb8 Qxf2 60. Nc6
{ ...and I won on time! Perhaps not the cleanest conversion, but given the clock situation, I was more than happy to avoid losing this! And in fact, this win was actually was my highest rated opponent @@StartBracket@@ELO: 2607@@EndBracket@@ scalp to date @@StartBracket@@12/03/2024@@EndBracket@@ in online blitz!   So as you can see, the Modern Defence preparation worked out well. Having gone from playing a lost opening in OTB Classical, to solving that line, to then discovering a second problematic line in the Modern, to solving that line too, to then finally scoring my greatest rated blitz game to date against an International Master!   So to me, this is what the study of a novel opening is all about. The answers to your problems will need to be worked out @@StartBracket@@which is why I wanted to take you on this journey of understanding the Modern Defence, rather than just showing you the conclusion that 3. e4 is the correct way to face the Modern@@EndBracket@@.   Since switching my repertoire to 1. c3, I cannot believe how great my results have been — in all time controls, both online and in person. I hope the study of 1.c3 Venom will inspire you to think deeper about your own openings, as well as introduce a creative and practical spark in your opening play!   I'd also like to take a moment to thank Dylan  (my supervisor)  for teaching me the ways of the Chessable Import and believing whole-heartedly in me and 1.c3 Venom from the very beginning. I'd also like to thank Steven  (my training partner)  for investigating many of the lines of 1.c3 Venom with me, and his continued support throughout the publishing process. I'd also like to thank quarkchu, Fenderstrat1981, kyrasanangel, GLSmyth, and Massive_Attack, for beta-testing the course — without your attention to detail and constructive feedback, the course would be nowhere near as polished.  And finally, thank YOU for joining me on this journey to explore 1.c3 Venom to its fullest! I will try my absolute hardest to stay involved with the 1.c3 Venom community on Chessable, and answer any questions / thoughts you may have!   So hopefully see you there!   Michael Green   First time Chessable Author & FIDE Instructor }
